\id PSA Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h Psalms
\mt1 The Book of Psalms.
\c 1
\p
\v 1 Blessed is the man, that hath not gone in the counsel of the impious, & hath not stood in the way of sinners, and hath not sit in the chair of pestilence: \f + \fr 1:1 \ft not consented to evil suggestions.\f* \f + \fr 1:1 \ft not continued in sin.\f* \f + \fr 1:1 \ft not finally persisted in wicked life.\f*
\v 2 But his will is in the way of our Lord, and in his law he will meditate day and night. \f + \fr 1:2 \ft He is wholly occupied & delighted in keeping God's commandments.\f*
\v 3 And he shall be as a tree, that is planted nigh to the streams of waters, which shall give his fruit in his time. And his leaf shall not fall: and all things whatsoever he shall do, shall prosper. \f + \fr 1:3 \ft To him that useth God's grace well, more grace is continually given.\f* \f + \fr 1:3 \ft Through such grace he shall persevere.\f* \f + \fr 1:3 \ft all things work to the good of them that love God sincerely.\f*
\v 4 The impious not so, not so: but as dust, which the wind driveth from the face of the earth. \f + \fr 1:4 \ft The wicked are carried with every light tentation.\f*
\v 5 Therefore the impious shall not rise again in judgment: nor sinners in the Council of the just. \f + \fr 1:5 \ft All rising at the last day, the wicked shall not rise with hope nor comfort, but in desolation.\f* \f + \fr 1:5 \ft the happy congregation of the blessed.\f*
\v 6 For our Lord knoweth the way of the just, and the way of the impious shall perish. \f + \fr 1:6 \ft approveth & rewardeth.\f* \f + \fr 1:6 \ft in eternal damnation.\f*
\c 2
\p
\v 1 Why did the Gentiles rage, and peoples meditate vain things? \f + \fr 2:1 \ft Both gentiles\f* \f + \fr 2:1 \ft and Jews strive in vain against Christ.\f*
\v 2 The kings of the earth stood up, and the Princes came together in one against our Lord, and against his Christ. \f + \fr 2:2 \ft Pilate and Herod.\f* \f + \fr 2:2 \ft Annas and Caiphas.\f*
\v 3 Let us break their bonds a-sunder: and let us cast away their yoke from us. \f + \fr 2:3 \ft The voice of wicked men,\f* \f + \fr 2:3 \ft & especially libertines striving to shake off all discipline.\f*
\v 4 He that dwelleth in the heavens shall laugh at them: and our Lord shall scorn them. \f + \fr 2:4 \ft God for all this will turn the hearts of many.\f*
\v 5 Then shall he speak to them in his wrath, & in his fury he shall trouble them. \f + \fr 2:5 \ft severely reprehend,\f* \f + \fr 2:5 \ft and justly punish the obstinate.\f*
\v 6 But I am appointed king by him over Sion his holy hill, preaching his precept. \f + \fr 2:6 \ft Christ shall reign in his Kingdom the Church.\f*
\v 7 The Lord said to me: Thou art my Son, I this day have begotten thee. \f + \fr 2:7 \ft God the Father speaketh to\f* \f + \fr 2:7 \ft God the Son.\f*
\v 8 Ask of me, and I will give thee the Gentiles, for thine inheritance, and thy possession the ends of the earth. \f + \fr 2:8 \ft Christ as man hath the Church for his inheritance.\f* \f + \fr 2:8 \ft Spread through the whole world.\f*
\v 9 Thou shalt rule them in a rod of iron, and as a potter's vessel thou shalt break them in pieces. \f + \fr 2:9 \ft God's inflexible will & power.\f*
\v 10 And now ye kings understand: take instruction you that judge the earth. \f + \fr 2:10 \ft Aprophecy that Kings shall be converted, and submit themselves to Christ's discipline.\f*
\v 11 Serve our Lord in fear: and rejoice to him with trembling. \f + \fr 2:11 \ft None is secure before death.\f*
\v 12 Apprehend discipline lest sometime our Lord be wrath, and you perish out of the just way. \f + \fr 2:12 \ft Some fall from the way of salvation.\f*
\v 13 when his wrath shall burn in short time, blessed are all that trust in him. \f + \fr 2:13 \ft God will judge justly in the end of this short life both the evil and good. So this Psalm concludeth with the ninth key.\f*
\c 3
\p
\v 1 The Psalm of David, when he fled from the face of Absalom his son.
\v 2 Lord why are they multiplied that trouble me? Many rise up against me. \f + \fr 3:2 \ft O God let me know how grievously I have sinned,\f* \f + \fr 3:2 \ft that all Israel (1. Reg. 15. v. 13.) with all their heart followeth Absalom. So against Christ, the Priests, the People, & Gentiles are conspired.\f*
\v 3 Many say to my soul: There is no salvation for him in his God. \f + \fr 3:3 \ft my life.\f* \f + \fr 3:3 \ft he cannot escape.\f*
\v 4 But thou Lord art my protector, my glory, & exalting my head. \f + \fr 3:4 \ft But I avouch that God always defendeth me,\f* \f + \fr 3:4 \ft giving me victory,\f* \f + \fr 3:4 \ft & confirming my Kingdom.\f*
\v 5 With my voice I have cried to our Lord: and he hath heard me from his holy hill. \f + \fr 3:5 \ft heaven.\f*
\v 6 I have slept, and have been at rest; and have risen up, because our lord hath taken me. \f + \fr 3:6 \ft Ilay down\f* \f + \fr 3:6 \ft and rested in expectation of thy help.\f* \f + \fr 3:6 \ft And am delivered. Christ died, was buried, & rose again.\f*
\v 7 I will not fear thousands of people compassing me: arise Lord, save me my God. \f + \fr 3:7 \ft Iknow thou wilt help me, and so I beseech thee to do.\f*
\v 8 Because thou hast strucken all that are my adversaries without cause: thou hast broken the teeth of sinners. \f + \fr 3:8 \ft The strength and fury.\f*
\v 9 Salvation is our Lord's: and thy blessing upon thy people. \f + \fr 3:9 \ft health and safety cometh from God.\f* \f + \fr 3:9 \ft Aboundance of grace promised to God's servants.\f*
\c 4
\p
\v 1 Unto the end in songs, the Psalm of David. \f + \fr 4:1 \ft In an instrument apt for verses.\f* \f + \fr 4:1 \ft This Psalm pertaineth to the beloved, signified by the word David. S. Aug. li. 17. c. 14. civit. S. Beda in Psal.\f*
\v 2 When I invocated, the God of my justice heard me: in tribulation thou hast enlarged to me. Have mercy on me, and hear my prayer. \f + \fr 4:2 \ft When Saul unjustly persecuted just David, God heard his prayers.\f* \f + \fr 4:2 \ft being straitly besieged (1. Reg. 23. 26.)\f* \f + \fr 4:2 \ft Likewise help me whensoever I shall need.\f*
\v 3 Ye sons of men how long are you of heavy heart? Why love you vanity, and seek lying? \f + \fr 4:3 \ft Why do you still harden your hearts?\f* \f + \fr 4:3 \ft honour, and transitory glory,\f* \f + \fr 4:3 \ft false and deceitful riches?\f*
\v 4 And know ye that our Lord hath made his holy one marvelous: our Lord will hear me, when I shall cry to him. \f + \fr 4:4 \ft Every godly soul.\f* \f + \fr 4:4 \ft Rich with virtues.\f* \f + \fr 4:4 \ft Every just soul hath confidence in God, that he will here his cry.\f*
\v 5 Be ye angry, and sin not: the things that you say in your hearts, in your chambers be ye sorry for. \f + \fr 4:5 \ft Just anger is good & necessary against sin.\f* \f + \fr 4:5 \ft but then is most need to beware not to exceed in passion, have therefore a continual purpose never to sin.\f* \f + \fr 4:5 \ft Evil cogitations\f* \f + \fr 4:5 \ft bewail & repent before you sleep.\f*
\v 6 Sacrifice ye the sacrifice of justice, and hope in our Lord. Many say: Who sheweth us good things? \f + \fr 4:6 \ft Not only external but most especially internal sacrifice of justice, and observation of God's commandments is most necessary.\f* \f + \fr 4:6 \ft The solid rewards promised by God?\f*
\v 7 The light of thy countenance, o Lord is signed upon us: thou hast given gladness in my heart. \f + \fr 4:7 \ft reason and grace are freely given to man, whereby he may know that God will reward the just. Heb. 11. v. 6.\f* \f + \fr 4:7 \ft Wherein a just man inwardly rejoiceth.\f*
\v 8 By the fruit of their corn, and wine, and oil, they are multiplied. \f + \fr 4:8 \ft For example and in figure of heavenly rewards, God gave temporal wealth in the old testament.\f* \f + \fr 4:8 \ft See previous note\f* \f + \fr 4:8 \ft See previous note\f*
\v 9 In peace in the self same I will sleep, and rest: \f + \fr 4:9 \ft In this confidence the just may rest contented.\f*
\v 10 Because thou Lord hast singularly settled me in hope. \f + \fr 4:10 \ft God so promiseth every just person in particular.\f*
\c 5
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for her that obtaineth the inheritance. The Psalm of David. \f + \fr 5:1 \ft The faithful just soul that overcometh her enemies by virtue.\f* \f + \fr 5:1 \ft eternal glory.\f*
\v 2 Receive, o Lord my words with thine ears, understand my cry. \f + \fr 5:2 \ft The prayer of the whole Church, or of any faithful (ever beloved) soul.\f*
\v 3 Attend to the voice of my prayer, my King and my God.
\v 4 Because I will pray to thee: Lord in the morning thou wilt hear my voice. \f + \fr 5:4 \ft God's help is presently granted of his part, though it be sometimes deferred for the more good of his servants.\f*
\v 5 In the morning I will stand by thee and will see: because thou art not a God that wilt iniquity. \f + \fr 5:5 \ft Before all other affairs we must pray to God. S. Cyprian. in fine orat. Dominicæ.\f*
\v 6 Neither shall the malignant dwell near thee: neither shall the unjust abide before thine eyes. \f + \fr 5:6 \ft The wicked and wickedness have no conversation with God.\f* \f + \fr 5:6 \ft in the day of judgement.\f*
\v 7 Thou hatest all that work iniquity: thou wilt destroy all that speak lie. The bloody and deceitful man our Lord will abhor: \f + \fr 5:7 \ft by final sentence of eternal damnation.\f*
\v 8 But I in the multitude of thy mercy. I will enter into thy house: I will adore toward thy holy temple in thy fear. \f + \fr 5:8 \ft Not in man's power, but in God's mercy must the just trust.\f* \f + \fr 5:8 \ft In the Church of God.\f* \f + \fr 5:8 \ft with reverential fear, as in God's presence.\f*
\v 9 Lord conduct me in thy justice: because of mine enemies direct my way in thy sight.
\v 10 Because there is no truth in their mouth: their heart is vain. \f + \fr 5:10 \ft No true nor solid goodness in the wicked.\f* \f + \fr 5:10 \ft They think nothing but vanity, and mischief.\f*
\v 11 Their throat is an open sepulchre, they did deceitfully with their tongues, judge them o God . Let them fail of their cogitations, according to the multitude of their impieties expel them, because they have provoked thee o Lord. \f + \fr 5:11 \ft yielding loathsome stench, bitterness, and rancor,\f* \f + \fr 5:11 \ft yet they flatter with feigned good words.\f* \f + \fr 5:11 \ft Albeit the just desire the conversion of the wicked, yet if they will not repent, then the just conform their desires to God's just judgement: which shall be manifested in the end of the world.\f*
\v 12 And let all be glad, that hope in thee, they shall rejoice for ever: and thou shalt dwell in them. And all that love thy name shall glory in thee,
\v 13 because thou wilt bless the just. Lord, as with a shield of thy good will, thou hast crowned us. \f + \fr 5:13 \ft The just shall receive sentence of eternal glory.\f*
\c 6
\p
\v 1 Unto the end in songs, the Psalm of David for the octave. \f + \fr 6:1 \ft This Psalm pertaineth also to penitents in the new testament.\f*
\v 2 Lord, rebuke me not in thy fury; nor chastise me in thy wrath. \f + \fr 6:2 \ft condemn me not eternally.\f* \f + \fr 6:2 \ft Spare me also for part of the temporal pain, which I deserve.\f*
\v 3 Have mercy on me Lord, because I am weak: heal me Lord, because all my bones be troubled. \f + \fr 6:3 \ft Give me the medicine of grace.\f* \f + \fr 6:3 \ft My sorrow hath inwardly pierced me even to the bones.\f*
\v 4 And my soul is troubled exceedingly: but thou Lord how long? \f + \fr 6:4 \ft with fear of thy just wrath.\f* \f + \fr 6:4 \ft leavest thou me in this calamity?\f*
\v 5 Turn thee, o Lord, and deliver my soul: save me for thy mercy. \f + \fr 6:5 \ft Shew again thy favourable countenance,\f* \f + \fr 6:5 \ft from this fearful affliction.\f* \f + \fr 6:5 \ft Though my sins have deserved the contrary yet shew thy mercy.\f*
\v 6 Because there is not in death that is mindful of thee: and in hell who shall confess to thee? \f + \fr 6:6 \ft This life is the time of repentance, after death no\f* \f + \fr 6:6 \ft In hell nothing but blasphemy.\f*
\v 7 I have laboured in my sighing, I will every night wash my bed; I will water my couch with my tears. \f + \fr 6:7 \ft Ihave in part lamented.\f* \f + \fr 6:7 \ft Iwill add more sorrow & penance.\f* \f + \fr 6:7 \ft Iwill persist in my penance, till I be throughly watered with thy grace.\f*
\v 8 My eye is troubled for fury: I have waxen old among all mine enemies. \f + \fr 6:8 \ft mine eyes are dim with weeping, for fear of thy just judgement.\f* \f + \fr 6:8 \ft my hairs are gray with sorrow.\f* \f + \fr 6:8 \ft whereat mine enemies rejoice.\f*
\v 9 Depart from me all ye that work iniquity: because our Lord hath heard the voice of my weeping. \f + \fr 6:9 \ft After due sorrow the true penitent hath confidence in God, against his enemies.\f* \f + \fr 6:9 \ft Will most certainly accept of true repentance.\f*
\v 10 Our Lord hath heard my petition, our Lord hath received my prayer.
\v 11 Let all mine enemies be ashamed, & very sore troubled: let them be converted and ashamed very quickly. \f + \fr 6:11 \ft These are not imprecations, but threatenings, that the wicked may amend, or else predictions if they persist in sin.\f*
\c 7
\p
\v 1 The Psalm of David which he sung to our Lord, for the words of Chusi the son of Jemini. \f + \fr 7:1 \ft This Chusi defeated the counsel of Achitophel, as S. Aug. S. Basil & S. Chris. expound it. Others think he speaketh of that Chusi (or Chusai) who reported to him the death of Absalom. 2. Reg. 18. v. 31.\f* \f + \fr 7:1 \ft (2. Reg. 16.)\f*
\v 2 O Lord my God I have hoped in thee: save me from all that persecute me, and deliver me.
\v 3 Lest sometime he as a Lion violently take my soul, whilst there is none to redeem, nor to save. \f + \fr 7:3 \ft Absalom, or any other enemy, if God do not resist and hinder him.\f* \f + \fr 7:3 \ft my life.\f*
\v 4 O Lord my God if I have done this, if there be iniquity in my hands: \f + \fr 7:4 \ft Such evil as mine enemies feign & object against me.\f*
\v 5 If I have rendered to them that repayed me evils, let me worthily fall empty from mine enemies. \f + \fr 7:5 \ft Let me not have the victory of them.\f*
\v 6 Let the enemy persecute my soul, and take it, and tread down my life in the earth, and bring down my glory into the dust. \f + \fr 7:6 \ft Let me die with ignominy.\f*
\v 7 Arise Lord in thy wrath: and be exalted in the coasts of mine enemies. \f + \fr 7:7 \ft Shew thy power.\f*
\v 8 And arise, o Lord my God, in the precept which thou hast commanded: and a synagogue of peoples shall compass thee. \f + \fr 7:8 \ft Seeing thou didst command to make me King, it behoveth thee to protect me.\f* \f + \fr 7:8 \ft many will serve thee the only true God.\f*
\v 9 And for it return on high: our Lord judgeth peoples. Judge me, o Lord, according to my justice, and according to my innocency upon me. \f + \fr 7:9 \ft For this increase of faithful people.\f* \f + \fr 7:9 \ft My just cause against my particular enemies\f* \f + \fr 7:9 \ft let fall upon me.\f*
\v 10 The wickedness of sinners shall be consumed, and thou shalt direct the just, which searchest the heart and reins, o God.
\v 11 My just help is from our Lord, who saveth those that be right of heart.
\v 12 God is a just judge, strong, & patient: is he angry every day? \f + \fr 7:12 \ft God doth not punish all sinners presently, but often deferreth.\f*
\v 13 Unless you will be converted, he shall shake his sword, he hath bent his bow, and prepared it. \f + \fr 7:13 \ft Expecting if they will amend.\f*
\v 14 And in it he hath prepared the vessels of death: he hath made his arrows for them that burn.
\v 15 Behold he hath bred with injustice: he hath conceived sorrow, and brought forth iniquity. \f + \fr 7:15 \ft The injurious persecutor purposing injustice, conceiveth envy, and bringeth forth iniquity.\f*
\v 16 He hath opened a pit, and digged it up: and he is fallen into the ditch, which he made.
\v 17 His sorrow shall be turned upon his head: and his iniquity shall descend upon his crown. \f + \fr 7:17 \ft Envy & desire to hurt others turneth to the ruin of the envyers.\f*
\v 18 I will confess to our Lord according to his justice: and will sing to the name of our Lord most high.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 Unto the end for presses, the Psalm of David. \f + \fr 8:1 \ft Belonging to the new Testament.\f* \f + \fr 8:1 \ft Suffering of Christ, and of Christians.\f*
\v 2 O Lord our Lord, how marvelous is thy name in the whole earth! Because thy magnificence is elevated above the heavens. \f + \fr 8:2 \ft God the Lord of all by creation, is our singular Lord,\f* \f + \fr 8:2 \ft God more excellent than the heavens, he being the Creator, they a creature.\f*
\v 3 Out of the mouth of infants & sucklings, thou hast perfected praise because of thine enemies, that thou mayest destroy the enemy & revenger. \f + \fr 8:3 \ft Fulfilled when Christ coming into Jerusalem, children sang Ozanna. Mat. 21.\f*
\v 4 Because I shall see thy heavens, the works of thy fingers: the moon and the stars, which thou hast founded.
\v 5 What is man, that thou art mindful of him? Or the son of man, that thou visitest him?
\v 6 Thou hast minished him a little less than Angels; with glory and honour thou hast crowned him: \f + \fr 8:6 \ft The Son in assumpted human nature, became less than Angels.\f* \f + \fr 8:6 \ft But in him man's nature is exalted above Angels.\f*
\v 7 And hast appointed him over the works of thy hands. \f + \fr 8:7 \ft Christ the Lord of all creatures.\f*
\v 8 Thou hast subjected all things under his feet, all sheep and oxen: moreover also the beasts of the field. \f + \fr 8:8 \ft Yea of Angels. Heb. 2.\f* \f + \fr 8:8 \ft Not only all reasonable creatures, but all beasts, and other things obey him. The sea and the winds obey him. Mat. 8.\f*
\v 9 The birds of the air, & fishes of the sea; that walk the paths of the sea.
\v 10 O Lord our Lord, how marvelous is thy name in the whole earth! \f + \fr 8:10 \ft The same end & beginning signify, that as God was marvelous in creating man in so happy state, that if he would, he might have avoided both sin & death: so he is marvelous in that he so rewardeth the blessed in the resurrection, that they can neither sin nor die.\f*
\c 9
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for the secrets of the son, the Psalm of David. \f + \fr 9:1 \ft Christ's coming in humility, and Christians' afflictions, are hidden from the world, in God's providence.\f*
\v 2 I will confess to thee, o Lord, with all my heart: I will tell all thy marvelous things. \f + \fr 9:2 \ft Give thanks.\f*
\v 3 I will be glad and rejoice in thee: I will sing to thy name, o most High. \f + \fr 9:3 \ft In mind\f* \f + \fr 9:3 \ft and body.\f*
\v 4 In turning mine enemy backward: they shall be weakened, and perish before my face. \f + \fr 9:4 \ft God repelleth the enemy, when man is not able to resist.\f*
\v 5 Because thou hast done my judgment and my cause: thou hast sit upon the throne which judgest justice. \f + \fr 9:5 \ft Ajust man doth his endeavor, not of himself, but by God's grace overcometh the enemy.\f*
\v 6 Thou hast rebuked the Gentiles, and the impious hath perished: their name thou hast destroyed for ever, and for ever and ever. \f + \fr 9:6 \ft All sinners, called Gentiles, because they were generally accounted wicked.\f* \f + \fr 9:6 \ft The vain glorious fame of sinners partly decayeth in this world, but most especially in the world to come.\f*
\v 7 The swords of the enemy have failed unto the end: and their cities thou hast destroyed.
\v 8 Their memory hath perished with a sound: and our Lord abideth for ever. He hath prepared his throne in judgment: \f + \fr 9:8 \ft Judicial seats of men are often corrupted, but God's never.\f*
\v 9 and he will judge the whole world in equity, he will judge the people in justice.
\v 10 And our Lord is made a refuge for the poor: an helper in opportunities, in tribulation. \f + \fr 9:10 \ft God doth not presently deliver the good from afflictions: but when it is to their spiritual profit.\f*
\v 11 And let them hope in thee that know thy name: because thou hast not forsaken them that seek thee, o Lord.
\v 12 Sing to our Lord, which dwelleth in Sion: declare his studies among the Gentiles. \f + \fr 9:12 \ft His precepts which men ought chiefly to study.\f*
\v 13 Because requiring blood he hath remembered them: he hath not forgotten the cry of the poor. \f + \fr 9:13 \ft God revengeth the blood of Martyrs.\f*
\v 14 Have mercy on me, o Lord: See my humiliation by my enemies. \f + \fr 9:14 \ft Procured by mine enemies.\f*
\v 15 Which exaltest me from the gates of death, that I may declare all thy praises in the gates of the daughter of Sion. \f + \fr 9:15 \ft In the public view of the Church.\f*
\v 16 I will rejoice in thy salvation: the Gentiles are fastened in the destruction, which they made. In this snare, which they hid, is their foot taken. \f + \fr 9:16 \ft The wicked are entangled in the snares which they lay for others.\f*
\v 17 Our Lord shall be known doing judgments: the sinner is taken in the works of his own hands.
\v 18 Let sinners be turned into hell, all nations that forget God. \f + \fr 9:18 \ft As the first works of Christ in all humility and patience were strange, and hidden to the world (v. 1.) so his last judgement shall be in majesty and manifest to all in exalting the blessed and suppressing the wicked.\f*
\v 19 Because to the end there shall not be oblivion of the poor man: the patience of the poor, shall not perish in the end.
\v 20 Arise Lord, let not man be strengthened: Let the Gentiles be judged in thy sight. \f + \fr 9:20 \ft By Gentiles is often understood all great sinners. For the Jews despised Gentiles: as the Romans did all Barbarous nations.\f*
\v 21 Appoint Lord a Law-giver over them: that the Gentiles may know that they be men. \f + \fr 9:21 \ft Suffer a tyrant to rule over them, that thereby they may learn what it is to use others unjustly. It seemeth to S. Augustine a Prophecy, that such as receive not Christ, shall believe Antichrist.\f*
\v 22 Why Lord hast thou departed far off, despisest in opportunities, in tribulation? \f + \fr 9:22 \ft In great persecution it seemeth to the weak, that god deferreth his assistance very long.\f*
\v 23 Whilst the impious is proud, the poor is set on fire: they are caught in the counsels which they devise. \f + \fr 9:23 \ft Extremely vexed & tormented.\f* \f + \fr 9:23 \ft The Prophet answereth to the complaint of the just, that indeed the wicked are caught in their own snares.\f*
\v 24 Because the sinner is praised in the desires of his soul: and the unjust man is blessed.
\v 25 The sinner hath exasperated our Lord, according to the multitude of his wrath he shall not seek. \f + \fr 9:25 \ft Not seek to recover God's favour.\f*
\v 26 There is no God in his sight: his ways are defiled at all time. Thy judgments are taken away from his face: he shall rule over all his enemies. \f + \fr 9:26 \ft The wicked doth domineer for a time, and thinketh he shall do so still.\f*
\v 27 For he hath said in his heart: I will not be moved from generation unto generation without evil. \f + \fr 9:27 \ft And never fall into any adversity, but still remain without misery or any evil.\f*
\v 28 Whose mouth is full of cursing, and bitterness, and guile: under his tongue labour and sorrow.
\v 29 He sitteth in wait with the rich in secret places, to kill the innocent.
\v 30 His eyes look upon the poor: he lieth in wait in secret, as a lion in his den.
\v 31 He lieth in wait to take the poor man violently, violently to take the poor man whilst he draweth him. In his snare he will humble himself, and shall fall when he shall have dominion over the poor.
\v 32 For he hath said in his heart: God hath forgotten, he hath turned away his face not to see for ever.
\v 33 Arise Lord God, let thy hand be exalted: forget not the poor. \f + \fr 9:33 \ft The prayer of the just in tribulation.\f*
\v 34 Wherefore hath the impious provoked God? For he hath said in his heart: He will not inquire.
\v 35 Thou seest, that thou considerest labour & sorrow: that thou mayest deliver them into thy hands. To thee is the poor left: to the orphan thou wilt be an helper.
\v 36 Break the arm of the sinner and malignant: his sin shall be sought, and shall not be found.
\v 37 Our Lord shall reign for ever, and for ever and ever: ye Gentiles shall perish from his land. \f + \fr 9:37 \ft Ye vilest men.\f*
\v 38 Our Lord hath heard the desire of the poor: thy ear hath heard the preparation of their heart. \f + \fr 9:38 \ft The just ought always to be ready prepared in heart, to suffer patiently all that shall happen unto them.\f*
\v 39 To judge for the pupil and the humble, that man add no more to magnify himself upon the earth. \f + \fr 9:39 \ft As the first works of Christ in all humility and patience were strange, and hidden to the world (v. 1.) so his last judgement shall be in majesty and manifest to all in exalting the blessed and suppressing the wicked.\f*
\c 10
\p
\v 1 Unto the end the psalm of David. I Trust in our Lord, how say ye to my soul: Pass over unto the mountain as a sparrow? \f + \fr 10:1 \ft S. Augustine applieth it to heretics, persuading Catholics to repair unto their separate congregation, falsely calling it the mountain.\f* \f + \fr 10:1 \ft Ye my friends say thus.\f*
\v 2 For behold sinners have bent the bow, they have prepared their arrows in the quiver, that they may shoot in the dark, at them that be right of heart. \f + \fr 10:2 \ft Persecuters using all rigour and force,\f* \f + \fr 10:2 \ft falsely pretend other causes against the innocent to destroy them.\f*
\v 3 For they have destroyed the things, which thou didst perfit: but the just what hath he done? \f + \fr 10:3 \ft It is the manner of persecuters, and especially of heretics, to destroy and pull down that others have built.\f*
\v 4 Our Lord is in his holy temple, our Lord his seat is in heaven.
\v 5 His eyes have respect unto the poor: his eye-lids examine the sons of men. \f + \fr 10:5 \ft Though God seem to wink or sleep, yet his providence still watcheth, and observeth all men's actions.\f*
\v 6 Our Lord examineth the just and the impious but he that loveth iniquity, hateth his own soul. \f + \fr 10:6 \ft Proveth by tribulations.\f* \f + \fr 10:6 \ft Continuance in sin bringeth damnation to the soul.\f*
\v 7 He shall rain snares upon sinners: fire and brimstone, and blast of storms the portion of their cup. \f + \fr 10:7 \ft God sparing for the time at last must needs of justice punish severely.\f*
\v 8 Because our Lord is just and hath loved justice: his countenance hath seen equity.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 Unto the end for the octave, the Psalm of David. \f + \fr 11:1 \ft Christ's first\f* \f + \fr 11:1 \ft and last coming,\f* \f + \fr 11:1 \ft will bring joy to the elect.\f*
\v 2 Save me Lord, because the holy hath failed because verities are diminished from among the children of men. \f + \fr 11:2 \ft Christ calleth his mystical body himself. Act. 9. v. 4.\f* \f + \fr 11:2 \ft False and double dealing hinder from true faith.\f*
\v 3 They have spoken vain things every one to his neighbour, deceitful lips, they have spoken in heart and heart.
\v 4 Our Lord destroy all deceitful lips, & the tongue that speaketh great things. \f + \fr 11:4 \ft Indolent & arrogant.\f*
\v 5 Which have said: We will magnify our tongue, our lips are of us, who is our Lord?
\v 6 For the misery of the needy, and mourning of the poor, now will I arise, saith our Lord: I will put in a salvation, I will do confidently in him. \f + \fr 11:6 \ft When sin most abounded Christ came into this world: and in like case will come to judge.\f*
\v 7 Words of our Lord be chaste words: silver examined by fire, tried from the earth, purged seven fold.
\v 8 Thou Lord wilt preserve us: and keep us from this generation for ever. \f + \fr 11:8 \ft Yet still there remain some just whom God preserveth.\f*
\v 9 The impious walk round about: according to thy highness thou hast multiplied the children of men. \f + \fr 11:9 \ft God sometimes suffereth the wicked to do what evil they desire.\f*
\c 12
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, the Psalm of David. How long, o Lord wilt thou forget me unto the end? How long doest thou turn away thy face from me? \f + \fr 12:1 \ft It more pertaineth to the new testament than to the old.\f*
\v 2 How long shall I put counsels in my soul, sorrow in my heart by day? \f + \fr 12:2 \ft Careful & almost perplex cogitations by reason of long persecution & man's weakness.\f* \f + \fr 12:2 \ft Very often every day.\f*
\v 3 How long shall mine enemies be exalted over me? Regard and hear me, o Lord my God.
\v 4 Illuminate mine eyes that I sleep not in death at any time: lest sometime mine enemy say: I have prevailed against him. \f + \fr 12:4 \ft Fall not into mortal sin,\f*
\v 5 They that trouble me, will rejoice if I be moved: but I have hoped in thy mercy.
\v 6 My heart shall rejoice in thy salvation: I will sing to our Lord, which giveth me good things: and I will sing to the name of our Lord most high. \f + \fr 12:6 \ft Patience in tribulation, and reward for victory.\f*
\c 13
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm of David. The fool hath said in his heart: There is no God. They are corrupt, and are become abominable in their studies: there is not that doth good no not one. \f + \fr 13:1 \ft Wicked men drowned in sin are at last so besotted in their understanding, that they think in their heart (though they dare not utter it) that there is no God: that is, none that hath divine providence in governing the world, nor that will judge all in the end.\f* \f + \fr 13:1 \ft Defiled with all sorts of sin.\f* \f + \fr 13:1 \ft Not only the most wicked, but also all mankind were unable without a Redeemer to do good.\f*
\v 2 Our Lord hath looked forth from heaven upon the children of men, to see if there be that understandeth, and seeketh after God.
\v 3 All have declined, they are become unprofitable together: there is not that doth good, no not one. Their throat is an open sepulchre, with their tongues they did deceitfully, the poison of asps under their lips. Whose mouth is full of cursing and bitterness: their feet swift to shed blood. Destruction and infelicity in their ways, and the way of peace they have not known: there is no fear of God before their eyes. \f + \fr 13:3 \ft Without faith in Christ none had meritorious works. * These three verses being not in the Hebrew, nor Greek, yet are in the English, an. 1577. and are three distinct verses in other psalms. 5. 9. & 35.\f* \f + \fr 13:3 \ft They are wholly occupied in vexing others.\f*
\v 4 Shall not all they know that work iniquity, that devour my people as food of bread? \f + \fr 13:4 \ft The Prophet speaketh this in the person of God.\f* \f + \fr 13:4 \ft With greediness to hurt the good.\f*
\v 5 They have not invocated our Lord, there have they trembled for fear, where no fear was. \f + \fr 13:5 \ft Not believing in God, they feared Idols, that is, devils:\f* \f + \fr 13:5 \ft who indeed cannot hurt God's servants.\f*
\v 6 Because our Lord is in the just generation, you have confounded the counsel of the poor man: because our Lord is his hope. \f + \fr 13:6 \ft Though innumerable be very wicked, yet some are just.\f* \f + \fr 13:6 \ft Mocked & derided those that trust in God.\f*
\v 7 Who will give from Sion the salvation of Israel? When our Lord shall have turned away the captivity of his people, Jacob shall rejoice, and Israel shall be glad. \f + \fr 13:7 \ft The Prophet wisheth, and withal Prophesieth that Christ our Saviour will come, who is promised to Israel.\f* \f + \fr 13:7 \ft Redeemed man from the captivity of the devil.\f* \f + \fr 13:7 \ft Those that supplant vice\f* \f + \fr 13:7 \ft and contemplate God.\f*
\c 14
\p
\v 1 The Psalm of David. Lord who shall dwell in thy tabernacle? Or who shall rest in thy holy hill? \f + \fr 14:1 \ft In heaven, as appeareth by the last verse.\f*
\v 2 He that walketh without spot, and worketh justice. \f + \fr 14:2 \ft One requisite thing is to be free or cleansed from sin.\f* \f + \fr 14:2 \ft The second is to do good.\f*
\v 3 He that speaketh truth in his heart, that hath not done guile in his tongue. Nor hath done evil to his neighbour, and hath not taken reproach against his neighbour. \f + \fr 14:3 \ft Sincerely in thought,\f* \f + \fr 14:3 \ft word, and\f* \f + \fr 14:3 \ft deed.\f* \f + \fr 14:3 \ft Nor harkened to detraction.\f*
\v 4 The malignant is brought to nothing in his sight: but them that fear our Lord, he glorifieth. He that sweareth to his neighbour, and deceiveth not, \f + \fr 14:4 \ft Glory is the reward of good works.\f*
\v 5 That hath not given his money to usury, and hath not taken gifts upon the innocent, He that doth these things, shall not be moved for ever. \f + \fr 14:5 \ft Usury excludeth from heaven.\f* \f + \fr 14:5 \ft Likewise doing wrong for bribes.\f*
\c 15
\p
\v 1 The inscription of the title to David himself. Preserve me, o Lord, because I have hoped in thee. \f + \fr 15:1 \ft Stylographia signifieth a thing most worthy to be noted, to wit, Christ crucified:\f* \f + \fr 15:1 \ft and most worthy of the Prophet's consideration.\f* \f + \fr 15:1 \ft Christ as man did often pray, as appeareth in the Gospel.\f*
\v 2 I have said to our Lord: Thou art my God, because thou needest not my goods. \f + \fr 15:2 \ft Christ's passion was not needful nor profitable to God but to man.\f*
\v 3 To the Saints that are in his land, he hath made all my wills marvelous in them. \f + \fr 15:3 \ft God speaketh shewing that Christ should make his marvelous charity known to his Apostles, and other servants.\f*
\v 4 Their infirmities were multiplied: afterward they made haste. I will not assemble their conventicles of blood: neither will I be mindful of their names by my lips. \f + \fr 15:4 \ft Men feeling their infirmities and miseries,\f* \f + \fr 15:4 \ft make haste in seeking remedies.\f* \f + \fr 15:4 \ft Sacrifices of idols shall cease in Gentiles.\f* \f + \fr 15:4 \ft Their names shall be changed from heathen to be called Christians.\f*
\v 5 Our Lord the portion of mine inheritance, and of my cup: thou art he, that will restore mine inheritance unto me. \f + \fr 15:5 \ft Eternal glory consisteth in seeing God.\f* \f + \fr 15:5 \ft God is the reward of suffering pains for Christ.\f*
\v 6 Cords are fallen to me in goodly places: for mine inheritance is goodly unto me. \f + \fr 15:6 \ft In division of temporal inheritance, land is measured by cords, as Josue 10. so portions in heaven are given with large measure:\f* \f + \fr 15:6 \ft Christ also received all nations for his inheritance.\f*
\v 7 I will bless our Lord, who hath given me understanding: moreover also even till night my veins have rebuked me. \f + \fr 15:7 \ft Wisdom to make good election of spiritual things rather than temporal.\f* \f + \fr 15:7 \ft Not only by day, but also by night.\f* \f + \fr 15:7 \ft Also my corporal pains give me instruction.\f*
\v 8 I foresaw our Lord in my sight always: because he is at my right hand, that I be not moved. \f + \fr 15:8 \ft Christ had God continually before his eyes: every man ought to think frequently of God.\f* \f + \fr 15:8 \ft For god still protecteth the just.\f*
\v 9 For this thing my heart hath been glad, and my tongue hath rejoiced: moreover also my flesh shall rest in hope.
\v 10 Because thou wilt not leave my soul in hell: neither wilt give thy holy one to see corruption . Thou hast made the ways of life known to me, thou shalt make me full of joy with thy countenance: delectations on thy right hand, even to the end. \f + \fr 15:10 \ft In limbo Patrum.\f* \f + \fr 15:10 \ft Christ's body corrupted not in the grave.\f* \f + \fr 15:10 \ft Death and resurrection is the way to life.\f* \f + \fr 15:10 \ft Perfect glory consisteth in seeing God.\f* \f + \fr 15:10 \ft In eternity.\f*
\c 16
\p
\v 1 The prayer of David. Hear, o Lord my justice: attend my petition. With thine ears hear my prayer, not in deceitful lips. \f + \fr 16:1 \ft In my just cause hear my petition\f* \f + \fr 16:1 \ft seeing I pray sincerely, not in feigned affection.\f*
\v 2 From thy countenance let my judgment proceed: let thine eyes see equities. \f + \fr 16:2 \ft Thou that seest all things declare my right against mine adversaries.\f*
\v 3 Thou hast proved my heart, and visited it by night: by fire thou hast examined me, and there is no iniquity found in me. \f + \fr 16:3 \ft My intention.\f* \f + \fr 16:3 \ft Most secret cogitations.\f* \f + \fr 16:3 \ft By tribulations.\f* \f + \fr 16:3 \ft Whose conscience is pure from grievous sin, may pray with this confidence, otherwise repentance is first necessary. But the whole Church may ever pray in this manner, because there be always some just and holy, in respect of whom it is truly called holy.\f*
\v 4 That my mouth speak not the works of men: for the words of thy lips I have kept the hard ways. \f + \fr 16:4 \ft For thy precepts.\f* \f + \fr 16:4 \ft The narrow way of virtue.\f*
\v 5 Perfit my passes in thy paths, that my steps be not moved. \f + \fr 16:5 \ft None can of themselves walk rightly, but by God's help.\f*
\v 6 I have cried, because thou hast heard me, o God: incline thine ear to me, and hear my words.
\v 7 Make thy mercies marvelous, which savest them that hope in thee.
\v 8 From them that resist thy right hand keep me, as the apple of the eye. Under the shadow of thy wings protect me: \f + \fr 16:8 \ft Against thy omnipotent power.\f*
\v 9 from the face of the impious, that have afflicted me. Mine enemies have compassed my soul, \f + \fr 16:9 \ft From their cruel and furious countenance.\f*
\v 10 they have shut up their fat: their mouth hath spoken pride. \f + \fr 16:10 \ft They have shut out all pity or commiseration.\f*
\v 11 Casting me forth now have they compassed me: they have set their eyes to bend them unto the earth. \f + \fr 16:11 \ft They intend utterly to destroy me even to the ground.\f*
\v 12 They have taken me as a lion ready to the prey: and as a lion's whelp dwelling in hid places.
\v 13 Arise Lord, prevent him, and supplant him: deliver my soul from the impious, thy sword \f + \fr 16:13 \ft Except God prevent, man's industry is not sufficient.\f* \f + \fr 16:13 \ft Refrain their power, which they have by thy permission, that they may not persecute so much as they intend.\f*
\v 14 from the enemies of thy hand. Lord from a few out of the land divide them, in their life: their belly is filled of thy secrets. They are filled with children: and they have left their remnants to their little ones. \f + \fr 16:14 \ft This is a prophecy, that the wicked, which are many, shall at the day of judgement be separated from the elect\f* \f + \fr 16:14 \ft which judgement beginneth sometimes in this life.\f* \f + \fr 16:14 \ft The pleasures of this world, which God approveth not, nor acknowledgeth amongst good things.\f*
\v 15 But I in justice shall appear to thy sight: I shall be filled when thy glory shall appear? \f + \fr 16:15 \ft The just shall be approved.\f* \f + \fr 16:15 \ft Nothing doth satiate man's mind, but the sight of God in eternal glory.\f*
\c 17
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, to the servant of our Lord David, who spake to our Lord the words of this canticle, in the day, that our Lord delivered him out of the hand of all his enemies, and out of the hand of Saul, and he said: I will love thee o Lord my strength: \f + \fr 17:1 \ft Though literally this Psalm pertained to David, yet in figure of Christ, and of the Church, or every just soul.\f* \f + \fr 17:1 \ft The Holy Ghost inspired David to render these thanks for his often delivery from dangers.\f* \f + \fr 17:1 \ft Saul is specially named, because he was his most potent worldly enemy.\f* \f + \fr 17:1 \ft These first words (as also diverse others) are added, and many changed in this and other Psalms by the Septuagint, who often leaving the Hebrew text render the sense, and so this agreeth in substance with the same Psalm recorded 2. Reg. 22.\f* \f + \fr 17:1 \ft By whom I am strong.\f* \f + \fr 17:1 \ft (2. Reg. 22.)\f*
\v 2 Our Lord is my firmament, and my refuge, and my deliverer.
\v 3 My God is my helper, and I will hope in him. My protector and the horn of my salvation, and my receiver. \f + \fr 17:3 \ft High & firm salvation.\f*
\v 4 Praising I will invocate our Lord: & I shall be saved from mine enemies.
\v 5 The sorrows of death have compassed me: and torrents of iniquity have troubled me. \f + \fr 17:5 \ft This is aptly applied to all mankind after his fall, declaring our state in sin, and inducing to penance, in the office of Mass on Septuagesima Sunday.\f* \f + \fr 17:5 \ft Mortal flesh subject to death.\f* \f + \fr 17:5 \ft Violent incursions of tentations to sin.\f*
\v 6 The sorrows of hell have compassed me: the snares of death have prevented me. \f + \fr 17:6 \ft Exceeding great afflictions of mind, like torments of hell, which I also fear.\f* \f + \fr 17:6 \ft Secret tentations have deceived me.\f*
\v 7 In my tribulation I have invocated our Lord, and have cried to my God: And he hath heard my voice from his holy temple: and my cry in his sight, hath entered into his ears. \f + \fr 17:7 \ft Earnest prayer is the best remedy in all tribulations.\f* \f + \fr 17:7 \ft As it is certain that God heard David's prayers, so he assuredly heareth all that sincerely fly unto him.\f*
\v 8 The earth was shaken & trembled: the foundations of mountains were troubled, and were moved, because he was wrath with them. \f + \fr 17:8 \ft God's anger against sin maketh high and lofty things to shake, even the most obstinate presumptuous sinners.\f*
\v 9 Smoke arose in his wrath: and fire flamed up from his face: coals were kindled from him. \f + \fr 17:9 \ft Divine wrath is like to smoke of the nostrils, or flaming fire, & burning coals.\f*
\v 10 He bowed the heavens, and descended: and darkness under his feet. \f + \fr 17:10 \ft God's punishment sometimes cometh so swiftly, as if the heavens bowed towards the earth.\f* \f + \fr 17:10 \ft God's fury is as a dark desolate night, or horrible mist.\f*
\v 11 And he ascended upon the cherubs, and flew: he flew upon the wings of winds. \f + \fr 17:11 \ft Yet when sinners repent, God most speedily, as flying with wings of mercy, comforteth & protecteth them.\f*
\v 12 And he put darkness his covert, his tabernacle is round about him: darksome water in the clouds of the air. \f + \fr 17:12 \ft God being in himself incomprehensible, is also secret in his determinations, and covert in his proceedings or acts.\f*
\v 13 Because of the brightness in his sight the clouds passed, hail and coals of fire. \f + \fr 17:13 \ft God's splendor oppressing man's sense, yet instructeth him by his marvelous works. Which mystically signifieth, that Christ illuminateth the world by his Apostles, and other preachers denouncing his justice, peace, and his will in all things pertaining to man.\f*
\v 14 And our Lord thundered from heaven, and the Highest gave his voice: hail and coals of fire.
\v 15 And he shot his arrows, and dissipated them: he multiplied lightnings, and troubled them.
\v 16 And the fountains of waters appeared, and the foundations of the world were revealed. At thy rebuke, o Lord, at the blast of the spirit of thy wrath.
\v 17 He sent from on high, and took me: and he received me out of many waters. \f + \fr 17:17 \ft From tribulations.\f*
\v 18 He delivered me from my most strong enemies, and from them that hated me: because they were made strong over me. \f + \fr 17:18 \ft From Saul, Absalom, Moabites, Ammonites, and temporal & spiritual enemies.\f*
\v 19 They prevented me in the day of mine affliction: and our Lord was made my protector.
\v 20 And he brought me out into largeness: he saved me, because he would me. \f + \fr 17:20 \ft Of his good pleasure without my deserts.\f*
\v 21 And our Lord will reward me according to my justice, and according to the purity of my hands he will reward me.
\v 22 Because I have kept the ways of our Lord, neither have I done impiously from my God.
\v 23 Because all his judgments are in my sight: and his justices I have not repelled from me.
\v 24 And I shall be immaculate with him, and shall keep me from mine iniquity. \f + \fr 17:24 \ft By his grace.\f*
\v 25 And our Lord will reward me according to my justice: & according to the purity of my hands in the sight of his eyes. \f + \fr 17:25 \ft He repeateth the 21. verse, inculcating that God will\f*
\v 26 With the holy thou shalt be holy, and with the innocent man thou shalt be innocent.
\v 27 And with the elect thou shalt be elect: and with the perverse thou shalt be perverted.
\v 28 Because thou wilt save the humble people: and the eyes of the proud thou wilt humble.
\v 29 Because thou dost illuminate my lamp o Lord: my God illuminate my darkness.
\v 30 Because in thee I shall be delivered from tentation, and in my God I shall go over the wall. \f + \fr 17:30 \ft Pass over all difficulties.\f*
\v 31 My God his way is unpolluted: the words of our Lord are examined by fire: he is protector of all that hope in him. \f + \fr 17:31 \ft God's precepts.\f*
\v 32 For who is God but our Lord? Or who is God but our God? \f + \fr 17:32 \ft One only God, Creator and Saviour of all.\f*
\v 33 God that girded me with strength: and made my way immaculate.
\v 34 That perfited my feet as it were of harts: and setting me upon high things.
\v 35 That teacheth my hands to battle: and hast put mine arms as a bow of brass. \f + \fr 17:35 \ft Amongst other acts David killed a lion, and a bear, & Goliath. 1. Reg. 17.\f*
\v 36 And hast given me the protection of thy salvation: & thy right hand hath received me. And thy discipline hath corrected me unto the end: and thy discipline, the same shall teach me.
\v 37 Thou hast enlarged my passes under me: and my steps are not weakened:
\v 38 I will pursue mine enemies, and overtake them: and will not return till they fail.
\v 39 I will break them, neither shall they be able to stand: they shall fall under my feet.
\v 40 And thou hast girded me with strength to battle: and hast supplanted them that rise against me under me.
\v 41 And mine enemies thou hast given me their back, & them that hate me thou hast destroyed. \f + \fr 17:41 \ft As God giveth strength to his servants, so he diminisheth the natural strength and courage of his enemies.\f*
\v 42 They cried, neither was there that would save them, to our Lord, neither did he hear them.
\v 43 And I will break them to powder, as the dust before the face of wind: as the durt of the streets I will destroy them.
\v 44 Thou wilt deliver me from the contradictions of the people: thou wilt appoint me to be head of the Gentiles.
\v 45 Apeople which I knew not hath served me: in the hearing of the ear it hath obeyed me. \f + \fr 17:45 \ft Conversion of Gentiles to Christ, as the Moabites, Idumeans, and others were subdued by David. 1. Par. 11. 14. 18. 19. 20.\f*
\v 46 The children being aliens have lied to me, the children aliens are inveterated, and have halted from their paths. \f + \fr 17:46 \ft The revolting and reprobation of the Jews, prefigured by Absalom's rebellion and others. 2. Reg. 15. 16.\f*
\v 47 Our Lord liveth, and blessed be my God, and the God of my salvation be exalted.
\v 48 O God which givest me revenges, & subduest peoples under me, my deliverer from mine angry enemies. \f + \fr 17:48 \ft God still protecteth the Church of Christ, as he preserved David.\f*
\v 49 And from them that rise up against me thou wilt exalt me: from the unjust man thou wilt deliver me.
\v 50 Therefore will I confess to thee among nations, o Lord: and will say a Psalm to thy name. \f + \fr 17:50 \ft Use of Psalms is most frequent in the Church of Gentiles. See the proemial Annotations. page. 2.\f*
\v 51 Magnifying the salvations of his king, and doing mercy to his Christ David, and to his seed for ever.
\c 18
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, the Psalm of David. \f + \fr 18:1 \ft Pertaining to the beloved of the new Testament.\f*
\v 2 The heavens shew forth the glory of God, and the firmament declareth the works of his hands. \f + \fr 18:2 \ft The silent works of God declare his Majesty to them that consider thereof, his Preachers declare the same by words, to all that will hear.\f*
\v 3 Day unto day uttereth word: and night unto night sheweth knowledge. \f + \fr 18:3 \ft The constant course of times sheweth that the same was disposed by God's power, and daily propagation of faith, especially of Christian doctrine, sheweth Christ's power, & assured perpetuity of his Church.\f*
\v 4 There are no languages, nor speeches, whose voices are not heard. \f + \fr 18:4 \ft Some of every language or nation have believed in Christ, receiving the Catholic Religion.\f*
\v 5 Their sound hath gone forth into all the earth; and unto the ends of the round world the words of them. \f + \fr 18:5 \ft S. Paul affirmeth that this hath been fulfilled by the Apostles preaching in all the world. Rom. 10.\f*
\v 6 He put his tabernacle in the sun: & himself as a bridegroom coming forth of his bride-chamber. He hath rejoiced as a giant to run the way, \f + \fr 18:6 \ft By the sun a most excellent and superelemental creature, the Prophet describeth Christ, making his course through this world, illuminating, comforting, and strengthening the Church his tabernacle, wherein he perpetually dwelleth.\f* \f + \fr 18:6 \ft Christ the bridegroom, & the Church his bride are never divorced; his love, wisdom, and power, ever conserving her by his immaculate law.\f*
\v 7 his coming forth from the top of heaven: And his recourse even to the top thereof: neither is there that can hide himself from his heat.
\v 8 The law of our Lord is immaculate converting souls: the testimony of our Lord is faithful, giving wisdom to little ones. \f + \fr 18:8 \ft The old law was likewise pure in itself and holy, but the new also maketh the observers immaculate.\f*
\v 9 The justices of our Lord be right, making hearts joyful: the precept of our Lord lightsome, illuminating the eyes.
\v 10 The fear of our Lord is holy, permanent for ever and ever: the judgments of our Lord be true, justified in themselves.
\v 11 To be desired above gold and much precious stone: and more sweet above honey and the honey-comb.
\v 12 For thy servant keepeth them, in keeping them is much reward. \f + \fr 18:12 \ft How sweet the law of God is, his servants find not by reading, or by hearing only, but by keeping it.\f* \f + \fr 18:12 \ft Conformably to this text the Prophet professeth (Psa. 118. v. 12.) that he kept them for reward, in which place the heretics' translation is corrupted.\f*
\v 13 Sins who understandeth? From my secret sins cleanse me: \f + \fr 18:13 \ft None in this life knoweth perfectly his own estate, whether he be worthy of love or hate, Eccle. 9. but hopeth and feareth.\f*
\v 14 and from other mens spare thy servant. If they shall not have dominion over me, then shall I be immaculate; and shall be cleansed from the greatest sin. \f + \fr 18:14 \ft If mortal sins have not dominion in the soul, it is just: and shall be in time immaculate from all sin.\f*
\v 15 And the words of my mouth shall be such as may please: and the meditation of my heart in thy sight always. O Lord my helper and my Redeemer. \f + \fr 18:15 \ft God's helping grace is still necessary to persevere,\f* \f + \fr 18:15 \ft as his first grace redeeming man is necessary for our first conversion.\f*
\c 19
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, the Psalm of David. \f + \fr 19:1 \ft Though such a prayer was very fitly made for David, Ezechias, or other Kings of Juda, yet it more properly serveth for Christian Kings and Prelates.\f*
\v 2 Our Lord hear thee in the day of tribulation: the name of the God of Jacob protect thee. \f + \fr 19:2 \ft The King or other superior praying for himself, his subjects pray with him, and for him. It may also be applied to Christ, praying whilst he was mortal, or now praying for his mystical body the Church: but in both these cases our prayers are only necessary for his servants, not for him.\f*
\v 3 Send he aid to thee from the holy place: and from Sion defend he thee.
\v 4 Be he mindful of all thy sacrifice: and be thy holocaust made fat. \f + \fr 19:4 \ft The Hebrew word MINCA signifieth sacrifice of flour, and unbloody, so pertaineth to the Eucharist, in form of bread and wine.\f* \f + \fr 19:4 \ft Be acceptable for him, for whom it is offered.\f*
\v 5 Give he unto thee according to thy heart: and confirm he all thy counsel.
\v 6 We shall rejoice in thy salvation: and in the name of our God we shall be magnified. \f + \fr 19:6 \ft In the prosperous state of thee our superior.\f*
\v 7 Our Lord accomplish all thy petitions: now have I known that our Lord hath saved his \sc Christ\sc*. He shall hear him from his holy heaven: the salvation of his right hand is in powers. \f + \fr 19:7 \ft His anointed King, or Priest. Mystically faithful people acknowledge the victory of Christ our Saviour over death and all his enemies.\f* \f + \fr 19:7 \ft In great strength, or heavenly forces.\f*
\v 8 These in chariots, and these in horses: but we will invocate in the name of the Lord our God.
\v 9 They are bound, & have fallen: but we have risen & are set upright. \f + \fr 19:9 \ft Men trusting in human and worldly power fall into captivity.\f*
\v 10 Lord save the king, and hear us in the day, that we shall invocate thee. \f + \fr 19:10 \ft By protection of the head the body is also conserved.\f*
\c 20
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, the Psalm of David. \f + \fr 20:1 \ft Pertaining to the new Testament, principally to Christ, partly to godly and victorious Kings, and generally to all the blessed, which overcome spiritual enemies.\f*
\v 2 Lord in thy power the king shall be glad: and upon thy salvation he shall rejoice exceedingly. \f + \fr 20:2 \ft Christ our King as man overcoming his enemies by his divine power, rejoiceth in victory.\f*
\v 3 The desire of his heart thou hast given him: and of the will of his lips thou hast not defrauded him. \f + \fr 20:3 \ft Christ's most special desire was the salvation of his people.\f*
\v 4 Because thou hast prevented him in blessings of sweetness, thou hast put on his head a crown of precious stone. \f + \fr 20:4 \ft This most principally verified in Christ, is also applied to Martyrs, which suffer, or are ready in preparation of mind to suffer death for the truth.\f*
\v 5 He asked life of thee: and thou gavest him length of days for ever, and for ever and ever.
\v 6 Great is his glory in thy salvation: glory and great beauty thou shalt put upon him.
\v 7 Because thou shalt give him to be a blessing for ever and ever: thou shalt make him joyful in gladness with thy countenance. \f + \fr 20:7 \ft All Saints receive blessing of glory, but only Christ imparteth such grace to others: for in him all are blessed that are eternally glorified. Gen. 21. Ioan. 1.\f*
\v 8 Because the king hopeth in our Lord: and in the mercy of the Highest he shall not be moved.
\v 9 Let thy hand be found of all thy enemies: let thy right hand find all that hate thee. \f + \fr 20:9 \ft The just conforming their desires to God's will, do pray that the wicked may be punished. It is also a Prophecy, that so it shall come to pass.\f*
\v 10 Thou shalt put them as an oven of fire in the time of thy countenance: our Lord in his wrath shall trouble them, and fire shall devour them. \f + \fr 20:10 \ft And so it followeth in the next verse: Thou shalt put them &c.\f* \f + \fr 20:10 \ft This also cannot be understood of any but of Christ, who in the general or particular judgement shall give sentence upon the wicked.\f* \f + \fr 20:10 \ft And immediately hell fire shall devour them.\f*
\v 11 Their fruit thou shalt destroy from the land: and their seed from the children of men. \f + \fr 20:11 \ft All the wicked, and namely the Jews who persecuted Christ, fail in their devices.\f*
\v 12 Because they have turned the evils upon thee: they have devised counsels, which they could not establish.
\v 13 Because thou shalt put them back: in thy remnants thou shalt prepare their countenance.
\v 14 Be exalted Lord in thy power: we will chant and sing thy powers. \f + \fr 20:14 \ft Whilst the wicked perish, the just rejoice & praise God in song and Psalm.\f*
\c 21
\p
\v 1 Unto the end for the morning enterprise, the Psalm of David. \f + \fr 21:1 \ft Redemption of mankind undertaken by Christ, and performed by his death, began to be shewed by his Resurrection in the morning of the third day. S. Augu.\f* \f + \fr 21:1 \ft In figure of Christ the beloved of God.\f*
\v 2 God my God have respect to me: why hast thou forsaken me? Far from my salvation are the words of my sins. \f + \fr 21:2 \ft God is God of all his creatures, but in more peculiar sort God of Christ by personal union.\f* \f + \fr 21:2 \ft Thou neither deliverest me from dying: nor yieldest me such comfort as thou vouchsafest to other Saints. v. 6. Mat. 27.\f* \f + \fr 21:2 \ft Iam neither delivered from dying, nor comforted in my passion, having undertaken to die for the sins of mankind, & reputed them as mine own words or facts.\f*
\v 3 My God I shall cry by day, & thou wilt not hear: and by night, and not for folly unto me. \f + \fr 21:3 \ft Albeit I cry by day,\f* \f + \fr 21:3 \ft and by night, on the cross and in the garden, to have the chalice of death removed from me, & shall not be heard,\f* \f + \fr 21:3 \ft yet there is no folly, nor fault in this petition, which is with submission of man's will to God's will.\f*
\v 4 But thou dwellest in the holy place, the praise of Israel. \f + \fr 21:4 \ft Thou from heaven wilt hear when it is convenient.\f* \f + \fr 21:4 \ft Whose wisdom and goodness the Church worthily praiseth.\f*
\v 5 In thee our fathers have hoped: they hoped, and thou didst deliver them. \f + \fr 21:5 \ft Patriarchs, Prophets, and other holy men praying in their distresses obtained their requests.\f*
\v 6 They cried to thee, and were saved: they hoped in thee, and were not confounded. \f + \fr 21:6 \ft Were temporally delivered by thy mighty hand from their persecutors.\f* \f + \fr 21:6 \ft Not frustrate of their humble prayers.\f*
\v 7 But I am a worm and no man: a reproach of men and outcast of the people. \f + \fr 21:7 \ft God that comforteth his servants in their tribulations, left Christ without his ordinary consolation, to suffer more than ever any other did.\f* \f + \fr 21:7 \ft Wicked persecuters respected not Christ as a man, but contemned him, as a very worm\f* \f + \fr 21:7 \ft as most reproachful of all men\f* \f + \fr 21:7 \ft as the basest of all the people.\f*
\v 8 All that see me have scorned me: they have spoken with the lips, & wagged the head. \f + \fr 21:8 \ft Almost all became Christ's cruel enemies at the time of his passion, afflicting, blaspheming, and scorning him, as the Evangelists record.\f*
\v 9 He hoped in the Lord, let him deliver him: let him save him, because he will him. \f + \fr 21:9 \ft The Evangelists write how all these things were fulfilled by wicked men, speaking these blasphemies, and reproaches.\f* \f + \fr 21:9 \ft God seemed to be well pleased with Christ, as with his own Son: if it be so, let him deliver him from these afflictions, say these blasphemers.\f*
\v 10 Because thou art he that hast drawn me out of the womb: my hope from the breasts of my mother. \f + \fr 21:10 \ft Divine power without man formed me in the womb of my mother a Virgin.\f*
\v 11 Upon thee I have been cast from the matrice: from my mother's womb thou art my God, \f + \fr 21:11 \ft As I have no father but thee O God: so without intermission from mine incarnation to this time, I have had thee my protector:\f* \f + \fr 21:11 \ft leave me not now without comfort, seeing I must die as thou hast determined, and I freely consented: yet leave me not in death but raise me again to life. Psal. 15. v. 9. 10.\f*
\v 12 depart not from me. Because tribulation is very nigh: because there is not that will help. \f + \fr 21:12 \ft Almost all are become mine enemies, and those few that would, cannot help me.\f*
\v 13 Many calves have compassed me: fat bulls have besieged me. \f + \fr 21:13 \ft Delicate lascivious young men,\f* \f + \fr 21:13 \ft and the scribes, Pharisees, and elders of the people have all conspired against me.\f*
\v 14 They have opened their mouth upon me, as a lion ravening and roaring. \f + \fr 21:14 \ft Condemning me and persuading the people to cry: Crucify, crucify him.\f*
\v 15 As water I am poured out: and all my bones are dispersed. My heart is made as wax melting in the midst of my belly. \f + \fr 21:15 \ft So weakened with pains of torments, as fluid water not able to consist.\f* \f + \fr 21:15 \ft My bones and strongest parts of my body are weakened, verified, when our Saviour fell down under his cross.\f* \f + \fr 21:15 \ft The part that first and last liveth is weakened as soft wax by heat of the fire, and ready to fail.\f*
\v 16 My strength is withered as a potsherd, and my tongue cleaved to my jaws: and thou hast brought me down into the dust of death. \f + \fr 21:16 \ft All my powers and radical humidity is dried up, as a potter's vessel is baked in the furnace.\f* \f + \fr 21:16 \ft Through exceeding great drought, which our Saviour professed on the cross saying: I thirst.\f* \f + \fr 21:16 \ft Thus thou O God has suffered me to come to the last breath of life, next to death. Yet finally our Saviour gave up his spirit before he should have died. v. 21.\f*
\v 17 Because many dogs have compassed me: the counsel of the malignant hath besieged me. They have digged my hands and my feet: \f + \fr 21:17 \ft Again this Royal Prophet recounteth by whom and how our B. Saviour should suffer, even as clear as the Evangelists afterwards have written the history.\f*
\v 18 they have numbered all my bones. But themselves have considered and beheld me: \f + \fr 21:18 \ft Our Saviour's body was so racked on the cross, that his bones might be seen and counted.\f* \f + \fr 21:18 \ft The persecuters wittingly determined all this cruelty: beheld it with their eyes, and without all compassion persisted in malice, rejoiced, and blasphemed.\f*
\v 19 they have divided my garments among them: and upon my vesture they have cast lot. \f + \fr 21:19 \ft The soldiers that crucified our Saviour, taking his garments for their prey:\f* \f + \fr 21:19 \ft yet in mystery of his Church divided not his coat.\f*
\v 20 But thou Lord prolong not thy help from me: look toward my defence. \f + \fr 21:20 \ft He prophesieth Christ's speedy resurrection.\f*
\v 21 Deliver, o God, my soul from the sword: and mine only one from the hand of the dog. \f + \fr 21:21 \ft Christ's soul was not separated from his body by force of the torments, but he preventing death freely yielded up his spirit. Ioan. 10. v. 9. & 10.\f* \f + \fr 21:21 \ft The most pure, and sanctified soul, of whose fullness all other just souls are sanctified.\f* \f + \fr 21:21 \ft That it stay not in hell, which devoured all other souls in the old Testament.\f*
\v 22 Save me out of the lion's mouth: and my humility from the horns of unicorns.
\v 23 I will declare thy name to my brethren: in the midst of the Church I will praise thee, \f + \fr 21:23 \ft The propagation of the Church of Christ in all nations.\f*
\v 24 Ye that fear our Lord praise him: all the seed of Jacob glorify ye him. \f + \fr 21:24 \ft Not the carnal but spiritual children of Jacob, Isaac, and Abraham. Rom. 9. v. 8.\f*
\v 25 Let all the seed of Israel fear him: because he hath not contemned nor despised the petition of the poor. Neither hath he turned away his face from me: and when I cried to him he heard me,
\v 26 With thee is my praise in the great Church: I will render my vows in the sight of them that fear him. \f + \fr 21:26 \ft The Church gathered both of Jews and Gentiles is very great and universal.\f* \f + \fr 21:26 \ft Our Saviour promised to give his own body, the bread of life. Ioan. 6. and performed the same at his last supper.\f*
\v 27 The poor shall eat, and shall be filled: and they shall praise our Lord that seek after him: their hearts shall live for ever and ever. \f + \fr 21:27 \ft Those that be faithful, humble, and poor in spirit participate the fruit of this most excellent Sacrament.\f* \f + \fr 21:27 \ft The effect of this B. Sacrament is the resurrection in glory, and life everlasting.\f*
\v 28 All the ends of the earth shall remember, and be converted to our Lord. And all the families of the Gentiles shall adore in his sight. \f + \fr 21:28 \ft Gentiles which have been idolaters shall recollect themselves, when they hear Christ preached, and shall turn to true Religion.\f*
\v 29 Because the kingdom is our Lord's: and he shall have dominion over the Gentiles. \f + \fr 21:29 \ft Although men can neither deserve to be converted, nor to persevere in justice; yet Christ meriteth to have a continual Kingdom, which is the perpetual visible Catholic Church.\f*
\v 30 All the fat ones of the earth have eaten, and adored: in his sight shall all fall that descend into the earth. \f + \fr 21:30 \ft Not only the poor sort, but also the mighty ones of the world shall be converted to Christ, participate his B. Body in the Sacrament,\f* \f + \fr 21:30 \ft and religiously adore the same.\f* \f + \fr 21:30 \ft All that adore God, shall adore him in this Sacrament.\f*
\v 31 And my soul shall live to him: and my seed shall serve him. \f + \fr 21:31 \ft Death being once overcome, it shall have no more power.\f* \f + \fr 21:31 \ft Again the Prophet inculcateth the continuance of the Catholic Church.\f*
\v 32 The generation to come shall be shewed to our Lord: and the heavens shall shew forth his justice to the people that shall be born, whom our Lord hath made. \f + \fr 21:32 \ft Apostles, and other preachers of Christ.\f*
\c 22
\p
\v 1 The Psalm of David. Our Lord ruleth me, and nothing shall be wanting to me: \f + \fr 22:1 \ft Christ the good pastor, governeth, protecteth,\f*
\v 2 in place of pasture there he hath placed me . Upon the water of refection he hath brought me up: \f + \fr 22:2 \ft and feedeth his faithful flock.\f* \f + \fr 22:2 \ft Baptism of regeneration,\f*
\v 3 he hath converted my soul. He hath conducted me upon the paths of justice, for his name. \f + \fr 22:3 \ft which is the first justification.\f* \f + \fr 22:3 \ft God's precepts which the baptised must observe Mat. 28. v. 20.\f* \f + \fr 22:3 \ft Salvation is in the name and power of Christ, not in man's own merit.\f*
\v 4 For although I shall walk in the midst of the shadow of death, I will not fear evils: because thou art with me. Thy rod and thy staff: they have comforted me. \f + \fr 22:4 \ft In great dangers of tentations to mortal sin,\f* \f + \fr 22:4 \ft yet by God's grace we may resist.\f* \f + \fr 22:4 \ft God's direction and law is straight,\f* \f + \fr 22:4 \ft and strong.\f*
\v 5 Thou hast prepared in my sight a table against them that trouble me. Thou hast fatted my head with oil: and my chalice inebriating how goodly is it! \f + \fr 22:5 \ft Christ hath prepared for our spiritual food the B. Sacrament of the Eucharist. S. Cyprian, Epist. 65. Eutym. in hunc Psal.\f* \f + \fr 22:5 \ft Against all spiritual enemies, the world, the flesh, and the devil.\f* \f + \fr 22:5 \ft Christian souls are also strengthened by the Sacraments of Confirmation, Penance, holy Orders, Matrimony, and Extreme Unction.\f* \f + \fr 22:5 \ft The B. Sacrament and Sacrifice of Christ's body and blood.\f*
\v 6 And thy mercy shall follow me all the days of my life. And that I may dwell in the house of our Lord, in longitude of days. \f + \fr 22:6 \ft Continual and final perseverance is by God's special grace.\f* \f + \fr 22:6 \ft In eternal life.\f*
\c 23
\p
\v 1 The first of the Sabbath, the Psalm of David. The earth is our Lord's, and the fullness thereof: the round world, and all that dwell therein. \f + \fr 23:1 \ft Christ rising from death the first day of the week, had all power given him in heaven and in earth. Mat. 28.\f* \f + \fr 23:1 \ft Not only the soil it-self, but all the fruit, and all that dwell therein are God's.\f*
\v 2 Because he hath founded it upon the seas: and upon the rivers hath prepared it.
\v 3 Who shall ascend into the mount of our Lord? Or who shall stand in his holy place? \f + \fr 23:3 \ft Though Christ created and redeemed all, yet only the just shall inherit heaven.\f*
\v 4 The innocent of hands, and of clean heart, that hath not taken his soul in vain, nor sworn to his neighbour in guile. \f + \fr 23:4 \ft Not occupied himself in vain and unprofitable things, but in commendable works.\f*
\v 5 He shall receive blessing of our Lord: and mercy of God his Saviour. \f + \fr 23:5 \ft God's mercy goeth before justification: just works follow, and so glory is the reward of all.\f*
\v 6 This is the generation of them that seek him, of them that seek the face of the God of Jacob. \f + \fr 23:6 \ft This sort of people thus serving God, shall receive everlasting bliss.\f*
\v 7 Lift up your gates ye Princes, and be ye lifted up, o eternal gates: and the King of glory shall enter in. \f + \fr 23:7 \ft The Prophet contemplating in spirit Christ's Ascension, inviteth Angels to receive him, and (by prosopopoeia) speaketh also to the gates of heaven, by which he is to enter.\f*
\v 8 Who is this King of glory? Our Lord strong & mighty, our Lord mighty in battle. \f + \fr 23:8 \ft Angels answer admiring, & demanding as in a dialogue, how Christ is become so glorious.\f* \f + \fr 23:8 \ft The Prophet answereth that Christ by his power hath overcome all enemies in battle.\f*
\v 9 Lift up your gates ye Princes, and be ye lifted up, o eternal gates: and the King of glory shall enter in. \f + \fr 23:9 \ft Again he willeth Angels to open the gates, and biddeth the gates to enlarge themselves.\f*
\v 10 Who is this King of glory? The Lord of powers he is the King of glory. \f + \fr 23:10 \ft The Angels demand as before:\f* \f + \fr 23:10 \ft The Prophet answereth, That Christ is Lord also of Angels, and all heavenly powers under God.\f*
\c 24
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, the Psalm of David. To thee, O Lord, I have lifted up my soul: \f + \fr 24:1 \ft This Psalm pertaineth more properly to the new testament. And is artificially composed: the verses beginning with distinct letters in order of the Hebrew Alphabet, to the last verse.\f* \f + \fr 24:1 \ft My mind to be attentive.\f*
\v 2 my God in thee is my confidence, let me not be ashamed. \f + \fr 24:2 \ft Not be frustrate of my petition.\f*
\v 3 Neither let mine enemies scorn me: for all that expect thee, shall not be confounded. \f + \fr 24:3 \ft That patiently expect the time when God will assist.\f*
\v 4 Let all be confounded that do unjust things in vain. Lord shew me thy ways: and teach me thy paths. \f + \fr 24:4 \ft This manner of praying is frequent in the Psalms, signifying as a prophecy, that so it will come to pass, and the conformity of the just to God's justice.\f*
\v 5 Direct me in thy truth, and teach me: because thou art God my Saviour, and thee have I expected all the day. \f + \fr 24:5 \ft In true faith and religion.\f* \f + \fr 24:5 \ft All our life we must desire more and more knowledge of true doctrine.\f*
\v 6 Remember, O Lord, thy commiserations, and thy mercies: that are from the beginning of the world.
\v 7 The sins of my youth, and my ignorances do not remember. According to thy mercy remember thou me: for thy goodness, O Lord. \f + \fr 24:7 \ft From the first use of reason, at which time many are careless,\f* \f + \fr 24:7 \ft & negligent to learn how to serve God.\f*
\v 8 Our Lord is sweet, and righteous: for this cause he will give a law to them that sin in the way. \f + \fr 24:8 \ft As God is sweet in giving good motions:\f* \f + \fr 24:8 \ft so he is severe to them that resist his grace.\f*
\v 9 He will direct the mild in judgment: he will teach the meek his ways.
\v 10 All the ways of our Lord be mercy and truth, to them that seek after his testament and his testimonies. \f + \fr 24:10 \ft God mercifully preventeth with his grace:\f* \f + \fr 24:10 \ft and justly rewardeth good works.\f* \f + \fr 24:10 \ft God's law is his covenant with man:\f* \f + \fr 24:10 \ft and testimony of his will.\f*
\v 11 For thy name, o Lord, thou wilt be propitious to my sin: for it is much. \f + \fr 24:11 \ft Sin in respect of aversion from God is great, & needeth his grace.\f*
\v 12 Who is the man that feareth our Lord? He appointeth him a law in the way that he hath chosen. \f + \fr 24:12 \ft He that feareth God, which is the beginning of wisdom, receiveth five spiritual commodities here mentioned:\f* \f + \fr 24:12 \ft 1. God instructeth him by his law:\f*
\v 13 His soul shall abide in good things: and his seed shall inherit the land. \f + \fr 24:13 \ft 2. bestoweth all necessaries upon him:\f* \f + \fr 24:13 \ft 3. others shall imitate his good example.\f*
\v 14 Our Lord is a firmament to them that fear him: & his testament that it may be made manifest to them. \f + \fr 24:14 \ft 4. God will protect him:\f* \f + \fr 24:14 \ft 5. According to God's covenant he shall enjoy the manifest sight of God for his eternal reward.\f*
\v 15 Mine eyes are always to our Lord: because he will pluck my feet out of the snare.
\v 16 Have respect to me, and have mercy on me: because I am alone and poor. \f + \fr 24:16 \ft Man's weakness without God's help.\f*
\v 17 The tribulations of my heart are multiplied: deliver me from my necessities. \f + \fr 24:17 \ft Tribulations cannot be avoided, but must necessarily be suffered: therefore, o God, give us grace to pass through them without sin.\f*
\v 18 See my humiliation and my labour, and forgive all my sins. \f + \fr 24:18 \ft Mine affliction.\f* \f + \fr 24:18 \ft Take away the cause, and affliction will be mitigated.\f*
\v 19 Behold mine enemies, because they are multiplied, and with unjust hatred hated me. \f + \fr 24:19 \ft Wicked men of hatred do endeavour to draw others into sin.\f*
\v 20 Keep my soul, and deliver me: I shall not be ashamed, because I hoped in thee. \f + \fr 24:20 \ft Those that hope in God shall never be confounded.\f*
\v 21 The innocent and righteous have cleaved to me: because I expected thee.
\v 22 Deliver Israel, o God, out of all his tribulations. \f + \fr 24:22 \ft All the letters of the Alphabet being complete in this Psalm, this last verse beginneth with Pere, Redeem, praying God to redeem and deliver Israel, that is, the whole Church, from tribulations.\f*
\c 25
\p
\v 1 Unto the end the Psalm of David. Judge me, o Lord, because I have walked in my innocency: and hoping in our Lord I shall not be weakened. \f + \fr 25:1 \ft This Psalm is also a convenient prayer for any Christian in tribulation.\f* \f + \fr 25:1 \ft Be thou, o God, arbiter of the cause between Saul and me, thou knowest mine innocency in this behalf, though I am unjustly charged by Saul and his friends.\f*
\v 2 Prove me Lord, and tempt me: burn my reins and my heart. \f + \fr 25:2 \ft Lest perhaps I be not so innocent as I desire, and as in respect of Saul I hope that I am, do thou O God prove me as thou wilt by tribulations.\f*
\v 3 Because thy mercy is before mine eyes: and I am well pleased in thy truth.
\v 4 I have not sitten with the Council of vanity: and with them that do unjust things I will not enter in. \f + \fr 25:4 \ft David in confidence of a good conscience, and zeal against the wicked, allegeth his sincere proceeding, more than ordinary men may do, God so inspiring him extraordinarily.\f*
\v 5 I have hated the Church of the malignant: and with the impious I will not sit.
\v 6 I will wash my hands among innocents: and will compass thy altar, o Lord: \f + \fr 25:6 \ft The rest of this Psalm every Priest reciteth in Mass, before he offer the holy Sacrifice, professing & putting himself in memory, that he must only communicate with 5. I have hated the Church of the malignant.] Holy David forced by reason of persecution to dwell\f* \f + \fr 25:6 \ft and so approach to the Altar. prefigured Levit. 6. v. 4.\f*
\v 7 That I may hear the voice of praise, and shew forth all thy marvelous works. \f + \fr 25:7 \ft Shutting the ears of my heart from evil and vain thoughts I will attend to godly inspirations,\f* \f + \fr 25:7 \ft and so with mental prayer and external voice (as the holy order of this sacred office requireth) praise thee, o God, in thy marvelous works.\f*
\v 8 Lord I have loved the beauty of thy house, and the place of the habitation of thy glory. \f + \fr 25:8 \ft Icannot but singularly love the excellency of this place dedicated to thy service: where is true faith, unity, and charity of thy people, the guard of holy Angels, the administration of sacred mysteries, assistance of the Holy Ghost, real presence of Christ our Lord, all replenished with Divine majesty.\f* \f + \fr 25:8 \ft This representeth unto me the glorious heavenly kingdom of God and all Saints.\f*
\v 9 Destroy not, o God, my soul with the impious, and my life with bloody men. \f + \fr 25:9 \ft Suffer me not therefore to be contaminate by the wicked, nor to be devoured with them.\f*
\v 10 In whose hands are iniquities: their right hand is replenished with gifts. \f + \fr 25:10 \ft They are still ready to commit more and more iniquities.\f* \f + \fr 25:10 \ft Themselves being corrupted, endeavour by gifts of worldly commodities to corrupt others.\f*
\v 11 But I have walked in mine innocency: redeem me, and have mercy on me. \f + \fr 25:11 \ft Every one ought so to purge his conscience, that he may be innocent or free from great sins.\f* \f + \fr 25:11 \ft Deliver me from this necessity of dwelling among the wicked.\f*
\v 12 My foot hath stood in the direct way: in the Churches I will bless thee o Lord. \f + \fr 25:12 \ft Iintend to walk right.\f* \f + \fr 25:12 \ft Idesire to praise thee amongst thy true faithful servants.\f*
\c 26
\p
\v 1 The Psalm of David before he was anointed. Our Lord is my illumination, and my salvation, whom shall I fear? Our Lord is the protector of my life, of whom shall I be afraid? \f + \fr 26:1 \ft Before his second anointing, as is probable. 2. Reg. 2.\f* \f + \fr 26:1 \ft Against ignorance God illuminateth his servants.\f* \f + \fr 26:1 \ft Against infirmity he giveth strength.\f* \f + \fr 26:1 \ft So he needeth not to fear any man's malice, subtlety, nor force. Luc. 21. v. 15.\f*
\v 2 Whilst the harmful approach upon me, to eat my flesh. Mine enemies that trouble me, themselves are weakened and are fallen.
\v 3 If camps stand together against me, my heart shall not fear. If battle rise up against me, in this will I hope.
\v 4 One thing I have asked of our Lord, this will I seek for, that I may dwell in the house of our Lord all the days of my life. That I may see the pleasantness of our Lord, and visit his temple. \f + \fr 26:4 \ft How special a benefit David esteemed it to be in the Catholic Church, the only true house of God!\f*
\v 5 Because he hath hid me in his tabernacle: in the day of evils he hath protected me, in the secret of his tabernacle. \f + \fr 26:5 \ft Albeit the spiritual or carnal enemy seek to overthrow me, yet I am secure in the Catholic Church.\f* \f + \fr 26:5 \ft God either suffereth not the enemy to find his servant,\f*
\v 6 In a rock he hath exalted me: and now he hath exalted my head over mine enemies. I have gone round about, and have immolated in his tabernacle an host of jubilation: I will sing, and say a Psalm to our Lord. \f + \fr 26:6 \ft or not to be able to hurt him spiritually.\f* \f + \fr 26:6 \ft When a martyr or confessor dieth, then he getteth the victory against the persecutors.\f* \f + \fr 26:6 \ft Diligently recounting all thy benefits, I render thanks by sacrifice and praise.\f* \f + \fr 26:6 \ft Not only in heart, but also singing with loud voice and instrument.\f*
\v 7 Hear, o Lord, my voice, wherewith I have cried to thee: have mercy on me, and hear me.
\v 8 My heart hath said to thee, my face hath sought thee out: thy face, o Lord, I will seek. \f + \fr 26:8 \ft In my inward sincere cogitations I desire and seek that I may see thee\f* \f + \fr 26:8 \ft face to face. 1. Cor. 13. v. 12.\f*
\v 9 Turn not away thy face from me: decline not in wrath from thy servant. Be thou my helper: forsake me not, neither despise me, o God my Saviour. \f + \fr 26:9 \ft In the mean time, o Lord, grant me thy favour,\f* \f + \fr 26:9 \ft leave me not, though thou be angry with me.\f* \f + \fr 26:9 \ft He speaketh in the person of orphans.\f*
\v 10 because my father and my mother have forsaken me: but our Lord hath taken me. \f + \fr 26:10 \ft Though carnal parents forsake the just man in tribulation, yet God hath then most special care of him.\f*
\v 11 Give me a law, o Lord, in thy way: and direct me in the right path, because of mine enemies. \f + \fr 26:11 \ft Establish my heart in thy law.\f* \f + \fr 26:11 \ft Conserve me in the right way, which thou hast already taught me: and it is the more necessary, because mine enemies labour to pervert me.\f*
\v 12 Deliver me not into the souls of them that trouble me: because unjust witnesses have risen up against me: and iniquity hath lied to it-self. \f + \fr 26:12 \ft The wills.\f* \f + \fr 26:12 \ft False witnesses accused David, others accused Christ: Mat. 26. others do still accuse the just Mat. 5.\f* \f + \fr 26:12 \ft The wicked please themselves in lying, but the chief hurt finally turneth upon themselves.\f*
\v 13 I believe to see the good things of our Lord, in the land of the living. \f + \fr 26:13 \ft The Prophet and all just men are comforted by God, and hope of reward in heaven.\f*
\v 14 Expect our Lord, do manfully: and let thy heart take courage, and expect thou our Lord. \f + \fr 26:14 \ft The just exhorteth his own soul to patience,\f* \f + \fr 26:14 \ft fortitude,\f* \f + \fr 26:14 \ft and longanimity.\f*
\c 27
\p
\v 1 Apsalm to David himself. To thee, o Lord, I will cry, my God keep not silence from me: lest at any time thou hold thy peace from me, & I shall be like to them that go down into the lake. \f + \fr 27:1 \ft Omit not to comfort me.\f*
\v 2 Hear, o Lord, the voice of my petition whilst I pray to thee: whilst I lift up my hands to thy holy temple.
\v 3 Draw me not together with sinners: and with them that work iniquity destroy me not. Which speak peace with their neighbour, but evils in their hearts. \f + \fr 27:3 \ft Suffer me not to be overcome: for God tempteth none to evil. Iac. 1.\f*
\v 4 Give them according to their works, & according to the wickedness of their inventions. According to the works of their hands give unto them: render them their retribution. \f + \fr 27:4 \ft The just in zeal of justice pray that sin may be punished.\f*
\v 5 Because they have not understood the works of our Lord, and in the works of his hands thou shalt destroy them, & not build them up. \f + \fr 27:5 \ft Ignorance doth not excuse when men may and will not understand.\f* \f + \fr 27:5 \ft God saveth not without our cooperation with his grace.\f*
\v 6 blessed be our Lord: because he hath heard the voice of my petition.
\v 7 Our Lord is my helper, and my protector: in him my heart hath hoped, and I was holpen. And my flesh flourished again: & with my will I will confess to him. \f + \fr 27:7 \ft Being comforted in spirit my body is as it were refreshed.\f* \f + \fr 27:7 \ft Freely & gladly.\f*
\v 8 Our Lord is the strength of his people: and he is the protector of the salvations of his anointed. \f + \fr 27:8 \ft God protecteth and prospereth the King's good endeavours for his people.\f*
\v 9 Save thy people, o Lord, and bless thine inheritance: and rule them, and extol them for ever. \f + \fr 27:9 \ft As Psal. 19. and often elsewhere the subjects pray for their Superior: so mutually the superior prayeth for the subjects.\f*
\c 28
\p
\v 1 The Psalm of David, in the consummation of the tabernacle. Bring to our Lord ye children of God: bring to our Lord the sons of rams. \f + \fr 28:1 \ft 2. Reg. 6. v. 17. 1. Par. 16. v. 1.\f* \f + \fr 28:1 \ft Offer sacrifice of thanks for the singular benefits after recounted in this Psalm.\f* \f + \fr 28:1 \ft Rams were of the more principal things that were offered in the law of Moyses. But the sons of rams import in mystical sense better hosts than rams.\f*
\v 2 Bring to our Lord glory and honour, bring to our Lord glory unto his name: adore ye our Lord in his holy court. \f + \fr 28:2 \ft The first thing in sacrifice is to glorify, honour, and adore God in sincerity of spirit,\f* \f + \fr 28:2 \ft in his holy Catholic Church.\f*
\v 3 The voice of our Lord upon waters, the God of majesty hath thundered: Our Lord upon many waters. \f + \fr 28:3 \ft Here is a greater matter intimated than happened in the bringing of the Ark into a tabernacle prepared in Sion, when David danced, and offered hosts for sacrifice, others joining with him in that solemnity. But this voice of our Lord upon waters is rather verified of our Blessed Saviour's own preaching with\f* \f + \fr 28:3 \ft majesty\f* \f + \fr 28:3 \ft thundering, & by his Apostles upon\f* \f + \fr 28:3 \ft many waters, many nations:\f*
\v 4 The voice of our Lord in power: the voice of our Lord in magnificence. \f + \fr 28:4 \ft in power of miracles,\f* \f + \fr 28:4 \ft in magnificence preaching, as having indeed power, not as the Scribes and Pharisees. Mat. 7. v. 29.\f*
\v 5 The voice of our Lord breaking cedars: and our Lord shall break the cedars of Libanus: \f + \fr 28:5 \ft Breaking cedars; among innumerable others, converting highest Potentates\f* \f + \fr 28:5 \ft of Libanus; Emperors, Kings, and greatest Princes of the world:\f*
\v 6 And he shall break them in pieces as a calf of Libanus. And the beloved as the son of unicorns. \f + \fr 28:6 \ft as a calf of Libanus; so meekly submitting themselves to Christ's yoke, and spiritual obedience of his Church.\f* \f + \fr 28:6 \ft All which is done by Christ our Lord the beloved of God,\f* \f + \fr 28:6 \ft as the son of unicorns, is most tenderly beloved by the parents.\f*
\v 7 The voice of our Lord dividing the flame of fire. \f + \fr 28:7 \ft This voice of our Lord dividing the flame of fire. The Holy Ghost proceeding from the Father and the Son, came upon the Apostles, as in divided tongues of fire.\f*
\v 8 The voice of our Lord shaking the desert, and our Lord shall move the desert of Cades. \f + \fr 28:8 \ft Wherewith the desert, the Gentiles of the wide and wild world, were shaken and moved,\f* \f + \fr 28:8 \ft the desert of Cades, some of the Jews also compunct in heart with remorse of conscience, hearing the voice of Saint Peter and other Apostles.\f*
\v 9 The voice of our Lord preparing harts, and he shall discover thick woods : and in his temple all shall say glory. \f + \fr 28:9 \ft The same voice of our lord preparing harts, inspiring the minds of men with speed, like hinds and does to ascend the high hills of free and perfect life, in contemplative virtues.\f* \f + \fr 28:9 \ft So our Saviour shall discover the thick woods, reveal the hidden Mysteries of the old Law, by preaching Christian doctrine, and use of Christian Religion\f* \f + \fr 28:9 \ft in his holy Temple, the Catholic Church, wherein all true Christians shall glorify God.\f* \f + \fr 28:9 \ft cervos.\f*
\v 10 Our Lord maketh to inhabit the flood: and our Lord shall sit King for ever. \f + \fr 28:10 \ft Making the great aboundance of people, who are like the sea when it overfloweth the land, to dwell in the same Church.\f* \f + \fr 28:10 \ft Christ our Lord sitting, & ruling King over all for ever:\f*
\v 11 Our Lord will give strength to his people: our Lord will bless his people in peace. \f + \fr 28:11 \ft by his grace giving strength to his people, to pass through the tentations of this life,\f* \f + \fr 28:11 \ft and bless the just\f*
\c 29
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of Canticle, in the dedication of David's house. \f + \fr 29:1 \ft The general name of Psalm common to this whole book containing in all 150. is more particularly appropriated to some, which more specially were played upon musical instruments, as on the Psalter, Harp, &c. Others are called Canticles, which were most usually sung with human voices. So this, called a Psalm of Canticle, signifieth that voices began the music, and instruments were adjoined. As contrarywise others are called Canticles of Psalms, where instruments began and voices followed.\f* \f + \fr 29:1 \ft After many great tribulations, King David prospering built an excellent house or palace (2. Reg. 5. v. 11. Paralip. 14. v. 1.) And at his first dwelling therein, made this Psalm, beginning himself to sing the same with voice, other musicians joined with him in praises of God and thanks-giving for his benefits.\f*
\v 2 I will exalt thee, o Lord because thou hast received me: neither hast delighted mine enemies over me. \f + \fr 29:2 \ft Though God in himself is most high, and neither needeth, nor can be exalted by men, yet the royal Prophet knew it was his duty to sing thanks and praises to him,\f* \f + \fr 29:2 \ft for his delivery from many troubles and dangers.\f* \f + \fr 29:2 \ft Not suffering his enemies to be delighted in his ruin.\f*
\v 3 O Lord my God I have cried to thee, and thou hast healed me. \f + \fr 29:3 \ft Conserved my body in health amongst innumerable dangers.\f*
\v 4 Lord thou hast brought forth my soul out of hell: thou hast saved me from them that go down into the lake. \f + \fr 29:4 \ft Preserved my soul from greater dangers of sins, and so from hell.\f*
\v 5 Sing to our Lord ye his Saints: and confess to the memory of his holiness. \f + \fr 29:5 \ft Ye that are just and holy praise God for it, from whom it cometh, and not from yourselves:\f* \f + \fr 29:5 \ft confess his mere goodness without your deserts.\f*
\v 6 Because wrath is in his indignation: and life in his will. At evening shall weeping abide: and in the morning gladness. \f + \fr 29:6 \ft When he is angry,\f* \f + \fr 29:6 \ft yet he meaneth well unto us.\f* \f + \fr 29:6 \ft The state of a just man's life is often changed from sorrow to comfort, and from comfort to sorrow.\f*
\v 7 And I said in my aboundance: I will not be moved for ever. \f + \fr 29:7 \ft Though we suppose ourselves firmly established:\f*
\v 8 O Lord in thy will thou hast given strength to my beauty. Thou hast turned away thy face from me, and I became troubled. \f + \fr 29:8 \ft yet God of his good will towards us sometimes giveth strength, and courage,\f* \f + \fr 29:8 \ft sometimes suffereth us to our own weakness,\f*
\v 9 To thee o Lord I will cry: and I will pray to my God. \f + \fr 29:9 \ft therefore we must still cry and pray for God's help,\f*
\v 10 What profit is in my blood, whilst I descend into corruption? Shall dust confess to thee, or declare thy truth? \f + \fr 29:10 \ft in manner here expressed or the like.\f*
\v 11 Our Lord hath heard, and had mercy on me: our Lord is become my helper.
\v 12 Thou hast turned my mourning into joy unto me: thou hast cut my sackcloth, and hast compassed me with gladness.
\v 13 That my glory may sing to thee, and I be not compunct: Lord my God for ever will I confess to thee. \f + \fr 29:13 \ft Finally in this my good state\f* \f + \fr 29:13 \ft Ishall always confess and praise thee.\f*
\c 30
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, the Psalm of David, for excess of mind. \f + \fr 30:1 \ft Pertaining to the new Testament:\f* \f + \fr 30:1 \ft especially to the just troubled: & almost distracted in mind in great affliction. See. v. 23.\f*
\v 2 In thee o Lord have I hoped, let me not be confounded for ever: in thy justice deliver me. \f + \fr 30:2 \ft How grievously soever I am afflicted yet I trust in thee,\f* \f + \fr 30:2 \ft therefore I pray thus.\f*
\v 3 Incline thine ear to me, make haste to deliver me. Be unto me for a God protector: and for a house of refuge, that thou mayst save me.
\v 4 Because thou art my strength, and my refuge: and for thy name thou wilt conduct me, and wilt nourish me.
\v 5 Thou wilt bring me out of this snare, which they have hid for me: because thou art my protector.
\v 6 Into thy hands I commend my spirit: thou hast redeemed me, o Lord God of truth. \f + \fr 30:6 \ft Ioffer and resign myself to thee.\f* \f + \fr 30:6 \ft Thou hast often delivered me. This verse is most aptly applied in all resignations of our souls to God's will, namely whensoever we receive the B. Sacrament: likewise in the hour of death, and at many other times.\f*
\v 7 Thou hast hated them that observe vanities, unprofitably. But I have hoped in our Lord:
\v 8 Ishall rejoice and be joyful in thy mercy. Because thou hast respected my humility, thou hast saved my soul out of necessities.
\v 9 Neither hast thou shut me up in the hands of the enemy: thou hast set my feet in a large place. \f + \fr 30:9 \ft not suffered me to be shut up.\f*
\v 10 Have mercy upon me, o Lord, because I am in tribulation: mine eye is troubled for wrath, my soul, and my belly:
\v 11 Because my life is decayed for sorrow: and my years for groanings. My strength is weakened for poverty; and my bones are troubled. \f + \fr 30:11 \ft All my parts external and internal, body and mind are troubled.\f*
\v 12 Above all mine enemies I am made a reproach, both to my neighbours exceedingly: and a fear to my acquaintance. They that saw me, fled forth from me: \f + \fr 30:12 \ft My friends dare not converse with me, lest they incur displeasure for my sake.\f*
\v 13 I am forgotten, from the heart as one dead. I am made as a vessel destroyed:
\v 14 because I have heard the reprehension of many that abide round about: In that whilst, they assembled together against me, they consulted to take my soul.
\v 15 But I have hoped in thee. O Lord: I said, Thou art my God:
\v 16 my lots are in thy hands. Deliver me out of the hands of my enemies, and from them that persecute me.
\v 17 Illustrate thy face upon thy servant, save me in thy mercy: \f + \fr 30:17 \ft Make thy light so shine in my soul, that I may understand that is right.\f* \f + \fr 30:17 \ft And through thy mercy deliver me from the force of mine adversaries.\f*
\v 18 Lord let me not be confounded, because I have invocated thee. Let the impious be ashamed, and brought down into hell:
\v 19 let the deceitful lips be made mute. Which speak iniquity against the just, in pride and abuse. \f + \fr 30:19 \ft So proudly behaving themselves, as if they had no superior, neither in earth nor in heaven, to whom they shall at last render account:\f* \f + \fr 30:19 \ft and abusing their present power and authority, which they have of God.\f*
\v 20 How great is the multitude of thy sweetness, o Lord which thou hast hid for them that fear thee. Thou hast perfited it for them that hope in thee, in the sight of the children of men. \f + \fr 30:20 \ft As yet in this present life the reward of the just is hid:\f* \f + \fr 30:20 \ft but shall be made manifest in sight of all men.\f*
\v 21 Thou shalt hide them in the secret of thy face from the disturbance of men. Thou shall protect them in thy tabernacle from the contradiction of tongues. \f + \fr 30:21 \ft In the mean time the just is in great estimation in the secret knowledge of God.\f* \f + \fr 30:21 \ft title of honour, as we speak to a king; your majesty: or to a noble man, your Lordship.\f*
\v 22 Blessed be our Lord: because he hath made his mercy marvelous to me in the fenced city.
\v 23 But I have said in the excess of my mind: I am cast away from the sight of thine eyes. Therefore thou hast heard the voice of my prayer, whilst I cried to thee. \f + \fr 30:23 \ft In mine extreme affliction being almost distracted in my mind, I said that in reason I would not have said. Holy Job spake some things in such state of affliction. cap. 3. & 42.\f*
\v 24 Love our Lord all ye his Saints: because our Lord will require truth, & will repay them aboundantly that do proudly. \f + \fr 30:24 \ft The prophet, or other just person, exhorteth all the servants of God\f*
\v 25 Do ye manfully, and let your heart take courage, all ye that hope in our Lord. \f + \fr 30:25 \ft to constancy.\f* \f + \fr 30:25 \ft Longanimity,\f* \f + \fr 30:25 \ft and final perseverance to the end.\f*
\c 31
\p
\v 1 To David himself understanding. Blessed are they, whose iniquities are forgiven: and whose sins be covered. \f + \fr 31:1 \ft This Psalm sheweth how David was brought to understand his sins, to confess, bewail, and obtain remission of them.\f* \f + \fr 31:1 \ft The first blessing of a sinner is the forgiveness of his sins.\f* \f + \fr 31:1 \ft By charity, which covereth the multitude of sins. 1. Pet. 4.\f*
\v 2 Blessed is the man, to whom our Lord hath not imputed sin, neither is there guile in his spirit. \f + \fr 31:2 \ft Satisfaction being made.\f* \f + \fr 31:2 \ft When sinners repent sincerely without guile, then God forgiveth: without which cooperation none is justified.\f*
\v 3 Because I held my peace, my bones are inveterated, whilst I cried all the day. \f + \fr 31:3 \ft Because I acknowledged not my grievous sins, I was still sore afflicted:\f* \f + \fr 31:3 \ft though otherwise I ceased not to pray, but without any fruit or good effect.\f* \f + \fr 31:3 \ft waxed as if they were old.\f*
\v 4 Because day & night thy hand is made heavy upon me: I am turned in my anguish, whilst the thorn is fastened. \f + \fr 31:4 \ft Thy divine providence reducing me,\f* \f + \fr 31:4 \ft by remorse of mine own conscience, which telleth me that I deserve all this affliction.\f*
\v 5 I have made my sin known to thee: and my injustice I have not hid. I said: I will confess against me my injustice to our Lord: and thou hast forgiven the impiety of my sin. \f + \fr 31:5 \ft Therefore I do no longer dissemble with men, nor am silent to thee, but expressly acknowledge my sins.\f*
\v 6 For this shall every holy one pray to thee, in time convenient. But yet in the flood of many waters, they shall not approach to him. \f + \fr 31:6 \ft As I do now recall myself being strucken with God's heavy hand; so must every one that will be purged from his sins and sanctified pray to thee, when he is afflicted.\f* \f + \fr 31:6 \ft Though calamities be marvelous great like to a deluge:\f* \f + \fr 31:6 \ft yet they shall not oppress him, that relieth upon God.\f*
\v 7 Thou art my refuge from tribulation, which hath compassed me: my exultation, deliver me from them that compass me.
\v 8 I will give thee understanding, and will instruct thee in the way, that thou shalt go: I will fasten mine eyes upon thee. \f + \fr 31:8 \ft God speaketh, promising by these tribulations to give his servants understanding, and instruction:\f*
\v 9 Do not become as horse and mule, which have no understanding. In bit and bridle bind fast their cheeks that approach not to thee. \f + \fr 31:9 \ft Be not therefore careless, like to brute beasts, but considerative of your actions.\f* \f + \fr 31:9 \ft The Prophet or any just soul beseeching God to hold this strait hand of discipline over sinners, for their conversion.\f*
\v 10 Many are the scourges of a sinner, but him that hopeth in our Lord mercy shall compass. \f + \fr 31:10 \ft Sinners deserve much punishment.\f* \f + \fr 31:10 \ft But repenting, and trusting in God shall find his mercy.\f*
\v 11 Be joyful in our Lord and rejoice ye just, and glory all ye right of heart. \f + \fr 31:11 \ft The end of true penance is joy, to which therefore the Prophet inviteth all penitents.\f*
\c 32
\p
\v 1 The Psalm of David. Rejoice ye just in our Lord; praising becometh the righteous. \f + \fr 32:1 \ft Not in yourselves.\f* \f + \fr 32:1 \ft Praise is not comely in the mouth of a sinner. Eccli. 15.\f*
\v 2 Confess ye to our Lord on the harp: on a psalter of ten strings sing to him. \f + \fr 32:2 \ft In mortification, offering your bodies a living host, Rom. 12.\f* \f + \fr 32:2 \ft Of this instrument this book is called the Psalter: and it signifieth the observation of the ten commandments, without which no praise pleaseth God.\f*
\v 3 Sing ye to him a new song: sing well to him in jubilation. \f + \fr 32:3 \ft Praising God for the grace of Christ in the new testament.\f*
\v 4 Because the word of our Lord is right, and all his works are in faith. \f + \fr 32:4 \ft God's rules and precepts are most just and right.\f* \f + \fr 32:4 \ft He performeth whatsoever he promiseth.\f*
\v 5 He loveth mercy and judgment: the earth is full of the mercy of our Lord. \f + \fr 32:5 \ft God ever joineth these virtues together.\f*
\v 6 By the word of our Lord the heavens are established: and by the spirit of his mouth all the power of them, \f + \fr 32:6 \ft God's word is omnipotent.\f*
\v 7 Gathering together the waters of the sea, as it were in a bottle: putting the depths in treasures. \f + \fr 32:7 \ft Unknown, as riches hid in secret places.\f*
\v 8 Let all the earth fear our Lord: and let all the inhabitants of the world be moved at him.
\v 9 Because he said, and they were made: he commanded and they were created,
\v 10 Our Lord dissipateth the counsels of nations: and he reproveth the cogitations of people, and he reproveth the counsels of princes. \f + \fr 32:10 \ft As in Babylon he confounded their tongues.\f*
\v 11 But the counsel of our Lord abideth for ever, the cogitations of his heart in generation and generation. \f + \fr 32:11 \ft His absolute will is always fulfilled.\f*
\v 12 Blessed is the nation, whose God is our Lord: the people whom he hath chosen for his inheritance. \f + \fr 32:12 \ft The people of Israel in the old testament: and Christians of all nations in the new.\f*
\v 13 Our Lord hath looked from heaven: he hath seen all the children of men. \f + \fr 32:13 \ft God's perpetual providence.\f*
\v 14 From his prepared habitation he hath looked upon all that inhabit the earth
\v 15 Who made their hearts severally: who understandeth all their works. \f + \fr 32:15 \ft God's wisdom infinite.\f*
\v 16 The king is not saved by much power: and the giant shall not be saved in the multitude of his strength. \f + \fr 32:16 \ft No power in earth is of any force without God.\f*
\v 17 The horse faileth to safety, and in the aboundance of his force he shall not be saved. \f + \fr 32:17 \ft Of his master\f* \f + \fr 32:17 \ft or of himself.\f*
\v 18 Behold the eyes of our Lord be upon them that fear him: and on them, that hope upon his mercy.
\v 19 That he may deliver their souls from death: and nourish them in famine.
\v 20 Our soul expecteth our Lord: because he is our helper and protector.
\v 21 Because in him our heart shall rejoice: and we have trusted in his holy name.
\v 22 Let thy mercy, o Lord, be made upon us, as we have hoped in thee. \f + \fr 32:22 \ft O God which hast all perfection, shew thy mercy in protecting & saving all that trust in thee.\f*
\c 33
\p
\v 1 To David, when he changed his countenance before Abimelech, and he dismist him, and he went away \f + \fr 33:1 \ft His proper name was Achis, 1. Reg. 21. but all Kings of Palestina were called Abimelech, as Pharao in Ægypt, Nabuchodonosor in Babylon.\f* \f + \fr 33:1 \ft This Psalm is also composed in order of the Alphabet.\f* \f + \fr 33:1 \ft (1. Reg. 21)\f*
\v 2 I will bless our Lord at all time: his praise always in my mouth. \f + \fr 33:2 \ft Ipraise God\f* \f + \fr 33:2 \ft both in prosperity and adversity.\f*
\v 3 In our Lord my soul shall be praised: let the mild hear, and rejoice. \f + \fr 33:3 \ft When I serve our Lord, my soul shall be praised in his service.\f*
\v 4 Magnify ye our Lord with me: and let us exalt his name for ever.
\v 5 I have sought out our Lord, and he hath heard me: and from all my tribulations he hath delivered me.
\v 6 Come ye to him, and be illuminated: and your faces shall not be confounded.
\v 7 This poor man hath cried, and our Lord hath heard him: and from all his tribulations he hath saved him. \f + \fr 33:7 \ft Every man, be he how poor soever, when he prayeth shall be heard.\f*
\v 8 The Angel of our Lord shall put in himself about them that fear him: and shall deliver them. \f + \fr 33:8 \ft The proper Guardian Angel of every one.\f*
\v 9 Taste ye, and see that our Lord is sweet: blessed is the man, that hopeth in him.
\v 10 Fear ye our Lord all ye his Saints: because there is no lack to them that fear him. \f + \fr 33:10 \ft With filial fear.\f*
\v 11 The rich have wanted, and have been hungry: but they that seek after our Lord shall not be diminished of any good. \f + \fr 33:11 \ft The rich of this world setting their mind upon their wealth, are poor in spiritual gifts.\f*
\v 12 Come children, hear me: I will teach you the fear of our Lord.
\v 13 who is the man that will have life: loveth to see good days? \f + \fr 33:13 \ft Every one desireth to be happy, but he indeed shall be happy, that flyeth from evil, and doth good.\f*
\v 14 Stay thy tongue from evil: and thy lips that they speak not guile.
\v 15 Turn away from evil, and do good: seek after peace and pursue it.
\v 16 The eyes of our Lord upon the just: and his ears unto their prayers.
\v 17 But the countenance of our Lord is upon them that do evil things: to destroy their memory out of the earth. \f + \fr 33:17 \ft God seeing all men's actions & intentions, will render as they deserve.\f*
\v 18 The just have cried, and our Lord hath heard them: and out of all their tribulations he hath delivered them.
\v 19 Our Lord is nigh to them, that are of a contrite heart: and the humble of spirit he will save.
\v 20 Many are the tribulations of the just: and out of all these our Lord will deliver them.
\v 21 Our Lord keepeth all their bones: there shall not one of them be broken. \f + \fr 33:21 \ft Though the just seem for a time to be forsaken, yet God that giveth them internal strength, will at last reward and crown in them his own gifts.\f*
\v 22 The death of sinners is very ill: and they that hate the just shall offend. \f + \fr 33:22 \ft For their sin they are suffered to fall into more sin.\f*
\v 23 Our Lord will redeem the souls of his servants: and all that hope in him shall not offend. \f + \fr 33:23 \ft Contrarywise those that accept of his grace, shall finally not offend.\f*
\c 34
\p
\v 1 To David himself. Judge o Lord them that hurt me: overthrow them that impugn me. \f + \fr 34:1 \ft David signifieth beloved, desirable, or strong of hand, that is Christ, above all beloved of God, desired of man, the strong conqueror of death and hell. S. Aug. in hunc locum.\f* \f + \fr 34:1 \ft By way of imprecation he prophesieth that God will overthrow the persecutors of Christ, and of Christians.\f*
\v 2 Take armour and shield: and rise up to help me. \f + \fr 34:2 \ft Offensive\f* \f + \fr 34:2 \ft Defensive.\f*
\v 3 Bring forth the sword, and shut up against them, that persecute me: say to my soul: I am thy salvation. \f + \fr 34:3 \ft Preoccupate and prevent the malice of the persecutor.\f*
\v 4 Let them be confounded & ashamed, that seek my soul. Let them be turned backward, and be confounded that think evil against me. \f + \fr 34:4 \ft Such a punishment and confusion shall fall in the end upon all the malicious, after that the just shall have overcome tribulations.\f*
\v 5 Be they made as dust before the face of wind; and the Angel of our Lord straitening them.
\v 6 Let their way be made darkness and slipperness: and the Angel of our Lord pursuing them.
\v 7 Because they have hid the destruction of their snare for me without cause: in vain have they upbraided my soul.
\v 8 Let the snare which he knoweth not, come on him; and the net, which he hath hid, catch him: and let him fall into the very same snare.
\v 9 But my soul shall rejoice in our Lord: and shall be delighted upon his salvation. \f + \fr 34:9 \ft In the time of trouble in hope,\f* \f + \fr 34:9 \ft after delivery, in eternal salvation.\f*
\v 10 All my bones shall say: Lord, who is like to thee? Delivering the needy from the hand of them that are stronger than he: the needy and poor from them that spoil him.
\v 11 Unjust witnesses rising up, asked me things that I knew not. \f + \fr 34:11 \ft Such false witnesses did rise against Christ. Mat. 26.\f* \f + \fr 34:11 \ft Things that were not; for God himself that knoweth all things, knoweth not that which neither was, is, nor can be.\f*
\v 12 They repayed me evil things for good, sterility to my soul. \f + \fr 34:12 \ft They made privation of my life: verified in Christ, not in David, for he was killed by his enemies.\f*
\v 13 But I when they were troublesome to me, did put on cloth of hair. I humbled my soul in fasting: and my prayer shall be turned into my bosom. \f + \fr 34:13 \ft All our Saviour's life was penance for others, needing none for himself.\f*
\v 14 As a neighbour, as our brother, so did I please: as mourning and sorrowful so was I humbled. \f + \fr 34:14 \ft Christ the good Samaritane, that relieved the wounded man. Luc. 10.\f*
\v 15 And they rejoiced against me, and came together: scourges were gathered together upon me, and I was ignorant. \f + \fr 34:15 \ft See previous note\f* \f + \fr 34:15 \ft See previous note\f* \f + \fr 34:15 \ft Our Lord knoweth not any just cause, why the Jews so persecuted him, for they had no just cause but mere malice.\f*
\v 16 They were dissipated, and not compunct, they tempted me, they scorned me with scorning: they gnashed upon me with their teeth.
\v 17 Lord when wilt thou regard? Restore thou my soul from their malignity, mine only one from the lions. \f + \fr 34:17 \ft As Psal. 21. and Mat. 27. God why has thou forsaken me? Not delivered me from temporal death, not yielded me such consolation, as thou gavest other Saints in their agonies?\f* \f + \fr 34:17 \ft A Prophecy of Christ's resurrection.\f*
\v 18 I will confess to thee in the great Church, in a grave people I will praise thee. \f + \fr 34:18 \ft Prophecy of the Catholic Church. as Psal. 21.\f*
\v 19 Let them not rejoice over me that are my adversaries unjustly: that hate me without cause, and twinkle with the eyes. \f + \fr 34:19 \ft This place is applied by our Saviour to himself. Ioan. 13.\f*
\v 20 Because they spake indeed peaceably to me: and in the anger of the earth speaking they meant guiles. \f + \fr 34:20 \ft The Pharisees and Herodians said: Master we know that thou art a true speaker &c. meaning to entrap him with treason. Mat. 22.\f*
\v 21 And they opened their mouth awide upon me: they said, Well, well, our eyes have seen. \f + \fr 34:21 \ft The same Pharisees and Priests judged him worthy of death, and procured the people to cry: Crucify him, crucify him.\f*
\v 22 Thou hast seen, o Lord, keep not silence: Lord depart not from me. \f + \fr 34:22 \ft Again his Resurrection is prophesied.\f*
\v 23 Arise and attend to my judgment: my God, and my Lord unto my cause.
\v 24 Judge me according to thy justice, o Lord my God, and let them not rejoice over me.
\v 25 Let them not say in their hearts: Well, well, to our soul: neither let them say, We have devoured him.
\v 26 Let them blush and be ashamed together, that rejoice at my evils. Let them be clothed with confusion and shame, that speak great things upon me. \f + \fr 34:26 \ft At the day of judgement the wicked shall receive sentence of damnation.\f*
\v 27 Let them rejoice and be glad, that will my justice: and let them say always: Our Lord be magnified, that will the peace of his servant. \f + \fr 34:27 \ft The Blessed in eternal glory.\f*
\v 28 And my tongue shall meditate thy justice, thy praise all the day.
\c 35
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, to the servant of our Lord David himself. \f + \fr 35:1 \ft More specially describing the state of men in the new testament, than in the old.\f* \f + \fr 35:1 \ft Instruction for David, not as a King, or a Prophet, but as the poor servant of God.\f*
\v 2 The unjust hath said within himself, that he would sin: there is no fear of God before his eyes. \f + \fr 35:2 \ft Wittingly and resolutely preferring wicked life before virtuous.\f*
\v 3 Because he hath done deceitfully in his sight: that his iniquity may be found unto hatred. \f + \fr 35:3 \ft God so hateth sin committed of mere malice that he commonly rejecteth such sinners, and more often offereth new grace to those, that sin of frailty or ignorance.\f*
\v 4 The words of his mouth are iniquity, and guile: he would not understand that he might do well. \f + \fr 35:4 \ft Some ignorance is invincible, when one hath a good will to learn, doing his endeavour to know the truth in doctrine, & his duty in manners, but cannot get knowledge thereof, and then he is excused before God, though he err in opinion, or in fact: others are negligent to learn, and their error is gross ignorance, and is a sin, greater or less, according to the importance of the thing, which they ought to know. Others, are more willful, desiring to be ignorant: that they may sin with the less remorse, or repining of their own conscience, and this is affected ignorance, and most heinous and odious sin. For which God often leaving them destitute of ordinary grace, which he giveth to others, they fall into reprobate sense, and into more horrible sins.\f*
\v 5 He hath meditated iniquity in his bed: he hath set himself on every way not good, and malice he hath not hated.
\v 6 Lord thy mercy is in heaven: and thy truth even to the clouds. \f + \fr 35:6 \ft God doth not utterly shut up his mercy from the most willful & wicked sinners, but giveth them sometimes good motions, and sufficient help, that they may repent, be justified, & saved, if they do not wittingly harden their own hearts, and still willfully repel God's grace.\f* \f + \fr 35:6 \ft For so God promiseth (who is most faithful) that he will forgive sinners, and receive them into his favour again, whensoever they resolving to serve him, repent and cease to sin.\f*
\v 7 Thy justice as the hills of God: thy judgments are great depth. Men & beasts thou wilt save, o Lord, \f + \fr 35:7 \ft Thou, o God, that hast care of all creatures, not only of men but also of brute beasts, art ever ready of thy part to save both moderate men, in whom the light of reason remaineth, and also gross senseless persons, which are become brutish like horse and mule or other beasts.\f*
\v 8 as thou hast multiplied thy mercy, o God. But the children of men shall hope in the covert of thy wings. \f + \fr 35:8 \ft For so our Lord multiplieth his mercy.\f* \f + \fr 35:8 \ft Yet with condition that senseless or brutish men, must become reasonable men, the children of men, not colts, whelps, pigs &c.\f* \f + \fr 35:8 \ft Sinners thus converted shall not only have all necessaries in this life, as all living creatures have in this world, but also shall hope of spiritual, heavenly, & eternal glory prepared for Angels, and children of men: as in the verses following.\f*
\v 9 They shall be inebriated with the plenty of thy house: and with the torrent of thy pleasure thou shalt make them drink.
\v 10 Because with thee is the fountain of life: and in thy light we shall see light.
\v 11 Extend thy mercy to them that know thee, and thy justice to them, that are of a right heart.
\v 12 Let not the foot of pride come to me: and let not the hand of a sinner move me. \f + \fr 35:12 \ft Lest any impediment hinder the obtaining and possession of eternal reward, the just must specially pray not to be infected with pride:\f* \f + \fr 35:12 \ft nor be overcome by the forcible tentations of other sinners, by persuasion, nor evil example.\f*
\v 13 There have they fallen that work iniquity: they were expelled, neither could they stand. \f + \fr 35:13 \ft The first sin, to wit of devils, was pride, and man's sin was by persuasion of the devil.\f* \f + \fr 35:13 \ft Neither of which could escape punishment.\f*
\c 36
\p
\v 1 A Psalm to David himself. Have no emulation toward the malignant: neither envy them that do iniquity. \f + \fr 36:1 \ft For David's and every just man's instruction.\f* \f + \fr 36:1 \ft Neither be thou offended that the wicked do prosper in this world, nor imitate them that thou mayst also prosper.\f*
\v 2 Because they shall quickly wither as grass: and as the blossoms of herbs they shall soon fall. \f + \fr 36:2 \ft For all this life & consequently the prosperity thereof is short, and uncertain.\f*
\v 3 Hope in our Lord and do good: and inhabit the land, and thou shalt be fed in the riches thereof. \f + \fr 36:3 \ft Put thy trust in God, living content in this world:\f* \f + \fr 36:3 \ft & he will give thee that is necessary.\f*
\v 4 Be delighted in our Lord: & he will give thee the petitions of thy heart.
\v 5 Reveal thy way to our Lord, and hope in him: and he will do it. \f + \fr 36:5 \ft Commend all thine affairs to God.\f*
\v 6 And he will bring forth thy justice as light: and thy judgment as midday: \f + \fr 36:6 \ft Partly making virtue appear to the comfort of the virtuous, and example of others in this life, but especially in the next world.\f*
\v 7 Be subject to our Lord, and pray him. Have no emulation in him, that prospereth in his way: in a man that doth injustices.
\v 8 Cease from wrath, and leave fury: have not emulation that thou be malignant.
\v 9 Because they that are malignant, shall be cast out: but they that expect our Lord, the same shall inherit the land. \f + \fr 36:9 \ft The land of the living.\f*
\v 10 And yet a little while, and the sinner shall not be: and thou shalt seek his place, and shall not find it.
\v 11 But the meek shall inherit the land, and shall be delighted in multitude of peace.
\v 12 The sinner shall observe the just: & shall gnash upon him with his teeth.
\v 13 But our Lord shall scorn him: because he foreseeth that his day shall come.
\v 14 Sinners have drawn out the sword: they have bent their bow; That they may deceive the poor and needy: that they may murder the right of heart.
\v 15 Let their own swords enter into their hearts: and let their bow be broken. \f + \fr 36:15 \ft By way of imprecation (as in many other places) the Prophet foresheweth that wicked men shall fall into the evils, which they prepare for others.\f*
\v 16 Better is a little to the just, above much riches of sinners.
\v 17 Because the arms of sinners shall be broken in pieces: but our Lord confirmeth the just.
\v 18 Our Lord knoweth the days of the immaculate: and their inheritance shall be for ever.
\v 19 They shall not be confounded in the evil time, and in the days of famine they shall be filled:
\v 20 because the sinners shall perish. But the enemies of our Lord forthwith as they shall be honoured and exalted, vanishing shall vanish as smoke.
\v 21 The sinner shall borrow, and not pay: but the just is merciful and will give.
\v 22 Because they that bless him shall inherit the land: but they that curse him shall perish.
\v 23 With our Lord the step of man shall be directed: and he shall like well of his way.
\v 24 When he shall fall, he shall not be bruised: because our Lord putteth his hand under. \f + \fr 36:24 \ft Though the just fall of frailty or ignorance into venial sin, yet God's grace shall stay him that he fall not into mortal. The just falleth seven times in the day, & riseth. Prov. 24.\f*
\v 25 I have been young, for I am old: and I have not seen the just forsaken, nor his seed seeking bread. \f + \fr 36:25 \ft So King David observed: and it very rarely happeneth, that the just or their children are destitute of necessary sustenance in this world\f*
\v 26 All the day he is merciful and lendeth: & his seed shall be in blessing.
\v 27 Decline from evil, & do good: and inhabit for ever & ever. \f + \fr 36:27 \ft In these two principles, Declining from evil and Doing good, true justice consisteth.\f* \f + \fr 36:27 \ft And he that finally observeth these two points, meriteth and shall possess heaven.\f*
\v 28 Because our Lord loveth judgment, and he will not forsake his saints: they shall be preserved for ever. The unjust shall be punished: and the seed of the impious shall perish.
\v 29 But the just shall inherit the land: and shall inhabit for ever and ever upon it.
\v 30 The mouth of the just shall meditate wisdom, and his tongue shall speak judgment.
\v 31 The law of his God in his heart: and his steps shall not be supplanted.
\v 32 The sinner considereth the just: and seeketh to murder him. \f + \fr 36:32 \ft To draw him to mortal sin, which is death of the soul.\f*
\v 33 But our Lord will not leave him in his hands: neither will he condemn him, when judgment shall be given of him.
\v 34 Expect our Lord, and keep his way: and he will exalt thee, that thou mayst inherit the land: when the sinners shall perish thou shalt see.
\v 35 I have seen the impious highly exalted, and advance as the cedars of Libanus.
\v 36 And I passed by, and behold he was not: and I sought him, and his place was not found.
\v 37 Keep innocency, and see equity: because there are remains for the peaceable man. \f + \fr 36:37 \ft Rewards.\f*
\v 38 But the unjust shall perish together: the remains of the impious shall perish.
\v 39 But the salvation of the just is of our Lord: and he is their protector in the time of tribulation. \f + \fr 36:39 \ft Man's justice and well doing is not of his own power but of God's grace.\f*
\v 40 And our Lord will help them, and deliver them: and he will take them away from sinners, and save them, because they have hoped in him.
\c 37
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of David, in recordation of the sabbath. \f + \fr 37:1 \ft In remembrance that by sin we lost the rest and peace, which man had in the state of innocency; secondly we lost the peace of conscience; thirdly the rest and peace of eternal felicity.\f*
\v 2 Lord rebuke me not in thy fury: nor chastise me in wrath. \f + \fr 37:2 \ft Condemn me not to eternal pain:\f* \f + \fr 37:2 \ft nor punish me in purgatory fire; but purge me so in this life, that the purging fire be not needful. By which fire (saith S. Aug.) though some shall be saved (gravior tamen erit ille ignis, quam quicquid potest homo pati in hac vita) yet that fire shall be more grievous, than whatsoever a man can suffer in this life. S. Gregory also expoundeth this same place, as if David said thus: I know it will come to pass, that after the end of this life, some shall be cleansed by purging flames, some shall be under the sentence of eternal damnation. But because I do esteem that transitory fire more intolerable than all present tribulation, I desire not only not to be\f*
\v 3 Because thy arrows are fast sticked in me: and thou hast fastened thy hand upon me. \f + \fr 37:3 \ft Afflictions of mind and body sent by thy just judgment.\f* \f + \fr 37:3 \ft Thou hast struck me with an heavy hand.\f*
\v 4 There is no health in my flesh at the face of thy wrath: my bones have no peace at the face of my sins. \f + \fr 37:4 \ft Ialready feel in my flesh, in all my bones, and powers, great affliction,\f* \f + \fr 37:4 \ft considering thy justice\f* \f + \fr 37:4 \ft and my sins.\f*
\v 5 Because mine iniquities are gone over my head: and as a heavy burden are become heavy upon me. \f + \fr 37:5 \ft Which are exceedingly increased, almost overwhelming my spirit.\f* \f + \fr 37:5 \ft Sins not washed away by penance by their weight carry the soul into more and more wickedness.\f*
\v 6 My scars are putrefied and corrupted, because of my foolishness. \f + \fr 37:6 \ft Still corrupting those parts which were whole before, as a pestered sore that is not cured.\f*
\v 7 I am become miserable, and am made crooked even to the end: I went sorrowful all the day. \f + \fr 37:7 \ft Not able to go straight to do any good work, being guilty of grievous sin.\f*
\v 8 Because my loins are filled with illusions: and there is no health in my flesh. \f + \fr 37:8 \ft Concupiscence striving in me.\f*
\v 9 I am afflicted and am humbled exceedingly: I roared for the groaning of my heart. \f + \fr 37:9 \ft From the sorrow of my heart my voice hath broken out into clamour.\f*
\v 10 Lord before thee is all my desire: and my groaning is not hid from thee. \f + \fr 37:10 \ft O God thou knowest my desire, to be restored to thy favour.\f*
\v 11 My heart is troubled, my strength hath forsaken me: and the light of mine eyes, and the same is not with me.
\v 12 My friends, and my neighbours have approached, & stood against me. And they that were near me, stood far off: \f + \fr 37:12 \ft Those that were my friends and companions in sin are become mine enemies, because I forsake them.\f*
\v 13 and they did violence which sought my soul. And they that sought me evils spake vanities: and meditated guiles all the day. \f + \fr 37:13 \ft Sought by all means to entangle me again.\f*
\v 14 But I as one deaf did not hear: and as one dumb not opening his mouth. \f + \fr 37:14 \ft Inow renounce all sin.\f*
\v 15 And I became as a man not hearing: and not having reproofs in his mouth.
\v 16 Because in thee, o Lord have I hoped, thou wilt hear me, o Lord my God. \f + \fr 37:16 \ft Inow rely upon thee, o God.\f*
\v 17 Because I said: Lest sometime mine enemies rejoice over me, and whilst my feet are moved, they spake great things upon me. \f + \fr 37:17 \ft For this cause I am returned to thee and do pray that mine enemies may not prevail against me.\f*
\v 18 Because I am ready for scourges: and my sorrow is in my sight always: \f + \fr 37:18 \ft Iresign myself to thee.\f*
\v 19 Because I will declare my iniquity: and I will think for my sin. \f + \fr 37:19 \ft Though thou knowest all, yet with mouth confession is made to salvation.\f* \f + \fr 37:19 \ft And I meditate of that which my sin hath deserved.\f*
\v 20 But mine enemies live, and are confirmed over me: and they are multiplied that hate me unjustly.
\v 21 They that repay evil things for good, detracted from me: because I followed goodness. \f + \fr 37:21 \ft One kind of detraction is in revealing secret faults, another in feigning and imputing false crimes, the third (here mentioned) in calling virtue vice, as penance hypocrisy.\f*
\v 22 Forsake me not, o Lord my God, depart not from me. \f + \fr 37:22 \ft Grant me Lord final perseverance in thy grace and service.\f*
\v 23 Attend unto my help, o Lord the God of my salvation.
\c 38
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, to Idithun himself, a canticle of David. \f + \fr 38:1 \ft Some expound this Psalm of the Jews in captivity in Babylon, but this title, and the matter contained shew, that it rather pertaineth to the new Testament.\f* \f + \fr 38:1 \ft To be sung by Idithun and his scholars & successors, or rather by Christians.\f*
\v 2 I have said: I will keep my ways, that I offend not in my tongue. I have set a guard to my mouth, when the sinner stood against me. \f + \fr 38:2 \ft Weak men in affliction, not able to deliver themselves, seek revenge, by murmuring and other evil speeches, but the perfect resolve to rule their tongues:\f*
\v 3 I was dumb and humbled, and kept silence from good things: and my sorrow was renewed. \f + \fr 38:3 \ft Even to forbear sometimes from their own just defence:\f* \f + \fr 38:3 \ft though thereby they endure more persecution.\f*
\v 4 My heart waxed hot within me: & in my meditation a fire shall burn. \f + \fr 38:4 \ft Sorrow suppressed maketh the heart to burn with zeal and indignation.\f*
\v 5 I have spoken in my tongue: Lord make mine end known to me. And the number of my days what it is: that I may know what is lacking to me. \f + \fr 38:5 \ft If it may please thee, let me know how long I shall live, desiring to die; as Elias desired. 3. Reg. 19.\f*
\v 6 Behold thou hast put my days measurable, and my substance is as nothing before thee. Doubtless all things are vanity, every man living. \f + \fr 38:6 \ft My life and all that I have is as nothing compared to thy eternity.\f*
\v 7 Surely man passeth as an image, yea and he is troubled in vain. He gathereth treasure, and knoweth not to whom he shall gather them. \f + \fr 38:7 \ft As a shadow or image appearing in a glass, which is quickly forgot.\f* \f + \fr 38:7 \ft Therefore there is no cause man should be troubled in mind for temporal miseries.\f*
\v 8 And now what is my expectation? Is not our Lord? And my substance is with thee.
\v 9 From all mine iniquities deliver me: a reproach to the foolish thou hast given me. \f + \fr 38:9 \ft Thou hast suffered me to be reproached by the foolish that prosper in this world.\f*
\v 10 I was dumb, and opened not my mouth, because thou didst it: \f + \fr 38:10 \ft Iknow my tribulation is by thy providence.\f*
\v 11 Remove thy scourges from me.
\v 12 By the strength of thy hand I have fainted in reprehensions, for iniquity thou hast chastised man. And thou hast made his soul pine away as a spider: but vainly is every man troubled. \f + \fr 38:12 \ft My life decayeth as a spider having spent all her moisture.\f*
\v 13 Hear my prayer, o Lord, and my petition; with thine ears receive my tears. Keep not silence: because I am a stranger with thee, and a pilgrim, as my fathers. \f + \fr 38:13 \ft All men are strangers in this life, heaven being our home.\f*
\v 14 Forgive me, that I may be refreshed before I depart: and shall be no more. \f + \fr 38:14 \ft That I may recover spiritual strength in this life:\f* \f + \fr 38:14 \ft after which I shall not be in state to do free works of satisfaction nor merit.\f*
\c 39
\p
\v 0 Redemption of mankind, and to denounce the same in \add the whole world: 12. prayeth for his servants, undertaking to satisfy for their sins.\add* \f + \fr 39:0 \ft Christ's coming and redeeming of mankind. The 5. key.\f*
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm to David himself. \f + \fr 39:1 \ft Pertaining unto the new Testament.\f*
\v 2 Expecting I expected our Lord, and he hath attended to me. \f + \fr 39:2 \ft The faithful of the old and new Testament rejoice in the coming of Christ.\f*
\v 3 And he heard my prayers, and brought me out of the lake of misery, and from the mire of dregs. And hath set my feet upon a rock: and hath directed my steps.
\v 4 And he hath put a new canticle into my mouth: a song to our God. Many shall see, and shall fear: and they shall hope in our Lord.
\v 5 Blessed is the man, whose hope is in the name of our Lord: and hath not had regard to vanities and false madness.
\v 6 Thou hast done many thy marvelous things, o Lord my God: & in thy cogitations there is none that may be like to thee. I have declared and have spoken: they multiplied above number. \f + \fr 39:6 \ft Christ by himself and by others preached the Gospel of salvation.\f* \f + \fr 39:6 \ft The multiplication of Christians thereby.\f*
\v 7 Sacrifice and oblation thou wouldest not: but ears thou hast perfited to me. Holocaust and for sin thou didst not require: \f + \fr 39:7 \ft No sacrifice of the old testament sufficed to satisfy God's justice for the sin of man.\f* \f + \fr 39:7 \ft Christ by the ear of obedience performed the redemption of man by his death, as was determined from eternity. S. Paul for (ears) saith (body). See Annotations Heb. 10.\f*
\v 8 then said I, Behold I come. In the head of the book it is written of me, \f + \fr 39:8 \ft The sum of holy Scripture is of Christ's Incarnation & death for redemption of man.\f*
\v 9 that I should do thy will: my God I would, and thy law in the midst of my heart.
\v 10 I have declared thy justice in the great Church, lo I will not stay my lips: Lord thou hast known it. \f + \fr 39:10 \ft Again Christ inculcateth the preaching and receiving of his Gospel in the whole world.\f*
\v 11 Thy justice I have not hid in my heart: thy truth and thy salvation I have spoken. I have not hid thy mercy, and thy truth from the great Council. \f + \fr 39:11 \ft In the greatest and wisest congregations of this world, Christ concealeth not his mercy and truth. So himself professed before Annas, Caiphas, Pilate, and their counsels. Saint Paul preached Christ at Athens, and in many nations, and so the other Apostles. For their voice went into all the coasts of the earth.\f*
\v 12 But thou, o Lord, make not thy commiserations far from me: thy mercy, and thy truth have always received me. \f + \fr 39:12 \ft The Prophet now speaketh in the name of Christ's mystical body the Church: praying to be made partaker of mercy, and to be delivered from evils.\f*
\v 13 Because evils have compassed me, which have no number: mine iniquities have overtaken me, & I was not able to see. They are multiplied above the hairs of my head: and my heart hath forsaken me. \f + \fr 39:13 \ft The sins also of those which believe in Christ are so many, that they cannot be fully seen in particular.\f* \f + \fr 39:13 \ft Ialmost faint in considering so many and so great iniquities amongst those that profess Christ.\f*
\v 14 It may please thee, o Lord, to deliver me: Lord have respect to help me. \f + \fr 39:14 \ft The whole Church prayeth in the name of all for the infirm members.\f*
\v 15 Let them be confounded and ashamed together, that seek my soul to take it away. Let them be turned backward, and be ashamed that will me evils. \f + \fr 39:15 \ft The Prophet foresheweth that the reprobate for their obstinate malice, seeking to hurt others shall be confounded.\f*
\v 16 Let them forthwith receive their confusion, that say to me: Well, well. \f + \fr 39:16 \ft That scornfully say: Well, well: wishing all evil to good men.\f*
\v 17 Let all that seek thee rejoice and be glad upon thee: and let them that love thy salvation, say always: Our Lord be magnified: \f + \fr 39:17 \ft Which not only in mouth and outward profession, but also in sincerity of heart seek thee, may with confidence rejoice, and praise God.\f*
\v 18 But I am a beggar, and poor: Our Lord is careful to me. Thou art my helper, & my protector: my God be not slack. \f + \fr 39:18 \ft Christ speaketh in the name of sinners truly repenting, whose sins he undertaketh to redeem, and wash away by his passion.\f* \f + \fr 39:18 \ft The faithful of the old testament pray for Christ's first coming into this world, & the faithful now pray for his second coming to purge his Church, and to reward the good.\f*
\c 40
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm to David himself. \f + \fr 40:1 \ft Pertaining to the new testament, as appeareth by the 10. verse alleged by our Saviour.\f*
\v 2 Blessed is the man that understandeth concerning the needy, and the poor: in the evil day our Lord will deliver him. \f + \fr 40:2 \ft He is happy that is not scandalized in Christ (Luc. 7. v. 23.) coming in poverty, & suffering extreme afflictions.\f* \f + \fr 40:2 \ft He that trusteth in Christ, notwithstanding the contrary motives of his worldly misery, shall be delivered by him in all distress.\f*
\v 3 Our Lord preserve him, and give him life, and make him blessed in the land: and deliver him not unto the will of his enemies. \f + \fr 40:3 \ft Our Lord will give to such servants more grace in this life, and glory in the next.\f* \f + \fr 40:3 \ft Not suffer him to be overcome in tentations.\f*
\v 4 Our Lord help him upon the bed of his sorrow: thou hast turned all his couch in his infirmity. \f + \fr 40:4 \ft When such constant servants are sick to death, Christ will most especially comfort and help them.\f*
\v 5 Isaid: Lord have mercy on me: heal my soul, because I have sinned to thee. \f + \fr 40:5 \ft Christ in the behalf of his mystical body confesseth their sins, and prayeth for them.\f*
\v 6 Mine enemies have spoken evils to me: When shall he die and his name perish? \f + \fr 40:6 \ft After death suffered for mankind, Christ riseth, and his name and kingdom is glorious.\f*
\v 7 And if he came in to see, he spake vain things: his heart hath gathered together iniquity to himself. He went forth, and spake together. \f + \fr 40:7 \ft Those that came not of good will, but of malice to observe Christ's deeds and words, carped at both, sometimes saying, he taught against the law, and against Moyses; sometimes that he cast out devils in the power of Beelzebub.\f*
\v 8 All mine enemies whispered against me: they did think evils to me.
\v 9 They have determined an unjust word against me: shall not he that sleepeth add to rise again? \f + \fr 40:9 \ft At last they resolved that he should die.\f* \f + \fr 40:9 \ft But they could not so suppress his power, for he rose again in glory.\f*
\v 10 For the man also of my peace, in whom I hoped: who did eat my breads, hath greatly trodden me under-foot. \f + \fr 40:10 \ft By our Saviour's application of this verse, it is certain that the traitor Judas is here described. Ioa. 13. v. 18.\f*
\v 11 But thou, o Lord, have mercy upon me, and raise me up again: and I will repay them. \f + \fr 40:11 \ft In the day of judgement Christ Judge of all will render to every one as they deserve.\f*
\v 12 In this I have known that thou wouldest me: because mine enemy shall not rejoice over me.
\v 13 But me thou hast received because of innocency: and thou hast confirmed me in thy sight for ever. \f + \fr 40:13 \ft As before in respect of sinners, Christ Judge of all will render to every one: so here in his own person he avoucheth his own innocency, which made him apt to satisfy for others.\f*
\v 14 Blessed be our Lord the God of Israel from the beginning of the world, and for evermore: Be it, be it. \f + \fr 40:14 \ft For this mercy of Almighty God in saving the elect by his Son's death he is to be praised for ever eternally.\f* \f + \fr 40:14 \ft All the Blessed agree in this, that God is eternally to be praised and thereto say Amen, So be it, so be it. Some divide the Psalms into five books, supposing the first book to end here with these words, Be it, be it: not observing that the last Psalm hath not this ending. S. Jerom confuteth this opinion by our Saviour's and S. Peter's naming it the book, not books of Psalms. Luc. 20. v. 42. Act. 1. Moreover if this were the end of one book, then the Psalm following should not be called the 41. Psalm but the first Psalm of the second book.\f*
\c 41
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, understanding to the sons of Core. \f + \fr 41:1 \ft The sons of Core repented, and departed from their father's schism, and so escaped miraculously the horrible pit of damnation, into which their father and his complices fell. Num. 26. v. 10. By which example all seduced and deceived Christians are admonished, not to persist in schism or other sins. And worldly men, ambitious of honour be warned to desire & seek God above all things, first of all the kingdom of heaven (to be living members of the Catholic Church) and the justice thereof: to seek things which are above, not which are upon the earth; lest hell devour them, as it devoured the complices of Core. Num. 16. v. 31.\f*
\v 2 Even as the hart desireth after the fountains of waters: so doth my soul desire after thee, o God. \f + \fr 41:2 \ft Ahart waxing old, and burdened with much hair, and great horns, draweth a serpent into his nostrils: so being infected with poison, desireth most ardently to drink, and afterwards casteth his horns, and hair, and becometh as it were young again.\f* \f + \fr 41:2 \ft With such fervent desire a true penitent, feeling himself infected with poison of sins, seeketh the water of God's grace.\f*
\v 3 My soul hath thirsted after God the strong living: when shall I come and appear before the face of God? \f + \fr 41:3 \ft See previous note\f* \f + \fr 41:3 \ft The soul being justified, and still assaulted with new tentations desireth to be with God.\f*
\v 4 My tears have been breads unto me day and night: whilst it is said to me daily: Where is thy God? \f + \fr 41:4 \ft Ihave had no other refection, but to lenify my sorrow with weeping.\f* \f + \fr 41:4 \ft The wicked exprobate the just, as though God would never help them, because he suffereth them to be sometimes long in tribulation.\f*
\v 5 These things have I remembered, and have poured out my soul in me, because I shall pass into the place of a marvelous tabernacle, even to the house of God. In the voice of exultation, and confession: the sound of one feasting. \f + \fr 41:5 \ft King David was not permitted to build the temple, much less did he enter into any such marvelous tabernacle in his mortal life, but must needs be understood, to speak here of the heavenly tabernacle, prepared by Christ for his servants.\f*
\v 6 Why art thou sorrowful my soul? & why dost thou trouble me? Hope in God, because yet I will confess to him: the salvation of my countenance, \f + \fr 41:6 \ft The Prophet comforteth himself, or any just soul, in\f* \f + \fr 41:6 \ft Irender thanks and praises.\f*
\v 7 and my God. My soul is troubled toward myself; therefore will I be mindful of thee from the land of Jordan, and Hermoniim from the little mountain. \f + \fr 41:7 \ft All this life is like to the small strait place between Jordan and a little hill called Hermoniim, but from this straitness the hope of the just is, to be placed in heaven.\f*
\v 8 Depth calleth on depth, in the voice of thy flood-gates. All thy high things, and thy ways have passed over me. \f + \fr 41:8 \ft One tentation still succeedeth another:\f* \f + \fr 41:8 \ft and the same so great, as if God opened the gates, and suffered them to overflow like floods of water.\f*
\v 9 In the day our Lord hath commanded his mercy: and in the night a song of him. With me is prayer to the God of my life: \f + \fr 41:9 \ft But God helpeth in opportunity, not suffering his servants to be tempted above their strength, giving them fruit with tentations:\f* \f + \fr 41:9 \ft yea in the greatest tribulation, he giveth ordinarily most comfort, making them sing spiritually in heart, if not also in voice.\f* \f + \fr 41:9 \ft One special means to procure divine consolation is prayer in distress.\f*
\v 10 I will say to God: Thou art my defender. Why hast thou forgotten me? And why go I sorrowful, whilst mine enemy afflicteth me?
\v 11 Whilst my bones are broken, mine enemies that trouble me have upbraided me: Whilst they say to me day by day: Where is thy God?
\v 12 Why art thou heavy, o my soul? & why dost thou trouble me? Hope in God, because yet I will confess to him: the salvation of my countenance, and my God. \f + \fr 41:12 \ft Still the just soul taketh comfort in assured hope of salvation, the eternal vision of God.\f*
\c 42
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of David. Judge me, o God, & discern my cause from the nation not holy, from the unjust and deceitful man deliver me. \f + \fr 42:1 \ft Holy David often prefiguring Christ, here representeth every faithful servant of God, and particularly when they begin a great and holy work; as when Priests celebrate the divine Sacrifice, they with their assistants recite by interchangeable verses this Psalm.\f* \f + \fr 42:1 \ft After that we have examined, and prepared ourselves to the most holy Sacrifice and Sacrament, according to S. Paul's admonition (let a man prove himself, and so eat this bread, & drink this chalice, 1. Cor. 11.) we pray God, to judge between our true sincere intention, and the unjust deceitful endeavours of our enemy:\f* \f + \fr 42:1 \ft and so to deliver and protect us from subtle malice.\f*
\v 2 Because thou art God my strength: why hast thou repelled me? And why go I sorrowful whilst the enemy afflicteth me. \f + \fr 42:2 \ft With thee I can do any thing, without thee nothing,\f* \f + \fr 42:2 \ft thou seemest sometimes not to regard me,\f* \f + \fr 42:2 \ft whilst tentations are more sensible than thy grace.\f*
\v 3 Send forth thy light and thy truth: they have conducted me, and have brought me into thy holy hill, and into thy tabernacles. \f + \fr 42:3 \ft As thou hast sent Christ the light and truth into this world, grant us the same now in particular.\f* \f + \fr 42:3 \ft These two gifts of God, the light of knowing our duties and truth, with sincere intention to perform the same, have brought us into thy Church and unto thy Altar.\f*
\v 4 And I will go in to the altar of God: to God, which maketh my youth joyful. I will confess to thee on the harp o God my God: \f + \fr 42:4 \ft Accompanied with light of truth, & sincere intention, we confidently approach to thine Altar, o God,\f* \f + \fr 42:4 \ft who changest our old corruption into newness of life.\f* \f + \fr 42:4 \ft But to this purpose we praise God on the harp, mortifying our affections.\f* \f + \fr 42:4 \ft The former word is of the plural number in Hebrew, Eloim, the other of the singular, signifying the Blessed Trinity, one God.\f* \f + \fr 42:4 \ft See previous note\f*
\v 5 why art thou sorrowful, o my soul? And why dost thou trouble me? Hope in God, because yet will I confess to him: the salvation of my countenance, and my God. \f + \fr 42:5 \ft Thou needest not therefore my soul, to be pensive or desolate.\f* \f + \fr 42:5 \ft But trust in God,\f* \f + \fr 42:5 \ft praise him,\f* \f + \fr 42:5 \ft whom I hope to see face to face,\f* \f + \fr 42:5 \ft the true eternal God.\f*
\c 43
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for the sons of Core to understanding. \f + \fr 43:1 \ft Though this Psalm doth first and literally pertain to the people of Israel, yet all things happening to them, were in figure of the Christian Catholic Church, which began with difficulties, afterwards prospered, and again suffereth much persecution.\f* \f + \fr 43:1 \ft Core signifieth caluus, bald; also calvaria a scull, or place of sculls: the name of the place where our Saviour was crucified: so the children of Core signify the children of Christ. S. Aug.\f*
\v 2 O God we have heard with our ears: our fathers have declared to us. The work that thou hast wrought in their days: & in the days of old. \f + \fr 43:2 \ft The particular calling of Abraham out of Chaldea, protection of him, and Isaac, and Jacob, the delivery of all Israel out of Ægypt, and establishing them in the promised land of Chanaan, with innumerable, great, & strange things done for them.\f*
\v 3 Thy hand destroyed the nations, and thou didst plant them: thou didst afflict the peoples, and expel them.
\v 4 For not by their own sword did they possess the land, and their own arm did not save them: But thy right hand, and thine arm, and the illumination of thy countenance: because thou wast pleased in them. \f + \fr 43:4 \ft The Israelites conquered not by ordinary power, but by the miraculous hand of God. See Iosue 23.\f* \f + \fr 43:4 \ft Not that this people deserved of themselves, but of God's free election, all the world being wicked, he gave peculiar grace to Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, and some others, & then for their sakes protected the whole people, in them conserving a visible Church.\f*
\v 5 Thou art the same my King and my God: which commandest the salvations of Jacob.
\v 6 In thee we shall turn out our enemies with the horn, & in thy name we shall contemn them that rise up against us. \f + \fr 43:6 \ft As in former examples, so in David's time, not man's strength, but God's hand gave them great victories.\f* \f + \fr 43:6 \ft As an oxe with his horn casteth a small thing into the wind.\f*
\v 7 For I will not hope in my bow: and my sword will not save me.
\v 8 For thou hast saved us from them that afflict us: and them that hate us thou hast confounded.
\v 9 In God we shall be praised all the day: and in thy name we will confess for ever.
\v 10 But now thou hast repelled and confounded us: and thou wilt not go forth, o God, in our hosts. \f + \fr 43:10 \ft The Prophet foretelleth that after prosperity God would suffer the Jews to fall into captivity, & many afflictions, which also signified allegorically diverse states of Christ's Church.\f*
\v 11 Thou hast turned us back behind our enemies: and they that hated us spoiled for themselves.
\v 12 Thou hast given us as sheep that are to be eaten: and thou hast dispersed us among the nations. \f + \fr 43:12 \ft The Jews are now marvelously dispersed and depressed.\f*
\v 13 Thou hast sold thy people without price: and there was no multitude in the exchanges of them. \f + \fr 43:13 \ft In the destruction of Jerusalem the remnant of the people were sold for small, as it were for no price. They had sold Christ for thirty pence;\f* \f + \fr 43:13 \ft and now no multitude, nor number of money at all was given for them, but thirty of them were sold for one penny. Iosephus de bello Iudaico.\f*
\v 14 Thou hast made us a reproach to our neighbours, a scorn and mocking stock to them that are round about us.
\v 15 Thou hast made us for a parable to the Gentiles: a wagging of the head among the peoples.
\v 16 All the day my shame is against me, and the confusion of my face hath covered me.
\v 17 At the voice of the upbraider, and the reproacher: at the face of the enemy and persecutor.
\v 18 All these things have come upon us, neither have we forgotten thee: and we have not done wickedly in thy testament. \f + \fr 43:18 \ft Until Christ's passion the Jewish people did not wholly fall from God and true religion. And of them were chosen the Apostles, and many others, that founded and propagated the Church of Christ.\f*
\v 19 And our heart hath not revolted backward: & thou hast declined our paths from thy way. \f + \fr 43:19 \ft The negative particle is here understood by zeugma, according to the Hebrew, thus: Our heart hath not revolted backward, neither hast thou suffered our paths to decline from the way.\f*
\v 20 Because thou hast humbled us in the place of affliction, and the shadow of death hath covered us. \f + \fr 43:20 \ft Another Hebrew phrase, if we have, for, we have not.\f*
\v 21 If we have forgotten the name of our God, and if we have spread forth our hands to a strange god,
\v 22 Will not God inquire of these things? For he knoweth the secrets of the heart. Because for thee we are killed all the day: we are esteemed as sheep of slaughter. \f + \fr 43:22 \ft The Prophets and others, persecuted partly before Christ, much more the Apostles, and other Christians in the new Testament.\f*
\v 23 Arise, why sleepest thou, o Lord? Arise, and expel us not to the end. \f + \fr 43:23 \ft Aprayer in affliction.\f*
\v 24 Why dost thou turn away thy face, forgettest our poverty and our tribulation?
\v 25 Because our soul is humbled in the dust: our belly is glued in the earth. \f + \fr 43:25 \ft We are at death's door, ready to become dust.\f* \f + \fr 43:25 \ft Lying as groveling sorrowing on the earth: Arise Lord, help us: and redeem us for thy name, till thou deliver us from these tribulations.\f*
\v 26 Arise Lord, help us: and redeem us for thy name.
\c 44
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for them, that shall be changed, to the sons of Core for understanding, a Canticle for the beloved. \f + \fr 44:1 \ft Pertaining to the new Testament.\f* \f + \fr 44:1 \ft Gentiles converted from paganism to Christianity:\f* \f + \fr 44:1 \ft and all others returning from schism, or other sins,\f* \f + \fr 44:1 \ft for their instruction.\f* \f + \fr 44:1 \ft This Psalm is a marriage song of the beloved bridegroom and bride, Christ and his Church.\f*
\v 2 My heart hath uttered a good word: I tell my works to the king. My tongue is the pen of a scribe, that writeth swiftly. \f + \fr 44:2 \ft Ihave received by divine inspiration in my heart and cogitation,\f* \f + \fr 44:2 \ft a most high Mystery.\f* \f + \fr 44:2 \ft To the honour therefore and glory of this King (whom I secretly see in my heart) I utter and refer all my works, and this particular Canticle.\f* \f + \fr 44:2 \ft From the aboundance of my heart, my tongue also speaketh,\f* \f + \fr 44:2 \ft & that presently without delay.\f*
\v 3 Goodly of beauty above the sons of men, grace is poured abroad in thy lips: therefore hath God blessed thee for ever. \f + \fr 44:3 \ft Description of Christ, most excellent in all internal and external gifts.\f*
\v 4 Be girded with thy sword upon thy thigh, o most mighty. \f + \fr 44:4 \ft The Prophet seeing in spirit the perfections which he wisheth in Christ, in manner of congratulating, describeth his fortitude, fighting against the devil for the Church.\f*
\v 5 With thy beauty and fairness intend, proceed prosperously, and reign, Because of truth, and mildness, and justice: and thy right hand shall conduct thee marvelously. \f + \fr 44:5 \ft Purposing,\f* \f + \fr 44:5 \ft prosecuting,\f* \f + \fr 44:5 \ft and perfecting the conquest, and so establishing thy spiritual Kingdom.\f* \f + \fr 44:5 \ft Not with warlike armour of this world, but by assaulting the adversary with truth:\f* \f + \fr 44:5 \ft defending thyself and thy soldiers with the shield of mildness,\f* \f + \fr 44:5 \ft and striking the enemy with the sword of justice. Which right force of spiritual fight hath marvelous good success.\f*
\v 6 Thy sharp arrows, the peoples underneath thee shall fall into the hearts of the king's enemies. \f + \fr 44:6 \ft Preaching of Christ's Gospel, his grace moving the hearts of the hearers, is lively and forcible, more piercing than any two edged sword.\f* \f + \fr 44:6 \ft The example of people converted, shall move the hearts of the adversaries to come also unto the truth.\f*
\v 7 Thy seat o God for ever and ever: a rod of direction the rod of thy Kingdom. \f + \fr 44:7 \ft Christ's Kingdom shall have no end. Luc. 1. v. 33.\f*
\v 8 Thou hast loved justice, and hast hated iniquity: therefore God, thy God, hath anointed thee with the oil of gladness above thy fellows. \f + \fr 44:8 \ft Thou defendest and rewardest the good, finally forsakest and punishest the wicked.\f* \f + \fr 44:8 \ft More peculiarly the God of Christ, by hypostatical union.\f* \f + \fr 44:8 \ft Diverse Kings (as David himself, Iosaphat, Ezechias, and Iosias) were as godly as Salomon, and persevered good to the end, which is doubted Salomon did not; but Christ incomparably was anointed, & endued with all graces above all Kings.\f*
\v 9 Myrrh, and Aloes, and Cassia from thy garments, from houses of ivory, out of the which \f + \fr 44:9 \ft Mortification which conserveth from putrefying.\f* \f + \fr 44:9 \ft humility assuaging pride,\f* \f + \fr 44:9 \ft being small in the first spring, groweth great.\f* \f + \fr 44:9 \ft Humanity assumpted, and sanctified persons, in whom Christ dwelleth as in clean, shining, odoriferous houses.\f*
\v 10 the daughters of kings have delighted thee in thy honour. \f + \fr 44:10 \ft Sincere faithful souls more dear to their spouse Christ, than daughters of temporal Kings.\f*
\v 11 The Queen stood on thy right hand in golden raiment: compassed with variety. Hear daughter, and see, and incline thine ear: and forget thy people, and the house of thy father. \f + \fr 44:11 \ft The Catholic Church, in faith purified as gold:\f* \f + \fr 44:11 \ft with variety of states, as Clergy, Laity, and diverse sorts of religious Orders, and other professions, all united in the same faith, hope, and charity.\f* \f + \fr 44:11 \ft Carefully all that Christ thy spouse speaketh to thee by his Spirit.\f* \f + \fr 44:11 \ft Diligently put the same in practice:\f* \f + \fr 44:11 \ft with all obedience and readiness, and return not to former infidelity, nor to corrupt life.\f*
\v 12 And the King will covet thy beauty: because he is the Lord thy God, and they shall adore him. \f + \fr 44:12 \ft Christ loveth the Church adorned with his gifts,\f* \f + \fr 44:12 \ft and mutually his true children love and serve him.\f*
\v 13 And the daughters of Tyre with gifts, all the rich of the people shall beseech thy countenance. \f + \fr 44:13 \ft Many of all nations submit themselves, and all that they have to Christ.\f*
\v 14 All the glory of that daughter of the King is within, in borders of gold, \f + \fr 44:14 \ft Internal virtues are most special ornaments:\f* \f + \fr 44:14 \ft exterior are required to edify others in diverse sorts of virtues.\f*
\v 15 clothed round about with varieties. Virgins shall be brought to the King after her: her neighbours shall be brought to thee. \f + \fr 44:15 \ft By this means many more are converted to Christianity:\f* \f + \fr 44:15 \ft and one country inviteth and draweth another.\f*
\v 16 They shall be brought in joy and exultation: they shall be brought into the temple of the King.
\v 17 For thy fathers there are born sons to thee: thou shalt make them Princes over all the earth. \f + \fr 44:17 \ft As Apostles came in place of Patriarchs and Prophets: so still Bishops and Priests succeed in the Church, Pastors, and governors thereof.\f*
\v 18 They shall be mindful of thy name in all generation and generation. Therefore shall peoples confess to thee for ever: and for ever and ever. \f + \fr 44:18 \ft These Pastors shall still teach the true Christian doctrine.\f* \f + \fr 44:18 \ft And still there shall be Christian people that will follow and profess the same.\f*
\c 45
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, to the sons of Core, for the secrets. \f + \fr 45:1 \ft Belonging to the Church of Christ.\f* \f + \fr 45:1 \ft As well the cause, why God suffereth his Church to be persecuted, as his assured protection in difficulties, are hidden secrets to the world.\f*
\v 2 Our God is a refuge and strength: an helper in tribulations, which have found us exceedingly. \f + \fr 45:2 \ft All refuge is not secure, for one man is not able always to defend another: but God is a sure and strong refuge.\f* \f + \fr 45:2 \ft Ever able and in convenient time willing to help.\f* \f + \fr 45:2 \ft This whole world is full of tribulations, but the Church suffered the greatest in the first persecutions, & shall suffer as great in the time of Antichrist. English Catholics suffer most of all nations in this age, and cannot be suppressed, but still increase in number and fortitude.\f*
\v 3 Therefore will we not fear when the earth shall be troubled: and mountains transported into the heart of the sea. \f + \fr 45:3 \ft Therefore all Catholics may assuredly know, that the whole Church cannot fail\f* \f + \fr 45:3 \ft though very many, as now in England,\f* \f + \fr 45:3 \ft and very eminent persons, as some noblemen, and some Priests have revolted, yet all will not.\f*
\v 4 Their waters have sounded, and were troubled: the mountains were troubled in his strength.
\v 5 The violence of the river maketh the city of God joyful: the Highest hath sanctified his tabernacle. \f + \fr 45:5 \ft Such bad examples make the good to recollect themselves more diligently, and to rejoice in God's grace, by which they stand fast.\f*
\v 6 God is in the midst thereof, it shall not be moved: God will help it in the morning early. \f + \fr 45:6 \ft Before the heat of persecution shall invade all, for the elect the days of tribulation are shortened.\f*
\v 7 Nations are troubled, and Kingdoms are inclined: he gave his voice, the earth was moved. \f + \fr 45:7 \ft Sometimes one nation or Kingdom rebelleth against the Church, but cannot destroy it.\f* \f + \fr 45:7 \ft By the spirit of Christ, Antichrist, and all his members shall be destroyed.\f*
\v 8 The Lord of hosts is with us: the God of Jacob is our defender.
\v 9 Come ye, & see the works of our Lord, what wonders he hath put upon the earth:
\v 10 taking away wars even unto the end of the earth. He shall destroy bow, & break weapons: and shields he shall burn with fire. \f + \fr 45:10 \ft The Church sometimes hath great peace and tranquility.\f*
\v 11 Be quiet, and see that I am God: I shall be exalted among the gentiles, and I shall be exalted in the earth. \f + \fr 45:11 \ft God himself restraineth the wicked, suddenly abating their fury, or cutting off their forces.\f*
\v 12 The Lord of hosts is with us: the God of Jacob is our defender.
\c 46
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for the sons of Core. \f + \fr 46:1 \ft For Christians that leave the sins of their fathers, and rejoice in Christ crucified. See Annotations. Psal. 4.\f*
\v 2 All ye Nations clap hands: make jubilation to God in the voice of exultation. \f + \fr 46:2 \ft True joy of the heart sheweth it-self both in voice of exultation, and also in gesture of body, by clapping of hands, dancing (as King David did before the Ark 2. Reg. 6.) likewise with instruments.\f*
\v 3 Because our Lord is high, terrible: a great King over all the earth. \f + \fr 46:3 \ft To all the wicked,\f* \f + \fr 46:3 \ft not only of one or few kingdoms, but of all the earth.\f*
\v 4 He hath made peoples subject to us: & gentiles under our feet. \f + \fr 46:4 \ft When Kings and countries become Christians, they are made subjects to the Church that was before, not heads and rulers therefore.\f*
\v 5 He hath chosen his inheritance in us: the beauty of Jacob which he loved.
\v 6 God is ascended in jubilation: and our Lord in the voice of trumpet. \f + \fr 46:6 \ft Christ God & man, after his Passion, rose from death and ascended:\f* \f + \fr 46:6 \ft Not leaving his Church desolate, but making her joyful by another comforter, the Holy Ghost.\f*
\v 7 Sing ye to our God, sing ye: Sing ye to our King, sing ye. \f + \fr 46:7 \ft The same Christ is our God, by his Divinity:\f* \f + \fr 46:7 \ft and our King by his Humanity.\f*
\v 8 Because God is King of all the earth: sing ye wisely. \f + \fr 46:8 \ft Do your endeavour to understand what you sing, read, or hear in God's word. At least to know the principal Mysteries, and points of Christian doctrine, every one according to their capacity and state or profession.\f*
\v 9 God shall reign over the gentiles: God sitteth upon his holy seat.
\v 10 Princes of peoples are gathered together with the God of Abraham: because the strong gods of the earth are exceedingly advanced. \f + \fr 46:10 \ft The faithful of the old and new Testament are united in the service of one & the same eternal God.\f* \f + \fr 46:10 \ft In respect of the Blessed Trinity, holy Scripture here, and in many places useth names of the plural number, as Eloim, Gods, not dividing God's substance, which is one, but insinuating distinction of Divine Persons, The Father, the Son, and the Holy Ghost. Which Mystery is more expressly mentioned in Baptism, & professed by Christian Gentiles, than it was by the people of the Jews.\f*
\c 47
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of Canticle to the sons of Core, the second of the Sabbath. \f + \fr 47:1 \ft Voices beginning the music instruments prosecuted.\f* \f + \fr 47:1 \ft Especially for the second day of the week, the day after the sabbath, which is our Sunday, called Dominica, our Lord's day.\f*
\v 2 Great is our Lord, and to be praised exceedingly, in the city of our God, in his holy mount. \f + \fr 47:2 \ft Jerusalem, and mount Sion were most obliged to praise God, for greatest benefits received: so the Catholic Church thereby prefigured, & having received far greater, is most of all bound to be grateful.\f*
\v 3 Mount Sion is founded with the exultation of the whole earth, the sides of the North, the city of the great King. \f + \fr 47:3 \ft This cannot be affirmed of Sion, or Jerusalem, but is only verified of the Catholic Christian Church:\f* \f + \fr 47:3 \ft whose coasts do extend to the North, & to all quarters of the round earth.\f*
\v 4 God shall be known in the houses thereof, when he shall receive it. \f + \fr 47:4 \ft The same one God, one Christ, one Faith, & one Religion in all particular Churches of the whole militant Church.\f* \f + \fr 47:4 \ft And this Universality and Unity shall be, after that Christ taking man's nature shall be ascended, and shall send the Holy Ghost, to found & begin this Church.\f*
\v 5 For behold the kings of the earth were gathered together: they assembled in one. \f + \fr 47:5 \ft For the assured certainty of that is foreshewed, the Prophet speaketh in the pretertense, as if it were already done in his time, which he then saw in spirit.\f*
\v 6 They seeing it so were in admiration, were troubled, were moved:
\v 7 Trembling took them. Their sorrows as a woman travailing. \f + \fr 47:7 \ft Nothing more moveth the heart, & affecteth all the body and soul, than spiritual cogitations of faith and religion, and therefore it is compared to a woman travailing with child, who hath most careful and grievous pains.\f*
\v 8 In a vehement spirit thou shalt break the ships of Tharsis. \f + \fr 47:8 \ft In which great conflict of man's spirit, God by his grace giveth force, to break through the contrary assaults of our enemy, to remove all impediments, and to overcome the difficulties.\f*
\v 9 As we have heard, so have we seen in the city of the Lord of hosts, in the city of our God: God hath founded it for ever. \f + \fr 47:9 \ft This consideration, that all is now done, that was of old prophesied, is a marvelous confirmation to Christians.\f*
\v 10 We have received thy mercy, o God, in the midst of thy temple. \f + \fr 47:10 \ft Grace and mercy is only granted to those that are within, or come unto the Catholic Church.\f*
\v 11 According to thy name, o God, so also is thy praise unto the ends of the earth: thy right hand is full of justice. \f + \fr 47:11 \ft As God is praised for his mercy, so also for his justice: which do never prejudice the one the other.\f*
\v 12 Let mount Sion be glad, and the daughters of Juda rejoice, because of thy judgments, o Lord.
\v 13 Compass Sion, and embrace ye her: tell ye in her towers. \f + \fr 47:13 \ft Consider the fortresses or the Church, which are the holy Fathers, and Doctors, that watch and defend her walls.\f*
\v 14 Set your hearts on her strength: and distribute ye her houses, that you may declare it in another generation. \f + \fr 47:14 \ft So rest you assured for all matters of faith in this pillar of truth.\f* \f + \fr 47:14 \ft Observe and mark diligently how many particular Churches were speedily founded in the world,\f* \f + \fr 47:14 \ft and declare this to other generations, that they may also hold fast the same faith, or return unto it, if they be relapsed; or at last embrace it, if sooner they have not.\f*
\v 15 Because this is God, our God for ever, and for ever and ever: he shall rule us evermore. \f + \fr 47:15 \ft Christ God incarnate that worketh all this, is our very God and Saviour, not for a few years, an hundred, six hundred, or a thousand, but for ever & ever.\f* \f + \fr 47:15 \ft He shall rule as a King, and consequently have a Kingdom, his militant Church, evermore, to the very end of this world. As he shall likewise have his triumphant Church in eternity.\f*
\c 48
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, to the sons of Core a Psalm. \f + \fr 48:1 \ft In this and diverse other titles, both before and yet ensuing, is said, To the sons, or, for the sons of Core, a Psalm, or Canticle, or understanding & the like; but in no place, a Psalm, Canticle &c. of the sons of Core: which no way proveth that they were the authors of such Psalms, but rather the contrary.\f*
\v 2 Hear these things all ye Gentiles: receive with your ears all ye that inhabit the earth. \f + \fr 48:2 \ft All ye nations and sorts of people\f* \f + \fr 48:2 \ft that dwell upon the earth, learn this lesson which I will teach you.\f*
\v 3 All ye earthly persons, and children of men: together in one the rich and the poor.
\v 4 My mouth shall speak wisdom, and the meditation of my heart prudence.
\v 5 I will incline mine ear unto a parable: I will open my proposition on a Psalter. \f + \fr 48:5 \ft Holy David harkened to God inspiring him,\f* \f + \fr 48:5 \ft and declared to others that which he received from God,\f* \f + \fr 48:5 \ft not only by his pen or tongue, but also for better instilling it into their minds he sounded it upon the instrument called the Psalter, which had ten strings, signifying the observation of the ten commandments.\f*
\v 6 Why shall I fear in the evil day? The iniquity of my heel shall compass me. \f + \fr 48:6 \ft What especial thing is there in this life, why or for which I or any have cause to fear the dreadful day of judgement?\f* \f + \fr 48:6 \ft Marry this we must fear, iniquity, by which any supplanteth, defraudeth, oppresseth, or any way wrongeth others, for that will involve the offender in the sentence of eternal damnation.\f*
\v 7 They that trust in their strength: and glory in the multitude of their riches. \f + \fr 48:7 \ft Such be they that trust in their present power, riches, or other worldly things.\f*
\v 8 A brother doth not redeem, man shall redeem: he shall not give unto God his reconciliation. \f + \fr 48:8 \ft Aman's own brother cannot help a sinner in that day,\f* \f + \fr 48:8 \ft much less any other man: so the Hebrew phrase by zeugma, understandeth another negative particle.\f*
\v 9 And the price of the redemption of his own soul: and he shall labour for ever, \f + \fr 48:9 \ft Still suffer pain,\f*
\v 10 and shall live yet unto the end. \f + \fr 48:10 \ft and not die, but live in eternal torments.\f*
\v 11 He shall not see death, when he shall see the wise dying, the unwise, and the fool shall perish together. And they shall leave their riches to strangers: \f + \fr 48:11 \ft All both wise and foolish do die temporally: but the wise living in eternal joy, the foolish live in eternal pain.\f* \f + \fr 48:11 \ft Those that believe not any other life after this,\f* \f + \fr 48:11 \ft and those that believing another life, yet live badly in this, shall perish in eternal damnation.\f*
\v 12 and their sepulchres their houses for ever. Their Tabernacles in generation and generation: they have renowned their names in their lands. \f + \fr 48:12 \ft They shall never return from their sepulchers\f* \f + \fr 48:12 \ft to enjoy again their houses and earthly possessions.\f* \f + \fr 48:12 \ft Which vainly they labour to establish in their posterity.\f*
\v 13 And man when he was in honour, did not understand: he was compared to beasts without understanding, and became like to them. \f + \fr 48:13 \ft Amost pithy and brief consideration, for man to think, how absurdly, he being endowed with reason, understanding, & free will, like unto Angels, and capable of eternal glory, setteth his whole study and care upon corporal and temporal things, so making himself like unto brute beasts.\f*
\v 14 This their way is a scandal to them: and afterward in their mouth they shall take pleasure. \f + \fr 48:14 \ft This care of worldly things is the stumbling block, and cause of eternal ruin:\f* \f + \fr 48:14 \ft yet they shall be obstinate, and praise their own desires, still persisting therein.\f*
\v 15 As sheep they are put in hell: death shall feed upon them. And the just shall rule over them in the morning: and their aid shall wax old in hell from their glory. \f + \fr 48:15 \ft Among other creatures a sheep can least help herself in misery: even so the damned in hell are altogether unable to deliver themselves from thence, or to get any relief.\f* \f + \fr 48:15 \ft In the general resurrection they shall be most of all in misery, as ever dying and never dead: the just whom they wronged, shall be their judges, all friends shall fail them, after they have passed their glory and pleasure in this world.\f*
\v 16 Nevertheless God will redeem my soul out of the hand of hell, when he shall take me, \f + \fr 48:16 \ft The confidence of the just.\f*
\v 17 Fear not when a man shall be made rich: and when the glory of his house shall be multiplied.
\v 18 Because when he shall die, he shall not take all things: neither shall his glory go down with him. \f + \fr 48:18 \ft He shall leave all worldly things and take nothing with him.\f*
\v 19 Because his soul in his life shall be blessed: he will confess to thee when thou shalt do him good. \f + \fr 48:19 \ft Temporally:\f* \f + \fr 48:19 \ft so long as he enjoyeth worldly profits, he will seem grateful to God.\f*
\v 20 He shall enter in, even to the progenies of his fathers: and he shall not see light for ever. \f + \fr 48:20 \ft But they shall not see the true light of heaven.\f*
\v 21 Man, when he was in honour, did not understand: he was compared to beasts without understanding, and became like to them. \f + \fr 48:21 \ft Remember and consider, o worldly man, that God made thee an excellent creature: which thou neglecting makest thyself like to a beast. As, v. 13.\f*
\c 49
\p
\v 1 A Psalm to Asaph. The God of gods our Lord hath spoken: and he hath called the earth, from the rising of the sun even to the going down. \f + \fr 49:1 \ft To be sung or tuned by Asaph a master of music.\f*
\v 2 Out of Sion the beauty of his comeliness. \f + \fr 49:2 \ft The Church of Christ began in Sion.\f*
\v 3 God will come manifestly: our God and he will not keep silence. Fire shall burn forth in his sight: and round about him a mighty tempest. \f + \fr 49:3 \ft Christ that came in humility, & more obscurely to suffer, and to redeem us, will come in majesty, and manifestly to judge.\f* \f + \fr 49:3 \ft Immediately before the general judgement, fire shall burn all transitory things.\f*
\v 4 He shall call the heaven from above: and the earth to discern his people. \f + \fr 49:4 \ft Give signs in the firmament,\f* \f + \fr 49:4 \ft and in earth.\f*
\v 5 Gather ye together his Saints unto him: which ordain his testament above sacrifices. \f + \fr 49:5 \ft Which know that to keep God's commandments in following virtues, is above the oblation of external sacrifice.\f*
\v 6 And the heavens shall shew forth his justice: because God is Judge.
\v 7 Hear, o my people, and I will speak: Israel, and I will testify to thee: God thy God am I. \f + \fr 49:7 \ft God instructeth his people.\f*
\v 8 I will not rebuke thee in thy sacrifices: and thy holocausts are in my sight always. \f + \fr 49:8 \ft Sacrifices are grateful to God:\f*
\v 9 I will not take calves out of thy house: nor buck-goats out of thy flocks. \f + \fr 49:9 \ft But in regard that God needeth not these earthly things, he rather requireth a grateful mind. For otherwise man indeed can give nothing to God: seeing all that is in the whole world is God's own in propriety.\f*
\v 10 Because all the wild beasts of the woods be mine, the cattle in the mountains and oxen.
\v 11 I have known all the fowls of the air: and the beauty of the field is with me.
\v 12 If I shall be hungry, I will not tell thee: for the round earth is mine, and the fullness thereof.
\v 13 Will I eat the flesh of oxen? Or will I drink the blood of buck-goats?
\v 14 Immolate to God the sacrifice of praise, and pay thy vows to the Highest. \f + \fr 49:14 \ft Spiritual sacrifices of praise,\f* \f + \fr 49:14 \ft & due payment of voluntary vows made in honour of God,\f*
\v 15 And invocate me in the day of tribulation: I will deliver thee, and thou shalt glorify me. \f + \fr 49:15 \ft and praying to him for help in tribulation are most grateful.\f*
\v 16 But to the sinner God hath said: Why doest thou declare my justices, and takest my testament by thy mouth? \f + \fr 49:16 \ft He that will teach others, must especially fly from sin, & serve God sincerely.\f*
\v 17 But thou hast hated discipline & cast my words behind thee.
\v 18 If thou didst see a thief, thou didst run with him: and with adulterers thou didst put thy portion.
\v 19 Thy mouth hath abounded with malice: and thy tongue forged guiles.
\v 20 Sitting thou spakest against thy brother, and against thy mother's son thou didst put a scandal:
\v 21 these things hast thou done, and I have held my peace. Thou hast thought unjustly that I will be like thee: I will reprove thee, and set it against thy face.
\v 22 Understand these things you that forget God: lest sometime he take you violently and there be none to deliver you.
\v 23 The sacrifice of praise shall glorify me: and there is the way, by which I will shew him the salvation of God. \f + \fr 49:23 \ft God is honoured by man's gratitude, and other good works.\f*
\c 50
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm of David, \f + \fr 50:1 \ft Pertaining not only to David, but also to all penitents, especially of the new testament.\f*
\v 2 when Nathan the Prophet came to him, after that he had sinned with Bethsabee.
\v 3 Have mercy on me, o God, according to thy great mercy. And according to the multitude of thy commiserations, take away mine iniquity. \f + \fr 50:3 \ft My sins being very great, need thy great mercy.\f* \f + \fr 50:3 \ft Yea many sorts of thy mercies: not only remission of the crimes, but also mitigation of the pains due for the same: Thy merciful grace, to be truly sorry, to make some part of satisfaction, to beware hereafter not to fall again, to give better example of penance, and of virtuous life, and to persevere to the end.\f*
\v 4 Wash me more amply from mine iniquity: & cleanse me from my sin. \f + \fr 50:4 \ft O God thou hast forgiven me, and taken away my sins, as thy Prophet hath told me (2. Reg. 12. v. 13.) but my soul so foully polluted, needeth yet more washing.\f* \f + \fr 50:4 \ft Cleanse also the dregs that remain, and all habits and inclinations to sin. So our Saviour afterwards taught. (Ioan. 13. v. 10.) He that is washed needeth not saving to wash his feet (ill affections and relics of former sins) but is clean wholly.\f*
\v 5 Because I do know mine iniquity: and my sin is before me always. \f + \fr 50:5 \ft Whilst I did not know, nor consider, nor acknowledge my sins, I could not be forgiven, but now I know and acknowledge them:\f* \f + \fr 50:5 \ft and I cease not to consider of them with sorrow.\f*
\v 6 To thee only have I sinned, and have done evil before thee: that thou mayst be justified in thy words, and mayst overcome when thou art judged. \f + \fr 50:6 \ft Principally (for so this particle, only, here signifieth) the enormities of my sins consist in that I have offended thy Divine Goodness and Majesty, the King of the worlds, immortal, invisible, only God, to whom is due all honour and glory for ever and ever, 1. Tim. 1. v. 17.\f* \f + \fr 50:6 \ft Thou which hast promised forgiveness to all sinners that truly convert, shall herein be justified by receiving me again to grace:\f* \f + \fr 50:6 \ft and overthrow thy calumniators, that judge wickedly of thy proceedings, as if either thy justice or mercy were perverted.\f*
\v 7 For behold I was conceived in iniquities: & my mother conceived me in sins. \f + \fr 50:7 \ft I & all are born in original sin, the relics whereof, concupiscence and weakness, incline us to other sins, which we have added. In regard of which our infirmity, thy mercy is ready to recall us and help us.\f*
\v 8 For behold thou hast loved truth: the uncertain and hidden things of thy wisdom thou hast made manifest to me. \f + \fr 50:8 \ft Besides thou hast also given me knowledge of true faith, and right doctrine, which thou ever lovest, and art accustomed to reduce, and direct such into the true way of penance.\f* \f + \fr 50:8 \ft Yea thou hast moreover shewed to me things uncertain, or unknown to many others, given me the gift and spirit of prophecy, to know hid mysteries, and to every one God giveth some particular benefits, which he loveth in him, and is ready of his part to confirm and maintain the same, that they be not lost.\f*
\v 9 Thou shalt sprinkle me with hyssop, and I shall be cleansed: thou shalt wash me, and I shall be made whiter than snow. \f + \fr 50:9 \ft Most merciful Lord thou wilt (as I see in the spirit of prophecy) sprinkle me, and all men with thy blood from the Cross, where they shall give thee vinegar about hyssop to drink (Ioan. 9.)\f* \f + \fr 50:9 \ft by which washing I shall be clean from sin, and become in time pure, yea whiter than snow. A figure of this hyssop was observed in Moyses' Law. Num. 16. signifying the lively heat of Christ's infinite charity.\f*
\v 10 To my hearing thou shalt give joy and gladness, and the bones humbled shall rejoice. \f + \fr 50:10 \ft When mine affections shall be clean purged, I shall take singular great delight to hear of thee,\f* \f + \fr 50:10 \ft and all my powers of mind and body, which are now afflicted, shall rejoice.\f*
\v 11 Turn away thy face from my sins: and wipe away all mine iniquities. \f + \fr 50:11 \ft Leave off thy cogitation of punishing, to which purpose first take away mine iniquities, for otherwise if they remain, God's justice cannot but punish them.\f*
\v 12 Create a clean heart in me, o God: and renew a right spirit in my bowels. \f + \fr 50:12 \ft Create in me new grace, whereby my heart shall be pure. So S. Paul calleth a just soul a new creature, Galat. 6. v. 15.\f* \f + \fr 50:12 \ft In my inward thoughts.\f*
\v 13 Cast me not away from thy face: and thy Holy spirit take not from me. \f + \fr 50:13 \ft Suffer me not so to fall again, that thy grace depart from me.\f*
\v 14 Render unto me the joy of thy salvation? And confirm me with the principal spirit. \f + \fr 50:14 \ft Which I had before my fall, of Christ promised of my seed, and alter not the same for my sins. David also and other penitents pray here, that God will restore unto them the joy, which they had in the state of grace, of eternal salvation promised.\f* \f + \fr 50:14 \ft Confirm & conserve in me hereafter a strong, constant, and willing spirit to persevere.\f*
\v 15 I will teach the unjust thy ways: and the impious shall be converted to thee. \f + \fr 50:15 \ft No way can a penitent better shew himself grateful to God, for remission of his sins, than by instructing, exhorting, & persuading other sinners to repentance, to leave their former ill ways, and turn to God.\f*
\v 16 Deliver me from bloods, o God, the God of my salvation: and my tongue shall exult thy justice. \f + \fr 50:16 \ft From the guilt and punishment of murder, causing Urias and others with him to be slain. Other penitents pray to be delivered from what sins soever they have committed, by shedding blood, or other wrongs & injuries, promising to praise God's justice, in offering and giving grace, according to his promise to sinners, that they may repent.\f*
\v 17 Lord thou wilt open my lips: & my mouth shall shew forth thy praise. \f + \fr 50:17 \ft Thou, o God, first stirring me up, opening my lips, which of myself I cannot do, then my tongue and mouth will praise thee.\f*
\v 18 Because if thou wouldest have had sacrifice, I had verily given it: with holocausts thou wilt not be delighted. \f + \fr 50:18 \ft If thou wouldest especially legal sacrifice, I would easily have offered great store:\f* \f + \fr 50:18 \ft but the best of that kind is not sufficient:\f*
\v 19 Asacrifice to God is an afflicted spirit: a contrite and humbled heart, o God, thou wilt not despise. \f + \fr 50:19 \ft true contrition of heart pleaseth thee far better.\f*
\v 20 Deal favourably, o Lord, in thy good will with Sion: that the walls of Jerusalem may be built up. \f + \fr 50:20 \ft After a penitent hath remission of his own sins, he must pray for the whole Church.\f*
\v 21 Then shall thou accept sacrifice of justice, oblations, & holocausts: then shall they lay calves upon thine altar. \f + \fr 50:21 \ft The Church prospering, her faithful children shall offer\f* \f + \fr 50:21 \ft the sacrifice of justice, rendering to every one that is due;\f* \f + \fr 50:21 \ft also free offerings without obligation,\f* \f + \fr 50:21 \ft yea holocausts, which is the chiefest,\f* \f + \fr 50:21 \ft holocausts, which is the chiefest, (1) calves, and like hosts upon the altar, according to the state of the old law: but in the law of Christ, the most B. Sacrifice by him instituted.\f*
\c 51
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, understanding to David,
\v 2 When Doeg the Idumeite came and told Saul: David is come into the house of Achimelech. \f + \fr 51:2 \ft Of the race of Esau, half a Jew, but either an Infidel, or fautor of Infidels, a spy for Saul, a persecutor of David, & a murderer of Innocents. 1. Reg. 22. v. 9. 18.\f* \f + \fr 51:2 \ft High Priest, slain with 84. more Priests and others, because they were supposed to favour David. ibidem.\f* \f + \fr 51:2 \ft (1. Reg. 22.)\f*
\v 3 Why doest thou glory in malice, which are mighty in iniquity? \f + \fr 51:3 \ft Thou persecutor Doeg, why art thou so malicious, to abuse thy credit with King Saul, to the murdering of innocents?\f*
\v 4 All the day hath thy tongue thought injustice: as a sharp razor thou hast done guile. \f + \fr 51:4 \ft Playing the part of a spy, in betraying to Saul, that I was with Achimelech?\f*
\v 5 Thou hast loved malice more than benignity: iniquity rather than to speak equity. \f + \fr 51:5 \ft Though he told a truth, yet it was iniquity to betray innocents.\f*
\v 6 Thou hast loved all words of precipitation, a deceitful tongue.
\v 7 Therefore will God destroy thee for ever, he will pluck thee out, & remove thee out of thy tabernacle: & thy root out of the land of the living. \f + \fr 51:7 \ft Thou shalt utterly be destroyed,\f* \f + \fr 51:7 \ft & all thy race.\f*
\v 8 The just shall see, and fear, and shall laugh at him, and they shall say:
\v 9 Behold the man, that hath not put God for his helper. But hath hoped in the multitude of his riches, and hath prevailed in his vanity. \f + \fr 51:9 \ft for a short time in this world.\f*
\v 10 But I as a fruitful olive tree in the house of God, have hoped in the mercy of God for ever: and for ever and ever. \f + \fr 51:10 \ft David prophesieth his own exaltation, and conservation of his seed in the Kingdom of Israel.\f*
\v 11 I will confess to thee for ever, because thou hast done it: and I will expect thy name, because it is good in the sight of thy Saints. \f + \fr 51:11 \ft Sing praise & thanks to thee.\f* \f + \fr 51:11 \ft Thy Goodness, which agreeth to thy name.\f*
\c 52
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for Mæleth, understandings of David. The fool hath said in his heart: There is no God. \f + \fr 52:1 \ft Weakness, or mourning.\f* \f + \fr 52:1 \ft S. Augustin expoundeth this Psalm as an instruction to those that suffer persecution and injuries, especially near the end of the world.\f*
\v 2 They are corrupt, and become abominable in iniquities: there is not that doth good.
\v 3 God hath looked forth from heaven, upon the children of men: to see if there be that understandeth, or seeketh after God.
\v 4 All have declined, they are become unprofitable together: there is not that doth good, no there is not one.
\v 5 Shall they not all know that work iniquity, that devour my people as food of bread?
\v 6 God they have not invocated: there have they trembled for fear, where no fear was. Because God hath dissipated the bones of them that please men: they are confounded, because God hath despised them. \f + \fr 52:6 \ft God will overthrow all the counsels and forces\f* \f + \fr 52:6 \ft of worldly politics.\f*
\v 7 Who will give out of Sion the salvation of Israel? When God shall convert the captivity of his people: Jacob shall rejoice, and Israel shall be glad. \f + \fr 52:7 \ft The true Church afflicted desireth Christ's coming to deliver the oppressed.\f*
\c 53
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, in songs understanding for David \f + \fr 53:1 \ft Though historically this Psalm\f* \f + \fr 53:1 \ft was sung by David the author thereof, shewing how he prayed in danger, and rendered thanks for his delivery,\f*
\v 2 when the Zipheites were come, and said to Saul: Is not David hid with us? \f + \fr 53:2 \ft when upon notice given that he abode in the mountains, Saul straitly besieged him, with a great army, but the Philistiims invading the country, Saul was forced to leave David, and to turn his forces against them, 1. Reg. 23. yet it pertaineth also literally to all just men in distress, especially to the Church of Christ, praying in like dangers, and God by his like providence delivering his servants in extremities.\f* \f + \fr 53:2 \ft 1. Reg. c. 23. & 26.\f*
\v 3 O God save me in thy name: and in thy strength judge me. \f + \fr 53:3 \ft For the glory of thy name\f* \f + \fr 53:3 \ft for the justness of my cause defend me.\f*
\v 4 O God hear my prayer with thine ears: receive the words of my mouth.
\v 5 Because strangers have risen up against me, & the strong have sought my soul: and they have not set God before their eyes. \f + \fr 53:5 \ft Barbarous highland men have betrayed the place of mine abode to the persecuters.\f*
\v 6 For behold God helpeth me: and our Lord is the receiver of my soul. \f + \fr 53:6 \ft But I fear them not, because I am in God's protection.\f*
\v 7 Turn away the evils of mine enemies: and in thy truth destroy them. \f + \fr 53:7 \ft Ajust prayer, that God will turn intended mischief upon the devisers' heads,\f* \f + \fr 53:7 \ft according to his promise, that he will defend the innocent.\f*
\v 8 I will voluntarily sacrifice to thee, and will confess to thy name o Lord, because it is good: \f + \fr 53:8 \ft Offering voluntary sacrifice, more than is commanded.\f* \f + \fr 53:8 \ft And praise thee, o God.\f*
\v 9 Because thou hast delivered me out of all tribulation: and mine eye hath looked down upon mine enemies. \f + \fr 53:9 \ft As I am bound\f* \f + \fr 53:9 \ft Irejoice in thy just judgements against the wicked.\f*
\c 54
\p
\v 1 Unto the end in songs, understanding to David. \f + \fr 54:1 \ft Asong as well for King David himself, as others of all times\f* \f + \fr 54:1 \ft to sing\f* \f + \fr 54:1 \ft and consider God's providence, in suffering one man to afflict another in this life.\f*
\v 2 Hear my prayer, o God, despise not my petition.
\v 3 Attend to me and hear me.
\v 4 I am made sorrowful in my exercise: and am troubled at the voice of the enemy: and at the tribulation of the sinner. Because they have wrested iniquities upon me: & in anger they were troublesome to me. \f + \fr 54:4 \ft This life is a warfare, and a continual combat.\f* \f + \fr 54:4 \ft Calumniated me,\f* \f + \fr 54:4 \ft and persecuted me in great fury.\f*
\v 5 My heart is troubled in me: & the fear of death is fallen upon me. \f + \fr 54:5 \ft So inwardly afflicted, as if death were at hand.\f*
\v 6 Fear and trembling are come upon me: and darkness hath covered me. \f + \fr 54:6 \ft Ihave scarce sense, or discourse of reason, being almost overwhelmed with trouble.\f*
\v 7 And I said: Who will give me wings as of a dove, and I will fly: and rest? \f + \fr 54:7 \ft Would God I could fly, that in the simplicity of a dove, I might speedily part away from these afflictions.\f*
\v 8 Lo I have gone far flying away: and I abode in the wilderness. \f + \fr 54:8 \ft Ihave fled so far as I could from troubles:\f*
\v 9 I expected him, that saved me from pusillanimity of spirit, and tempest. \f + \fr 54:9 \ft For the rest I remitted to God's will and good pleasure,\f* \f + \fr 54:9 \ft and he suffered me not to be overthrown,\f* \f + \fr 54:9 \ft though I am weak,\f* \f + \fr 54:9 \ft and the tentations are great.\f*
\v 10 Precipitate, o Lord, and divide their tongues: because I have seen iniquity, and contradiction in the city. \f + \fr 54:10 \ft O God abate the pride of arrogant persecuters,\f* \f + \fr 54:10 \ft suffer them not to agree amongst themselves.\f* \f + \fr 54:10 \ft They are full of all iniquity,\f* \f + \fr 54:10 \ft they have also contentions among themselves, turn the same to our good.\f*
\v 11 Day and night shall iniquity compass it upon the walls thereof, and labour in the midst thereof, and injustice. \f + \fr 54:11 \ft With their continual great iniquity, they have their troubles,\f* \f + \fr 54:11 \ft but leave not their injustice.\f*
\v 12 And there hath not ceased out of the streets thereof usury and guile. \f + \fr 54:12 \ft They are still usurers, and deceitful oppressors of the poor.\f*
\v 13 For if mine enemy had spoken evil to me, I would verily have born it. And if he that hated me had spoken great things upon me: I would perhaps have hid myself from him. \f + \fr 54:13 \ft It is a greater grief to suffer injuries of those that seem to be friends.\f*
\v 14 But thou a man of the same mind: my guide, and my familiar. \f + \fr 54:14 \ft Aman that was, or seemed of the same mind, faith, and religion,\f* \f + \fr 54:14 \ft whom I so trusted, that I would have gone, whithersoever he should have led me.\f*
\v 15 Which didest take sweet meats together with me: in the house of God we walked with consent. \f + \fr 54:15 \ft Thou that didst participate the same holy sacraments with me,\f* \f + \fr 54:15 \ft in the Catholic Church.\f*
\v 16 Let death come upon them: and let them go down quick into hell. Because there is wickedness in their habitations, in the midst of them. \f + \fr 54:16 \ft As Core & his complices: spoken of just zeal, not of desire to revenge: verified in those that sin wittingly and knowing, for they descend, as it were, alive into hell.\f* \f + \fr 54:16 \ft The whole crew of the wicked conspire in iniquity.\f*
\v 17 But I have cried to God, and our Lord will save me.
\v 18 In the evening, and morning, & at midday, I will speak, and declare, and he will hear my voice. \f + \fr 54:18 \ft The Prophet alludeth to three more specially appointed hours of Divine service, the daily sacrifice at morning, and evening, and other sacrifices commonly about midday. Which also are the three principal times of Divine Service in the Church of Christ: Matins, Evensong, and the Sacrifice of Mass. Which Eutymius and other Grecians call Liturgiam. S. Clement also (li. 7. c. 25. Apost. Instit.) testifieth that the Apostles ordained three set hours of common prayer every day.\f* \f + \fr 54:18 \ft * or pray\f*
\v 19 He will redeem my soul in peace from them, that approach to me: because among many they were with me. \f + \fr 54:19 \ft Many enemies combined together approached unto me, to overthrow me.\f*
\v 20 God will hear, and he which is before the worlds will humble them. \f + \fr 54:20 \ft Eternal God.\f*
\v 21 For there is no change with them, & they feared not God: he hath stretched forth his hand in repaying. \f + \fr 54:21 \ft They will never repent of their wickedness.\f*
\v 22 They have contaminated his testament, they are divided by the wrath of his countenance; and his heart hath approached. His words are made softer than oil: and the same are darts. \f + \fr 54:22 \ft They harden their hearts against his threatened wrath:\f* \f + \fr 54:22 \ft but God's providence illuminateth others to know and teach the truth, when it is impugned or contemned.\f* \f + \fr 54:22 \ft God's words, which in themselves are meek and sweet,\f* \f + \fr 54:22 \ft are hard to the incredulous, & as darts that wound them. Christ said (Ioan. 6.) Unless one eat my flesh, & drink my blood, he shall not have life in him, which the Capharnaites not understanding said one to another: This is a hard speech, who can abide it? Which S. Augustin here saith was the first heresy against our Saviour's preaching. It was not hard to S. Peter, who in the name of the rest, answered, that Christ had the words of eternal life. He yet understood not the secret of our Lord's speech, but he piously believed that the words were good, which he understood not.\f*
\v 23 Cast thy care upon our Lord: and he will nourish thee: he will not give fluctuation to the just for ever. \f + \fr 54:23 \ft Therefore in all doubts of doctrine, in all distresses of persecution, and other difficulties which surpass thy weakness, cast thy care upon our Lord, and he will nourish thee.\f* \f + \fr 54:23 \ft He will not suffer the just to remain always in fluctuation, that is, in doubtful, dangerous, and wavering thoughts or perplexities, as when a ship is tossed in the waves of the sea, but will give quiet repose of mind, as in a sure haven without danger of drowning.\f*
\v 24 But thou, o God, wilt bring them down into the pit of destruction. Bloody and deceitful men shall not live half their days, but I will hope in thee, o Lord. \f + \fr 54:24 \ft Contrarywise the wicked and obstinate shall fall into destruction.\f* \f + \fr 54:24 \ft Often or for most part blood-suckers die before the course of nature requireth, as Saul, Absalom, Achitophel, Achab, Jezabel, and the like.\f*
\c 55
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for a people, that is made far from the Saints, David in the inscription of the title, when the foreigners held him in Geth. \f + \fr 55:1 \ft This Psalm pertaineth also to future times,\f* \f + \fr 55:1 \ft for the use of any just persons, or people, that are against their will separated from the public divine Service of holy Church:\f* \f + \fr 55:1 \ft most worthy to be noted with title, for perpetual memory,\f* \f + \fr 55:1 \ft made by David when the Philistiims detected him to their King in Geth.\f*
\v 2 Have mercy on me, o God, because man hath trodden upon me: all the day impugning he hath afflicted me. \f + \fr 55:2 \ft Now one sort of ill disposed men, now another,\f* \f + \fr 55:2 \ft never cease to seek my destruction.\f*
\v 3 Mine enemies have trodden upon me all the day: because they are many that war against me. \f + \fr 55:3 \ft Saul with his great army, the Philistiims, & other strangers, some in manifest hostility, others detecting and betraying me to mine adversaries. So all that live godly in Christ have many enemies visible and invisible.\f*
\v 4 From the height of the day I shall fear: but I will trust in thee. \f + \fr 55:4 \ft Of these most eminent great dangers I am indeed afeared,\f* \f + \fr 55:4 \ft but so that my trust and assured confidence is in thee, o God.\f*
\v 5 In God I will praise my words, in God have I hoped: I will not fear what flesh may do to me. \f + \fr 55:5 \ft Words and promises made to me, or the good which I speak or do by God's grace.\f*
\v 6 All the day did they detest my words; against me all their cogitations are unto evil. \f + \fr 55:6 \ft They calumniate whatsoever I say,\f* \f + \fr 55:6 \ft wrestling all my words to evil sense.\f*
\v 7 They will inhabit and keep secret: they will observe my heel. As they have expected my soul, \f + \fr 55:7 \ft They meet together, and secretly conspire to entrap me or catch me tripping.\f* \f + \fr 55:7 \ft To take my life:\f*
\v 8 for nothing shalt thou save them: in wrath thou wilt break peoples. O God, \f + \fr 55:8 \ft for this their vain purpose to destroy me, thou wilt save them, as they deserve, that is,\f* \f + \fr 55:8 \ft thou wilt break them in pieces.\f*
\v 9 I have shewed my life to thee: thou hast set my tears in thy sight. As also in thy promise:
\v 10 then shall mine enemies be turned backward. In what day soever I shall invocate thee: lo I have known that thou art my God.
\v 11 In God I will praise the word, in our Lord will I praise thee saying: I have hoped in God, I will not fear what man can do to me. \f + \fr 55:11 \ft Iwill always gratefully acknowledge thy promises, and sayings, for they are assured.\f*
\v 12 In me, o God are thy vows, which I will render, praises to thee. \f + \fr 55:12 \ft Ihave purposed and vowed to offer sacrifice of praise, and by thy help will perform it.\f*
\v 13 Because thou hast delivered my soul from death, and my feet from falling: that I may please before God, in the light of the living. \f + \fr 55:13 \ft Do that pleaseth God,\f* \f + \fr 55:13 \ft in true faith and pious works.\f*
\c 56
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, destroy not, to David in the inscription of the title, when he fled from the face of Saul into the cave. \f + \fr 56:1 \ft The heroical facts of David are for example to all Christians.\f* \f + \fr 56:1 \ft Innocent David having opportunity to kill his unjust persecutor, obeyed the motion of God, suggesting unto him, not to destroy his enemy, contrary to the counsel of his friends:\f* \f + \fr 56:1 \ft a thing most worthy to be recorded for perpetual memory,\f* \f + \fr 56:1 \ft being in so great and unjust trouble, as to lie in the cave of a mountain, yet spared to kill, or hurt him, that drive him into such straits. See the history 1. Reg. 24.\f*
\v 2 Have mercy on me, o God, have mercy on me: because my soul hath trusted in thee. And I will hope in the shadow of thy wings, until iniquity pass.
\v 3 I will cry to God the highest: God that hath done me good.
\v 4 He sent from heaven, and delivered me: he hath given into reproach them that trod upon me. God hath sent his mercy and his truth, \f + \fr 56:4 \ft Extraordinary divine help, passing man's power.\f* \f + \fr 56:4 \ft It fell reproachfully to Saul, that David might have slain him if he would, yet did neither hurt him, nor insult upon him, but meekly and piously admonished him of his error, and injurious persecution.\f*
\v 5 and hath delivered my soul out of the midst of lions' whelps: I slept troubled. The sons of men, their teeth are weapons and arrows: and their tongue a sharp sword. \f + \fr 56:5 \ft My life\f* \f + \fr 56:5 \ft from most mighty and ravenous persecuters.\f* \f + \fr 56:5 \ft Though they have not lion's natural teeth, yet they exercise cruelty by artificial weapons,\f* \f + \fr 56:5 \ft and with their cruel tongues incite their followers to the same fury. 1. Reg. 22. v. 16.\f*
\v 6 Be exalted above the heavens, o God: and thy glory upon all the earth.
\v 7 They prepared a snare for my feet: and bowed down my soul. They digged a pit before my face: and they are fallen into it. \f + \fr 56:7 \ft Saul endeavoured many ways to overthrow David, amongst other means provoked him to set upon the Philistiims, thinking they should have slain him. 1. Reg. 18. v. 17. but the same Philistiims overthrew Saul. 1. Reg. 31.\f*
\v 8 My heart is ready, o God, my heart is ready: I will sing, and say a Psalm. \f + \fr 56:8 \ft Psalms more in use with Christian Gentiles, than they were with the Jews. See page. 12.\f*
\v 9 Arise my glory, arise psalter and harp: I will arise early.
\v 10 I will confess to thee among peoples, o Lord: and I will say a Psalm to thee among the Gentiles. \f + \fr 56:10 \ft See previous note\f*
\v 11 Because thy mercy is magnified even to the heavens, and thy truth even to the clouds.
\v 12 Be exalted above the heavens o God: and thy glory upon all the earth.
\c 57
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, destroy not, to David, in the inscription of the title. \f + \fr 57:1 \ft This Psalm was made upon the same occasion, and to the same purpose as the former,\f* \f + \fr 57:1 \ft to exhort the just and innocent to patience,\f* \f + \fr 57:1 \ft by David's memorable example.\f*
\v 2 If in very deed you speak justice: judge right things ye sons of men. \f + \fr 57:2 \ft Few are so wicked, but they speak and pretend just things:\f*
\v 3 For in the heart you work iniquities: in the earth your hands forge injustice. \f + \fr 57:3 \ft But neither think well,\f* \f + \fr 57:3 \ft nor do well, but both contrary, which feigned sanctity is double iniquity.\f*
\v 4 Sinners are alienated from the matrice, they have erred from the womb: they have spoken false things. \f + \fr 57:4 \ft These wicked sinners that flatter and incite King Saul, seem to have spent all their life from their infancy in malice.\f*
\v 5 They have fury according to the similitude of a serpent: as of the asp that is deaf, and stoppeth his ears. \f + \fr 57:5 \ft Their fury is unquiet, till they may wound the innocent with their poisonful sting,\f* \f + \fr 57:5 \ft neither will they harken to good admonitions, but stop their ears like an asp, that layeth one ear close to the ground, & stoppeth the other with his tail.\f*
\v 6 Which will not hear the voice of the enchanters, and of the sorcerer enchanting wisely.
\v 7 God shall break their teeth in their mouth, the cheek-tooth of the lions, our Lord will break in pieces. \f + \fr 57:7 \ft But God will break their cruel force,\f* \f + \fr 57:7 \ft though it seemeth most strong and insuperable.\f*
\v 8 They shall come to nothing as water running down: he hath bent his bow till they be weakened. \f + \fr 57:8 \ft God's just determination of punishing the wicked still remaineth bent and ready, though execution be some while deferred.\f*
\v 9 As wax that melteth, shall they be taken away: fire hath fallen on them, and they have not seen the sun. \f + \fr 57:9 \ft That force and power which is now invincible, hard and strong like a lion's strongest teeth, shall then be as impotent and soft as wax:\f* \f + \fr 57:9 \ft God's wrath, like fire, the most forcible element, shall fall upon them, and they shall be cast into utter darkness, deprived of the sun and all comfortable light.\f*
\v 10 Before your thorns did understand the old briar: as living so in wrath he swalloweth them. \f + \fr 57:10 \ft Before their malice can bring to effect the great mischiefs which they plot and purpose, God suddenly cutteth them off, before they fully understand of either sickness or death, casteth them as it were alive into hell.\f*
\v 11 The just shall rejoice when he shall see revenge: he shall wash his hands in the blood of a sinner. \f + \fr 57:11 \ft The just rejoice in the punishment of the wicked for three causes, first in zeal of justice, conforming his will and mind to God's judgement; secondly, for that himself through God's mercy hath escaped that terrible damnation; thirdly, for that he is now delivered from molestation, and continual tribulation.\f*
\v 12 And man shall say: If certes there be fruit to the just: there is a God certes judging them on the earth. \f + \fr 57:12 \ft The just seeing, or by faith knowing what punishment remaineth for the wicked, is thereby assured that the good shall reap fruit for his well-doing, and that in the mean time God ruleth and judgeth on the earth, though as yet it appeareth not so evidently.\f*
\c 58
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, destroy not, to David in the inscription of the title, when Saul sent, and watched his house to kill him. \f + \fr 58:1 \ft King Saul having thrice attempted in vain to kill David ( 1. Reg. 18. v. 11. &c. 19. v. 9. ) sent some of his guard to fetch him, from his own house, that he might be slain: but God moved the mind of Michol, to admonish him of the danger and to help him away in safety, though Saul thought she would have been a scandal unto him (or cause of ruin) by the hands of the Philistians. 1. Reg. 18. v. 21. Upon which occasion David made this Psalm. As he also made others,\f*
\v 2 Deliver me from mine enemies, o my God: and from them that rise up against me defend me.
\v 3 Deliver me from them that work iniquity: and from bloody men save me.
\v 4 Because lo they have taken my soul: the strong have fallen violently upon me. \f + \fr 58:4 \ft They have so straitly besieged me, that it is now in their hands to take away my life.\f*
\v 5 Neither is it mine iniquity, nor my sin, o Lord: without iniquity have I run, and gone directly. \f + \fr 58:5 \ft Of my part I have committed no fault against mine enemies, for which they can have any just cause to persecute me.\f*
\v 6 Rise up to meet me, and see: and thou, o Lord, the God of powers, God of Israel, attend to visit all nations: have no mercy on all that work iniquity. \f + \fr 58:6 \ft The Prophet foreseeing in spirit, that the Catholic Church shall be unjustly persecuted, prayeth, and teacheth others to pray, that God will mercifully visit his faithful people of all nations:\f* \f + \fr 58:6 \ft and not spare obstinate persecuters.\f*
\v 7 They will return at evening: and they shall suffer famine as dogs, and shall compass the city. \f + \fr 58:7 \ft Persecuters labouring how much, or how long soever, shall at night, that his, in the end of all their wicked endeavours be unsatisfied in their desires,\f* \f + \fr 58:7 \ft as hungry dogs that run hunting all the day, & night also, still seeking & not finding wherewith to fill their ravenous mouths and devouring bellies.\f*
\v 8 Behold they will speak in their mouth, and a sword in their lips: because who hath heard? \f + \fr 58:8 \ft They threaten and determine to use all cruelty,\f* \f + \fr 58:8 \ft as if there were no God, that heareth, and will punish it.\f*
\v 9 And thou, o Lord wilt scorn them: thou wilt bring to nought all the nations.
\v 10 I will keep my strength to thee: because thou art my receiver: \f + \fr 58:10 \ft Through God's grace the Church is still strong and the virtuous do persevere.\f*
\v 11 my God, thy mercy shall prevent me.
\v 12 God will shew unto me concerning mine enemies, kill them not lest sometime my peoples forget. Disperse them in thy strength: and depose them my protector, o Lord. \f + \fr 58:12 \ft God suffereth afflictions to fall upon his servants, to keep them exercised, lest in prosperity they forget their duties to him.\f* \f + \fr 58:12 \ft Deprive them of power, that they may not do so much evil as they desire.\f*
\v 13 The sin of their mouth, the word of their lips: and let them be taken in their pride. And for cursing and lying they shall be talked of \f + \fr 58:13 \ft After that their iniquity is complete\f* \f + \fr 58:13 \ft they shall be accused and punished for their blasphemies and lies.\f*
\v 14 in consummation: in wrath of consummation and they shall not be. And they shall know that God will rule over Jacob: and over the ends of the earth.
\v 15 They shall be turned at evening, and shall suffer famine as dogs: & shall compass the city. \f + \fr 58:15 \ft As v. 7.\f*
\v 16 They shall be dispersed to eat: and if they be not filled, they will murmur also. \f + \fr 58:16 \ft They shall in vain seek oil for their lamps with the foolish virgins, repent with Judas, and finding no help,\f* \f + \fr 58:16 \ft shall continually blaspheme in hell.\f*
\v 17 But I will sing thy strength: and will exalt thy mercy in the morning. Because thou art become my receiver, and my refuge in the day of my tribulation. \f + \fr 58:17 \ft In the resurrection.\f*
\v 18 My helper, I will sing to thee, because thou art God my receiver: my God, my mercy.
\c 59
\p
\v 0 victories, 11. achieved by God's only power. \f + \fr 59:0 \ft King David's thanks for victories. The 8. key.\f*
\v 1 Unto the end, for them that shall be changed, in the inscription of the title to David himself, for doctrine, \f + \fr 59:1 \ft The change of state from adversity to prosperity in the people of Israel, was a figure of the like change in the Church of Christ,\f* \f + \fr 59:1 \ft worthy to be remembered,\f* \f + \fr 59:1 \ft for the instruction\f* \f + \fr 59:1 \ft of God's beloved,\f*
\v 2 when he set fire on Mesopotamia of Syria, and in Sobal, and Joab returned, and struck Idumæa in the valley of salt-pits twelve thousand. \f + \fr 59:2 \ft as the same are more largely recorded in the books of Kings.\f*
\v 3 O God thou hast repelled us, & hast destroyed us: thou wast angry and hast had mercy on us. \f + \fr 59:3 \ft God suffereth his people to be afflicted, as well for their sins, as for exercise in virtue,\f* \f + \fr 59:3 \ft after sheweth his mercy in pardoning, and favour in advancing them.\f*
\v 4 Thou hast moved the earth, and hast troubled it: heal the breaches thereof, because it is moved.
\v 5 Thou hast shewed unto thy people hard things: thou hast made us drink the wine of compunction. \f + \fr 59:5 \ft Punishing sinners.\f*
\v 6 Thou hast given a signification to them that fear thee: that they fly from the face of the bow. \f + \fr 59:6 \ft Warning them to amend.\f*
\v 7 That thy beloved may be delivered, save me with thy right hand, and hear me. \f + \fr 59:7 \ft and then restoreth them to former good state.\f*
\v 8 God hath spoken in his holy: I shall rejoice, and shall divide Sichem: and shall measure the valley of tabernacles. \f + \fr 59:8 \ft God also as he hath promised by his holy oracle,\f* \f + \fr 59:8 \ft hath advanced King David in his temporal Kingdom, and doth much more advance him, and other elect in everlasting life.\f*
\v 9 Galaad is mine, and Manasses is mine: and Ephraim the strength of my head.
\v 10 Juda my king: Moab the pot of my hope. Into Edom I will stretch out my shoe: the foreigners are subject to me. \f + \fr 59:10 \ft As a vessel for meaner uses.\f* \f + \fr 59:10 \ft Bring it under my dominion.\f*
\v 11 Who shall conduct me into a fenced city? Who shall conduct me even into Idumea?
\v 12 Shall not thou, o God, that hast expelled us: and wilt not thou o God, go forth in our hosts? \f + \fr 59:12 \ft As God doth sometimes punish\f* \f + \fr 59:12 \ft so he also rewardeth.\f*
\v 13 Give us aid from tribulation: because man's salvation is vain.
\v 14 In God we shall do strength: and he shall bring to nothing them that afflict us. \f + \fr 59:14 \ft Strongly, with fortitude.\f*
\c 60
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, in hymns to David. \f + \fr 60:1 \ft In songs of praise and thanks to God.\f*
\v 2 Hear, o God, my petition: attend to my prayer.
\v 3 From the ends of the earth I have cried to thee: whilst my heart was in anguish, thou didst exalt me on a rock. \f + \fr 60:3 \ft From all coasts of the earth faithful people pray to God.\f* \f + \fr 60:3 \ft The Church builded upon an assured foundation, is exalted to great power and dignity.\f*
\v 4 Thou hast conducted me, because thou art made my hope: a tower of strength from the face of the enemy. \f + \fr 60:4 \ft God conducteth, defendeth, and delivereth those that confidently trust in him.\f*
\v 5 Ishall inhabit in thy tabernacle for ever: I shall be protected in the covert of thy wings. \f + \fr 60:5 \ft In the Church, a place of assured protection.\f*
\v 6 Because thou my God hast heard my prayer: thou hast given inheritance to those that fear thy name.
\v 7 Thou wilt add days upon the days of the king: his years even unto the day of generation and generation. \f + \fr 60:7 \ft Christ's kingdom, the Church, perpetual to the end of this world, and eternal after the general Resurrection.\f*
\v 8 He is permanent for ever in the sight of God: his mercy and truth who shall require? \f + \fr 60:8 \ft Who is able to understand or explicate how great Christ's mercy is in redeeming us,\f* \f + \fr 60:8 \ft and his truth in performing his promised rewards?\f*
\v 9 So will I say a Psalm to thy name for ever and ever: that I may render my vows from day to day. \f + \fr 60:9 \ft For so inestimable benefits I will always praise thee with Psalms, Canticles, or other thanks in this life.\f* \f + \fr 60:9 \ft and eternally in the life to come.\f*
\c 61
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for Idithun a Psalm of David. \f + \fr 61:1 \ft Directed to Idithun, one of the masters of music, to sing it, or to make tune for it.\f*
\v 2 Shall not my soul be subject to God? For of him is my salvation. \f + \fr 61:2 \ft The wicked treating to ruinate others, David, or any just man, feareth them not, because his soul is subject to God.\f*
\v 3 For he is my God, and my saviour: my receiver, I shall be moved no more. \f + \fr 61:3 \ft Therefore I firmly purpose never to be moved from God.\f*
\v 4 How long set you violently upon a man: you all do kill, as it were upon a wall that is leaning, and a wall shaken. \f + \fr 61:4 \ft In vain do you mine adversaries still assault me,\f* \f + \fr 61:4 \ft though ye be all confederate to kill me,\f* \f + \fr 61:4 \ft supposing me to be like a ruinous or shaken wall, that is easily thrown down.\f*
\v 5 But yet they thought to repel my price. I ran in thirst: they blessed with their mouth, and cursed with their heart. \f + \fr 61:5 \ft They think still to deprive me of my reward, the price of my labours and merits,\f* \f + \fr 61:5 \ft but I run so much more diligently, as thirsting after righteousness in this life, and glory in the next, to finish my course.\f* \f + \fr 61:5 \ft Amost dangerous tentation, when after threats and cruelty, persecutors endeavour by sweet words and promises to persuade the just to fall into sin.\f*
\v 6 But yet my soul be thou subject to God: because my patience is from him.
\v 7 Because he is my God, and my saviour: my helper I shall not remove. \f + \fr 61:7 \ft Iresolutely purpose not to yield to any tentation.\f*
\v 8 In God is my salvation, and my glory: the God of my help, and my hope is in God.
\v 9 Hope in him all ye the congregation of people: pour out your hearts before him: God is our helper for ever. \f + \fr 61:9 \ft God's faithful servants are not only constant themselves, but also exhort and persuade all others, as much as in them lieth, to serve God and trust in him.\f*
\v 10 But yet the children of men are vain, the children of men are liars in balances: that they may deceive by vanity together. \f + \fr 61:10 \ft Using false weights they defraud one another.\f*
\v 11 Hope not in iniquity, and covet not robberies: if riches abound set not your heart upon them.
\v 12 Once hath God spoken, these two things have I heard: \f + \fr 61:12 \ft God having once spoken it is most assured.\f* \f + \fr 61:12 \ft Two especial attributes of God.\f*
\v 13 That power is God's, and mercy, o Lord, is to thee: because thou wilt render to every one according to his works. \f + \fr 61:13 \ft God is omnipotent, so that he can both reward and punish infinitely;\f* \f + \fr 61:13 \ft and Merciful, that he is ready to receive all sinners into his favour, if they will repent & turn to him.\f*
\c 62
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of David when he was in the desert of Juda. \f + \fr 62:1 \ft Holy David made this devout meditation when he was in the forest of Haret, or desert of Ziph. 1. Reg. 22. & 23. and could not come to the tabernacle of God, nor to Jerusalem, where he especially desired to be, in the inheritance of our Lord, which was to him a great affliction. As the like is now to Catholics, when they are put in close prison for their faith, or otherwise hindered, that they cannot be present at the most holy and daily Sacrifice. In which case we must supply as we may, this great loss, and comfort ourselves with this, or like Psalm, or prayer, saying: O God my God, to thee I watch.\f*
\v 2 O God my God to thee I watch, from the morning light. My soul hath thirsted to thee, my flesh to thee very many ways. \f + \fr 62:2 \ft Even from the first dawning of the morning,\f* \f + \fr 62:2 \ft my soul thirsteth after thee,\f* \f + \fr 62:2 \ft yea also my very flesh, and whole body feeleth great pains, by this affliction of mind, and desireth relief and rest.\f*
\v 3 In a desert land, and inaccessible, and without water, so in the holy have I appeared to thee, that I might see thy strength, and thy glory. \f + \fr 62:3 \ft Being now in case that I cannot serve thee, o God, as I would, yet I exhibit myself present in spirit, before thy holy place,\f* \f + \fr 62:3 \ft meditating thy power, and thy glory.\f*
\v 4 Because thy mercy is better than lives, my lips shall praise thee. \f + \fr 62:4 \ft This consolation in banishment from thy divine Service, is sweeter to me than many temporal lives, or any worldly prosperity.\f*
\v 5 So will I bless thee in my life: and in thy name I will lift up my hands. \f + \fr 62:5 \ft for as the Passions of Christ abound in us (saith S. Paul. 2. Cor. 1. ) so also by Christ our comfort aboundeth.\f*
\v 6 As with marrow and fatness let my soul be filled: and my mouth shall praise with lips of exultation. \f + \fr 62:6 \ft Replenish my soul, o God, with the aboundance of thy grace,\f* \f + \fr 62:6 \ft so shall I be more able to praise thee.\f*
\v 7 If I have been mindful of thee upon my bed, in the morning I will meditate on thee: \f + \fr 62:7 \ft Seeing in the night, also in my bed I meditate on thee;\f* \f + \fr 62:7 \ft Iwill more diligently do the same in the morning.\f*
\v 8 because thou hast been my helper.
\v 9 And in the covert of thy wings I will rejoice, my soul hath cleaved after thee: thy right hand hath received me.
\v 10 But they in vain have sought my soul, they shall enter into the inferior parts of the earth. \f + \fr 62:10 \ft My temporal and spiritual enemies:\f* \f + \fr 62:10 \ft and they shall be damned for their sins.\f*
\v 11 They shall be delivered into the hands of the sword, they shall be the portions of foxes. \f + \fr 62:11 \ft It happened literally to Saul, that he was slain in battle; which he made against his enemies\f* \f + \fr 62:11 \ft and his dead body was hung on a wall (1. Reg. 31.) exposed to wild beasts, or birds, though it was afterwards burnt and buried.\f*
\v 12 But the king shall rejoice in God, all shall be praised that swear by him: because the mouth is stopped of those that speak wicked things. \f + \fr 62:12 \ft David was presently after Saul's death exalted to the Kingdom, in figure of Christ, whose name and glory was exalted, after the destruction of the Jews by Pagan Emperors.\f*
\c 63
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm of David.
\v 2 Hear o God my prayer when I make petition: from the fear of my enemy deliver my soul.
\v 3 Thou hast protected me from the assembly of the malignant: from the multitude of them that work iniquity. \f + \fr 63:3 \ft By example of thy former protection,\f* \f + \fr 63:3 \ft from the conspiracy of wicked men, I trust most assuredly in thy help.\f*
\v 4 Because they have sharpened their tongues as a sword: they have bent the bow a bitter thing,
\v 5 that they may shoot in secrets at the immaculate.
\v 6 Suddenly they will shoot at him, and will not fear: they have confirmed to themselves a wicked word. They have talked to hide snares: they have said, Who shall see them? \f + \fr 63:6 \ft They are resolved to entrap me.\f*
\v 7 They have searched iniquities: they have failed searching with scrutiny. \f + \fr 63:7 \ft But as they have failed, so they shall still fail, and be overreached in their bad counsels, as Achitophel. 2. Reg. 17.\f*
\v 8 Man shall come to a deep heart: and God shall be exalted. Children's arrows are made their wounds: \f + \fr 63:8 \ft God hath chosen the weak of this world to confound the strong.\f*
\v 9 and their tongues are weakened against them. All that saw them were troubled: \f + \fr 63:9 \ft Much marveled seeing the wicked so punished.\f*
\v 10 and every man feared. And they shewed forth the works of God: and they understood his doings.
\v 11 The just shall rejoice in our Lord, and shall hope in him, & all the right of heart shall be praised. \f + \fr 63:11 \ft The just shall be praised, for rightly serving God.\f*
\c 64
\p
\v 1 To the end, a Psalm of David, the Canticle of Jeremy, and Ezechiel, to the people of the transmigration, when they began to go forth. \f + \fr 64:1 \ft The seventy Interpreters seeing David here prophesy of the people's return from Babylon, added the names of Jeremy and Ezechiel, who being in that captivity prophesied the same more largely. As likewise these and other Prophets, foresaw in spirit, and more especially prophesied the going forth of all nations from Babylon, that is, forsaking Idolatry, and embracing true Religion in the Church of Christ, so S. Augustin, Eutymius, and others.\f*
\v 2 An hymn, o God, becometh thee in Sion: & a vow shall be rendered to thee in Jerusalem. \f + \fr 64:2 \ft Not in Babylon, nor elsewhere, but only in the Church, praises and vows are grateful to God.\f*
\v 3 Hear my prayer: all flesh shall come to thee. \f + \fr 64:3 \ft All nations shall know thee.\f*
\v 4 The words of the wicked have prevailed upon us: and thou wilt be propitious to our impieties. \f + \fr 64:4 \ft The wicked are insolent in threatening;\f* \f + \fr 64:4 \ft but thou mercifully pardoning our sins, they shall not hurt us.\f*
\v 5 Blessed is he whom thou hast chosen and taken: he shall dwell in thy courts. \f + \fr 64:5 \ft They are happy to whom thou hast prepared grace and glory.\f*
\v 6 We shall be replenished in the goods of thy house: holy is thy temple, marvelous in equity. Hear us, o God our saviour, the hope of all the ends of the earth, and in the sea far. \f + \fr 64:6 \ft The voices of the faithful, rejoicing in the hope of\f* \f + \fr 64:6 \ft Nothing polluted shall enter into heaven. Apo. 21.\f*
\v 7 Preparing mountains in thy strength, girded with might: \f + \fr 64:7 \ft Thou which art all powerful, as appeareth by the huge mountains\f*
\v 8 which troublest the depths of the sea, the sound of the waves thereof. \f + \fr 64:8 \ft seas, and other thy works.\f*
\v 9 The Gentiles shall be troubled, and they that inhabit the borders shall be afraid of thy signs: the out-goings of the morning and evening thou shalt delight. \f + \fr 64:9 \ft Thou wilt by thy omnipotent power move the hearts of obdurate men, and so convert innumerable of all nations to thee.\f* \f + \fr 64:9 \ft Thou wilt draw many to thee, with joy and gladness, from the uttermost coasts of the east and west.\f*
\v 10 Thou hast visited the earth, and hast inebriated it: thou hast multiplied to enrich it. The river of God is replenished with waters, thou hast prepared their meat: because so is the preparation thereof. \f + \fr 64:10 \ft God wrought diverse miracles in waters ( Gen. 7. Exo. 7. 14. 15. Iosue. 3. 4. Reg. 5. 6 &c.)\f* \f + \fr 64:10 \ft likewise in providing meat for his people ( Exo. 16, 3. Reg. 17, 4. Reg. 4, 7. &c.) which were figures of Baptism, Eucharist, and other Sacraments of Christ, washing from sins, and augmenting grace,\f* \f + \fr 64:10 \ft so replenishing the Church with most sacred Mysteries.\f*
\v 11 Inebriate her rivers, multiply her fruits: in her drops she shall rejoice springing. \f + \fr 64:11 \ft Endowing the Apostles and other preachers with spiritual grace and learning,\f* \f + \fr 64:11 \ft continuing the succession of pastors to water and seed the faithful people.\f*
\v 12 Thou wilt bless the crown of the year of thy goodness: and thy fields shall be replenished with plenty. \f + \fr 64:12 \ft God blesseth the whole course, or circle of time, of the Church militant in this world,\f* \f + \fr 64:12 \ft and the crown, or happy end of every just person's life.\f*
\v 13 The beautiful places of the desert shall be fat: and the little hills shall be girded about with exultation. \f + \fr 64:13 \ft Even those which before had only a shew of beauty, but indeed were barren, shall yield aboundant fruit.\f* \f + \fr 64:13 \ft Those which are more eminent shall particularly rejoice in their own and other's spiritual progress in virtue.\f*
\v 14 The rams of the sheep are clothed, and the valleys shall abound with corn: they will cry, yea they will say an hymn. \f + \fr 64:14 \ft The principal pastors shall in proportion rejoice above the rest for the grace and glory of all their flock.\f* \f + \fr 64:14 \ft The subjects also and inferior people shall be satiate with their happy lot.\f* \f + \fr 64:14 \ft All together, prelates and people, higher and lower shall with uniform voice sing praises to God, and perpetual hymns.\f*
\c 65
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Canticle of resurrection. Make ye jubilation to God all the earth, \f + \fr 65:1 \ft Mystical resurrection, Gentiles succeeding in place of the Jews.\f* \f + \fr 65:1 \ft Shew your internal joy by external words and deeds.\f*
\v 2 say a Psalm to his name: give glory to his praise.
\v 3 Say ye to God: How terrible are thy works, o Lord! In the multitude of thy strength thine enemies shall lie to thee. \f + \fr 65:3 \ft In drowning the world, in confounding the tongues in Babel, in burning Sodom and Gomorrha with brimstone, in plaguing the Ægyptians, in drowning Pharao and his whole army in the red sea; in destroying the Chananites and other infidels, in punishing the ten tribes, and afterwards the other two by captivity, & innumerable other punishments, all for sins,\f* \f + \fr 65:3 \ft for which even the wicked, though not sincerely converted, yet of servile fear, feigned and falsely promised to amend, but performed it not: as Pharao afflicted with plagues, was forced to promise liberty to the children of Israel, which he afterwards denied.\f*
\v 4 Let all the earth adore thee, and sing to thee: let it sing a Psalm to thy name.
\v 5 Come ye, and see the works of God: terrible in counsels over the children of men.
\v 6 Who turneth the sea into dry land, in the river they shall pass on foot, there we shall rejoice in him. \f + \fr 65:6 \ft The red sea,\f* \f + \fr 65:6 \ft when Iosue brought the people over Iordan,\f* \f + \fr 65:6 \ft in remembering and reciting these singular benefits.\f*
\v 7 Who ruleth in his strength for ever his eyes look upon the gentiles: they that exasperate him let them not be exalted in themselves. \f + \fr 65:7 \ft God's chosen people the Jews did often exasperate God by their ingratitude, murmuring, and other sins: whom the Prophet therefore admonished,\f* \f + \fr 65:7 \ft not to be proud, lest they be subdued and brought low.\f*
\v 8 Ye Gentiles bless our God: and make the voice of his praise heard. \f + \fr 65:8 \ft By way of invitation the Psalmist prophesieth the conversion of Gentiles.\f*
\v 9 Who hath put my soul in life: and hath not given my feet to be moved. \f + \fr 65:9 \ft The voice of the whole Church: confessing God's providence and protection, that she never faileth; for the Jews falling from Christ the Gentiles believed in him; and some nations or countries falling from Religion, others are converted.\f*
\v 10 Because thou hast proved us, o God: by fire thou hast tried us, as silver is tried. \f + \fr 65:10 \ft God suffereth his Church to be persecuted with all kinds of tribulation, as some are here recited.\f*
\v 11 Thou hast brought us into a snare, thou hast laid tribulations on our back: thou hast set men upon our heads.
\v 12 We have passed through fire and water: and thou hast brought us out into refreshing. \f + \fr 65:12 \ft But through God's assistance his servants pass through, and overcome all tentations.\f*
\v 13 I will go into thy house with holocausts: I will render thee my vows: \f + \fr 65:13 \ft Sacrifice of thanks,\f* \f + \fr 65:13 \ft and voluntary vows,\f*
\v 14 which my lips have distinguished. And my mouth hath spoken in my tribulation. \f + \fr 65:14 \ft that which any promiseth to God in tribulation, they must perform accordingly.\f*
\v 15 Holocausts with marrow will I offer to thee, with incense of rams: I will offer to thee oxen with buck goats. \f + \fr 65:15 \ft These were the best external sacrifices of the old law:\f*
\v 16 Come ye, hear, and I will tell all ye that fear God, what great things he hath done for my soul. \f + \fr 65:16 \ft But both then and now the internal sacrifices of contrite heart, of justice, and of divine praise best please God.\f*
\v 17 To him have I cried with my mouth, and have exulted under my tongue. \f + \fr 65:17 \ft From the heart, which is under the tongue, and directeth the tongue what to speak.\f*
\v 18 If I have beheld iniquity in my heart, our Lord will not hear. \f + \fr 65:18 \ft Whosoever will be heard in prayer, must repent of his sins.\f*
\v 19 Therefore hath God heard, and hath attended to the voice of my petition.
\v 20 Blessed be God who hath not removed my prayer, and his mercy from me.
\c 66
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, in hymns, a Psalm of Canticle to David. \f + \fr 66:1 \ft This Psalm beginning to be sung by voices, instruments were adjoined.\f*
\v 2 God have mercy upon us, and bless us: illuminate his countenance upon us, and have mercy on us. \f + \fr 66:2 \ft God first remit our sins:\f* \f + \fr 66:2 \ft then give us thy manifold graces,\f* \f + \fr 66:2 \ft grant faith and repentance,\f* \f + \fr 66:2 \ft and so forgiveness of sins.\f*
\v 3 That we may know thy way upon earth: in all nations thy salvation.
\v 4 Let peoples, o God, confess to thee: let all peoples confess to thee. \f + \fr 66:4 \ft All nations shall be converted.\f*
\v 5 Let nations be glad & rejoice: because thou judgest peoples in equity, and the nations in earth thou doest direct.
\v 6 Let peoples, o God, confess to thee, let all peoples confess to thee:
\v 7 the earth hath yielded her fruit. God, our God bless us, \f + \fr 66:7 \ft God the Father,\f* \f + \fr 66:7 \ft God the Son,\f*
\v 8 God bless us: and let all the ends of the earth fear him. \f + \fr 66:8 \ft God the Holy Ghost, save the people of all nations, by Evangelical preaching of thee, the most Blessed Trinity.\f*
\c 67
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm of Canticle, to David himself.
\v 2 Let God arise, and let his enemies be dispersed, and let them that hate him fly from his face. \f + \fr 67:2 \ft In manner of praying that God will vouchsafe to defend the Church, the Psalmist prophesieth that God will arise,\f* \f + \fr 67:2 \ft and the enemies shall fly away, not daring to abide the combat.\f*
\v 3 As smoke vanisheth, let them vanish away: as wax melteth at the presence of fire, so let sinners perish at the presence of God.
\v 4 And let the just make merry, and rejoice in the sight of God: and let them be delighted in mirth. \f + \fr 67:4 \ft As God is terrible to the wicked: so he is comfortable to the just.\f*
\v 5 Sing to God, say a Psalm to his name: make way to him, who mounteth upon the west, Lord is his name. Rejoice ye in his sight, they shall be troubled at the presence of him: \f + \fr 67:5 \ft Resist not God's inspiration, but receive it with joy and thanks.\f* \f + \fr 67:5 \ft Who triumpheth over death\f* \f + \fr 67:5 \ft God is Lord, not only of these or those nations, countries or other creatures, but absolutely and universally of all.\f*
\v 6 the father of orphans, and judge of widows. God in his holy place: \f + \fr 67:6 \ft That is the true holy Church, which hath\f*
\v 7 God that maketh men to inhabit of one manner in a house. That bringeth forth them that be bound, in strength, likewise them that exasperate, that dwell in sepulchres. \f + \fr 67:7 \ft unity in doctrine, touching faith and manners. S. Cypr. ep. 76.\f* \f + \fr 67:7 \ft That be bound in sin,\f* \f + \fr 67:7 \ft even rebellious wills are altered by God's mercy, & freely embrace his law,\f* \f + \fr 67:7 \ft also the dead and dry hearts that cared not for spiritual things are softened, and quickened with new grace.\f*
\v 8 O God when thou wentest forth in the sight of thy people, when thou didst pass through the desert. \f + \fr 67:8 \ft The benefits bestowed on the Israelites, are written in the books of Moyses, Iosue, and Judges.\f*
\v 9 The earth was moved, and the heavens also distilled, at the presence of the God of Sina, at the face of the God of Israel.
\v 10 Voluntary rain shalt thou separate, o God, to thine inheritance: and it was weakened, but thou hath perfiteth it. \f + \fr 67:10 \ft Not man's deserving, but God's mere good will, and free grace caused Christ to come, and by himself and his Apostles to preach the Evangelical doctrine, which watereth the whole world.\f* \f + \fr 67:10 \ft God chose the weak, but made them strong.\f*
\v 11 Thy living creatures shall dwell in it: thou hast prepared in thy sweetness for the poor, o God. \f + \fr 67:11 \ft Those whom thou has chosen, and so made thine own peculiar people, shall enjoy this grace.\f* \f + \fr 67:11 \ft Thou gavest Manna in the desert, the B. Sacrament in the new testament.\f*
\v 12 Our Lord shall give the word to them that evangelize, with great power. \f + \fr 67:12 \ft God giveth to the Preacher what to speak,\f* \f + \fr 67:12 \ft and to some he giveth also power to work miracles, in confirmation of their doctrine. Mar. 16.\f*
\v 13 The King of hosts the beloved of the beloved: and to the beauty of the house, to divide the spoils. \f + \fr 67:13 \ft Some potent King, or (as it is in Hebrew) Kings being beloved, of the beloved of God, the only Son of God, shall yield themselves to the same beloved Son of God:\f* \f + \fr 67:13 \ft which shall redound to the glory and beauty of his Church, gaining such spiritual preys from the devil.\f*
\v 14 If ye sleep among the midst of the lots, the wings of a dove laid over with silver, and the hinder parts of her back in the paleness of gold. \f + \fr 67:14 \ft If you be in such danger, that the adversaries cast dice, or lots for your persons, and goods, yet you shall be delivered, as if a dove, with her glistering feathers, like silver and gold, fly away into a secure place, without loss or diminution, but rather with increase of virtues.\f*
\v 15 Whilst the heavenly discerneth kings over her, with snow they shall be made white in Selmon. \f + \fr 67:15 \ft When the heavenly King determineth thus of earthly Kings,\f* \f + \fr 67:15 \ft they shall be purged from their sins, and made white like snow, that falleth in mount Selmon. which is a shadowed hill, thick with trees, in mount Ephraim near to Jordan.\f*
\v 16 The mountain of God a fat mountain. A mountain curded as cheese, a fat mountain: \f + \fr 67:16 \ft The Church of God is visible, and durable like to a mountain.\f* \f + \fr 67:16 \ft Combined, or joined together, as when milk is turned into curd, and so into cheese.\f* \f + \fr 67:16 \ft Fruitful, enriched by spiritual gifts of the Holy Ghost.\f*
\v 17 why suppose you curded mountains? A mountain, in which it hath well pleased God to dwell therein: for indeed our Lord will dwell even to the end. \f + \fr 67:17 \ft Ye that are not of this Church, do in vain and erroneously imagine, that any other mountains are united.\f*
\v 18 The chariot of God is ten thousand fold, thousands of them that rejoice, our Lord in them, in Sina in the holy place. \f + \fr 67:18 \ft Innumerable Angels, ministers of God's will, do continually attend upon his Divine Majesty, as if he (who otherwise needeth no service) were carried by them, as in a\f* \f + \fr 67:18 \ft So God appeared in Majesty, when he gave his law in mount Sinai.\f*
\v 19 Thou art ascended on high, thou hast taken captivity: thou hast received gifts in men: for even those that do not believe, our Lord God to inhabit. \f + \fr 67:19 \ft Christ ascended with innumerable Angels attending upon him,\f* \f + \fr 67:19 \ft carried with him the fathers of the old testament, that had been captive,\f* \f + \fr 67:19 \ft as man he received gifts of God, in and for men, his faithful servants,\f* \f + \fr 67:19 \ft yea also he received for his merit, that innumerable, which before were incredulous were converted, and God dwelt in their souls.\f*
\v 20 Blessed be our Lord day by day: the God of our salvations will make us a prosperous journey.
\v 21 Our God is the God of saving: and the issues of death are of our Lord, our Lord. \f + \fr 67:21 \ft Our Lord, I say, our Lord, and none but he could overcome death by dying.\f*
\v 22 But yet God still break the heads of his enemies: the hairy crown of them, that walk in their sins. \f + \fr 67:22 \ft Though Christ died to deliver all men from death, yet he will give capital sentence of eternal death to all that obstinately remain his enemies, and multiply sins upon sins, to the end of their temporal life.\f*
\v 23 Our Lord said: Out of Basan I will convert, I will convert into the depth of the sea. \f + \fr 67:23 \ft Even of the rudest barbarous nations, many shall be converted to Christianity\f* \f + \fr 67:23 \ft namely God's grace is extended into the Islands of the Ocean, and other seas.\f*
\v 24 That thy foot may be dipped in blood: the tongue of thy dogs \add (made red)\add* with the same \add (blood)\add* of the enemies. \f + \fr 67:24 \ft But such severe slaughter shall fall upon the obstinate contemners of this grace, that men's feet shall be defiled in their blood, and dogs shall lap it.\f* \f + \fr 67:24 \ft Ex inimicis ab ipso.\f*
\v 25 They have seen thy enterings in, o God, the enterings of my God: of my King who is in the holy place. \f + \fr 67:25 \ft Many have seen, or known in general, but the faithful more exactly know how Christ came into this world, his conversation therein, and his going forth;\f* \f + \fr 67:25 \ft his reigning now in heaven our Mediator, by whom all other intercessors have access to God.\f*
\v 26 Princes came before joined with them that sang, in the midst of young women playing on timbrels. \f + \fr 67:26 \ft The Apostles sowing the first seed of Evangelical doctrine,\f* \f + \fr 67:26 \ft with whom other Apostolical men,\f* \f + \fr 67:26 \ft and other souls of all nations converted by their preaching, most joyfully sing together in heart, voice, & instruments: especially in good works, shew their grateful affections to our Redeemer.\f*
\v 27 In Churches bless ye God our Lord, of the fountains of Israel. \f + \fr 67:27 \ft And all this in the particular Churches of diverse Kingdoms, and parts of the world:\f* \f + \fr 67:27 \ft beginning with the Israelites in Jerusalem, and so proceeding into all Jury, and Samaria, and to the utmost of the earth. Act. 1.\f*
\v 28 There Benjamin a young man, in excess of mind. The Princes of Juda their leaders: the Princes of Zabulon, the Princes of Nephthali. \f + \fr 67:28 \ft S. Paul of Jacob's youngest son Benjamin, last called to Apostleship, was chiefly sent to the Gentiles.\f* \f + \fr 67:28 \ft Other Apostles of diverse tribes sent first to the Jews, secondarily to Gentiles.\f*
\v 29 Command thy strength, o God: confirm this, o God, which thou hast wrought in us. \f + \fr 67:29 \ft As the Church began by the omnipotent power of God; so by the same only power it is conserved.\f*
\v 30 From thy temple in Jerusalem, kings shall offer gifts to thee.
\v 31 Rebuke the wild beasts of the reed, the congregation of bulls in the kine of thy peoples: that they may exclude them, which are tried with silver. Dissipate the nations that will wars: \f + \fr 67:31 \ft Chastise therefore, o God, all persecuters of thy Church, who are but as weak wavering reeds, in comparison of thy power,\f* \f + \fr 67:31 \ft no better than bulls, with kine, that is, captains and popular people,\f* \f + \fr 67:31 \ft endeavouring to alienate the constant proved Confessors from their faith.\f*
\v 32 Legates shall come out of Ægypt: Æthiopia shall prevent his hands to God. \f + \fr 67:32 \ft Aprophecy that many should be converted to Christ in Ægypt, & Æthiopia: as appeareth by the innumerable multitude of religious Monks, & Nuns in those countries, shortly after the Apostles' days.\f*
\v 33 Ye Kingdoms of the earth sing to God: sing to our Lord: \f + \fr 67:33 \ft The like afterwards in all other nations, whom therefore the Prophet inviteth to praise God, for so inestimable benefits in the whole world.\f*
\v 34 Sing ye to God, that mounteth upon the heaven of heaven, to the East. Behold he will give to his voice the voice of strength: \f + \fr 67:34 \ft Christ will come to judge, in terror of voice, and with magnificence, accompanied with holy Angels and other Saints.\f*
\v 35 give you glory to God upon Israel, his magnificence, and his power in the clouds.
\v 36 God is marvelous in his Saints, the God of Israel he will give power and strength to his people, God be blessed.
\c 68
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for them that shall be changed, to David. \f + \fr 68:1 \ft Pertaining to the new Testament,\f* \f + \fr 68:1 \ft for Gentiles converted to Christianity, and from vice to virtue,\f* \f + \fr 68:1 \ft prefigured in David.\f*
\v 2 Save me, o God: because waters are entered into my soul. \f + \fr 68:2 \ft Vehement afflictions environ my heart.\f*
\v 3 I stick fast in the mire of the depth: and there is no sure standing. I am come into the depth of the sea: and a tempest hath overwhelmed me. \f + \fr 68:3 \ft Iam as one entangled with quicksand or quagmire in the bottom of a great water.\f*
\v 4 I have laboured crying, my jaws are made hoarse: my eyes have failed, whilst I hope in my God. \f + \fr 68:4 \ft Our Lord sweat blood for anguish in his prayer, and was not delivered from his passion, neither are his servants presently delivered from tribulations, but as is most to God's honour and their own good.\f*
\v 5 They are multiplied above the hairs of my head, that hate me without cause. Mine enemies are made strong, that have persecuted me unjustly: then did I pay the things that I took not. \f + \fr 68:5 \ft Our Saviour who had no sin, payed the ransom for all sins.\f*
\v 6 O God thou knowest my foolishness: and mine offences are not hid from thee. \f + \fr 68:6 \ft O God thou knowest, that this which seemeth folly to worldly men, is true wisdom\f* \f + \fr 68:6 \ft and though men charge men with offences, thou knowest that I am innocent.\f*
\v 7 Let them not be ashamed upon me, which expected thee, o Lord, Lord of hosts. Let them not be confounded upon me that seek thee, o God of Israel. \f + \fr 68:7 \ft Suffer not the weak to be scandalized in my passions.\f*
\v 8 Because for thee have I sustained reproach, confusion hath covered my face.
\v 9 I am become a foreigner to my brethren, and a stranger to the sons of my mother.
\v 10 Because the zeal of thy house hath eaten me: and the reproaches of them that reproached thee, fell upon me. \f + \fr 68:10 \ft The zeal of seeking God's honour, in propagating and advancing his Church, is the cause of persecution. As we see those are less persecuted, which have less godly zeal.\f*
\v 11 And I covered my soul in fasting: and it was made a reproach to me. \f + \fr 68:11 \ft The wicked do reproach those that mortify themselves.\f*
\v 12 And I put hair cloth my garment, & I became a parable to them.
\v 13 They spake against me that sat in the gate; and they sung against me that drank wine. \f + \fr 68:13 \ft The great men and judges, also the drunkards and rascality of the people.\f*
\v 14 But I, my prayer to thee, o Lord: a time of thy good pleasure, o God. In the multitude of thy mercy hear me, in the truth of thy salvation: \f + \fr 68:14 \ft But I direct my prayer to thee.\f* \f + \fr 68:14 \ft Expecting the time of thy good pleasure.\f*
\v 15 Deliver me out of the mire, that I stick not fast: deliver me from them that hate me, and from the depths of waters. \f + \fr 68:15 \ft Tribulations.\f*
\v 16 Let not the tempest of water drown me, nor the depth swallow me: neither let the pit shut his mouth upon me. \f + \fr 68:16 \ft Though Christ died and was buried, and in soul descended into hell, yet he could not be holden in his sepulchre, nor in limbo, but rose again.\f*
\v 17 Hear me, o Lord, because thy mercy is benign: according to the multitude of thy commiserations have respect to me.
\v 18 And turn not away thy face from thy servant: because I am in tribulation, hear me speedily.
\v 19 Attend to my soul, and deliver it: because of mine enemies deliver me. \f + \fr 68:19 \ft That they may either be converted, or confounded, and so do no more hurt.\f*
\v 20 Thou knowest my reproach & my confusion, & my shame.
\v 21 In thy sight are all they that afflict me, my heart hath looked for reproach and misery. And I expected somebody that would be sorry together with me, and there was none: and that would comfort me, and I found not. \f + \fr 68:21 \ft Not any that could mitigate our Saviour's affliction, would shew compassion towards him.\f*
\v 22 And they gave gall for my meat: & in my thirst they gave me vinegar to drink. \f + \fr 68:22 \ft But contrarywise when he complained of thirst, they gave him gall and vinegar to drink.\f*
\v 23 Let their table be made a snare before them, & for retributions, and for a scandal. \f + \fr 68:23 \ft A Prophecy of the destruction of the Jews, at the time of Pasch, when they should think to eat their paschal lamb with joy.\f*
\v 24 Let their eyes be darkened that they see not: and make their back crooked always. \f + \fr 68:24 \ft They are also blind in heart, that they will not see the truth of Christ's doctrine:\f* \f + \fr 68:24 \ft but bow themselves to earthly things, and worldly gains even to this day.\f*
\v 25 Pour out thy wrath upon them: and let the fury of thy wrath overtake them.
\v 26 Let their habitation be made desert: and in their tabernacles let there be none to dwell.
\v 27 Because whom thou hast strucken, they have persecuted: and upon the sorrow of my wounds they have added. \f + \fr 68:27 \ft Christ, whom God of his mercy designed to suffer death, for redemption of mankind, the Jews of mere envy and malice persecuted to death.\f*
\v 28 Add thou iniquity upon their iniquity: and let them not enter into thy justice. \f + \fr 68:28 \ft Aprophecy that God would suffer them, to fall from one iniquity to another.\f*
\v 29 Let them be put out of the book of the living: and with the just let them not be written. \f + \fr 68:29 \ft In the end of their lives, they shall not be found in the book of life, where they suppose themselves to be written.\f*
\v 30 I am poor and sorrowful: thy salvation, o God, hath received me. \f + \fr 68:30 \ft The voice of Christ, humbling himself to death, even to death of the Cross:\f* \f + \fr 68:30 \ft from which he rose again.\f*
\v 31 I will praise the name of God with canticle: and will magnify him in praise.
\v 32 And it shall please God more than a young calf: that bringeth forth horns and hoofs. \f + \fr 68:32 \ft Devout praise and thanks-giving please God more than sacrifices of the most tender calves, which were otherwise also grateful sacrifices.\f*
\v 33 Let the poor see and rejoice: seek ye God, and your soul shall live.
\v 34 Because our Lord hath heard the poor: and he hath not despised his prisoners. \f + \fr 68:34 \ft God doth assuredly comfort all such, as are imprisoned for professing the truth.\f*
\v 35 Let the heavens and earth praise him, the sea, and all the creeping beasts in them. \f + \fr 68:35 \ft All the creatures of God.\f*
\v 36 Because God will save Sion: and the cities of Juda shall be built up. And they shall inhabit there, & by inheritance, they shall get it. \f + \fr 68:36 \ft God will always establish and protect the Catholic Church:\f* \f + \fr 68:36 \ft and particular Churches, members of the universal, shall also prosper.\f*
\v 37 And the seed of his servants shall possess it, and they that love his name shall dwell in it. \f + \fr 68:37 \ft Perpetual succession of the Catholic Church.\f*
\c 69
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm of David, in remembrance, that our Lord saved him. \f + \fr 69:1 \ft An apt prayer also for the afflicted in the new Testament,\f* \f + \fr 69:1 \ft from the danger of Absalom (2. Reg. 18.) or from any persecutor.\f*
\v 2 O God intend unto my help: Lord make haste to help me. \f + \fr 69:2 \ft All men at all times need God's help:\f* \f + \fr 69:2 \ft but most present need, in present dangers. The rest of this Psalm is contained in the 39. Psalm from the 15. verse. But there the whole Church prayeth for help, the world being almost drowned in sins; here David, or other particular persons, or peoples pray in their several distresses.\f*
\v 3 Let them be confounded and be ashamed, that seek my soul.
\v 4 Let them be turned away backward, and be ashamed that will me evils. Let them be turned away forthwith ashamed, that say to me: Well, well.
\v 5 Let all that seek thee rejoice, and be glad in thee, and let them say always: Our Lord be magnified: which love thy salvation.
\v 6 But I am needy and poor: O God help me, thou art my helper, and deliverer: o Lord be not slack.
\c 70
\p
\v 1 A Psalm for David, of the sons of Jonadab, and the former captives. In thee o Lord I have hoped, let me not be confounded for ever: \f + \fr 70:1 \ft Though this Psalm (as also diverse others) is entitled to, or for David, it proveth not that some other was the author thereof, but the Seventy Interpreters insinuate hereby, that it pertaineth in more particular sort to David, growing old;\f* \f + \fr 70:1 \ft they add also the sons of Jonadab a most holy family;\f* \f + \fr 70:1 \ft who for their singular piety, were suffered to remain in Jerusalem in the first captivity. Jer. 35.\f* \f + \fr 70:1 \ft The words of David, or any faithful just person.\f*
\v 2 in thy justice deliver me, and receive me. Incline thine ear to me and save me. \f + \fr 70:2 \ft God of his justice revengeth the injuries done to his servants.\f*
\v 3 Be unto me for a God protector, and for a fenced place: that thou mayst save me: Because thou art my firmament, and my refuge.
\v 4 My God deliver me out of the hand of the sinner, and out of the hand of him that doth against the law, and of the unjust.
\v 5 Because thou art my patience, o Lord; o Lord my hope from my youth. \f + \fr 70:5 \ft Through thy grace I have patience to expect thy pleasure, when I shall be relieved.\f*
\v 6 Upon thee have I been confirmed from the womb: from my mother's belly thou art my protector. In thee is my singing always:
\v 7 I was made to many as a wonder: & thou art a strong helper. \f + \fr 70:7 \ft It seemeth strange to most men, why the just have more troubles than the wicked.\f*
\v 8 Let my mouth be filled with praise, that I may sing thy glory: all the day thy greatness. \f + \fr 70:8 \ft Anecessary prayer for perseverance, which none can have without special and continual help of grace.\f*
\v 9 Reject me not in the time of old age: when my strength shall fail, forsake me not. \f + \fr 70:9 \ft Against this special danger, and last assaults of the enemy, Christ hath instituted the Sacrament of Extreme Unction.\f*
\v 10 Because mine enemies have said to me: and they that watched my soul consulted together.
\v 11 saying: God hath forsaken him, pursue, and take him: because there is none to deliver.
\v 12 O God be not far from me: my God have respect to mine aid.
\v 13 Let them be confounded & fail that detract from my soul: let them be covered with confusion and shame, that seek evils to me.
\v 14 But I will always hope: and will add upon all thy praise. \f + \fr 70:14 \ft The best means to conserve virtue, is to exercise the same, adding good works towards our neighbours, and praises to God.\f*
\v 15 My mouth shall shew forth thy justice: all the day thy salvation. Because I have not known learning, I will enter into the powers of our Lord: \f + \fr 70:15 \ft Iprofess not exact knowledge of natural things;\f* \f + \fr 70:15 \ft but I consider and contemplate the infinite power of God, which appeareth in his works,\f* \f + \fr 70:15 \ft and his just judgements, as partly have appeared in punishing, and rewarding some in this life, but especially will be manifest in the end of this world.\f*
\v 16 O Lord I will be mindful of thy justice only.
\v 17 O God thou hast taught me from my youth: and until now I will pronounce thy marvelous works.
\v 18 And unto ancient age, and old age: o God, forsake me not? Until I shew forth thy arm to all the generation, that is to come. Thy might,
\v 19 and thy justice, o God, even to the highest, great marvels, which thou hast done: O God who may be like to thee?
\v 20 How great tribulations hast thou shewed me, many and evil: and turning thou hast quickened me: and from the depths of the earth thou hast brought me back again. \f + \fr 70:20 \ft After tribulations recreated me.\f*
\v 21 Thou hast multiplied thy magnificence: and being turned thou hast comforted me.
\v 22 For I also will confess to thee in the instruments of Psalm thy truth: O God, I will sing to thee on the harp, holy one of Israel.
\v 23 My lips shall rejoice when I shall sing to thee; and my soul which thou hast redeemed. \f + \fr 70:23 \ft Iwill praise thee with mouth and heart.\f*
\v 24 Yea and my tongue all the day shall meditate thy justice: when they shall be confounded and ashamed that seek evils to me.
\c 71
\p
\v 1 Concerning Salomon. \f + \fr 71:1 \ft This Psalm is of Christ, prefigured by Salomon, whose Kingdom was most glorious of all the Kings of God's people; for of King Salomon himself many things in this Psalm cannot be truly understood. S. Aug.\f*
\v 2 O God give thy judgment to the king: and thy justice to the son of the king. To judge thy people in justice, and thy poor in judgment. \f + \fr 71:2 \ft O God most blessed Trinity, give power and authority, to the Son of Man, God incarnate, King of all kings,\f* \f + \fr 71:2 \ft the Son of king David, to judge for mankind against the devil.\f* \f + \fr 71:2 \ft Christ paying ransom for all mankind, and so man renouncing the devil and serving God, is justly, not injuriously delivered from captivity of sin, and of the devil.\f*
\v 3 Let the mountains receive peace for the people: and the little hills justice. \f + \fr 71:3 \ft Aprophecy of the Apostles receiving power to preach Christ's Gospel, of peace and reconciliation of men to God by penance,\f* \f + \fr 71:3 \ft and of other Apostolical men that follow their steps.\f*
\v 4 He shall judge the poor of the people, and shall save the children of the poor: and he shall humble the calumniator. \f + \fr 71:4 \ft Salomon in figure of Christ was for a time a just and good King.\f*
\v 5 And he shall continue with the sun, and before the moon in generation and generation. \f + \fr 71:5 \ft But only Christ, not Salomon, nor any other King of that people, continueth or reigneth for ever.\f*
\v 6 He shall descend as rain upon a fleece: and as drops distilling upon the earth. \f + \fr 71:6 \ft The manner of Christ's Incarnation most silent, sweet, and grateful.\f*
\v 7 There shall rise in his days justice, and aboundance of peace, until the moon be taken away. \f + \fr 71:7 \ft Again the Prophet inculcateth, that Christ's kingdom, his Church, shall continue for ever.\f*
\v 8 And he shall rule from sea unto sea: and from the river even to the ends of the round world. \f + \fr 71:8 \ft The Church is not only universal in all times, but also in places.\f*
\v 9 Before him shall the Æthiopians fall down: and his enemies shall lick the earth.
\v 10 The kings of Tharsis, and the Islands shall offer presents: the kings of the Arabians, and of Saba shall bring gifts. \f + \fr 71:10 \ft The three Sages or Kings, which adored our Saviour, and offered gold, frankincense, & myrrh, were the first that fulfilled this prophecy: & afterwards Constantin the Great, and other Emperors, Kings, and Princes.\f* \f + \fr 71:10 \ft Amongst other Islands Great Brittany (the greatest of Europe) was converted to Christ, according to this prophecy: first some few in the Apostles' time (Metaphrastes apud Surium, Theodoret, epist. ad Timoth. Sophronius Ser. de Nat. Apost, & alij.) More in the time of Eleutherius. Lastly, our English nation by S. Augustin and others sent by S. Gregory.\f*
\v 11 And all kings of the earth shall adore him: all nations shall serve him.
\v 12 Because he shall deliver the poor from the mighty: and the poor which had no helper.
\v 13 He shall spare the poor and needy: and he shall save the souls of the poor.
\v 14 From usuries and iniquity he shall redeem their souls: and their name shall be honourable before him.
\v 15 And he shall live, and there shall be given him of the gold of Arabia, and they shall adore it always: all the day they shall bless him. \f + \fr 71:15 \ft How is this prophecy verified, except the Church be always visible?\f*
\v 16 And there shall be a firmament in the earth in the tops of mountains, the fruit thereof shall be extolled far above Libanus: and they shall flourish of the city, as the grass of the earth.
\v 17 Be his name blessed for ever: before the sun his name is permanent. And all the tribes of the earth shall be blessed in him: all nations shall magnify him.
\v 18 Blessed be our Lord the God of Israel, who only doth marvelous things. \f + \fr 71:18 \ft No miracles can be done but by God's power.\f*
\v 19 And blessed be the name of his majesty for ever: and all the earth shall be filled with his majesty. Be it, be it. \f + \fr 71:19 \ft Above all other desires, the holy Prophet wished God's glory, and praises in all the earth, as it is in heaven.\f*
\v 20 The praises of David, the son of Jesse are ended. \f + \fr 71:20 \ft It seemeth by this appendix added by Esdras, that this Psalm was last composed, though not put in the last place, but as it came to his hands.\f* \f + \fr 71:20 \ft David the natural son of Jesse, made no more Hymns, that is, no more musical praises of God after this Psalm, but: the prefigured David Christ our Saviour, the Son of God, in his body the Church, singeth still new praises. S. Aug. in enarrat. Psal. sequentis. 72.\f*
\c 72
\p
\v 1 A Psalm to Asaph. How good is God to Israel, to them that are of a right heart! \f + \fr 72:1 \ft To be sung by Asaph the master of music, and his company.\f* \f + \fr 72:1 \ft God is so excellent good, as no tongue can express, no heart can conceive.\f*
\v 2 But my feet were almost moved, my steps almost slipped. \f + \fr 72:2 \ft The peace and prosperity of the wicked tempted me to leave the right narrow way, and to go the broad easy way with them.\f*
\v 3 Because I have had zeal upon the wicked, seeing the peace of sinners.
\v 4 Because there is no respect to their death: and stability in their plague. \f + \fr 72:4 \ft They never think of death;\f* \f + \fr 72:4 \ft and if they suffer some affliction, they quickly remove it from them.\f*
\v 5 In the labours of men they are not, and with men they shall not be scourged. \f + \fr 72:5 \ft They travail not so much as good men do, neither are they so often punished.\f*
\v 6 Therefore hath pride held them, they are covered with their iniquity and impiety. \f + \fr 72:6 \ft Which maketh them proud, and so they run into all sorts of iniquity.\f*
\v 7 Their iniquity hath proceeded as it were of fat: they have passed into the affection of the heart. \f + \fr 72:7 \ft Whatsoever mischief came in their mind, they feared not to commit it in fact.\f*
\v 8 They have thought and have spoken wickedness: they have spoken iniquity on high. \f + \fr 72:8 \ft Boldly extolling their own words and works, and despising others.\f*
\v 9 They have set their mouth unto heaven: and their tongue hath passed in the earth.
\v 10 Therefore will my people return here: and full days shall be found in them. \f + \fr 72:10 \ft For this prosperity of the wicked, some of God's people will fall from the right way,\f* \f + \fr 72:10 \ft and their days will abound with calamities.\f*
\v 11 And they have said: How doth God know, and is there knowledge in the highest? \f + \fr 72:11 \ft The voice of the weak, inclining to diffidence, & doubt of God's knowledge and providence.\f*
\v 12 Lo the sinners themselves, and they that abound in the world, have obtained riches.
\v 13 And I said: Then have I justified my heart without cause, and have washed my hands amongst innocents:
\v 14 And have been scourged all the day, and my chastising in the mornings.
\v 15 If I said: I will speak this: behold I reproved the nation of thy children. \f + \fr 72:15 \ft The Prophet in his own person answereth, that if he should say such things, he should reprove God's children as faulty, unworthy of his protection, and to be neglected; whereas it is God's providence to chastise his children whom he loveth.\f*
\v 16 I thought to know this thing, it is labour before me: \f + \fr 72:16 \ft In this life we cannot know the particular causes, why the just are afflicted, & many wicked prosper in this world.\f*
\v 17 Until I may enter into the sanctuary of God: and may understand concerning their latter ends.
\v 18 But yet for guiles thou hast put it to them: thou hast cast them down whilst they were elevated. \f + \fr 72:18 \ft But only in general we are taught, that evils are prepared for the guiles, or deceits,\f* \f + \fr 72:18 \ft pride, and other sins of the wicked.\f*
\v 19 How are they brought into desolation, they have failed suddenly: they have perished for their iniquity.
\v 20 As the dream of them that rise, o Lord, in thy city thou shalt bring their image to nothing. \f + \fr 72:20 \ft Not real but imaginary felicity.\f*
\v 21 Because my heart is inflamed, and my reins are changed: \f + \fr 72:21 \ft Almost burned up with afflictions.\f*
\v 22 And I am brought to nothing, and knew not.
\v 23 As a beast am I become with thee: and I always with thee. \f + \fr 72:23 \ft Charged with heavy burdens, without knowledge how long or to what end,\f* \f + \fr 72:23 \ft yet not destitute of thy protection.\f*
\v 24 Thou hast held my right hand: and in thy will thou hast conducted me, and with glory thou hast received me.
\v 25 For what is to me in heaven? And besides thee what would I upon the earth? \f + \fr 72:25 \ft Nothing to be desired in heaven nor in earth but God.\f*
\v 26 My flesh hath fainted, and my heart: God of my heart, and God my portion for ever. \f + \fr 72:26 \ft In body and mind I thirst after thee, my true inheritance.\f*
\v 27 For behold, they that make themselves far from thee, shall perish: thou hast destroyed all that fornicate from thee. \f + \fr 72:27 \ft Men by their freewill make themselves enemies to God.\f* \f + \fr 72:27 \ft Determined their damnation, foreseeing their final sins.\f*
\v 28 But it is good for me to cleave to God: to put my hope in our Lord God. That I may shew forth all thy praises, in the gates of the daughter of Sion.
\c 73
\p
\v 1 Understanding to Asaph. Why hast thou, o God, repelled for ever: is thy fury wrath upon the sheep of thy pasture? \f + \fr 73:1 \ft Instruction for the congregation of the faithful in distress, not to seek temporal rewards and prosperity, but to expect spiritual and eternal. S. Aug.\f* \f + \fr 73:1 \ft In long persecution the weak begin to fear or suspect, that God hath utterly abandoned them.\f*
\v 2 Be mindful of thy congregation, which thou hast possessed from the beginning. Thou hast redeemed the rod of thine inheritance: mount Sion, in which thou hast dwelt. \f + \fr 73:2 \ft But the stronger pray with confidence,\f* \f + \fr 73:2 \ft being\f* \f + \fr 73:2 \ft Another reason why God will conserve his Church is, because he hath delivered it often in a strong arm; as from bondage in Ægypt, from persecution and oppression in the time of Judges, and Kings, and lastly redeemed it from the tyranny of the devil by Christ's death.\f*
\v 3 Lift up thy hands upon their prides for ever: how great things hath the enemy done malignantly in the holy place? \f + \fr 73:3 \ft Thirdly the pride of the enemies moveth God to revenge their wickedness, & so to deliver his own people.\f*
\v 4 And they that hate thee have gloried: in the midst of thy solemnity. They have set their signs, for signs: \f + \fr 73:4 \ft They pretend to keep solemn feasts like to thine.\f* \f + \fr 73:4 \ft They set up altars against thine altars, or some new devised external shew, against the holy Rites of the Church:\f*
\v 5 and have not known, as in the issue on high. As in a wood of trees they have with axes \f + \fr 73:5 \ft and that in public places, in the ends of high ways, or ports, and pinnacles.\f* \f + \fr 73:5 \ft The Prophet describeth the manner how persecutors destroy temples and all sacred things.\f*
\v 6 cut out the gates thereof together: in hatchet and chip-axe they have cast it down.
\v 7 They have burnt thy sanctuary with fire: they have polluted the tabernacle of thy name in the earth.
\v 8 Their kindred together have said in their heart: Let us make all the festival days of God to cease from the earth. \f + \fr 73:8 \ft The whole crew or band of persecutors.\f*
\v 9 Our signs we have not seen, there is now no Prophet: and he will know us no more. \f + \fr 73:9 \ft The weak complain that God sheweth not wonted signs, nor sendeth succourse to his people, by raising some Prophet, or other means to help them.\f*
\v 10 How long, o God, shall the enemy upbraid: the adversary provoke thy name for ever?
\v 11 Why doest thou turn away thy hand, and thy right hand, out of the midst of thy bosom for ever?
\v 12 But God our King before the worlds: he hath wrought salvation in the midst of the earth. \f + \fr 73:12 \ft The perfect do answer, that God both hath, and will relieve his people.\f*
\v 13 Thou in thy strength hast confirmed the sea: thou hast crushed the head of Dragons in the waters. \f + \fr 73:13 \ft Made the red sea like walls.\f* \f + \fr 73:13 \ft Drowned Pharao and his host.\f*
\v 14 Thou hast broken the heads of the dragon: thou hast given him for meat to the peoples of the Æthiopians. \f + \fr 73:14 \ft Of black devils.\f*
\v 15 Thou hast broken up fountains, and torrents, thou hast dried the rivers of Ethan. \f + \fr 73:15 \ft Given water out of rocks,\f* \f + \fr 73:15 \ft made passage over Jordan.\f*
\v 16 The day is thine, and the night is thine: thou hast made the morning and the sun.
\v 17 Thou hast made all the coasts of the earth: the summer and the spring thou hast formed them.
\v 18 Be mindful of this, the enemy hath upbraided our Lord: and a foolish people hath provoked thy name.
\v 19 Deliver not to beasts the souls that confess to thee: and the souls of the poor forget not for ever.
\v 20 Have respect unto thy testament: because they that are obscure of the earth, are filled with houses of iniquities. \f + \fr 73:20 \ft Ignorant, blind, and barbarous infidels, lodge all Kinds of iniquity in their consciences.\f*
\v 21 Let not the humble be turned away being confounded: the poor and needy shall praise thy name. \f + \fr 73:21 \ft And therefore it is unmeet, that faithful people should be in bondage under them.\f*
\v 22 Arise God, judge thy cause: be mindful of those thy reproaches, that are from the foolish man all the day. \f + \fr 73:22 \ft These foolish audacious men do continually blaspheme all holy things.\f*
\v 23 Forget not the voices of thine enemies: the pride of them that hate thee, hath ascended always. \f + \fr 73:23 \ft Omit not to punish them,\f* \f + \fr 73:23 \ft seeing they are obstinate & obdurate in pride and in hatred.\f*
\c 74
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, Corrupt not, a Psalm of Canticle to Asaph. \f + \fr 74:1 \ft Either this was the beginning of a song, to the tune whereof this Psalm was sung; as some Hebrew Rabbins testify; or, as S. Augustin and other fathers explicate, the Septuagint do admonish us by occasion of this Psalm, not to fail in our hope, for that God will in no case violate his promise nor purpose, but will render to every one in the day of Judgement, as they deserve.\f*
\v 2 We will confess to thee, o God: we will confess, and will invocate thy name. We will tell thy marvelous works: \f + \fr 74:2 \ft Christ with his Apostles, and other assessory judges, will praise and thank God, for his admirable good providence, and government of this world.\f* \f + \fr 74:2 \ft This duplication of the same word, confirmeth us of the assured performance of that, which is here prophesied.\f*
\v 3 when I shall take a time, I will judge justices. \f + \fr 74:3 \ft Christ our singular, principal, and proper Judge only, and no mere creature, knoweth the determinate time of general judgement.\f*
\v 4 The earth is melted, and all that dwell in it: I have confirmed the pillars thereof. \f + \fr 74:4 \ft The earth at that time shall be purged with flaming fire:\f* \f + \fr 74:4 \ft yet shall not be destroyed, but changed in qualities.\f*
\v 5 Isaid to the wicked: Do not wickedly; and to them that offend: Exalt not the horn. \f + \fr 74:5 \ft An epitome, or brief sum of Christ's doctrine, to fly from sin.\f* \f + \fr 74:5 \ft Be not proud, abuse not the power you have, to do what you please.\f*
\v 6 Exalt not your horn on high: speak not iniquity against God.
\v 7 For neither from the East, nor from the West, nor from the desert mountains:
\v 8 because God is Judge. This man he humbleth, and him he exalteth: \f + \fr 74:8 \ft When other Judges sit on tribunals, some may be absent, or escape from their sentences: but all without exception shall be brought in person, when Christ God and Man shall judge.\f* \f + \fr 74:8 \ft Some shall have sentence of eternal pain in hell: some of eternal reward in glory,\f*
\v 9 because there is a cup in the hand of our Lord of mere wine full of mixture. And he hath poured it out of this into that, but yet the dregs thereof are not emptied: all the sinners of the earth shall drink. \f + \fr 74:9 \ft though (partly in this world, partly in particular judgement of every soul) God hath already, and will before the last day punish sinners, yet there resteth more punishment, and no impenitent sinners shall escape, but all shall drink of the bitter cup of eternal damnation.\f* \f + \fr 74:9 \ft Strong wine not delayed with water, but mingled with bitter sharp things, as gall, vinegar, brimstone, &c. and so poured into festered wounds, so they shall suffer untolerable endless pain, mixed with the worm of conscience, loss of glory, rancour of heart, and eternal desperation.\f* \f + \fr 74:9 \ft Variety of hellish torments, from one extreme to another: as from snow-waters to exceeding heat. Job. 24.\f*
\v 10 But I will shew forth for ever: I will sing to the God of Jacob.
\v 11 And I will break all the horns of sinners: and the horns of the just shall be exalted. \f + \fr 74:11 \ft The just for well using their power of freewill, and of all power given them in this life, are rewarded in heaven.\f*
\c 75
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, in praises, a Psalm to Asaph, a Canticle to the Assyrians. \f + \fr 75:1 \ft For the congregation of faithful and godly\f* \f + \fr 75:1 \ft Amongst others, one notorious example of God's providence is recorded of an hundred fourscore & five thousand Assirians, slain in one night by an Angel. 4. Reg. 19.\f*
\v 2 God is known in Jewry: in Israel his name is great. \f + \fr 75:2 \ft God was not only known in general, as to pagan Philosophers, and some others, but more particularly to the Jews, the issue of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, by his special benefits towards them.\f*
\v 3 And his place is made in peace; and his habitation in Sion. \f + \fr 75:3 \ft God suffering all other nations to err for their sins, in their fond fantasies of false gods, reserved the Israelites for his Church,\f* \f + \fr 75:3 \ft establishing the principality thereof in Sion.\f*
\v 4 There he brake the powers of bows, the shield, the sword, and the battle. \f + \fr 75:4 \ft For obtaining and conserving of Sion from wicked Infidels, God overthrew all sorts of contrary forces.\f*
\v 5 Thou doest illuminate marvelously from the eternal mountains: \f + \fr 75:5 \ft God not only gave his people temporal victories over their enemies, but also illuminated their minds with knowledge of true religion:\f*
\v 6 all the foolish of heart were troubled. They slept their sleep: and all the men of riches found nothing in their hands. \f + \fr 75:6 \ft others are often troubled in mind, hearing the truth, but are not converted through their obstinate folly.\f* \f + \fr 75:6 \ft Worldly men in supine carelessness, as in a sleep pass over this life, and afterwards find themselves excluded from heaven, for lack of merits, and good works, with the foolish virgins.\f*
\v 7 At thy reprehension, o God of Jacob, they have all slumbered that mounted on horses. \f + \fr 75:7 \ft God undertaking the defence of his people, and threatening the adverse part,\f* \f + \fr 75:7 \ft they failed in courage, as men overcome with drowsiness of sleep.\f*
\v 8 Thou art terrible, and who shall resist thee? From that time thy wrath. \f + \fr 75:8 \ft Even from the first notice of thy will, the adversaries were dejected, fearing thy potent wrath.\f*
\v 9 From heaven thou hast made thy judgment heard: the earth trembled and was quiet. \f + \fr 75:9 \ft Terrible signs from the firmament appearing before the day of judgement,\f* \f + \fr 75:9 \ft persecutors and others being terrified shall be astonished and silent.\f* \f + \fr 75:9 \ft The Prophets do often speak in the pretertense, for the assurance of the things to come.\f*
\v 10 When God arose unto judgment, that he might save all the meek of the earth. \f + \fr 75:10 \ft God will come to judge the world, more especially for the justs' sake.\f*
\v 11 Because the cogitation of man shall confess to thee: and the remains of the cogitation shall keep festival day to thee. \f + \fr 75:11 \ft Men that shall seriously think and meditate upon these things, will praise and thank God for them:\f* \f + \fr 75:11 \ft and the effect and sweet repast of such meditation, shall make as it were a great festival day, in the devout soul spiritually joined with God.\f*
\v 12 Vow ye and render to our Lord your God: all ye that round about him bring gifts. To the terrible, \f + \fr 75:12 \ft The soul thus inflamed with God's love, is then apt of gratitude, for his goodness towards man, to make vows of things whereto we are not obliged,\f* \f + \fr 75:12 \ft but most necessary it is to be maturely advised, and not rashly nor lightly to vow; for being once vowed, we are strictly bound to whatsoever we have lawfully promised. And it is great sin to vow undiscreetly.\f* \f + \fr 75:12 \ft Remembering that for vows, and all other works we must answer to God, who is a terrible judge, ready to punish in body and soul, sparing none for their greatness, nor Princes nor Kings, nor vulgar sort, for all are to him alike.\f*
\v 13 and him that taketh away the spirit of Princes, terrible to the kings of the earth.
\c 76
\p
\v 0 and therefore he still reneweth his purpose to serve God \add sincerely, 15. particularly remembering the delivery of Israel from Ægypt.\add* \f + \fr 76:0 \ft God's special protection of the Jews. The 4. key.\f*
\v 1 Unto the end, for Idithun, a psalm to Asaph. \f + \fr 76:1 \ft For Idithun to sing, or to make tune for it.\f* \f + \fr 76:1 \ft For the faithful congregation to consider God's benefits.\f*
\v 2 With my voice I have cried to our Lord: with my voice to God and he attended to me. \f + \fr 76:2 \ft Having heretofore prayed,\f* \f + \fr 76:2 \ft Ihave obtained.\f*
\v 3 In the day of my tribulation I sought God, with my hands in the night before him: and I was not deceived. My soul refused to be comforted, \f + \fr 76:3 \ft Especially being in tribulation, and praying with heart and hands lifted up, as well in the night as day:\f* \f + \fr 76:3 \ft Iwas not frustrate of my prayer.\f* \f + \fr 76:3 \ft Iwas sometimes in such anguish that nothing seemed comfortable,\f*
\v 4 I was mindful of God and was delighted, and was exercised: and my spirit fainted. \f + \fr 76:4 \ft but I relied upon God so firmly,\f* \f + \fr 76:4 \ft that my spirit came into an ecstasy or trance.\f*
\v 5 Mine eyes prevented the watches: I was troubled & spake not. \f + \fr 76:5 \ft Iarose early before the ordinary time of awaking,\f* \f + \fr 76:5 \ft my heart being attentive inwardly, I uttered nothing with my tongue.\f*
\v 6 Ithought upon old days: and the eternal years I had in mind.
\v 7 And I meditated in the night with my heart, and I was exercised, and I swept my spirit. \f + \fr 76:7 \ft Idiligently examined my conscience.\f*
\v 8 Why, will God reject for ever: or will he not add to be better pleased as yet? \f + \fr 76:8 \ft Assuredly God will not reject for ever, but he will be pleased with his Church.\f*
\v 9 Or will he cut off his mercy for ever, from generation unto generation?
\v 10 Or will God forget to have mercy? Or will he in his wrath keep in his mercies?
\v 11 And I said: Now have I begun; this is the change of the right hand of the Highest. \f + \fr 76:11 \ft Whilst I thus thought, I erred greatly, now I see and confess that God suffereth all calamities for the good of his servants:\f* \f + \fr 76:11 \ft and this I knew not by myself, but by the inspiration of God, making this change in me by his gracious hand.\f*
\v 12 I have been mindful of the works of our Lord: because I will be mindful from the beginning of thy marvelous works.
\v 13 And I will meditate in all thy works: and in thy inventions I will be exercised.
\v 14 O God in the holy is thy way: what god is great as our God?
\v 15 thou art the God that doest marvelous things. Thou hast made thy power known among peoples:
\v 16 thou hast with thine arm redeemed thy people, the children of Jacob, and Joseph. \f + \fr 76:16 \ft The progeny of Jacob, received and nourished in Ægypt for Joseph's sake, as his adopted children.\f*
\v 17 The waters saw thee, o God, the waters saw thee: and they were afraid, and the depths were troubled. \f + \fr 76:17 \ft The red sea, and Jordan felt thy divine power, and obeyed thy will.\f*
\v 18 A multitude of the sounding of waters: the clouds gave a voice. For indeed arrows do pass: \f + \fr 76:18 \ft Noise of waters meeting after the Israelites were passed, thunders and lightnings also happened, to the terror of the persecutors, though not mentioned in Exodus.\f*
\v 19 the voice of thy thunder in a wheel. Thy lightnings shined to the round world: the earth was moved and troubled.
\v 20 Thy way in the sea, and thy paths in many waters: and thy steps shall not be known.
\v 21 Thou hast conducted thy people as sheep: in the hand of Moyses and Aaron. \f + \fr 76:21 \ft By the ministry of Moyses and Aaron.\f*
\c 77
\p
\v 1 Understanding to Asaph. My people attend ye to my law: incline your ear unto the words of my mouth. \f + \fr 77:1 \ft Commended to Asaph a chief musician, that the people might understand and consider God's benefits.\f* \f + \fr 77:1 \ft Neither the law, nor the people was David's, but presenting God's person, he speaketh in his name or authority, with whose inspiration he was replenished. S. Greg. Prefat. in Job c. 2.\f*
\v 2 I will open my mouth in parables: I will speak propositions from the beginning. \f + \fr 77:2 \ft Albeit the Prophet reciteth historically things done, yet the same were parables, similitudes, and figures of other things:\f* \f + \fr 77:2 \ft yea of secret hidden Mysteries, obscurely signified in the old Testament, and revealed in the new.\f*
\v 3 How great things have we heard and have known them, and our fathers have told us. \f + \fr 77:3 \ft Which partly we know by written holy Scriptures\f* \f + \fr 77:3 \ft partly by Traditions.\f*
\v 4 They were not hid from their children, in another generation. Telling the praises of our Lord, and his powers, and his marvelous works which he hath done.
\v 5 And he raised up a testimony in Jacob: and made a law in Israel. How great things he commanded our fathers, to make the same known to their children: \f + \fr 77:5 \ft God of his mercy without precedent merit, raised up a peculiar people of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob,\f* \f + \fr 77:5 \ft and gave them a particular law, first of Circumcision, & more largely by Moyses.\f* \f + \fr 77:5 \ft So Abraham instructed his children & his house after him, Gen. 18.\f*
\v 6 that another generation may know. The children that shall be born, and shall rise up, and shall tell their children. \f + \fr 77:6 \ft in like sort others taught their children.\f*
\v 7 That they may put their hope in God, and may not forget the works of God: and may seek after his commandments. \f + \fr 77:7 \ft For three causes God gave his law, that his people may have confidence in him, he shewing his care to instruct and govern them:\f* \f + \fr 77:7 \ft that they remember his benefits:\f* \f + \fr 77:7 \ft and keep his commandments.\f*
\v 8 That they become not as their fathers: a perverse generation and exasperating. A generation, that hath not directed their heart, their spirit hath not been faithful towards God. \f + \fr 77:8 \ft The Jewish nation very often, and in great numbers murmured, rebelled, and committed other great sins, and therefore David exhorted the people of his time, not to do the like. And this exhortation pertaineth more especially to Christians, as S. Paul teacheth. 1. Cor. 10.\f*
\v 9 The children of Ephrem bending, and shooting with bow: were turned in the day of battle. \f + \fr 77:9 \ft They first (trusting in their own strength) without God's commandment (Num. 14.) went forth to battle and were overthrown. 1. Par. 7. v. 21.\f*
\v 10 They kept not the testament of God: and in his law they would not walk.
\v 11 And they forgat his benefits, and his marvelous works, which he shewed them.
\v 12 Before their fathers he did marvelous things in the land of Ægypt, in the field of Tanis. \f + \fr 77:12 \ft Tanis the principal city in Ægypt, near the river Nilus, where Moyses wrought his great miracles.\f*
\v 13 He divided the sea & brought them through: and he made the waters to stand as in a bottle.
\v 14 And he conducted them in a cloud by day: and all the night by light of fire. \f + \fr 77:14 \ft This cloud shadowed them from the heat of the sun in the day, and the fire shined in the night, all the time that\f*
\v 15 He struck the rock in the desert: and gave them water to drink as in a great depth. \f + \fr 77:15 \ft In mount Horeb: and there was continual water in all the camp, which occupied near four miles in length and breadth.\f*
\v 16 And he brought forth water out of the rock: and made waters run down as rivers.
\v 17 And they added as yet to sin unto him: they provoked the Highest to wrath in the place without water. \f + \fr 77:17 \ft Which naturally wanted water: but by miracle had aboundance.\f*
\v 18 And they tempted God in their hearts: so that they asked meats for their lives. \f + \fr 77:18 \ft Not content with Manna, they demanded to have flesh.\f*
\v 19 And they spake evil of God, they said: Can God prepare a table in the desert?
\v 20 Because he struck the rock and waters ran, & torrents flowed: Can he also give bread, or prepare a table for his people? \f + \fr 77:20 \ft Still incredulous, not believing God's omnipotency, they thought that, albeit he had given them manna and water, yet he could not give them flesh.\f* \f + \fr 77:20 \ft By bread in general is understood all competent meat usual for a table.\f*
\v 21 Therefore our Lord heard, and made delay: and fire was kindled in Jacob, and wrath ascended upon Israel. \f + \fr 77:21 \ft For this incredulity, murmuring, and other sins, God kept the children of Israel forty years in the desert, till all that were of age when they came from Ægypt, were dead, except only Iosue and Caleb.\f* \f + \fr 77:21 \ft In the mean time amongst other punishments, many murmurers were burnt to death with strange fire. Num. 11.\f*
\v 22 Because they believed not in God, nor hoped in his salvation.
\v 23 And he commanded the clouds from above, and opened the gates of heaven.
\v 24 And he rained them Manna to eat, and bread of heaven he gave to them.
\v 25 Bread of Angels did man eat: he sent them victuals in aboundance. \f + \fr 77:25 \ft Manna made by Angels.\f*
\v 26 He transported the South-wind from heaven: and in his power he brought in the South-west-wind. \f + \fr 77:26 \ft God so changed the wind, that it brought aboundance of quails and other birds into their camp. Exo. 16. Nu. 11.\f*
\v 27 And he rained upon them flesh as dust: and as the sand of the sea feathered fowls.
\v 28 And they fell in the midst of their camp: about their tabernacles.
\v 29 And they did eat and were filled exceedingly, and their desire he brought to them:
\v 30 They were not defrauded of their desire. As yet their meats were in their mouth: \f + \fr 77:30 \ft Immediately after a month (for so long they had aboundance of these birds, ibid. v. 20.) they were strucken with a plague, & many died for their concupiscence.\f*
\v 31 And the wrath of God ascended upon them. And he killed their fat ones, and the chosen of Israel he hindered. \f + \fr 77:31 \ft The most fresh strong men died, and so were hindered from possessing the promised land of Chanaan.\f*
\v 32 In all these things they sinned as yet: and they believed not in his marvelous works.
\v 33 And their days failed in vanity: and their years in haste. \f + \fr 77:33 \ft In forty years above six hundred thousand died.\f*
\v 34 When he slew them, they sought him: and they returned, and early they came to him. \f + \fr 77:34 \ft They offered morning sacrifice.\f*
\v 35 And they remembered that God is their helper: and the high God is their redeemer.
\v 36 And they loved him with their mouth, and with their tongue they did lie to him. \f + \fr 77:36 \ft But were not sincere in their hearts.\f*
\v 37 But their heart was not right with him: neither were they counted faithful in his testament.
\v 38 But he is merciful, and will be propitious to their sins: and he will not destroy them. And he abounded to turn away his wrath: and he kindled not all his wrath. \f + \fr 77:38 \ft Howsoever multitudes of people commit great sins, and are severely punished, yet God's mercy preserveth some by his effectual grace, and never suffereth the whole Church to fail, nor to be destroyed.\f*
\v 39 And he remembered that they are flesh: spirit going, and not returning. \f + \fr 77:39 \ft Man's life is like the wind, that still passeth, and the same returneth not. As Aristotle teacheth. Here the Hebrews note the midst of the Psalter, in 1263. verses, and so many in the rest.\f*
\v 40 How often have they exasperated him in the desert: provoked him to wrath in the place without water. \f + \fr 77:40 \ft The people of Israel murmured so often in the desert, that it was not easy to tell how often. See the Annotation.\f*
\v 41 And they returned, and tempted God: and the holy one of Israel they exasperated. \f + \fr 77:41 \ft For eftsoons repenting they offended God again and again.\f*
\v 42 They did not remember his hand: in the day that he redeemed them from the hand of the afflicter.
\v 43 As he put his signs in Ægypt, and his wonders in the field of Tanis. \f + \fr 77:43 \ft The first sign was in turning a rod into a serpent, which was a miracle, but no plague, the other signs were also plagues to the Ægyptians.\f*
\v 44 And he turned their rivers into blood, & their showers that they might not drink. \f + \fr 77:44 \ft The first plague.\f* \f + \fr 77:44 \ft Pools, lakes, and all sorts of water, yea showers, or rain water which seldom happeneth in Ægypt.\f*
\v 45 He sent upon them a swarm of flies, and it eat them: and the frog, and it destroyed them. \f + \fr 77:45 \ft The fourth plague, in order as they are recited in Exodus.\f* \f + \fr 77:45 \ft The second plague.\f* \f + \fr 77:45 \ft * Coenomyiam.\f*
\v 46 And he gave their fruits to the blast, and their labours to the locust. \f + \fr 77:46 \ft This was a less plague, not mentioned in Exodus, with the greater.\f* \f + \fr 77:46 \ft The eighth plague.\f*
\v 47 And he killed their vineyards with hail: and their mulberry trees with hoar-frost. \f + \fr 77:47 \ft The seventh plague.\f* \f + \fr 77:47 \ft This also is omitted in Exodus.\f*
\v 48 And he delivered their beast to hail: and their possession to fire. \f + \fr 77:48 \ft Not only all trees, and plants, but also beasts were subject to the hail,\f* \f + \fr 77:48 \ft and to fiery lightnings.\f*
\v 49 He sent upon them the wrath of his indignation: indignation, & wrath, and tribulation: immissions by evil angels. \f + \fr 77:49 \ft In these general terms, of wrath, indignation, and tribulation, the Prophet comprehendeth all the other plagues, to wit, the third of sciniphs, the fifth of pestilence, the sixth of boyles in men and beasts, the ninth of darkness three days together.\f* \f + \fr 77:49 \ft All which God sent by the ministry of devils, evil Angels.\f*
\v 50 He made a way to the path of his wrath, he spared not their lives from death: and their cattle he shut up in death.
\v 51 And he struck all the first-born in the land of Ægypt: the first fruits of all their labours in the tabernacles of Cham. \f + \fr 77:51 \ft The tenth and greatest plague, Exod. 11. v. 5. & c. 12. v. 29.\f*
\v 52 And he took away his people as sheep: and led them as a flock in the desert. \f + \fr 77:52 \ft After that Ægypt was thus plagued, God brought Israel out of their servitude, as a shepherd leadeth his sheep, and defendeth them.\f*
\v 53 And he brought them forth in hope, and they feared not: and the sea covered their enemies.
\v 54 And he brought them into the mount of his sanctification, the mount, which his right hand purchased. And he cast out the gentiles from their face: and by lot he divided the land of them in a cord of distribution: \f + \fr 77:54 \ft Judea a hilly country.\f* \f + \fr 77:54 \ft Into that country which God chose, and endowed with many blessings.\f* \f + \fr 77:54 \ft As is written in Josue.\f*
\v 55 And he made the tribes of Israel to dwell in their tabernacles.
\v 56 And they tempted, and exasperated God the highest, and they kept not his testimonies. \f + \fr 77:56 \ft After the conquest and quiet possession, the Israelites often fell into gross sins, especially in the time of Judges.\f*
\v 57 And they turned away themselves, & kept not the covenant: even as their fathers, they were turned as a crooked bow. \f + \fr 77:57 \ft Acrooked bow deceiveth the archer, so this people failed to serve God, and deceived themselves.\f*
\v 58 They incensed him to wrath in their hills: and in their gravens they provoked him to emulation. \f + \fr 77:58 \ft In their altars erected in hills to Idols.\f* \f + \fr 77:58 \ft By graven images of Idols, they provoked God to\f* \f + \fr 77:58 \ft * Sculptilibus.\f*
\v 59 God heard, and contemned: and he brought Israel to nothing exceedingly. \f + \fr 77:59 \ft Not absolutely to nothing, but punished them exceedingly, till they repented and then spared and delivered them from tribulation, as appeareth in the book of Judges.\f*
\v 60 And he rejected the tabernacle of Silo, his tabernacle, where he dwelt among men. \f + \fr 77:60 \ft The Ark of God sometime kept in Silo, Iosue 18. in the tribe of Ephraim, was taken by the Philistiims. 1. Reg. 4. and never returned thither again.\f* \f + \fr 77:60 \ft But wheresoever the Ark was, there God more especially heard their petitions, and gave answers.\f*
\v 61 And he delivered their force into captivity: and their beauty into the hands of the enemy. \f + \fr 77:61 \ft For their sins God suffered the Ark to be taken,\f*
\v 62 And he shut up his people in the sword: and he despised his inheritance. \f + \fr 77:62 \ft And the Israelites to be sore afflicted by their enemies.\f*
\v 63 Fire devoured their young men: and their virgins were not lamented. \f + \fr 77:63 \ft The zeal and just wrath of God suffered these calamities to happen.\f*
\v 64 Their Priests fell by the sword: and their widows were not wept for. \f + \fr 77:64 \ft Ophni and Phinees the sons of Heli slain: and Heli himself hearing that the Ark was taken, fell from his stool and broke his neck. 1. Reg. 4.\f*
\v 65 And our Lord was raised up as one that sleepeth: as a mighty man having surfeited of wine. \f + \fr 77:65 \ft Nevertheless God plagued the infidels, and conserved his Church. 1. Reg. 5.\f*
\v 66 And he struck his enemies on the hinder parts: an everlasting reproach he gave to them.
\v 67 And he rejected the tabernacle of Joseph: and the tribe of Ephraim he chose not. \f + \fr 77:67 \ft As before. v. 60.\f*
\v 68 But he chose the tribe of Juda, mount Sion which he loved. \f + \fr 77:68 \ft After a time the Ark was brought into the tribe of Juda.\f*
\v 69 And he built his sanctuary as of unicorns in the land, which he hath founded for ever. \f + \fr 77:69 \ft The Church was firm, and ever preserved in the old testament till Christ, and from Christ's time to the end of the world.\f*
\v 70 And he chose David his servant, and took him from the flocks of sheep: from after the ewes with young he took him. \f + \fr 77:70 \ft God's particular grace in choosing and exalting David, was a special benefit to the Israelites.\f*
\v 71 To feed Jacob his servant, and Israel his inheritance. \f + \fr 77:71 \ft To rule and govern the people of Israel.\f*
\v 72 And he fed them in the innocency of his heart: and in the understandings of his hands he conducted them. \f + \fr 77:72 \ft Prudently using his power and authority.\f*
\c 78
\p
\v 1 A Psalm to Asaph. O God the Gentiles are come into thine inheritance, they have polluted thy holy temple: they have made Jerusalem as a watch tower of fruits. \f + \fr 78:1 \ft To be sung by Asaph and his company, in the behalf of people united in faith.\f* \f + \fr 78:1 \ft Cruel infidels have invaded those things, which pertain to thy Church:\f* \f + \fr 78:1 \ft even possessed & profaned the holy temple of the Jews, & Churches of Catholic Christians. Fulfilled by Antiochus in Jerusalem, by the Vandals in Afrike, by Protestants, and Puritans, in diverse parts of Europe, and will be more universally by Antichrist in all Christendom.\f* \f + \fr 78:1 \ft Instead of great and fair Churches, God's servants are fain to use mean houses, yea poor cottages.\f*
\v 2 They have made the carcasses of thy servants, meats for the fowls of the air: the flesh of thy Saints for the beasts of the land. \f + \fr 78:2 \ft Some persecutors suffer not Martyrs' bodies to be buried, but hang them on poles and pinnacles, where birds may eat them.\f*
\v 3 They have poured out their blood as water round about Jerusalem: and there was none to bury them.
\v 4 We are become a reproach to our neighbours: a scorn and mock to them that are round about us. \f + \fr 78:4 \ft Christians Galileans, Catholics Homousians, and now Papists, in spite and reproach.\f*
\v 5 How long, o Lord, wilt thou be angry for ever: shall thy zeal be kindled as a fire? \f + \fr 78:5 \ft Sins provoking God's wrath are one cause why he suffereth his people to be persecuted.\f*
\v 6 Pour out thy wrath upon the Gentiles, that have not known thee: & upon the Kingdoms, that have not invocated thy name. \f + \fr 78:6 \ft Though the faithful commit some sins, yet in respect that they believe rightly, have zeal in God's cause, and deny not God, they are near to grace and favour.\f*
\v 7 Because they have devoured Jacob: and his place they have made desolate.
\v 8 Remember not our old iniquities, let thy mercies quickly prevent us: because we are become exceeding poor. \f + \fr 78:8 \ft Especially when they repent, and confess their sins; than those that neither know nor will know God, but obstinately impugn and resist the truth.\f* \f + \fr 78:8 \ft So much afflicted, and despised, that none will regard the truth which we profess.\f*
\v 9 Help us, o God our Saviour: and for the glory of thy name o Lord deliver us: and be propitious to our sins for thy name's sake.
\v 10 Lest they say perhaps amongst the Gentiles: where is their God? And be notified in the nations before our eyes. The revenge of the blood of thy servants, which hath been shed: \f + \fr 78:10 \ft Albeit, o Lord, thou suffer us to be punished, yet suffer\f* \f + \fr 78:10 \ft Therefore we pray, that the revenge of thy servants' blood may be so notified, that it cannot be denied, nor doubted of. Which is also here prophesied, that it will so come to pass in the end.\f*
\v 11 let the groaning of the fettered enter in thy sight. According to the greatness of thine arm possess thou the children of them that are put to death. \f + \fr 78:11 \ft Preserve also, o God, the relics of thy servants, the successors of thy Martyrs.\f*
\v 12 And render to our neighbours sevenfold in their bosom: their reproach wherewith they have reproached thee, o Lord. \f + \fr 78:12 \ft This also is a prophecy, that God will most severely revenge the blasphemy of persecutors.\f*
\v 13 But we thy people, and the sheep of thy pasture, will confess to thee for ever. Unto generation and generation we will shew forth thy praise. \f + \fr 78:13 \ft God's people delivered from persecution, and perpetually conserved, will always praise God for the same.\f*
\c 79
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for them that shall be changed, testimony to Asaph, a Psalm. \f + \fr 79:1 \ft Pertaining to the new Testament,\f* \f + \fr 79:1 \ft especially to Gentiles that shall be converted to Christ.\f* \f + \fr 79:1 \ft For perpetual memory to the congregation of faithful.\f*
\v 2 Thou that rulest Israel, attend: that conductest Joseph as a sheep. Which sittest upon the Cherubs, be manifest \f + \fr 79:2 \ft By Joseph the Prophet understandeth all Israel; because the first-birth-right being taken from Ruben was given to him, to wit double portion of inheritance, two tribes of twelve.\f* \f + \fr 79:2 \ft Appear and shew thy mighty hand before thy people:\f* \f + \fr 79:2 \ft whereof Ephraim, Benjamin, and Manasses following the Ark, when they marched or camped, should most directly see what appeared therein, the other nine tribes being places before it, and on both sides. Num. 2.\f*
\v 3 before Ephraim, Benjamin, and Manasses. Raise up thy might, and come to save us. \f + \fr 79:3 \ft Thou which always can help us, now use thy power in delivering us from this temporal misery.\f*
\v 4 O God convert us: and shew thy face, & we shall be saved. \f + \fr 79:4 \ft Set us in a better state.\f* \f + \fr 79:4 \ft Shew thy benign countenance and favour. Mystically, send the promised Messias, Christ, the essential Image of God. 2. Cor. 4. v. 4. Colos. 1. v. 15.\f*
\v 5 O Lord the God of hosts, how long wilt thou be angry upon the prayer of thy servant? \f + \fr 79:5 \ft How long wilt thou defer to hear our prayer?\f*
\v 6 Thou wilt feed us with the bread of tears: and give us drink with tears in measure. \f + \fr 79:6 \ft Thou dost justly punish us, but thou temperest the same with measure, that it exceed not to our ruin.\f*
\v 7 Thou hast made us to be a contradiction to our neighbours: and our enemies have scorned us.
\v 8 O God of hosts convert us: and shew thy face, and we shall be saved. \f + \fr 79:8 \ft God first preventing with his grace,\f* \f + \fr 79:8 \ft man may cooperate therewith to his justification and salvation.\f*
\v 9 Thou didst transport the vineyard out of Ægypt: thou didst cast out the Gentiles, and plantedst it. \f + \fr 79:9 \ft Thy Church and people,\f* \f + \fr 79:9 \ft The Chananites.\f*
\v 10 Thou wast the guide of the way, in the sight thereof: thou didst plant the roots thereof, and it filled the earth. \f + \fr 79:10 \ft The cloud and pillar of fire were visible guides.\f* \f + \fr 79:10 \ft And it multiplied mightily.\f*
\v 11 The shadow of it covered the mountains: and the boughs of it the cedars of God. \f + \fr 79:11 \ft Hyperbolical speech, to signify the great multiplication of the Israelites.\f*
\v 12 It extended her branches even to the sea; and her boughs unto the river. \f + \fr 79:12 \ft From the Mediterranean sea of Palestine,\f* \f + \fr 79:12 \ft to the river Euphrates. Exod. 23. v. 31. Deut. 11. v. 24.\f*
\v 13 Why hast thou destroyed the hedge thereof: and all that pass by the way do pluck it.
\v 14 The boar of the wood hath destroyed it: and the singular wild beast hath eaten it. \f + \fr 79:14 \ft Cruel enemies more like to most cruel beasts than to men.\f* \f + \fr 79:14 \ft Yea so cruel, as none else in the world are like unto them.\f*
\v 15 O God of hosts return: regard from heaven, and see, and visit this vineyard. \f + \fr 79:15 \ft The Prophet now prayeth for the coming of Christ, which he saw in spirit.\f*
\v 16 And perfit it, which thy right hand hath planted: and upon the son of man whom thou hast confirmed to thee. \f + \fr 79:16 \ft The Church of the old testament in her best state wanted the perfection which the Church of Christ hath.\f* \f + \fr 79:16 \ft Christ our Messias most commonly called by this title: The Son of man.\f*
\v 17 Things burnt with fire, and digged down at the increpation of thy countenance shall perish. \f + \fr 79:17 \ft So thy vineyard cannot endure if it be still afflicted, and trodden down.\f*
\v 18 Let thy hand be upon the man of thy right hand: and upon the son of man, whom thou hast confirmed to thee. \f + \fr 79:18 \ft Christ working by God's power redresseth all miseries.\f*
\v 19 And we depart not from thee, thou wilt quicken us: and we will invocate thy name.
\v 20 O Lord the God of hosts convert us: and shew thy face, and we shall be saved. \f + \fr 79:20 \ft The same is the 8. and the 15. verse (with little alteration) and here repeated the third time. In which we also pray for three things: First to be purged and converted from sin: secondly to be illuminated by Christ, the Image of God: Thirdly, to be sanctified, and saved in eternal glory, to have the fruition of the most Blessed Trinity.\f*
\c 80
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for wine presses, a Psalm to Asaph himself. \f + \fr 80:1 \ft This Psalm pertaineth not only to the old testament, but also to the new.\f* \f + \fr 80:1 \ft God's servants oppressed with tribulations.\f* \f + \fr 80:1 \ft To be sung by Asaph a chief master of music.\f*
\v 2 Rejoice to God our helper: make Jubilation to the God of Jacob.
\v 3 Take ye Psalm, and give timbrel: pleasant Psalter with the harp. \f + \fr 80:3 \ft Make ready all these musical instruments.\f*
\v 4 Sound ye with trumpet in the new moon, in the notable day of your solemnity. \f + \fr 80:4 \ft In the Calends, or first day of every month, in remembrance of God's providence, and perpetual government of all creatures:\f* \f + \fr 80:4 \ft and most especially solemnity in the first day of the seventh month, in memory of Isaac conserved from death, in whom God promised Abraham to multiply his seed, and to bless all nations. Gen. 17. v. 21. c. 21. v. 12. c. 22. v. 18.\f* \f + \fr 80:4 \ft The feast of Noemenia.\f* \f + \fr 80:4 \ft Feast of trumpets.\f*
\v 5 Because it is a precept in Israel, and judgment to the God of Jacob.
\v 6 He put it for a testimony in Joseph, when he came out of the Land of Ægypt: he heard a tongue which he knew not. \f + \fr 80:6 \ft The people of Israel signified by Joseph, as Psal. 79. v. 2.\f*
\v 7 He turned away his back from burdens: his hands served in baskets. \f + \fr 80:7 \ft God delivered the same people from their untolerable bondage of carrying burdens in baskets, from gathering straw, making bricks, and other servitude. Exo. 1. v. 14. c. 5. v. 7.\f* \f + \fr 80:7 \ft In memory of this benefit Pasch was instituted.\f*
\v 8 In tribulation thou didst invocate me, and I heard thee: I heard thee in the secret of the tempest: I proved thee at the water of contradiction. \f + \fr 80:8 \ft The admonition of God to the people:\f* \f + \fr 80:8 \ft yet after so great benefits thou didst murmur, and contradict me. Exo. 17. Num. 20.\f*
\v 9 Hear, o my people, and I will contest thee: Israel if thou wilt hear me. \f + \fr 80:9 \ft Seriously admonish thee.\f* \f + \fr 80:9 \ft Man by free will may choose whether he will obey or no.\f*
\v 10 There shall be no new god in thee, neither shalt thou adore a strange god. \f + \fr 80:10 \ft This was another great benefit, to give an express law, for their instruction.\f* \f + \fr 80:10 \ft The feast of Pentecost in memory of the law.\f*
\v 11 For I am the Lord thy God, which brought thee out of the land of Ægypt: dilate thy mouth and I will fill it. \f + \fr 80:11 \ft Observing my commandments, ask what thou wilt, and I will give it thee.\f*
\v 12 And my People heard not my voice: and Israel attended not to me.
\v 13 And I let them alone, according to the desires of their heart, they shall go in their own inventions.
\v 14 If my people had heard me, if Israel had walked in my ways:
\v 15 I had for nothing perhaps humbled their enemies: and had laid my hand upon those that afflict them. \f + \fr 80:15 \ft Very easily,\f* \f + \fr 80:15 \ft of my freewill and liberality, without necessity or obligation.\f*
\v 16 The enemies of our Lord have lied to him: and their time shall be for ever. \f + \fr 80:16 \ft The wicked that promise to serve God, and do it not, shall be in eternal torments.\f*
\v 17 And he fed them of the fat of corn: and out of the rock with honey he filled them. \f + \fr 80:17 \ft In the mean time God bestowed these benefits upon them, for the justs' sake.\f*
\c 81
\p
\v 1 A Psalm to Asaph. God stood in the assembly of gods, and in the midst he judgeth gods. \f + \fr 81:1 \ft The words of the Prophet, admonishing all Magistrates, that when they sit in judgement, or determine any cause, God who is there and every-where present,\f* \f + \fr 81:1 \ft attendeth their processes and therefore it behoveth them to be advised what they do: even as if they heard God speaking as here followeth:\f*
\v 2 How long judge ye iniquity: and accept ye the persons of sinners. \f + \fr 81:2 \ft The words of God, though not uttered sensibly, yet in effect intimated by his law, according whereto he will proceed in judgement against unjust judges.\f*
\v 3 Judge ye for the needy and the pupil: justify ye the humble, and the poor.
\v 4 Take away the poor: and deliver the needy from the hand of the sinner.
\v 5 They knew not, neither did they understand, they walk in darkness: all the foundations of the earth shall be moved. \f + \fr 81:5 \ft Such judges proceed in gross ignorance, not caring to understand, but content to walk in darkness.\f* \f + \fr 81:5 \ft Ye are so evil disposed, that you would turn all upside down, justifying the wicked, and condemning the just.\f*
\v 6 Isaid: You are gods, and the sons of the highest all. \f + \fr 81:6 \ft For your office which you participate of me, you are certain gods upon earth.\f*
\v 7 But you shall die as men: and fall as one of the Princes. \f + \fr 81:7 \ft But when you die you shall find that you are men, subject to God's judgement:\f* \f + \fr 81:7 \ft yea your punishment will be grievous, and importable: for the mighty shall mightily suffer torments.\f*
\v 8 Arise, o God, judge the earth: because thou shalt inherit in all the Gentiles. \f + \fr 81:8 \ft Again the words of the Prophet praying God,\f* \f + \fr 81:8 \ft that seeing he is Lord of all, he will judge all.\f*
\c 82
\p
\v 1 A Canticle of Psalm to Asaph.
\v 2 O God who shall be like to thee? Hold not thy peace, neither be thou appeased, o God: \f + \fr 82:2 \ft Seeing none is like to thee, o God,\f* \f + \fr 82:2 \ft shew thy power and majesty,\f* \f + \fr 82:2 \ft be not silent.\f*
\v 3 for behold thine enemies have made a sound: they that hate thee have lifted up the head. \f + \fr 82:3 \ft The cruel persecuters are most insolent\f* \f + \fr 82:3 \ft and proud.\f*
\v 4 They have taken malignant counsel upon thy people: and they have devised against thy Saints.
\v 5 They have said: Come, and let us destroy them out of the nation: and let the name of Israel be remembered no more. \f + \fr 82:5 \ft That there be no more any faithful people,\f* \f + \fr 82:5 \ft any Catholic left alive.\f*
\v 6 Because they have devised with one consent: they have together made a covenant against thee.
\v 7 The tabernacles of the Idumeians, and the Ismahelites, Moab, and the Agarens. \f + \fr 82:7 \ft The progeny of Esau,\f* \f + \fr 82:7 \ft the seed of Ismael\f* \f + \fr 82:7 \ft descending from the elder son of Lot.\f* \f + \fr 82:7 \ft The issue of Abraham by Agar, who falsely call themselves Saracens, as if they were of Sara.\f*
\v 8 Gebal, and Ammon, Amalec: the foreigners, with the inhabitants of Tyre. \f + \fr 82:8 \ft People of Gebal a city of Syria,\f* \f + \fr 82:8 \ft of the other son of Lot.\f* \f + \fr 82:8 \ft Those that first oppugned the Israelites, after they were parted from Ægypt. Exo. 17.\f* \f + \fr 82:8 \ft The Philistians,\f* \f + \fr 82:8 \ft and Tyrians, all near neighbours, and some of them near akin to the Israelites, were their great enemies.\f*
\v 9 Yea and Assur also is come with them: they are made an aid to the children of Lot. \f + \fr 82:9 \ft Others also coming further off, joined against God's people, in figure that all heretics, and other infidels conspire together against Catholics.\f*
\v 10 Do to them as to Madian, and Sisara: as to Jabin in the torrent Cisson. \f + \fr 82:10 \ft The Psalmist therefore prayeth (and withal prophesieth) that God will at last destroy them, as he did Madian. Num. 31. Iudic. 6. & 7.\f* \f + \fr 82:10 \ft Sisara, Captain general,\f* \f + \fr 82:10 \ft for Jabin King of Asor near Cisson. Iudic. 4. v. 7. & 23.\f*
\v 11 They perished in Endor: they were made as the dung of the earth. \f + \fr 82:11 \ft Within the territory of Manasses (Ios. 17.) which they invaded.\f* \f + \fr 82:11 \ft Slain and not buried.\f*
\v 12 Put their Princes as Oreb, and Zeb, and Zebee, and Salmana. All their Princes: \f + \fr 82:12 \ft These four Princes of the Madianites were slain by Gedeon's forces. Iudic. 7. & 8.\f*
\v 13 which have said: Let us possess the Sanctuary of God for an inheritance.
\v 14 My God put them as a wheel: and as stubble before the face of the wind. \f + \fr 82:14 \ft By four similitudes the Prophet describeth the punishment that shall fall upon persecuters.\f*
\v 15 Even as fire that burneth a wood: & as a flame that burneth the mountains.
\v 16 So shalt thou pursue them in thy tempest: and in thy wrath thou shalt trouble them.
\v 17 Fill their faces with ignominy: and they will seek thy name, o Lord. \f + \fr 82:17 \ft God by punishing seeketh the conversion of sinners, not their eternal death.\f*
\v 18 Let them be ashamed, and troubled for ever and ever: and let them be confounded, and perish. \f + \fr 82:18 \ft But such as be still obstinate, and finally impenitent do perish for ever.\f*
\v 19 And let them know that Lord is thy name, thou only the Highest in all the earth. \f + \fr 82:19 \ft God only the Creator of heaven and earth, is properly called LORD: Whose essential and incommunicable name\f*
\c 83
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, for wine presses, to the children of Core, a Psalm. \f + \fr 83:1 \ft For men afflicted in this vale of misery.\f* \f + \fr 83:1 \ft By the children of Core not being musicians (but porters in the temple, 1. Par. 26. ) S. Augustin here and in other titles of Psalms, understandeth the faithful Children of Christ.\f*
\v 2 How beloved are thy tabernacles, o Lord of hosts! \f + \fr 83:2 \ft The glorious mansions in heaven, which God hath prepared for the just.\f*
\v 3 my soul coveteth and fainteth unto the courts of our Lord. My heart and my flesh have rejoiced toward the living God. \f + \fr 83:3 \ft Vehement desires do sometimes deprive us of external sense.\f* \f + \fr 83:3 \ft The mind rejoicing in hope, the body is also recreated, relieved, and revived, which before was dull and heavy.\f*
\v 4 For the sparrow also hath found her an house: and the turtle-dove a nest for herself, where she may lay her young ones. Thine altars, o Lord of hosts: my King, and my God. \f + \fr 83:4 \ft As sparrows by natural instinct seeking habitations, find houses to dwell in,\f* \f + \fr 83:4 \ft and turtles have nests, wherein to lay their young ones: so faithful souls seek to dwell in heaven, and in the mean time to lay up good works within the Catholic Church; out of which (saith Saint Augustin in this place) how good soever works do seem (as when pagans and heretics feed the hungry, clothe the naked, receive strangers into their houses, visit the sick, comfort prisoners) being not laid in the nest, conculcabuntur, & conterentur: non servabuntur, non custodientur: they shall be trod under-foot, they shall be bruised in pieces: they shall not be conserved, they shall not be kept: but (that such works may be profitable and be conserved) they must be done in true faith, in the Catholic faith, in society of the unity of the Church.\f* \f + \fr 83:4 \ft Works are good, and rightly laid up when they are done in unity, and participation of God's Altars, the most proper places of Divine service, of external Sacrifice in this life, and spiritual sacrifice of perfect praises in eternal glory; where all Saints without ceasing sing: Holy, holy, holy, Lord God of hosts Isaiæ 6. Apoc. 4.\f*
\v 5 Blessed are they that dwell in thy house, o Lord: for ever and ever they shall praise thee. \f + \fr 83:5 \ft The Catholic Church.\f*
\v 6 Blessed is the man, whose help is from thee: he hath disposed ascensions in his heart, \f + \fr 83:6 \ft The just by God's grace and help, may resolve to ascend by steps and degrees, from virtue to virtue (v. 8.) even to heaven,\f*
\v 7 in the vale of tears, in the place which he hath appointed. \f + \fr 83:7 \ft though he be now in this vale of tears, by reason of man's sin, who otherwise was before sin in Paradise, a place of delight.\f*
\v 8 For the law-giver shall give blessing, they shall go from virtue into virtue: the God of gods shall be seen in Sion. \f + \fr 83:8 \ft Christ our Law-giver,\f* \f + \fr 83:8 \ft giveth aboundance of graces,\f* \f + \fr 83:8 \ft with continual increase.\f* \f + \fr 83:8 \ft But our only omnipotent God, is to be seen by this effect of his grace, in the Church and not elsewhere.\f*
\v 9 Lord God of hosts hear my prayer: receive with thine ear, o God of Jacob.
\v 10 Behold, o God our protector: and look upon the face of thy Christ. \f + \fr 83:10 \ft Agreeably to this the Church maketh all her petitions, concluding all prayers, By Christ our Lord.\f*
\v 11 Because better is one day in thy courts, above thousands. I have chosen to be an abject in the house of my God: rather than to dwell in the tabernacles of sinners. \f + \fr 83:11 \ft In respect of the future retribution, which every one shall receive according to their deserts, one day in God's Church is better than thousands out of it.\f* \f + \fr 83:11 \ft And better to\f* \f + \fr 83:11 \ft than in greatest palaces or highest dignities amongst sinners.\f*
\v 12 Because God loveth mercy and truth: our Lord will give grace and glory. \f + \fr 83:12 \ft The Divine wisdom so useth mercy, and verity, that neither may prejudice the other:\f* \f + \fr 83:12 \ft and so giveth grace in this life,\f* \f + \fr 83:12 \ft and glory in the next.\f*
\v 13 He will not deprive them of good things, that walk in innocency: o Lord of hosts, blessed is the man that hopeth in thee. \f + \fr 83:13 \ft Besides innocency conserved without sin, there is also innocency after remission of sin, of which the Prophet here speaketh.\f*
\c 84
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, to the children of Core, a Psalm.
\v 2 O Lord thou hast blessed thy land: thou hast turned away the captivity of Jacob. \f + \fr 84:2 \ft God bestowed many great benefits upon the people of Israel:\f* \f + \fr 84:2 \ft he brought them out of the bondage of Ægypt.\f*
\v 3 Thou hast forgiven the iniquity of thy people: thou hast covered all their sins. \f + \fr 84:3 \ft Remitted their manifold sins:\f* \f + \fr 84:3 \ft pardoned also a great part of due punishment.\f*
\v 4 Thou hast mitigated all thy wrath: thou hast turned away from the wrath of thine indignation.
\v 5 Convert us, o God our Saviour: and avert thy wrath from us. \f + \fr 84:5 \ft As thou hast spared thy peculiar people, so we beseech thee, o God Creator and general Saviour of all mankind,\f* \f + \fr 84:5 \ft mitigate thy wrath towards us all.\f*
\v 6 Wilt thou be wrath with us for ever? Or wilt thou extend thy wrath from generation unto generation?
\v 7 O God thou being turned shalt quicken us: and thy people shall rejoice in thee. \f + \fr 84:7 \ft Till God first shew his mercy, sinners lie dead in guilt of sin, but by his grace they are stirred up, and quickened:\f* \f + \fr 84:7 \ft and joyfully return to God.\f*
\v 8 Shew us, o Lord, thy mercy and give us thy salvation.
\v 9 I will hear what our Lord God will speak in me: because he will speak peace upon his people. And upon his saints: and upon them, that are converted to the heart. \f + \fr 84:9 \ft The words of the Prophet,\f* \f + \fr 84:9 \ft signifying that God had revealed unto him the redemption of mankind.\f* \f + \fr 84:9 \ft Not all men are justified, and saved, but those that are heartily and sincerely converted.\f*
\v 10 But yet his salvation is nigh to them that fear him: that glory may inhabit in our land. \f + \fr 84:10 \ft Though all be not saved (because many will not cooperate to God's grace) yet very many having the fear of God, which is the beginning of godly wisdom, freely accept of God's mercy, and so the Church is gloriously propagated.\f*
\v 11 Mercy and truth have met each other: justice and peace have kissed. \f + \fr 84:11 \ft Whereas God's mercy would save all, and his truth or justice requireth that sins be duly punished, by Christ's Passion and death, sufficient satisfaction is offered for all sins, and those that will be partakers by penance, and conformity to God's law, may have remission,\f* \f + \fr 84:11 \ft and so justice is observed, and peace made between God and his subjects.\f*
\v 12 Truth is risen out of the earth: and justice hath looked down from heaven. \f + \fr 84:12 \ft Integrity of conscience reigneth in good men,\f* \f + \fr 84:12 \ft God sending just means from heaven to save them.\f*
\v 13 For our Lord certes will give benignity: and our land shall give her fruit. \f + \fr 84:13 \ft God giveth grace,\f* \f + \fr 84:13 \ft and so men yield fruit.\f*
\v 14 Justice shall walk before him: and shall set his steps in the way. \f + \fr 84:14 \ft Yea they walk in justice, and right path of God's law.\f*
\c 85
\p
\v 1 Aprayer to David himself. Incline thine ear, o Lord, & hear me: because I am needy and poor. \f + \fr 85:1 \ft Aform of prayer for King David, and for any faithful person.\f* \f + \fr 85:1 \ft There be sundry just causes which move God to hear our prayers:\f* \f + \fr 85:1 \ft first our necessity requireth God's help.\f*
\v 2 Keep my soul, because I am holy: save thy servant my God, that hopeth in thee. \f + \fr 85:2 \ft Secondly, because we profess, and promise to lead a holy life.\f* \f + \fr 85:2 \ft Thirdly, because we trust and hope in God.\f*
\v 3 Have mercy on me, o Lord, because I have cried to thee all the day: \f + \fr 85:3 \ft Fourthly, because we persevere in prayer.\f*
\v 4 make joyful the soul of thy servant, because to thee, o Lord, have I lifted up my soul. \f + \fr 85:4 \ft Fifthly, if we pray with attention of mind.\f*
\v 5 Because thou, o Lord, art sweet, and mild: and of much mercy to all that invocate thee. \f + \fr 85:5 \ft Sixthly, because God of his own nature is benign, ready to bestow benefits.\f* \f + \fr 85:5 \ft Seventhly, he is meek to remit offences.\f* \f + \fr 85:5 \ft Eighthly he is merciful to mitigate the punishment, to those that make recourse unto him.\f* \f + \fr 85:5 \ft For these causes we pray as followeth.\f*
\v 6 Receive, o Lord, my prayer with thine ears: and attend to the voice of my petition.
\v 7 In the day of my tribulation I have called to thee: because thou hast heard me.
\v 8 There is not the like to thee amongst gods, o Lord: and there is not according to thy works.
\v 9 All nations whatsoever thou hast made, shall come, and shall adore before thee, o Lord: and they shall glorify thy name. \f + \fr 85:9 \ft Vocation of Gentiles.\f* \f + \fr 85:9 \ft They shall come by faith,\f* \f + \fr 85:9 \ft and glorify God by good works. Mat. 5. v. 17.\f*
\v 10 Because thou art great and doing marvelous things: thou only art God.
\v 11 Conduct me, o Lord, in thy way, and I will walk in thy truth: let my heart rejoice that it may fear thy name.
\v 12 I will confess to thee, o Lord my God, with all my heart, and will glorify thy name for ever. \f + \fr 85:12 \ft Confession of praise.\f*
\v 13 Because thy mercy is great upon me: & thou hast delivered my soul out of the lower hell. \f + \fr 85:13 \ft From the state of eternal damnation.\f*
\v 14 O God the wicked are risen up upon me, and the synagogue of the mighty have sought my soul: and they have not set thee in their sight.
\v 15 And thou, o Lord, the God of compassion and merciful, patient, and of much mercy, and true. \f + \fr 85:15 \ft In performing all promises.\f*
\v 16 Have respect to me and have mercy on me, give thine empire to thy servant: and save the son of thy handmaid. \f + \fr 85:16 \ft Adigression (usual to Prophets) of Christ's Empire & Kingdom the Church, given to him, being the son of an Immaculate Virgin, the handmaid of God.\f*
\v 17 Make with me a sign unto God, that they may see which hate me, and may be confounded: because thou o Lord hast holpen me. \f + \fr 85:17 \ft The chief and principal sign of Christ's, and his Church's glory, is his Resurrection, prefigured in Ionas.\f* \f + \fr 85:17 \ft Whereby all enemies are confounded, either to their conversion, or to eternal damnation. See S. Augustin.\f*
\c 86
\p
\v 1 To the children of Core, a Psalm of Canticle. The foundations thereof in the holy mountains: \f + \fr 86:1 \ft Christ's Church was first founded in Jerusalem on Whitsunday, Act. 2. in mount Sion, which hath two tops, in one of which the Temple stood, in the other David's tower or palace.\f*
\v 2 our Lord loveth the gates of Sion above all the Tabernacles of Jacob.
\v 3 Glorious things are said of thee, o city of God.
\v 4 I will be mindful of Rahab, and Babylon knowing me. Behold the foreigners, and Tyre, & the people of the Æthiopians, these were there. \f + \fr 86:4 \ft The Prophet in the person of Christ saith he will commend unto his Apostles, and other Apostolical men, that they convert all nations (as our Saviour gave express commission and commandment. Math. 28. Luc. 24. v. 47. Act. 1. v. 8. )\f* \f + \fr 86:4 \ft naming here Rahab (which is Ægypt) and Babylon:\f* \f + \fr 86:4 \ft The Philistiims, Tyrians, Æthiopians,\f* \f + \fr 86:4 \ft & the rest, shall be regenerate in this Church, which for the assured certainty thereof (after the Prophet's manner of speaking) is affirmed in the pretertense, as if it were then done.\f*
\v 5 Shall it not be said of Sion: Man and man, is born in her; and the Highest himself founded her? \f + \fr 86:5 \ft It shall be reported, or one shall say to another: Lo this and that man, all these and all these men are regenerate by Baptism in the Church of Christ.\f* \f + \fr 86:5 \ft God himself; Christ God and man, founded this Church.\f*
\v 6 Our Lord will declare in scriptures of peoples, and of Princes: of those that have been in her. \f + \fr 86:6 \ft The multitude of the elect is so great, that only God knoweth the number,\f* \f + \fr 86:6 \ft and the qualities of all sorts, of Princes, Prelates, and Peoples.\f*
\v 7 The habitation in thee, is as it were of all rejoicing. \f + \fr 86:7 \ft Great spiritual joy with peace of conscience, is in true Christian Catholics in the militant Church; but the blessed have the most absolute & secure joy of all, in the Church triumphant.\f*
\c 87
\p
\v 1 A Canticle of a Psalm, to the children of Core, unto the end, for Maheleth to answer, of understanding to Eman the Ezrahite. \f + \fr 87:1 \ft An instrument of music apt for lamentable songs. Not expressed in the title of any other Psalm. Perhaps because this Psalm mixeth not any consolation with mourning, as other Psalms do, which are also prayers in affliction. As the 30. 53. 63. 73.\f* \f + \fr 87:1 \ft Neither is this word in any other title. It is added here to admonish us, that as this Psalm and some others were sung by two choirs, one answering the other, so we must in answer and imitation of Christ, suffer long and great afflictions with patience, seeing he in his passion was left without ordinary consolation.\f* \f + \fr 87:1 \ft By some interpreted (his brethren) For Christ (saith S. Augustin) vouchsafeth to make them his brethren, which understand the mystery of his Cross, and not only are not ashamed thereof, but also faithfully glory therein.\f*
\v 2 O Lord the God of my salvation: in the day have I cried, and in the night before thee. \f + \fr 87:2 \ft Ihave cried to thee very often both by day and by night.\f*
\v 3 Let my prayer enter in thy sight: incline thine ear to my petition.
\v 4 Because my soul is replenished with evils: & my life hath approached to hell. \f + \fr 87:4 \ft Iam almost dead.\f*
\v 5 I am accounted with them that descend into the lake. I am become as a man without help, \f + \fr 87:5 \ft Accounted as dead, and ready to be buried.\f*
\v 6 free among the dead, as the wounded sleeping in the sepulchres, of whom thou art mindful no more: and they are cast off from thy hand. \f + \fr 87:6 \ft If I were dead, I should be free from these afflictions. Especially it agreeth to Christ, who was free, yea of infinite power amongst the dead.\f*
\v 7 They have put me in the lower lake: in the dark places, and in the shadow of death. \f + \fr 87:7 \ft Mine enemies have endeavoured not only to bereave me of temporal life, whereby I should go into limbus, but also to kill my soul spiritually, whereby I should descend into the lower hell of the damned.\f*
\v 8 Thy fury is confirmed upon me: and all thy waves thou hast brought in upon me. \f + \fr 87:8 \ft Thy just wrath also, o God, hath exceedingly afflicted me.\f*
\v 9 Thou hast made my familiars far from me: they have put me abomination to themselves. I was delivered and came not forth:
\v 10 mine eyes languished for poverty. I cried to thee o Lord all the day: I stretched out my hands to thee.
\v 11 Wilt thou do marvels to the dead: or shall physicians raise to life, and they confess to thee? \f + \fr 87:11 \ft O God deliver me whilst I am yet living, for I may not look for extraordinary and miraculous help, as to be raised again after death.\f*
\v 12 Shall any in the sepulchre declare thy mercy, and thy truth in perdition? \f + \fr 87:12 \ft When I shall be dead & buried, I cannot denounce thy praise, as now I can, to mortal men.\f*
\v 13 Shall thy marvelous works be known in darkness: and thy justice in the land of oblivion. \f + \fr 87:13 \ft Much less shall the damned praise thee in eternal perdition.\f*
\v 14 And I o Lord have cried to thee: and in the morning shall my prayer prevent thee.
\v 15 Why doest thou, o Lord, reject my prayer: turnest away thy face from me?
\v 16 I am poor, and in labours from my youth: and being exalted, humbled, and troubled. \f + \fr 87:16 \ft As well young\f* \f + \fr 87:16 \ft as waxing elder I have been still afflicted.\f*
\v 17 Thy wraths have passed upon me: and thy terrors have troubled me.
\v 18 They have compassed me as water all the day: they compassed me together.
\v 19 Thou hast made friend, and neighbour far from me and my familiars because of misery. \f + \fr 87:19 \ft My miserable estate hath alienated all friends, neighbours, & acquaintances from me.\f*
\c 88
\p
\v 1 Of understanding to Ethan the Ezrahite. \f + \fr 88:1 \ft Otherwise called Idithun. 1. Paral. 25. or rather Ethan, who was very wise, mentioned with others, to whom Salomon is preferred for wisdom. 3. Reg. 4. v. 31. and signifieth strong: applied here to those that are strong in assured hope of Christ's promises, notwithstanding it seemeth sometimes to the weak, that his promises are not performed.\f*
\v 2 The mercies of our Lord I will sing for ever. In generation and generation I will shew forth thy truth in my mouth. \f + \fr 88:2 \ft In all generations.\f*
\v 3 Because thou saidst: Mercy shall be built up for ever in the heavens: thy truth shall be prepared in them. \f + \fr 88:3 \ft The heavens shall rather fall, than God's truth fail. Mystically, in the Apostles, and by their preaching, the Church of Christ is built for ever.\f*
\v 4 I have ordained a testament with mine elect, I have sworn to David my servant:
\v 5 for ever will I prepare thy seed. And I will build thy seat unto generation and generation. \f + \fr 88:5 \ft David's seed conserved till Christ was born of his Virgin Mother: and in his spiritual seed, his kingdom the\f*
\v 6 The heavens shall confess thy marvelous works o Lord: yea and thy truth in the Church of Saints.
\v 7 For who in the clouds shall be equal to our Lord: shall be like to God among the sons of God? \f + \fr 88:7 \ft The Angels.\f*
\v 8 God who is glorified in the counsel of Saints, great and terrible over all that are round about him.
\v 9 O Lord God of hosts, who is like to thee? Thou art mighty, o Lord, and thy truth round about thee.
\v 10 Thou rulest over the power of the sea: and the moving of the waves thereof thou doest mitigate.
\v 11 Thou humbledst the proud one, as one wounded: in the arm of thy strength thou hast dispersed thine enemies. \f + \fr 88:11 \ft The Prophet alludeth to the plagues and miracles in Ægypt, and in other enemies.\f*
\v 12 The heavens are thine, and the earth is thine, the round earth, and the fullness thereof thou hast founded:
\v 13 the north and the sea thou hast created. Thabor and Hermon shall rejoice in thy name: \f + \fr 88:13 \ft Conversion of Gentiles.\f*
\v 14 thy arm is with might. Let thy hand be confirmed, and thy right hand exalted: \f + \fr 88:14 \ft Whether God punish, as with the left hand,\f* \f + \fr 88:14 \ft or bestow benefits, as with the right hand, all is to his glory, and according to mercy and truth.\f*
\v 15 justice and judgment is the preparation of thy seat. Mercy and truth shall go before thy face:
\v 16 blessed is the people that knoweth jubilation. Lord they shall walk in the light of thy countenance, \f + \fr 88:16 \ft They are spiritually happy, that do thus consider of God's marvelous proceedings, praise the same, and rejoice therein.\f*
\v 17 and in thy name they shall rejoice all the day: and in thy justice they shall be exalted.
\v 18 Because thou art the glory of their strength: and in thy good pleasure shall our horn be exalted. \f + \fr 88:18 \ft Power, and kingdom.\f*
\v 19 Because our protection is of our Lord: and of the holy one of Israel our King.
\v 20 Then didst thou speak in vision to thy Saints, and saidst: I have put help on the mighty one: & have exalted an elect one of my people. \f + \fr 88:20 \ft Thus God promised to establish the Kingdom of the Jews in David and his family. 1. Reg. 16. 1. Reg. 5. and other places. Which was performed as in a figure, but more fully in Christ. Act. 13. v. 22.\f*
\v 21 I have found David my servant: with mine holy oil have I anointed him.
\v 22 For mine hand shall help him: and mine arm shall strengthen him.
\v 23 The enemy shall nothing prevail in him: and the son of iniquity shall not add to hurt him.
\v 24 And I will cut down his enemies before his face: and them that hate him I will put to flight.
\v 25 And my truth, and my mercy with him: and in my name shall his horn be exalted.
\v 26 And I will put his hand in the sea: and his right hand in the rivers.
\v 27 He shall invocate me: Thou art my Father: my God, and the protector of my Salvation.
\v 28 And I will put him the first-begotten, high above the kings of the earth.
\v 29 I will keep my mercy unto him for ever: and my testament faithful to him.
\v 30 I will put his seed for ever and ever: and his throne as the days of heaven.
\v 31 But if his children shall forsake my law: and will not walk in my judgments.
\v 32 If they shall profane my justices: and not keep my commandments:
\v 33 I will visit their iniquities with a rod: and their sins with stripes.
\v 34 But my mercy I will not take away from him: neither will I hurt in my truth.
\v 35 Neither will I profane my testament: and the words that proceed from my mouth I will not make frustrate.
\v 36 Once I have sworn in my holy, if I lie to David:
\v 37 his seed shall continue for ever. \f + \fr 88:37 \ft I will not lie.\f*
\v 38 And his throne as the Sun in my sight, and as the Moon perfect for ever: and a faithful witness in heaven. \f + \fr 88:38 \ft Christian just souls as the sun,\f* \f + \fr 88:38 \ft and as the perfect, or full moon, See the first Tome, page. 716. S. Augustin also expoundeth this verse in the Anagogical sense, of the just after the Resurrection in glory, where the soul shall be like the sun, and the body, which now is mutable, shall be like the moon, not as now aways changing, but as the full moon, always perfect.\f*
\v 39 But thou hast repelled and despised: thou hast deferred thy Christ. \f + \fr 88:39 \ft Amongst many pensive things, this one word doth comfort us, thy promise remaineth, thou hast not denied to send Christ, but deferred him.\f* \f + \fr 88:39 \ft God having promised all the aforesaid, the Prophet in the person of the weak, lamenteth that the contrary shall happen as well in the temporal kingdom oppressed by the Assirians, Babylonians, Persians, Grecians, and Romans: as in the Church impugned by innumerable sorts of Heretics and other Infidels.\f*
\v 40 Thou hast overthrown the testament of thy servant: thou hast profaned his sanctuary on the earth.
\v 41 Thou hast destroyed all the hedges thereof: thou hast made the firmament thereof fear.
\v 42 All that pass by the way have spoiled him: he is become a reproach to his neighbours.
\v 43 Thou hast exalted the right hand of them that oppress him: thou hast made all his enemies joyful.
\v 44 Thou hast turned away the help of his sword: and hast not holpen him in battle.
\v 45 Thou hast destroyed him from emundation: and his seat thou hast broken down to the ground. \f + \fr 88:45 \ft From the use of Sacrifice and Sacraments, whereby sinners were wont to be cleansed.\f*
\v 46 Thou hast lessened the days of his time: thou hast overwhelmed him with confusion.
\v 47 How long, o Lord, doest thou turn away for ever: shall thy wrath burn as a fire? \f + \fr 88:47 \ft The Psalmist prayeth and prophesieth that God will respect the weakness of man, maintain his Church in many nations, & save many souls.\f*
\v 48 Remember what my substance is: for hast thou made all the children of men in vain?
\v 49 Who is the man that shall live, and shall not see death: shall deliver his soul from the hand of hell?
\v 50 Where are thine old mercies, o Lord, as thou swarest to David in thy truth?
\v 51 Be mindful, o Lord, of the reproach of thy servants (which I have held in my bosom) of many nations.
\v 52 Which thine enemies have reproached, o Lord, which they have reproached the commutation of thy Christ. \f + \fr 88:52 \ft As though Christ were changed and turned from us.\f*
\v 53 Blessed be our Lord for ever: Be it, be it. \f + \fr 88:53 \ft So we wish and pray that all may bless and praise thee. Amen.\f*
\c 89
\p
\v 1 Aprayer of Moyses the man of God. Lord, thou art made a refuge for us: from generation unto generation. \f + \fr 89:1 \ft Some Expositors think Moyses was the author of this Psalm, and of the ten next following. But others hold that David was Author of all, and that Moyses his name is here put in the title by Esdras, because his Psalm is like to the prayer of Moyses, when the people provoked God's wrath by their sins in the desert. And because man's creation, fall, punishment, and God's mercy towards him, are here described: which Moyses first writ, as going before the written law. And that Moyses made not this Psalm is probably gathered by the 10. verse, where the ordinary age of men is described to be (in strength and vigor) seventy years, or of fourscore: and the greater part (of the one or the other) is in labour and sorrow. And it is evident (Deut. 34. ) that Moyses lived in all an hundred and twenty years, and his eye was not dim, neither were his teeth moved. So Aaron, Josue, and others commonly lived longer than is here mentioned. But David was old and impotent at seventy years. 3. Reg. 1. Saint Hilarion, living near seventy years in his hermitage, S. Remigius governing the Church of Rhemes seventy years, and the like are accounted to have been full of days, and such as lived longer are reputed extraordinary. Again it is more evidently proved that Moyses was not author of the 94. and 95. Psalms.\f* \f + \fr 89:1 \ft Always from the beginning of the world to the end.\f*
\v 2 Before the mountains were made, or the earth and the world formed, from everlasting even unto everlasting thou art God. \f + \fr 89:2 \ft The Prophet sheweth that the world was created in and with time, not eternal.\f* \f + \fr 89:2 \ft And that only God is eternal.\f*
\v 3 Turn not away man into humiliation: thou saidst: Be converted ye children of men. \f + \fr 89:3 \ft God hath often said, that he would not the death of sinners, but rather that they be converted and live for ever.\f*
\v 4 Because a thousand years before thine eyes, are as yesterday that is past. And as a watch in the night, \f + \fr 89:4 \ft Though some lived long (none for all that did reach to a thousand years) yet it is nothing before God, and in respect of eternity.\f*
\v 5 things that are counted nothing shall their years be.
\v 6 In the morning as an herb he shall pass, in the morning he shall flourish, and pass: in the evening he shall fall, be hardened, and withered. \f + \fr 89:6 \ft The youth of man quickly passeth:\f* \f + \fr 89:6 \ft old age cannot last long: whereof cometh our English proverb: A young man may die soon, an old man cannot live long.\f*
\v 7 Because we have fainted in thy wrath, and in thy fury we are troubled.
\v 8 Thou hast put our iniquities in thy sight: our age in the light of thy countenance. \f + \fr 89:8 \ft Sin the cause of shortness of man's life.\f* \f + \fr 89:8 \ft Sæculum.\f*
\v 9 Because all our days have failed, and in thy wrath we have failed. Our years shall be considered as a spider: \f + \fr 89:9 \ft Man's life as brickle as a spider's web: or man's life wasteth continually, as a spider wasteth herself by spinning, and consuming her own substance.\f*
\v 10 the days of our years in them are seventy years. And if in strong ones eighty years: and the more of them, labour & sorrow. Because mildness is come upon us: and we shall be chastised. \f + \fr 89:10 \ft See previous note\f* \f + \fr 89:10 \ft It is of God's mild providence, that man's life is short, for that many if they were sure, or had probability to live long, would presume to sin more.\f*
\v 11 Who knoweth the power of thy wrath: and for fear \f + \fr 89:11 \ft Seeing God of his justice punished all mankind for one sin of our first parent, his wrath must needs be very great to every sinner, for his own proper sins.\f*
\v 12 to number thy wrath? So make thy right hand known: and men learned in heart, in wisdom.
\v 13 Turn, o Lord, how long? And be entreated for thy servants.
\v 14 We are replenished in the morning with thy mercy: and we have rejoiced, and art delighted all our days. \f + \fr 89:14 \ft The hope of glorious resurrection turneth our calamities into spiritual joy.\f*
\v 15 We have rejoiced for the days wherein thou hast humbled us: the years, wherein we have seen evils. \f + \fr 89:15 \ft Yes the more we suffer in this life for the truth, the greater is our comfort in hope of reward.\f*
\v 16 Look upon thy servants, and upon thy works: and direct their children. \f + \fr 89:16 \ft Not only in that we are thy creatures, but also in that we are thy servants, we are thy proper work: therefore in both these respects, o God, look upon us with clemency.\f* \f + \fr 89:16 \ft Lead also our posterity into the right way, and make them thy servants.\f*
\v 17 And let the brightness of our Lord God be upon us, and direct thou the works of our hands over us: and the work of our hands do thou direct. \f + \fr 89:17 \ft O God illuminate our understanding,\f* \f + \fr 89:17 \ft make our actions by thy grace profitable to us:\f* \f + \fr 89:17 \ft & make perfect in us the work of charity. In which one work all good works are included, and to which all other are directed. For then works are right (saith S. Augustin) when they are directed to this one end.\f*
\c 90
\p
\v 1 Praise of a Canticle to David. He that dwelleth in the help of the Highest, shall abide in the protection of the God of heaven. \f + \fr 90:1 \ft Praise of God's providence, with thanks,\f* \f + \fr 90:1 \ft which David sung with voice.\f* \f + \fr 90:1 \ft He that firmly relieth and resteth upon God's providence, is assuredly protected by him.\f*
\v 2 He shall say to our Lord: Thou art my protector, and my refuge: my God I will hope in him.
\v 3 Because he hath delivered me from the snare of the hunters, and from the sharp word. \f + \fr 90:3 \ft All secret and subtle machinations:\f* \f + \fr 90:3 \ft and from all cruelty of tyrants.\f*
\v 4 With his shoulders shall he overshadow thee: and under his wings thou shalt hope.
\v 5 With shield shall his truth compass thee: thou shalt not be afraid of the fear in the night. \f + \fr 90:5 \ft Terrors obscurely suggested by evil men or spirits, with erroneous conceit that men are not bound in time of temporal dangers to confess the truth.\f*
\v 6 Of the arrow flying in the day, of business walking in darkness: of invasion, and the midday devil. \f + \fr 90:6 \ft Open persecution threatening present death, except men deny the truth which they know,\f* \f + \fr 90:6 \ft circumvention of crafty enemies by subtle arguing, and drawing men into error, and so to decline from Catholic Religion,\f* \f + \fr 90:6 \ft long\f*
\v 7 A thousand shall fall on thy side, & ten thousand on thy right hand: but to thee it shall not approach. \f + \fr 90:7 \ft On thy left side, in adversity many fall from God,\f* \f + \fr 90:7 \ft & on thy right side, in prosperity many more forget and forsake God.\f*
\v 8 But thou shalt consider with thine eyes: and shalt see the retribution of sinners.
\v 9 Because thou o Lord art my hope: thou hast made the Highest thy refuge. \f + \fr 90:9 \ft In sincerely saying Thou art my hope thou makest God thy refuge.\f*
\v 10 There shall no evil come to thee: and scourge shall not approach to thy tabernacle.
\v 11 Because he hath given his Angels charge of thee: that they keep thee in all thy ways. \f + \fr 90:11 \ft Angels have protection of men by God's ordinance.\f* \f + \fr 90:11 \ft The devil corruptly allege this scripture (Mat. 4.) omitting\f*
\v 12 In their hands they shall bear thee: lest perhaps thou knock thy foot against a stone.
\v 13 Upon the asp and the basiliscus thou shall walk: & thou shalt tread upon the lion, and the dragon.
\v 14 Because he hath hoped in me, I will deliver him: I will protect him, because he hath known my name. \f + \fr 90:14 \ft God speaketh the rest that followeth in this Psalm.\f*
\v 15 He shall cry to me, and I will hear him: with him I am in tribulation: I will deliver him, and will glorify him. \f + \fr 90:15 \ft In eternal salvation.\f*
\v 16 With length of days I will replenish him: and I will shew him my salvation.
\c 91
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of Canticle, in the sabbath day. \f + \fr 91:1 \ft Voices beginning instruments prosecute this song:\f* \f + \fr 91:1 \ft when we rest from work, then especially we ought to think upon God's works, praise and thank him for the same.\f*
\v 2 It is good to confess to our Lord: and to sing to thy name, o Highest. \f + \fr 91:2 \ft To give thanks.\f*
\v 3 To shew forth thy mercy in the morning: and thy truth in the night. \f + \fr 91:3 \ft In prosperity.\f* \f + \fr 91:3 \ft in adversity.\f*
\v 4 In the instrument of ten strings, in Psalter: with Canticle, on the Harp. \f + \fr 91:4 \ft On every instrument of ten strings, signifying the observation of the ten commandments:\f* \f + \fr 91:4 \ft namely on the Psalter\f* \f + \fr 91:4 \ft also on the harp, which signifieth mortification.\f*
\v 5 Because thou hast delighted me, o Lord, in thy workmanship: and in the works of thy hands I will rejoice.
\v 6 How are thy works magnified, o Lord! Thy cogitations are made very profound.
\v 7 The unwise man will not know; and the fool will not understand these things. \f + \fr 91:7 \ft Carnal and sensual man,\f* \f + \fr 91:7 \ft he that thinketh only of present things, not of future.\f*
\v 8 When sinners shall spring up as grass: and all that work iniquity shall appear. That they may perish for ever:
\v 9 but thou the Highest for ever, o Lord.
\v 10 Because lo thine enemies, o Lord, because lo thine enemies shall perish: and all that work iniquity shall be dispersed.
\v 11 And my horn shall be exalted, as the unicorn's: and my old age in plentiful mercy. \f + \fr 91:11 \ft The just in confidence of a good conscience expect exaltation of their power:\f* \f + \fr 91:11 \ft and great consolation in the end of their life.\f*
\v 12 And mine eye hath looked upon mine enemies: and the malignant rising up against me, mine ears shall hear. \f + \fr 91:12 \ft Then shall the justice their enemies depressed: and themselves flourish, like the palm, and cedar trees as followeth:\f*
\v 13 The just shall flourish as a palm tree: as the cedar of Libanus shall he be multiplied.
\v 14 They that are planted in the house of our Lord, shall flourish in the courts of the house of our God. \f + \fr 91:14 \ft Militant Church:\f* \f + \fr 91:14 \ft triumphant.\f*
\v 15 As yet shall they be multiplied in plentiful old age: and they shall be well affected,
\v 16 that they may shew forth: That the Lord our God is righteous, and there is no iniquity in him. \f + \fr 91:16 \ft Publicly profess God's praise, as in the words following:\f*
\c 92
\p
\v 1 Praise of Canticle to David himself in the day before the sabbath, when the earth was founded. Our Lord hath reigned, he hath put on beauty: our Lord hath put on strength, and hath girded himself. For he hath established the round world, which shall not be moved. \f + \fr 92:1 \ft Praise to be sung with voice:\f* \f + \fr 92:1 \ft composed by David:\f* \f + \fr 92:1 \ft the sixth day of the week, which is our Friday,\f* \f + \fr 92:1 \ft in which day the Church of Christ was founded by his blood shed on the cross.\f* \f + \fr 92:1 \ft Our Saviour founding his Church by his death began then to reign therein\f* \f + \fr 92:1 \ft gloriously descending in soul into limbus, and in body to his grave:\f* \f + \fr 92:1 \ft he then put on all armour of strength to reform the world, and to enlarge his Kingdom, according to his own prediction where he said: If I be exalted from the earth, I will draw all things unto myself. Ioan. 12. v. 31.\f* \f + \fr 92:1 \ft Not only in Jury and Samaria, but the whole earth:\f* \f + \fr 92:1 \ft and the same Church shall not be destroyed.\f*
\v 2 Thy seat is prepared from that time: thou art from everlasting. \f + \fr 92:2 \ft Christ being eternal, hath an everlasting Church.\f*
\v 3 The rivers o Lord have lifted up: the rivers have lifted up their voice. The rivers have lifted up their waves, \f + \fr 92:3 \ft All sorts of persecuters, the High priests (who sometimes watered the spiritual land, like rivers) which Scribes, Pharisees, and other incredulous Jews, also Pagans, Turks, and Heretics have oppugned the Church.\f*
\v 4 above the voices of many waters. The surges of the sea are marvelous, marvelous is our Lord on high. \f + \fr 92:4 \ft With more force than any persecutions in the old Testament.\f* \f + \fr 92:4 \ft But though all these assaults be great and marvelous, yet Christ in protecting his Church, is more marvelous.\f*
\v 5 Thy testimonies are made credible exceedingly: holiness becometh thy house, o Lord for length of days. \f + \fr 92:5 \ft Articles of faith are not evidently apparent to knowledge, but evident to credibility, to those that are disposed by God's grace, illuminating their understanding, and moving their free will, to give consent of belief if they will.\f* \f + \fr 92:5 \ft It behoveth therefore all members of the Church to converse piously, and religiously in this life, seeing she hath so excellent a spouse, protector, and instructor,\f* \f + \fr 92:5 \ft even to the end of the world.\f*
\c 93
\p
\v 1 To David himself, in the fourth of the sabbath. Our Lord God of revenges: the God of revenges hath done freely. \f + \fr 93:1 \ft The Hebrew letter Lamed, which ordinarily is prefixed to the dative case, or signifieth to, being set before proper names, is a sign of the genitive case. Yet the Septuagint express it by the dative, and so doth the Latin, ipsi David, and consequently our English hath, to David himself, to shew a difference between sacred and profane writers. For in human books the writer and author is all one; but in divine, the Holy Ghost is the proper author, and a man is the writer. To signify therefore the principal author, David is sometimes named as the instrumental cause, to whom the Holy Ghost inspired this and other Psalms, and by whom they were written. And when the titles express otherwise:\f* \f + \fr 93:1 \ft Made and ordinarily sung in the fourth day of the week, our Wednesday, in which day Judas the traitor sold our Saviour Christ to his enemies. The revenge of which wickedness, and of all other sins, is here prophesied.\f* \f + \fr 93:1 \ft God more commonly called the God of mercy (which virtue in him is above all his works, Psal. 144. ) is also the God of revenges, according to his justice.\f* \f + \fr 93:1 \ft He proceedeth in judgement resolutely, not depending, nor fearing, nor respecting any person, power, dignity, wisdom or other like quality, but their just merits.\f*
\v 2 Be exalted thou that judgest the earth: render retribution to the proud. \f + \fr 93:2 \ft Aprayer of just zeal.\f*
\v 3 How long shall sinners, o Lord: how long shall sinners glory?
\v 4 Shall they utter, and speak iniquity? Shall all they speak that work injustice? \f + \fr 93:4 \ft Shall most wicked men still be suffered to speak so insolently?\f*
\v 5 Thy people, o Lord, they have humbled: and thine inheritance they have vexed. \f + \fr 93:5 \ft Adescription of heathenish and heretical cruelty.\f*
\v 6 The widow, and the stranger they have slain: and the pupils they have killed.
\v 7 And they have said: The Lord shall not see, neither shall the God of Jacob understand. \f + \fr 93:7 \ft Scarce any Atheists are so blind as thus to think, but many sinners so behave themselves, as if God saw not, knew not, or at least cared not what they do.\f*
\v 8 Understand ye foolish in the people: and ye fools be wise at sometime.
\v 9 He that planted the ear, shall he not hear? Or he that made the eye doth he not consider?
\v 10 He that chastiseth nations, shall he not rebuke: he that teacheth man knowledge?
\v 11 Our Lord knoweth the cogitations of men: that they be vain. \f + \fr 93:11 \ft So unpossible is it that God should be ignorant, or careless what men do, that he also knoweth and observeth most secret thoughts.\f*
\v 12 Blessed is the man whom thou shalt instruct, o Lord, and shalt teach out of thy law.
\v 13 That thou mayst give him quietness from the evil days: till a pit be digged for the sinner. \f + \fr 93:13 \ft Mitigate and temper his afflictions, that by patience and fortitude the just may persevere, and not be overwhelmed.\f*
\v 14 Because our Lord will not reject his people: and his inheritance he will not forsake. \f + \fr 93:14 \ft The whole Church shall never be rejected, nor forsaken.\f*
\v 15 Until justice be turned into judgment: and they who are near it, are all that are right of heart. \f + \fr 93:15 \ft Justice is converted into judgement, when just meaning is put in work and practice, that it may appear in judgement. Also God who doth & suffereth all justly, will conserve his inheritance the Church, even unto the day of judgement.\f* \f + \fr 93:15 \ft The sense is easy by transposing the words: all that are right of heart, are near it, that is, shall like and approve God's justice, when the wicked shall repine, and blaspheme it.\f*
\v 16 Who shall rise for me against the malignant? Or who shall stand with me against them that work iniquity?
\v 17 But that our Lord hath holpen me: within very little my soul had dwelt in hell.
\v 18 If I said: My foot is moved: thy mercy, o Lord, did help me. \f + \fr 93:18 \ft When I felt and complained that I was in danger, thou didst assist me.\f*
\v 19 According to the multitude of my sorrows in my heart: thy consolations have made my soul joyful.
\v 20 Doth the seat of iniquity cleave to thee: which makest labour in precept? \f + \fr 93:20 \ft Only faith sufficeth not, but careful labour, in keeping God's commandments is required.\f*
\v 21 They will hunt after the soul of the just: and will condemn innocent blood.
\v 22 And our Lord became my refuge: and my God the help of my hope. \f + \fr 93:22 \ft The just do hope for eternal salvation, to which God will bring them.\f*
\v 23 And he will repay them their iniquity: and in their malice he will destroy them: the Lord our God will destroy them. \f + \fr 93:23 \ft And God, the revenger of wrongs, will at last cast the wicked into eternal torments.\f*
\c 94
\p
\v 1 Praise of Canticle, to David himself. Come, let us rejoice to our Lord: let us make jubilation to God our saviour. \f + \fr 94:1 \ft Praise sung with voices:\f* \f + \fr 94:1 \ft inspired to David, & written by him.\f* \f + \fr 94:1 \ft With great and solemn exultation:\f* \f + \fr 94:1 \ft God our Creator, is also our Protector & Saviour.\f* \f + \fr 94:1 \ft This invitation is most fitly ordained by the Church for the proem or beginning of Matins.\f*
\v 2 Let us prevent his face in confession: and in Psalms let us make jubilation to him. \f + \fr 94:2 \ft Let us be more diligent, and prevent our accustomed time. For no man can prevent God's grace with any good work, who first preventeth us, else we can neither do, nor think any good thing.\f* \f + \fr 94:2 \ft Not only in singing his praise with voice, but also with musical instruments.\f*
\v 3 Because our Lord is a great God: and a great King above all gods.
\v 4 Because in his hand are the ends of the earth: and the heights of the mountains be his.
\v 5 Because the sea is his, and he made it: and his hands formed the dry land.
\v 6 Come let us adore, and fall down: and weep before our Lord, that made us. \f + \fr 94:6 \ft So also Isaias (c. 45. v. 23.) and S. Paul (Philip. 2.) teach that kneeling or bowing the knees, as an external religious ceremony, is acceptable to God.\f*
\v 7 Because he is the Lord our God, and we the people of his pasture, and the sheep of his hand. \f + \fr 94:7 \ft It is most just and necessary that we adore God, because he made us, and all this world for us, hath also redeemed us, and made us his people, as sheep of his pasture, and as a Pastor feedeth and governeth us.\f* \f + \fr 94:7 \ft Of his making.\f*
\v 8 Today if ye shall hear his voice, harden not your hearts. \f + \fr 94:8 \ft Though some have often repelled, and resisted God's grace, yet if they receive it being offered again, it will avail them to remission of sins.\f*
\v 9 As in the provocation according to the day of the tentation in the desert: where your fathers tempted me, proved me, and saw my works. \f + \fr 94:9 \ft The Israelites in the desert tempted God, by desiring water, and flesh, of voluptuous concupiscence without necessity. For Manna did both extinguish their thirst, and tasted unto them whatsoever they desired: Exod. 16. That also which was left ungathered when the sun waxed hot, melted (v. 21.) and served their cattle for drink. So this tentation was a figure of those, which require to communicate under both kinds, as if one did not contain as much as both.\f*
\v 10 Forty years was I offended with that generation, and said: These always err in heart. \f + \fr 94:10 \ft By this mention of the offence of forty years, as long before passed, is convinced that Moyses writ not this Psalm, who died in the very fortieth year of their abode in the desert. And Saint Paul citing the words of this Psalm (Heb. 4. ) manifestly acknowledgeth David the writer thereof, and that it was written long after Moyses' time in these words: (v. 7.) Again he limiteth a certain day: Today, in David saying after so long time, as is above said. Today if you shall hear his voice, do not obdurate your hearts. For if Jesus (that is Iosue) had given them rest, he would never speak of another day afterward.\f* \f + \fr 94:10 \ft Being greatly offended, I approached near unto them, in punishing the offenders.\f*
\v 11 And these have not known my ways: as I sware in my wrath: if they shall enter into my rest. \f + \fr 94:11 \ft Those that murmured died in the desert, and entered not into the promised land, even so those that finally offend Christ, shall not enter into everlasting rest. Heb. 3. & 4.\f*
\c 95
\p
\v 1 A Canticle to David himself, when the house was built after the captivity. Sing ye to our Lord a new song: sing to our Lord all the earth. \f + \fr 95:1 \ft Inspired to David, and written by him:\f* \f + \fr 95:1 \ft prophesying the restoration of the temple, after the future captivity. And that in figure of the universal redemption of mankind by Christ, from the captivity of the devil.\f* \f + \fr 95:1 \ft For a new benefit, far greater than the delivery of Israel from Ægypt.\f*
\v 2 Sing ye to our Lord, and bless his name: shew forth his salvation from day to day. \f + \fr 95:2 \ft The same words (Sing to our Lord) thrice repeated, signify the Blessed Trinity, as some Fathers note. Likewise v. 7. & 8. Bring ye to our Lord &c. in both places concluding in the singular number, bless his name, bring to his name, importing one God.\f*
\v 3 Shew forth his glory among the Gentiles, his marvelous works in all peoples.
\v 4 Because our Lord is great, and exceeding laudable: he is terrible above all gods.
\v 5 Because all the gods of the Gentiles are devils, but our Lord made the heavens. \f + \fr 95:5 \ft What creatures soever spiritual or corporal, visible or invisible the Pagans serve for gods, still they be devils that deceive them, and diverse ways usurp divine honour, making such idolaters to think, that there is divine power, where none is.\f* \f + \fr 95:5 \ft He only is true God, who is Creator of heaven, and of all creatures. For no creature can create any thing at all, that is, make any thing of nothing, but only God.\f*
\v 6 Confession and beauty in his sight: holiness and magnificence in his sanctification.
\v 7 Bring to our Lord ye families of Gentiles, bring ye to our Lord glory and honour:
\v 8 bring to our Lord glory unto his name. Take up hosts, and enter into his courts:
\v 9 adore ye our Lord in his holy court. Let all the earth be moved before his face:
\v 10 Say ye among the Gentiles that our Lord hath reigned. For he hath corrected the round world, which shall not be moved: he will judge peoples in equity. \f + \fr 95:10 \ft Diverse ancient Doctors read more in this place: Our Lord hath reigned from the wood, to wit, Christ by his death on the cross conquered the devil, sin, and death, and thence began to reign. S. Justinus Martyr, dialogo advers. Triphonem, Tertullian li. advers. Iudæos. c. 9. & 13. & advers. Marcionem li. 3. c. 19. & 21. S. Augustin in this place, according to the old Roman Psalter. Before him Arnobius, and after him Cassiodorus and others, whereby it is probable, that it was sometimes in the Hebrew text, and blotted out by the Jews.\f*
\v 11 Let the heavens be glad, and the earth rejoice, the sea be moved, and the fullness thereof: \f + \fr 95:11 \ft The Psalmist in aboundance of spirit inviteth all creatures to praise God, as Daniel in his Canticle. c. 3.\f*
\v 12 the fields shall be glad, and all things that are in them. Then shall the trees of the woods rejoice
\v 13 before the face of our Lord, because he cometh: because he cometh to judge the earth. He will judge the round world in equity, and peoples in his truth. \f + \fr 95:13 \ft Christ judgeth now in the world by his ministers, discerning and deciding causes, rewarding and punishing, but especially he will judge all in the last day.\f*
\c 96
\p
\v 1 To this David, when his land was restored again to him. Our Lord hath reigned, let the earth rejoice: let many Islands be glad. \f + \fr 96:1 \ft In figure of Christ,\f* \f + \fr 96:1 \ft whose body rose the third day after his death: to whom many returned believing in him after his resurrection, which fell from him in his passion: and to whom all things shall be subdued, as to their true Lord, in the day of judgement.\f* \f + \fr 96:1 \ft Holy David and other Prophets having great joy to see long before in spirit only, Christ's Kingdom extended in the whole earth, yea to the Islands, we Islanders have great cause to be glad, that God hath not only so blessed us long since, but as yet conserveth seed, whereby we trust the whole Island shall be again restored unto him.\f*
\v 2 Cloud and mist round about him: justice and judgment the correction of his seat. \f + \fr 96:2 \ft As in a cloud with terror God gave his law to the Jews: so in a cloud with greater terror and majesty, he will judge the world;\f* \f + \fr 96:2 \ft not as many corrupted seats of judgement, in this world, but as a corrected tribunal, where justice and right judgement shall be practised.\f*
\v 3 Fire shall go before him, and shall inflame his enemies round about.
\v 4 His lightnings shined to the round world, the earth saw: and was moved. \f + \fr 96:4 \ft These things are denounced as if they were already done, for the assured certainty thereof.\f*
\v 5 The mountains melted as wax, before the face of our Lord: before the face of our Lord all the earth.
\v 6 The heavens have shewed forth his justice: and all peoples have seen his glory.
\v 7 Let them all be confounded, that adore sculptiles: and that glory in their idols. Adore him all ye his Angels: \f + \fr 96:7 \ft As well the worshippers of graven or painted images of Jupiter, Mars, Bacchus & the like, as the worshippers of the same imagined false gods shall be confounded.\f*
\v 8 Sion heard, and was glad. And the daughters of Juda rejoiced, because of thy judgments, o Lord. \f + \fr 96:8 \ft The Catholic Church.\f* \f + \fr 96:8 \ft And all particular Churches, members of the universal.\f*
\v 9 Because thou Lord most high over all the earth: thou art exalted exceedingly above all gods.
\v 10 You that love our Lord, hate ye evil, our Lord keepeth the souls of his saints, out of the hand of the sinner he will deliver them.
\v 11 Light is risen to the just, and joy to the right of heart.
\v 12 Be glad ye just in our Lord: and confess ye to the memory of his sanctification. \f + \fr 96:12 \ft Praise our Lord Christ, who is sanctity it-self, and sanctifieth others.\f*
\c 97
\p
\v 0 his coming to judge the world. \f + \fr 97:0 \ft The Church in all nations. The 6. key.\f*
\v 1 A Psalm to David himself. Sing ye to our Lord a new song: because he hath done marvelous things. His right hand hath wrought salvation to himself: and his arm is holy. \f + \fr 97:1 \ft Prefiguring Christ, who hath made his salvation known in all nations.\f* \f + \fr 97:1 \ft Anew benefit of grace, making men new in spirit, requireth a new song of gratitude.\f* \f + \fr 97:1 \ft Raised up himself from death.\f*
\v 2 Our Lord hath made known his salvation: in the sight of the Gentiles he hath revealed his justice. \f + \fr 97:2 \ft Made his grace effectually known by raising men from sin, and delivering them from the power of the devil.\f*
\v 3 He hath remembered his mercy, and his truth to the house of Israel. All the ends of the earth have seen the salvation of our God. \f + \fr 97:3 \ft some of the Jews converted to Christianity. Rom. 11.\f*
\v 4 Make ye jubilation to God all the earth: chant, and rejoice, and sing. \f + \fr 97:4 \ft In voice.\f* \f + \fr 97:4 \ft In heart.\f* \f + \fr 97:4 \ft In instruments.\f* \f + \fr 97:4 \ft Cantate, exultate, psallite.\f*
\v 5 Sing to our Lord on harp, on harp and voice of Psalm:
\v 6 on long drawn trumpets, and voice of cornet of horn. Make jubilation in the sight of the King our Lord:
\v 7 let the sea be moved, and the fullness thereof: the round world, and they that dwell therein.
\v 8 The rivers shall clap with hand: the mountains together shall rejoice
\v 9 at the sight of our Lord: because he cometh to judge the earth. He will judge the round earth in justice, and the peoples in equity. \f + \fr 97:9 \ft Christ directeth and disposeth all things rightly in this world.\f* \f + \fr 97:9 \ft And will accordingly give just sentence in the end.\f*
\c 98
\p
\v 1 Apsalm to David himself. Our Lord hath reigned, let peoples be angry: he that sitteth upon the Cherubs, let the earth be moved. \f + \fr 98:1 \ft Though many enemies do rage and impugn Christ:\f* \f + \fr 98:1 \ft though the whole earth be troubled therewith, yet Christ who sitteth Lord over the highest Angels, Cherubins and Seraphins, obtaineth the victories, reigneth, and doth his will in the earth.\f*
\v 2 Our Lord great in Sion: and high above all peoples.
\v 3 Let them confess to thy great name: because it is terrible and holy.
\v 4 And the honour of the King loveth judgment. Thou hast prepared directions: thou hast done judgment and justice in Jacob. \f + \fr 98:4 \ft Requireth discretion.\f* \f + \fr 98:4 \ft in favour of thine elect people.\f*
\v 5 Exalt ye the Lord our God, and adore his foot-stool: because it is holy. \f + \fr 98:5 \ft Hebrew Doctors expound this of the Ark in the old testament, but the Doctors of the Church understand Christ's humanity, in the holy Eucharist.\f*
\v 6 Moyses and Aaron in his Priests: and Samuel among them that invocate his name: They invocated our Lord and he heard them: \f + \fr 98:6 \ft Here it is evident (and S. Augustin saith this place taketh away all doubt) that Moyses was a Priest, against those that for maintaining the heresy of Lay-headship, deny it.\f*
\v 7 in a pillar of a cloud he spake to them. They kept his testimonies, & the precept which he gave them.
\v 8 O Lord our God thou heardest them: God thou wast propitious to them, and taking vengeance upon all their inventions. \f + \fr 98:8 \ft God revenged the machinations made against them,\f*
\v 9 Exalt ye the Lord our God, and adore ye in his holy mount: because the Lord our God is holy.
\c 99
\p
\v 1 A Psalm in confession. \f + \fr 99:1 \ft of praise.\f*
\v 2 Make ye jubilation to God all the earth: serve ye our Lord in gladness. Enter ye in before his sight, in exultation. \f + \fr 99:2 \ft Not only Jews, but also all Gentiles.\f* \f + \fr 99:2 \ft God every-where present, yet more peculiarly, heareth his suppliants, praying in the temple, or places dedicated to his service.\f*
\v 3 Know ye that our Lord he is God: he made us, & not we ourselves. His people, and the sheep of his pasture: \f + \fr 99:3 \ft He only whom we serve as our Lord, is the only God, and there is no other.\f*
\v 4 enter ye into his gates in confession, his courts in hymns, confess ye to him. Praise ye his name: \f + \fr 99:4 \ft Peculiar dedicated place, as v. 2.\f*
\v 5 because our Lord is sweet, his mercy for ever, and his truth even unto generation and generation. \f + \fr 99:5 \ft As God is always merciful in giving and promising:\f* \f + \fr 99:5 \ft so he is ever faithful in performing.\f*
\c 100
\p
\v 1 A Psalm to David himself. Mercy and judgment I will sing to thee, o Lord: I will sing, \f + \fr 100:1 \ft These two capital divine virtues are ever joined in all God's works, for both which experienced towards himself, the Psalmists rendereth thanks and praises.\f*
\v 2 and I shall understand in the immaculate way, when thou shalt come to me. I walked through in the innocency of my heart, in the midst of my house. \f + \fr 100:2 \ft Iwill do mine endeavour to know the immaculate way,\f* \f + \fr 100:2 \ft which I cannot do, but by thy grace coming unto me. For by help thereof I did as followeth:\f*
\v 3 I did not propose before mine eyes any unjust thing: I hated them that do prevarication.
\v 4 Aperverse heart hath not cleaved to me: the malignant declining from me I knew not.
\v 5 One secretly detracting from his neighbour, him did I persecute. One of a proud eye, and unsatiable heart, with him I did not eat. \f + \fr 100:5 \ft That is, all and every one thus wickedly disposed I abhorred.\f*
\v 6 Mine eyes are towards the faithful of the earth that they may sit with me. A man that walketh in the immaculate way he did minister to me. \f + \fr 100:6 \ft Ikept such under, as a servant or slave.\f*
\v 7 He that doth proudly shall not dwell in the midst of my house: he that speaketh unjust things, hath not directed in the sight of mine eyes. \f + \fr 100:7 \ft Prospered not, got no benefit by me.\f*
\v 8 In the morning did I kill all the sinners of the earth: that I might destroy out of the city of our Lord all those that work iniquity. \f + \fr 100:8 \ft Speedily and without delay I cut off all disordered people:\f* \f + \fr 100:8 \ft that others might not be corrupted by them.\f*
\c 101
\p
\v 1 The prayer of the poor, when he shall be anxious, and shall make his petition before our Lord.
\v 2 Lord hear my prayer: and let my cry come to thee. \f + \fr 101:2 \ft Every petition is a prayer,\f* \f + \fr 101:2 \ft and that which proceedeth from more fervent affection, is called a cry, though it burst not out into clamour, nor perhaps into any voice at all. For God said to Moyses, praying in mere silence, but with vehemency of spirit (Exod. 14.) Why cryest thou to me?\f*
\v 3 Turn not away thy face from me: in what day soever I am in tribulation, incline thine ear to me. In what day soever I shall invocate thee, hear me speedily. \f + \fr 101:3 \ft Though sin provoke God's wrath, because we by sinning turn from him, and not he first from us: yet we pray God not so to leave us, but to give us new grace, that by humility, and penance we may return to him, and not die in sin.\f*
\v 4 Because my days have vanished as smoke: and my bones are withered as a dry burnt firebrand. \f + \fr 101:4 \ft Man's days, and all his works are nothing worth, but vanish like smoke, so long as he is in mortal sin:\f* \f + \fr 101:4 \ft yea his best works, as if he give alms, fast, pray, and die for the truth, yet all those avail nothing. 1. Cor. 13. but are\f* \f + \fr 101:4 \ft like dried sticks, or chips, fit to kindle the fire.\f*
\v 5 I am strucken as grass, and my heart is withered: because I have forgotten to eat my bread. \f + \fr 101:5 \ft My soul separated by sin from God, withereth as grass that is cut from the root:\f* \f + \fr 101:5 \ft because I have lost all favour and appetite to spiritual meat.\f*
\v 6 For the voice of my groaning, my bone hath cleaved to my flesh. \f + \fr 101:6 \ft In this miserable state\f* \f + \fr 101:6 \ft Iam as bones and flesh cleaving together without moisture, or radical humour.\f*
\v 7 I am become like a pelican of the wilderness: I am become as a night crow in the house. \f + \fr 101:7 \ft Ifled from conversation of men for sorrow and shame of my sins:\f* \f + \fr 101:7 \ft as a crow that only flieth by night: or as an owl or bat.\f*
\v 8 I have watched, and am become as a sparrow solitary in the house-top. \f + \fr 101:8 \ft Also as a sparrow having lost her mate, remaineth mourning and solitary in the accustomed nest, or near unto it.\f*
\v 9 All the day did mine enemies upbraid me: and they that praised me sware against me. \f + \fr 101:9 \ft Those that were wont to praise or flatter me, now are as sworn enemies against me.\f*
\v 10 Because I did eat ashes as bread, & mingled my drink with weeping. \f + \fr 101:10 \ft Bread savoured to me no better than ashes.\f* \f + \fr 101:10 \ft And drink gave me no comfort, but still I wept.\f*
\v 11 At the face of thy wrath and indignation: because lifting me up thou hast thrown me down. \f + \fr 101:11 \ft Iam most especially afflicted, because thou art angry.\f* \f + \fr 101:11 \ft In that thou didst sometime advance me in prosperity,\f* \f + \fr 101:11 \ft my fall is so much greater, and more grievous.\f*
\v 12 My days have declined as a shadow: and I am withered as grass. \f + \fr 101:12 \ft As a shadow declineth to nothing, & all becometh darkness, when the sun, and other light departeth, even so I, that am but a shadow, decline to mere darkness when thy favour parteth from me:\f* \f + \fr 101:12 \ft and I lose my beauty, as grass cut from the ground withereth.\f*
\v 13 But thou o Lord endurest for ever: and thy memorial in generation and generation. \f + \fr 101:13 \ft But I am marvelously comforted, considering that thou our Messias, the Son of God, art immutable for ever:\f* \f + \fr 101:13 \ft and thy memorable promise of redeeming mankind, will have effect in all generations.\f*
\v 14 Thou rising up shalt have mercy on Sion: because it is time to have mercy on it, because the time cometh. \f + \fr 101:14 \ft Thou rising to help, who seemedst to have forgot, wilt protect the Church, and every faithful soul.\f* \f + \fr 101:14 \ft Because thou hast deferred long:\f* \f + \fr 101:14 \ft and because the time by thee designed seemeth to approach.\f*
\v 15 Because the stones thereof have pleased thy servants: and they shall have pity on the earth thereof. \f + \fr 101:15 \ft Men that shall hear thine Apostles preach, shall prove good and fit matter, for the building of thy Church:\f* \f + \fr 101:15 \ft and the simplest poor people, as it were the earth or dust,\f* \f + \fr 101:15 \ft shall participate of this mercy.\f*
\v 16 And the Gentiles shall fear thy name o Lord, and all the kings of the earth thy glory. \f + \fr 101:16 \ft Besides those Jews that shall believe in Christ, much more the Gentiles shall fear and serve him.\f* \f + \fr 101:16 \ft His glory is so evident that all kings know it, though all be not converted.\f*
\v 17 Because our Lord hath built Sion: and he shall be seen in his glory.
\v 18 He hath had respect to the prayer of the humble: and he hath not despised their petition. \f + \fr 101:18 \ft Of holy Patriarchs, Priests, Prophets, and of all true penitents.\f*
\v 19 Let these things be written unto another generation: and the people that shall be created shall praise our Lord. \f + \fr 101:19 \ft That shall be made a new creature in Christ.\f*
\v 20 Because he hath looked forth from his high holy place: our Lord from heaven hath looked upon the earth.
\v 21 That he might hear the groanings of the fettered: that he might loose the children of them that are slain:
\v 22 That they may shew forth the name of our Lord in Sion: and his praise in Jerusalem. \f + \fr 101:22 \ft The faithful people of the Church, according to their hability endeavour to serve Christ.\f*
\v 23 In the assembling of the people together in one, and kings to serve our Lord.
\v 24 He answered him in the way of his strength: Shew me the fewness of my days.
\v 25 Call me not back in the half of my days: thy years are unto generation and generation. \f + \fr 101:25 \ft Grant me time and means to be mature in virtue in this life.\f*
\v 26 In the beginning, o Lord, thou didst found the earth: and the heavens are the works of thy hands.
\v 27 They shall perish, but thou art permanent: and they shall all wax old as a garment. And as a vesture thou shalt change them, and they shall be changed: \f + \fr 101:27 \ft Be changed in quality.\f*
\v 28 but thou art the self-same, and thy years shall not fail.
\v 29 The children of thy servants shall inhabit: and their seed shall be directed for ever. \f + \fr 101:29 \ft The Church of Christ perpetual.\f*
\c 102
\p
\v 1 To David himself. My soul bless thou our Lord: and all things, that are within me, his holy name. \f + \fr 102:1 \ft Inspired to David, and written by him.\f* \f + \fr 102:1 \ft Shew forth praises and thanks:\f* \f + \fr 102:1 \ft all my cogitations, affections, senses, and powers.\f*
\v 2 My soul bless thou our Lord: and forget not all his retributions.
\v 3 Who is propitious to all thine iniquities: who healeth all thine infirmities. \f + \fr 102:3 \ft The first benefit of grace is remission of sins:\f* \f + \fr 102:3 \ft the second, is curing evil habits, or dispositions.\f*
\v 4 Who redeemeth thy life from deadly falling: who crowneth thee in mercy and commiserations. \f + \fr 102:4 \ft The third, to conserve from falling again:\f* \f + \fr 102:4 \ft the fourth, to give victory and reward in aboundant measure.\f*
\v 5 Who replenisheth thy desire in good things: thy youth shall be renewed as the eagle's. \f + \fr 102:5 \ft The fifth, to grant all lawful petitions temporal and spiritual, which are good for the soul,\f* \f + \fr 102:5 \ft the sixth, resurrection of flesh in glory.\f*
\v 6 Our Lord doth mercies: and judgment to all that suffer wrong. \f + \fr 102:6 \ft Our Lord, whose special property is to shew mercy,\f* \f + \fr 102:6 \ft when the same is neglected; he revengeth the wrongs, delivering the oppressed, and punishing the oppressors.\f*
\v 7 He made his ways known to Moyses, his wills to the children of Israel. \f + \fr 102:7 \ft By giving them as written law.\f*
\v 8 Our Lord is pitiful, and merciful: long suffering, and very merciful. \f + \fr 102:8 \ft God is naturally pitiful to relieve the afflicted.\f* \f + \fr 102:8 \ft Merciful towards sinners.\f* \f + \fr 102:8 \ft Loath to be angry, or to punish.\f*
\v 9 He will not be angry always: neither will he threaten for ever. \f + \fr 102:9 \ft God punisheth not penitents with eternal pain, but with temporal: for though (as in the next verse) our sins of their own nature deserve eternal punishment, yet Christ paying our ransom, true penitents are only punished temporally.\f*
\v 10 He hath not done to us according to our sins: neither according to our iniquities hath he rewarded us.
\v 11 For according to the height of heaven from the earth: hath he strengthened his mercy upon them that fear him.
\v 12 As far as the East is distant from the West: hath he made our iniquities far from us. \f + \fr 102:12 \ft See here the perfect washing away, and separation of sins.\f*
\v 13 As a father hath compassion of his children, so hath our Lord compassion on them that fear him:
\v 14 because he hath known our making. He remembered that we are dust: \f + \fr 102:14 \ft In regard of our frailty he hath compassion: yet his mercy only availeth to them that fear him: as in the next words before, and v. 17.\f*
\v 15 man, his days are as grass, as the flower of the field, so shall he flourish.
\v 16 Because the spirit shall pass in him, and he shall not stand: and he shall know his place no more.
\v 17 But the mercy of our Lord from everlasting, and unto everlasting upon them that fear him. And his justice is upon the children's children, to them that keep his testament.
\v 18 And are mindful of his commandments to do them. \f + \fr 102:18 \ft Ajust man not only knoweth, & remembereth, but also doth the commandments.\f*
\v 19 Our Lord hath prepared his seat in heaven: and his Kingdom shall have dominion over all.
\v 20 Bless our Lord all ye his Angels: mighty in power, doing his word, that fear the voice of his words.
\v 21 Bless our Lord all ye his hosts: you his ministers, that do his will.
\v 22 Bless ye our Lord all his works: in every place of his dominion, my soul bless thou our Lord. \f + \fr 102:22 \ft All creatures, though naturally senseless, yet praise God, because they are his work,\f* \f + \fr 102:22 \ft and because they are in his dominion.\f*
\c 103
\p
\v 1 To David himself. My soul bless thou our Lord: o Lord my God thou art magnified exceedingly.
\v 2 Thou hast put on confession and beauty: being clothed with light as with a garment. Stretching out the heaven as a skin: \f + \fr 103:2 \ft Thou possessest all majesty, and matter of praise.\f*
\v 3 which coverest the higher parts thereof with waters. Which makest the cloud for thee to ascend on: which walkest upon the wings of winds. \f + \fr 103:3 \ft Thou hast compassed the sphere of the fixed stars with a sphere of crystalline substance; which is as water congealed.\f* \f + \fr 103:3 \ft According to our capacity the Prophet describeth the speedy coming, or working of God, as if he came in a swift cloud, or with wings of the wind, to signify that he worketh what and when he pleaseth without delay. He said, and things were made: he commanded and they were created, Psal. 32.\f*
\v 4 Which makest spirits thine Angels: and thy ministers a burning fire. \f + \fr 103:4 \ft Thy messengers to execute thy will:\f* \f + \fr 103:4 \ft & the same Angels are as a burning fire in operation, yea they dispatch more easily, and more speedily than we can conceive.\f*
\v 5 Which hast founded the earth upon the stability thereof: it shall not be inclined for ever and ever. \f + \fr 103:5 \ft Most firmly established by natural weight, in the center of the world.\f*
\v 6 The depth, as a garment, is his clothing: upon the mountains shall waters stand. \f + \fr 103:6 \ft The water\f* \f + \fr 103:6 \ft should naturally cover all the earth.\f*
\v 7 At thy reprehension they shall fly: at the voice of thy thunder they shall fear. \f + \fr 103:7 \ft But by thy commandment the waters are contained in their limited places.\f*
\v 8 The mountains ascend: and the plain fields descend into the place, which thou hast founded for them. \f + \fr 103:8 \ft The waters being contained in their appointed channels, both hills and fields appear, which otherwise would be covered.\f*
\v 9 Thou hast set a bound, which they shall not pass over: neither shall they return to cover the earth. \f + \fr 103:9 \ft The waters.\f*
\v 10 Which sendest forth fountains in the valleys: between the midst of mountains shall waters pass.
\v 11 All the beasts of the field shall drink: the wild asses shall expect in their thirst. \f + \fr 103:11 \ft Hope for and receive.\f*
\v 12 Over them shall the fowls of the air inhabit: out of the midst of rocks they shall give forth voices.
\v 13 Watering the mountains from higher places: of the fruit of thy work shall the earth be filled.
\v 14 Bringing forth grass for beasts, and herb for the service of men. That thou mayst bring forth bread out of the earth: \f + \fr 103:14 \ft By these three principal kinds of food, bread, wine, and oil, all sorts of nutriment are understood.\f*
\v 15 & wine may make the heart of man joyful. That he may make the face cheerful with oil: and bread may confirm the heart of man. \f + \fr 103:15 \ft See previous note\f* \f + \fr 103:15 \ft See previous note\f*
\v 16 The trees of the field shall be filled, and the cedars of Libanus, which he hath planted:
\v 17 there sparrows shall make their nest. The house of the heron is the leader of them:
\v 18 the high mountains for harts: the rock a refuge for the Irchins.
\v 19 He made the moon for seasons: the sun knoweth his going down.
\v 20 Thou didst appoint darkness, and night was made: in it shall all the beasts of the wood pass.
\v 21 The whelps of lions roaring, to raven, and to seek of God meat for themselves.
\v 22 The sun is risen, & they are gathered together: and in their couches they shall be placed.
\v 23 Man shall go forth to his work: and to his working until evening.
\v 24 How magnified are thy works, o Lord! Thou hast made all things in wisdom: the earth is filled with thy possession. \f + \fr 103:24 \ft With thy creatures.\f*
\v 25 This great sea, and very large, there are creeping beasts, whereof there is no number. Little beasts with great: \f + \fr 103:25 \ft Fishes, serpents, worms, and all living creatures that lack feet.\f* \f + \fr 103:25 \ft No kind of living creatures multiplieth so much as fishes. Aristotel li. 9. Animal. c. 17.\f*
\v 26 there ships shall pass. This dragon, whom thou madest to delude: \f + \fr 103:26 \ft Amost huge fish called Leviathan. Job. 40. v. 20.\f* \f + \fr 103:26 \ft Albeit in the water he passeth man's strength, yet deprived of water he is not able to defend himself. v. 29.\f*
\v 27 all expect of thee that thou give them meat in season.
\v 28 Thou giving unto them, they shall gather it: thou opening thy hand, all shall be filled with bounty.
\v 29 But thou turning away the face, they shall be troubled: thou shalt take away their spirit, and they shall fail, and shall return into their dust.
\v 30 Thou shalt send forth thy spirit, and they shall be created: and thou shalt renew the face of the earth.
\v 31 Be the glory of our Lord for ever: our Lord will rejoice in his works.
\v 32 Who looketh upon the earth, & maketh it to tremble: who toucheth the mountains, and they smoke.
\v 33 I will chant to our Lord in my life: I will sing to my God as long as I am.
\v 34 Let my speech be acceptable to him: but I will take delight in our Lord.
\v 35 Let sinners fail from the earth, and the unjust, so that they be not: my soul bless thou our Lord. \f + \fr 103:35 \ft Aprediction that impenitent sinners shall be damned, wherein the Prophet conforming his will to God's, uttereth it in form of a prayer.\f*
\c 104
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Confess ye to our Lord, and invocate his name: shew forth his works among the Gentiles. \f + \fr 104:1 \ft Alleluia signifieth more than Laudate Dominum, Praise ye our Lord. For by these two Hebrew words, Alleluia, the Prophet inviteth all men to praise God, with gladness, and jubilation, with heart, voice, and gesture, with instruments, and howsoever we are able. And therefore S. Jerom, S. Augustin, and all Catholic writers keep the same words, and translate it not, neither in the titles of Psalms, nor ordinarily in any place or holy Scripture. This is the first Psalm thus titled, and is the same Psalm in sense, and in good part of the words, which the Royal Prophet made, and caused to be sung, when he brought the Ark of God from the house of Obededom into his own house. 1. Par. 16. v. 8.\f* \f + \fr 104:1 \ft How much grateful is it now to God, that we celebrate the greater mysteries of the new Testament.\f* \f + \fr 104:1 \ft For an exposition of this Psalm read the places quoted in the inner margin.\f*
\v 2 Chant to him, and sing to him: tell ye all his marvelous works.
\v 3 Praise ye him in his holy name: let the heart of them rejoice that seek our Lord.
\v 4 Seek ye our Lord, and be confirmed: seek his face always. \f + \fr 104:4 \ft His present help.\f*
\v 5 Remember ye his marvelous works, which he hath done: his wonders, and the judgments of his mouth.
\v 6 The seed of Abraham his servants: the children of Jacob his elect.
\v 7 He is the Lord our God: in all the earth are his judgments. \f + \fr 104:7 \ft Not only in Israel, but in all the world.\f*
\v 8 He hath been mindful for ever of his testament; of the word which he commanded unto a thousand generations. \f + \fr 104:8 \ft For ever, to the end of the world.\f*
\v 9 Which he disposed to Abraham: and of his oath to Isaac.
\v 10 And he appointed it to Jacob for a precept: and to Israel for an eternal testament,
\v 11 saying: To thee will I give the land of Chanaan, the cord of your inheritance.
\v 12 When they were of small number, very few and sojourners thereof: \f + \fr 104:12 \ft But 70. persons.\f*
\v 13 And they passed from nation into nation, & from Kingdom to another people.
\v 14 He left not a man to hurt them: and he rebuked kings for their sake:
\v 15 Touch not my anointed, and toward my Prophets be not malignant.
\v 16 And he called a famine upon the land: and he destroyed all the strength of bread. \f + \fr 104:16 \ft By his providence suffered.\f*
\v 17 He sent a man before them: Joseph was sold to be a servant.
\v 18 They humbled his feet in fetters, iron passed through his soul,
\v 19 until his word came. The word of our Lord inflamed him:
\v 20 the king sent, and loosed him; the Prince of the people, and released him.
\v 21 He appointed him lord of his house: and Prince of all his possession.
\v 22 That he might instruct his Princes as himself: and might teach his ancients wisdom.
\v 23 And Israel entered into Ægypt, and Jacob was a sojourner in the land of Cham. \f + \fr 104:23 \ft Ægypt, possessed by Mesraim Cham's second son. Gen. 10. v. 13.\f*
\v 24 And he increased his people exceedingly: and strengthened them over their enemies.
\v 25 He turned their heart that they hated his people: and to work guile toward his servants. \f + \fr 104:25 \ft May it be understood, or believed (saith S. Augustin) that God turneth the heart of man to commit sins? Or is it no sin, or is it a small sin, to hate the people of God? Or to work guile towards his servants? Who will say this? What then, is God author of these so grievous sins, who is not to be supposed the author of a most small sin? This learned Father therefore answereth, that God perverted not a right heart, but turned that was of it-self perverse, to the hatred of his people, where he might use that evil well, not by making them evil, but by bestowing upon his own people good things, which the evil might easily envy. Which hatred & to the glory of his own name, the things that follow do teach us; which are here remembered to his praise.\f*
\v 26 He sent Moyses his servant: Aaron himself whom he chose. \f + \fr 104:26 \ft In whom God established the Priesthood of Moyses' law.\f*
\v 27 He did put in them the words of his signs, and of his wonders in the Land of Cham.
\v 28 He sent darkness, and obscured: and did not exasperate his words. \f + \fr 104:28 \ft The ninth plague of the Ægyptians.\f* \f + \fr 104:28 \ft God willingly, not as one loath or unwilling, performed all that he threatened.\f*
\v 29 He turned their waters into blood: and killed their fishes. \f + \fr 104:29 \ft The first plague.\f*
\v 30 Their land brought forth frogs in the inner chambers of their kings. \f + \fr 104:30 \ft The second plague.\f* \f + \fr 104:30 \ft David knew this by revelation, or by tradition, for it is not in Exodus.\f*
\v 31 He said, and the cænomyia came: and the sciniphs in all their coasts. \f + \fr 104:31 \ft The fourth plague.\f* \f + \fr 104:31 \ft The third plague.\f* \f + \fr 104:31 \ft a swarm of flies.\f*
\v 32 He made their rains hail: fire burning in their land. \f + \fr 104:32 \ft The seventh plague.\f*
\v 33 And he struck their vines, and their fig-trees: and he destroyed the wood of their coasts.
\v 34 He said, & the locust came, & the bruchus whereof there was no number. \f + \fr 104:34 \ft The eighth plague.\f* \f + \fr 104:34 \ft Aworm that spoileth corn,\f*
\v 35 And it did eat all the grass in their land: and it did eat all the fruit of their land.
\v 36 And he struck every first begotten in their land: the first fruits of all their labour. \f + \fr 104:36 \ft The tenth plague. The fifth & sixth of pestilence and boyles are omitted.\f*
\v 37 And he brought them forth with gold and silver, and there was not in their tribes a feeble person.
\v 38 Ægypt was glad at their departure: because the fear of them lay upon them.
\v 39 He spread a cloud for their protection, and fire to shine unto them by night.
\v 40 They made petition, and the quail came: and he filled them with the bread of heaven.
\v 41 He divided the rock, and waters flowed: rivers ran in the dry ground.
\v 42 Because he was mindful of his holy word, which he had uttered to Abraham his servant.
\v 43 And he brought forth his people in exultation, and his elect in joy.
\v 44 And he gave them the countries of the Nations: and they possessed the labours of peoples:
\v 45 That they might keep his justifications, and seek after his law.
\c 105
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Confess ye to our Lord because he is good: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 105:1 \ft God is of himself and essentially good. All other goodness is participated of him.\f*
\v 2 Who shalt speak the powers of our Lord, shall make all his praises to be heard? \f + \fr 105:2 \ft No creature can fully express God's perfections.\f*
\v 3 Blessed are they, that keep judgment, & do justice at all time. \f + \fr 105:3 \ft It is a happy state in this life, either to keep God's law:\f* \f + \fr 105:3 \ft or to repent and do worthy penance for transgressing.\f*
\v 4 Remember us, o Lord in the good pleasure of thy people: visit us in thy salvation: \f + \fr 105:4 \ft According to thy wonted benevolence, promised to thy people. Exod. 16. v. 13. Exod. 17. v. 6. Gen. 12.\f*
\v 5 To see in the goodness of thine elect, to rejoice in the joy of thy nation: that thou mayst be praised with thine inheritance. \f + \fr 105:5 \ft That we may see and enjoy the benefits promised to thine elect.\f*
\v 6 We have sinned with our fathers: we have dealt unjustly, we have done iniquity. \f + \fr 105:6 \ft We have erred and hurt ourselves:\f* \f + \fr 105:6 \ft we have wronged our neighbours:\f* \f + \fr 105:6 \ft we have offended against God.\f*
\v 7 Our fathers in Ægypt did not understand thy marvelous works: they were not mindful of the multitude of thy mercy. And they provoked thee to wrath going up unto the sea, the Red sea.
\v 8 And he saved them for his name sake; that he might make his power known. \f + \fr 105:8 \ft Albeit the people by their murmuring deserved more punishment, yet God for the glory of his own name saved them from utter destruction.\f*
\v 9 And he rebuked the Red sea, and it was made dry: and he led them in the depths as in a desert.
\v 10 And he saved them from the hand of them that hated them: and he redeemed them out of the hand of the enemy.
\v 11 And water overwhelmed those that afflicted them: there did not one of them remain.
\v 12 And they believed his words: and they sang his praises.
\v 13 They had quickly done, they forgot his works: and they expected not his counsel. \f + \fr 105:13 \ft They persevered not long in their duty towards God, seeing his omnipotent power by his marvelous works:\f* \f + \fr 105:13 \ft nor were content with his providence, but carnally coveted things not necessary.\f*
\v 14 And they coveted concupiscence in the desert: and tempted God in the place without water.
\v 15 He gave them their petition: and sent saturity into their souls. \f + \fr 105:15 \ft According to their carnal desires.\f*
\v 16 And they provoked Moyses in the camp: Aaron the holy of our Lord. \f + \fr 105:16 \ft Holy by his function.\f*
\v 17 The earth was opened, and swallowed Dathan, and overwhelmed the congregation of Abiron.
\v 18 And a fire flamed up in their synagogue: the flame burnt the sinners.
\v 19 And they made a calf in Horeb: and they adored the sculptile. \f + \fr 105:19 \ft They adored the image that represented a calf, not God.\f*
\v 20 And they changed their glory into the similitude of a calf that eateth grass. \f + \fr 105:20 \ft God being their true glory, they changed him for a false god of the Ægyptians (who especially honoured a calf called Apis) making an image thereof, and attributed their delivery from Ægypt to this imagined god. Exo. 32. v. 4. 8. Of which and the like foolish and abominable idolatry S. Paul writeth, Rom. 1. v. 23. They changed the glory of the incorruptible God into a similitude of the image of a corruptible man, and of fowls, and of four footed beasts, and of them that creep. Where we see what manner of images holy Scriptures condemn, and not the images of Christ and his Saints.\f*
\v 21 They forgat God, which saved them, which did great things in Ægypt,
\v 22 marvelous things in the land of Cham, terrible things in the Red sea.
\v 23 And he said to destroy them: if Moyses his elect had not stood in the way before him . To turn away his wrath that he should not destroy them: \f + \fr 105:23 \ft He said, he would destroy them, but for Moyses' prayer spared them.\f*
\v 24 and they esteemed for naught the land that was to be desired. They did not believe his word.
\v 25 and they murmured in their tabernacles: they heard not the voice of our Lord.
\v 26 And he lifted up his hand over them: to overthrow them in the desert:
\v 27 And to cast down their seed among the Nations: & to disperse them in the countries.
\v 28 And they were professed to Beelphegor: and they did eat the sacrifices of the dead. \f + \fr 105:28 \ft The Idol of Moabites, and Madianites.\f* \f + \fr 105:28 \ft As God is indeed the living God, that liveth of himself, and giveth life to others: so false gods are called dead gods, that cannot give life to any, but do kill all that serve them; at least spiritually, and often corporally.\f*
\v 29 And they provoked him in their inventions: & ruin was multiplied on them.
\v 30 And Phinees stood, and pacified: and the slaughter ceased. \f + \fr 105:30 \ft Phinees moved by the zeal of God (as the holy text witnesseth, Num. 25. v. 11. )\f*
\v 31 And it was reputed to him unto justice, in generation and generation even for ever.
\v 32 And they provoked him at the waters of contradiction: and Moyses was vexed for them: \f + \fr 105:32 \ft Moyses afflicted in spirit, by the enormous murmuring of the people, doubted whether God would give them water out of the rock or no: not doubting of his power, but of his will: and so when he should have spoken to the rock, Num. 20. v. 8. he spoke to the incredulous people. v. 10. and therein offended God: for which he was temporally punished. v. 12. Deut. 1. v. 37. &c. c. 3. v. 26. c. 4. v. 21.\f*
\v 33 because they exasperated his spirit. And he plainly affirmed in his lips:
\v 34 they destroyed not the nations, of which our Lord spake to them.
\v 35 And they were mingled among the nations, and learned their works:
\v 36 and they served their sculptiles: and it became a scandal to them.
\v 37 And they immolated their sons, and their daughters to devils.
\v 38 And they shed innocent blood: the blood of their sons and of their daughters, which they sacrificed to the sculptiles of Chanaan. And the land was infected with blood, \f + \fr 105:38 \ft Some Jews offered these most cruel, unnatural, and abominable sacrifices; perhaps in the times of Judges, when they were mingled with idolatrous people, and served their gods. Iud. 2. v. 12. c. 3. v. 6. But it is more express after David's time, whereof he here prophesieth, and was verified by Achaz. 4. Reg. 16. v. 3. and by Manasses. 4. Reg. 21. v. 6. Which with other idolatry King Iosias destroyed. 4. Reg. 23. v. 1.\f*
\v 39 & was contaminated in their works: and they did fornicate in their inventions.
\v 40 And our Lord was wrath with fury upon his people: and he abhorred his inheritance.
\v 41 And he delivered them into the hands of the nations: and they that hated them had the dominion of them.
\v 42 And their enemies afflicted them, and they were humbled under their hands:
\v 43 he did often deliver them. But they exasperated him in their counsel: and they were humbled in their iniquities.
\v 44 And he saw when they were afflicted: and he heard their prayer. \f + \fr 105:44 \ft God respected them with his merciful eye, and gave them grace to repent.\f*
\v 45 And he was mindful of his testament: and it repented him according to the multitude of his mercy.
\v 46 And he gave them into mercies in the sight of all, that had taken them. \f + \fr 105:46 \ft Here the Psalmist concludeth both the history and prophecy of this Psalm, with prayer and praise, as followeth.\f*
\v 47 Save us, o Lord our God: and gather us out of the Nations. That we may confess to thy holy name: & may glory in thy praise. \f + \fr 105:47 \ft Avery fit prayer in time of schism.\f*
\v 48 Blessed be our Lord the God of Israel from everlasting unto everlasting: and all the people shall say: Be it, be it.
\c 106
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Confess ye to our Lord, because he is good: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 106:1 \ft Praise God by confessing his mercy, providence, and goodness.\f*
\v 2 Let them say that are redeemed of our Lord, whom he redeemed out of the hand of the enemy: and out of the countries he gathered them: \f + \fr 106:2 \ft God of his mercy promised the Redeemer of mankind straight after Adam's fall:\f*
\v 3 From the rising of the sun, and the going down: from the north, and the sea. \f + \fr 106:3 \ft which redemption was intended for all, & faileth not of God's part in any, but of men's own willful refusing to be duly penitent, and to keep God's precepts.\f*
\v 4 They wandered in the wilderness, in a place without water: the way of city for habitation they found not. \f + \fr 106:4 \ft Literally of such as wander in this world, having no settled place to dwell in: spiritually of all mankind after his fall.\f*
\v 5 Hungry and thirsty: their soul fainted in them.
\v 6 And they cried to our Lord when they were in tribulation: and he delivered them out of their necessities. \f + \fr 106:6 \ft Whensoever they call upon God, he helpeth them, as is best for their spiritual health.\f*
\v 7 And he conducted them into the right way: to go into a city of habitation.
\v 8 Let the mercies of our Lord confess to him: and his marvelous works to the children of men. \f + \fr 106:8 \ft All God's benefits, which are of his mercy, not of man's desert, are just matter of praising God.\f*
\v 9 Because he hath filled the empty soul: and the hungry soul he hath filled with good things.
\v 10 Them that sat in darkness, and in the shadow of death: bound in neediness, and iron.
\v 11 Because they exasperated the words of God: and they provoked the counsel of the Highest. \f + \fr 106:11 \ft Calamities in this world are commonly inflicted for sins.\f*
\v 12 And their heart was humbled in labours: they were weakened, neither was there any to help.
\v 13 And they cried to our Lord when they were in tribulation: and he delivered them out of their necessities.
\v 14 And he brought them out of darkness, and the shadow of death: and brake their bonds asunder.
\v 15 Let the mercies of our Lord confess to him: & his marvelous works to the children of men.
\v 16 Because he hath destroyed the gates of brass; and the bars of iron he hath broken.
\v 17 He hath received them out of the way of their iniquity: for they were humbled for their injustices.
\v 18 Their soul did abhor all meat: & they approached even to the gates of death.
\v 19 And they cried to our Lord when they were in tribulation: and he delivered them out of their necessities.
\v 20 He sent his word, and healed them: and delivered them out of their destructions.
\v 21 Let the mercies of our Lord confess to him: & his marvelous works to the children of men.
\v 22 And let them sacrifice the sacrifice of praise: & shew forth his works in exultation.
\v 23 They that go down into the sea in ships, making traffic in the great waters.
\v 24 They have seen the works of our Lord, and his marvelous things in the depth.
\v 25 He said, and the blast of the storm stood: and the waves thereof were exalted.
\v 26 They ascend even to the heavens, and they descend even to the depths: their soul pined away in evils.
\v 27 They were troubled, and were moved as a drunken man: and all their wisdom was devoured.
\v 28 And they cried to our Lord when they were in tribulation, and he brought them out of their necessities. \f + \fr 106:28 \ft As before in the 6. 13. and 19. verses.\f*
\v 29 And he turned his storm into calm: & the waves thereof were quiet.
\v 30 And they rejoiced because they were quiet: and he conducted them into the haven of their will.
\v 31 Let the mercies of our Lord confess to him: and his marvelous works to the children of men. \f + \fr 106:31 \ft This verse also is four times in this Psalm. v. 8. 15. 21. and 31. to admonish us, that as there is one means to escape from all dangers by crying to God, as v. 6. 13. 19. and 28. with mourning and penance: so there is one cause of praise and thanks for our delivery, which is God's mercy and grace.\f*
\v 32 And let them exalt him in the Church of the people: and the chair of the ancients let them praise him.
\v 33 He turned the rivers into a desert: and the issues of waters into dryness. \f + \fr 106:33 \ft God to shew sometimes his power, also to benefit some, and to punish others, changeth the accustomed course of things, and states of men, at his divine pleasure, as here the Royal Prophet reciteth some examples. And some others are recorded in diverse times and places.\f* \f + \fr 106:33 \ft No doubt much change was made in the earth by Noe's flood. And many think that the land of Chanaan was made more fruitful in the time of the Jews' inhabiting, and now is more barren again.\f*
\v 34 The fruitful land into a salt ground, for the malice of them that inhabit it. \f + \fr 106:34 \ft He alludeth to the country about Sodome and Gomorre, which was most fruitful, and most pleasant, Gen. 13. v. 10. but shortly after was burnt with fire and brimstone, Gen. 19. v. 14. subverted, and turned into a dead and salt sea.\f*
\v 35 He turned the desert into pools of waters: and the land without water into issues of waters.
\v 36 And he placed the hungry there, and they built a city of habitation.
\v 37 And they sowed fields and planted vineyards: and they made fruit of nativity. \f + \fr 106:37 \ft Made aboundance of fruit to grow.\f*
\v 38 And he blessed them, and they were multiplied exceedingly: and their beasts he lessened not.
\v 39 And they were made few: and were vexed by the tribulation of evils, and with sorrow. \f + \fr 106:39 \ft Again some countries punished for sins.\f*
\v 40 Contempt was poured out upon Princes: and he made them wander where was no way, and not in the way.
\v 41 And he did help the poor out of poverty: and made families as sheep. \f + \fr 106:41 \ft Another change in relieving the poor being humbled.\f*
\v 42 The just shall see, and shall rejoice: & all iniquity shall stop her mouth.
\v 43 Who is wise and will keep these things? And will understand the mercies of our Lord?
\c 107
\p
\v 1 Acanticle of Psalm, to David himself. \f + \fr 107:1 \ft This Psalm was sung with instruments beginning the music, and voices following.\f*
\v 2 My heart is ready, o God, my heart is ready : I will chant and will sing in my glory. \f + \fr 107:2 \ft The former part of this Psalm to the 7. verse, is the same in sense, and almost in words, with the later part of the 56. from the 8. verse.\f*
\v 3 Arise my glory, arise psalter and harp: I will arise early.
\v 4 I will confess to thee in peoples, o Lord: and I will sing to thee in the Nations. \f + \fr 107:4 \ft King David subdued not only some parts of Chanaan, not subject to the Jews before (2. Reg. 5. 1. Par. 11.) but also brought the Philistiims, Moabites, Ammonites, Idumeans, Amalechites, the Kings of Soba, Syria, & Emath, to pay tribute. 2. Reg. 8. 1. Par. 18.\f* \f + \fr 107:4 \ft Yet all these victories & conquests were but a figure of Christ's power and dominion in all nations. And therefore the rest of this Psalm, by S. Augustin & other fathers' judgement, was rather prophetically uttered by David, in the person of Christ, & more perfectly performed by Christ in his Church, than historically averred of David himself.\f*
\v 5 Because thy mercy is great above the heavens: & thy truth even to the clouds.
\v 6 Be exalted above the heavens o God, and thy glory over all the earth:
\v 7 that thy beloved may be delivered. Save with thy right hand, and hear me: \f + \fr 107:7 \ft The rest of this Psalm is the same with the later part of the 59. from the 7. verse.\f*
\v 8 God spake in his holy: I will rejoice, and will divide Sichem, and I will measure the vale of tabernacles.
\v 9 Galaad is mine, and Manasses is mine: and Ephraim the protection of my head. Juda is my king:
\v 10 Moab the pot of my hope. Upon Idumea I will extend my shoe: the strangers are made my friends.
\v 11 Who will conduct me into a fenced city? Who will conduct me into Idumea?
\v 12 Wilt not thou, o God, which hast repelled us, and wilt not thou go forth, o God, in our hosts?
\v 13 Give us help out of tribulation: because man's salvation is vain.
\v 14 In God we shall do strength: and he will bring our enemies to nothing.
\c 108
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm of David.
\v 2 O God conceal not my praise: because the mouth of the sinner, and the mouth of the deceitful man is open upon me. \f + \fr 108:2 \ft The words of Christ.\f* \f + \fr 108:2 \ft The Pharisees and Herodians (Mat. 22.) with their mouth acknowledged Christ a true speaker, & a teacher of the way of God in truth, thereby to draw him into danger, and to shed his blood.\f*
\v 3 They have spoken against me with deceitful tongue, and with words of hatred they have compassed me: and they have impugned me without cause. \f + \fr 108:3 \ft At other times they accused him of great crimes, lastly of treason against Cæsar.\f*
\v 4 For that they should love me, they backbited me: but I prayed.
\v 5 And they set against me evil things for good: and hatred for my love.
\v 6 Appoint a sinner over him: and let the devil stand on his right hand. \f + \fr 108:6 \ft Aprediction that Judas would not make recourse to any good counseller, but complain of his miserable tormented conscience to the wicked, who gave him no comfort at all,\f* \f + \fr 108:6 \ft and so despairing, the devil persuaded him to hang himself.\f*
\v 7 When he is judged, let him come forth condemned: and let his prayer be turned into sin.
\v 8 Let his days be made few: and let another take his bishoprick. \f + \fr 108:8 \ft The office of Apostleship.\f*
\v 9 Let his children be made orphans: and his wife a widow. \f + \fr 108:9 \ft The posterity or successors of wicked persecuters prosper not long in this world.\f*
\v 10 Let his children be transported wandering, and let them beg: and let them be cast out of their habitations.
\v 11 Let the usurer search all his substance: and let strangers spoil his labours.
\v 12 Let there be none to help him: neither let there be any to have pity on his pupils.
\v 13 Let his children come to destruction: in one generation let his name be clean put out. \f + \fr 108:13 \ft Arch-heretics that devise new opinions, are shortly forsaken, their followers still coining new heresies of their own, differing from their false master.\f*
\v 14 Let the iniquity of his fathers return to memory in the sight of our Lord: and let not the sin of his mother be blotted out.
\v 15 Let them be before our Lord always, and let the memory of them perish out of the earth:
\v 16 For that he remembered not to do mercy.
\v 17 And he persecuted the poor, and needy man, and the compunct in heart to kill him.
\v 18 And he loved cursing, and it shall come to him: and he would not blessing, and it shall be far from him. And he put on cursing as a garment, and it entered as water into his inner parts, and as oil in his bones. \f + \fr 108:18 \ft Let them observe this, that use more swearing and blaspheming, than praying or meditating.\f*
\v 19 Be it to him as a garment, wherewith he is covered: and as a girdle, wherewith he is always girded.
\v 20 This is the work of them that detract from me before our Lord: and that speak evils against my soul.
\v 21 And thou Lord, Lord, do with me for thy name's sake: because thy mercy is sweet. Deliver me
\v 22 because I am needy and poor: and my heart is troubled within me. \f + \fr 108:22 \ft Christ's soul was pensive when he prayed in the garden, and he did works of penance for our sins all his life.\f*
\v 23 As a shadow when it declineth, am I taken away: and I am shaken as locusts.
\v 24 My knees are weakened with fasting: and my flesh is changed by reason of oil.
\v 25 And I am made a reproach to them: they saw me, and wagged their heads.
\v 26 Help me, o Lord my God: save me according to thy mercy. \f + \fr 108:26 \ft He prayed also for his resurrection, and glorification.\f*
\v 27 And let them know that this is thy hand: & thou, o Lord, hast done it.
\v 28 They will curse, and thou shalt bless: let them that rise up against me be confounded: but thy servant shall rejoice.
\v 29 Let them that detract from me, be clothed with shame: and let them be covered with their confusion, as with a double patched cloak. \f + \fr 108:29 \ft With all possible confusion.\f*
\v 30 I will confess to our Lord exceedingly with my mouth: and in the midst of many I will praise him.
\v 31 Because he hath stood on the right hand of the poor, that he might save my soul from the persecutors.
\c 109
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of David. Our Lord said to my Lord: Sit on my right hand: till I make thine enemies, the foot-stool of thy feet. \f + \fr 109:1 \ft God the Father.\f* \f + \fr 109:1 \ft To God the Son, the Lord of David, and of all mankind, yet the son of David, according to his humanity.\f* \f + \fr 109:1 \ft He limiteth not the time, but excludeth all time, wherein the enemy might imagine, that Christ's kingdom should cease: signifying that Christ shall reign, till all his enemies be subdued, much more afterwards in all eternity.\f*
\v 2 Our Lord will send forth the rod of thy strength from Sion: rule thou in the midst of thine enemies. \f + \fr 109:2 \ft The Church of Christ beginning in Jerusalem on Whitsunday, the fiftieth day from his Resurrection, continueth evermore.\f*
\v 3 With thee the beginning in the day of thy strength: in the brightness of holy things: from the womb before the day star I begat thee. \f + \fr 109:3 \ft Thou shall have principality,\f* \f + \fr 109:3 \ft in the day of thy powerful conquest, and rising from death.\f* \f + \fr 109:3 \ft In excellency of holy spiritual mysteries and graces:\f* \f + \fr 109:3 \ft because I God the Father, of my substance begat thee God the Son in eternity. The same which Micheas saith (c. 5. v. 2.) His coming forth from the beginning, from the days of eternity.\f*
\v 4 Our Lord sware, and it shall not repent him: Thou art a Priest for ever according to the order of Melchisedech. \f + \fr 109:4 \ft God most firmly, and unchangeably affirmed: that thou (Christ our Messias) art not only a King, but also a Priest:\f* \f + \fr 109:4 \ft not for a time, as Aaron was, but for ever,\f* \f + \fr 109:4 \ft neither of Aaron's order, but according to the order of Melchisedech.\f*
\v 5 Our Lord on thy right hand hath broken kings in the day of his wrath. \f + \fr 109:5 \ft Kings that sometimes persecute Christians, are subdued with other people to Christ.\f*
\v 6 He shall judge in nations, he shall fill ruins, he shall crush the heads in the land of many. \f + \fr 109:6 \ft He shall judge and punish the incredulous people,\f* \f + \fr 109:6 \ft make great slaughters amongst those that resist:\f* \f + \fr 109:6 \ft and bring Princes with their populous kingdoms to nothing.\f*
\v 7 Of the torrent in the way he shall drink: therefore shall he exalt the head. \f + \fr 109:7 \ft He shall in the mean time (and also his best servants) suffer much tribulation in this life\f* \f + \fr 109:7 \ft and for the same be highly exalted in life everlasting.\f*
\c 110
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. I will confess to thee, o Lord, with all my heart: in the counsel of the just, and the congregation. \f + \fr 110:1 \ft Iwill praise God both in secret for discharge of mine own conscience;\f* \f + \fr 110:1 \ft and in public for edification of others.\f* \f + \fr 110:1 \ft This Psalm in the Hebrew is composed with every verse and middle of verse, beginning with a distinct letter, in order of the Alphabet.\f*
\v 2 The works of our Lord are great: exquisite according to all his wills. \f + \fr 110:2 \ft God's will is the whole cause of all his works.\f*
\v 3 Confession and magnificence his work: and his justice continueth for ever and ever. \f + \fr 110:3 \ft Every work of his is praise-worthy and magnifical.\f*
\v 4 He hath made a memory of his marvelous works; a merciful & pitiful Lord: \f + \fr 110:4 \ft God hath left one most special and beneficial memory of all other benefits, his own body and blood, in memory of his Passion, and our redemption,\f*
\v 5 he hath given meat to them that fear him. He will be mindful for ever of his testament: \f + \fr 110:5 \ft the spiritual food and sustenance of all the souls that rightly fear him.\f* \f + \fr 110:5 \ft Of his promise to conserve his Church perpetually.\f*
\v 6 the force of his works he will shew forth to his people: \f + \fr 110:6 \ft The powerable operation of his death, and of all his mysteries.\f*
\v 7 To give them the inheritance of the gentiles: the works of his hands truth and judgment.
\v 8 All his commandments are faithful: confirmed for ever and ever, made in truth and equity. \f + \fr 110:8 \ft God's commandments do justify all that keep them.\f*
\v 9 He sent redemption to his people: he commanded his testament for ever. Holy and terrible is his name: \f + \fr 110:9 \ft He also of his mercy redeemed man, that he might be able to keep his precepts.\f*
\v 10 the fear of our Lord is the beginning of wisdom. Understanding is good to all that do it: his praise remaineth for ever and ever. \f + \fr 110:10 \ft Beginning with fear of God, bringeth at last by other degrees to true wisdom, which two are the first and last of the seven gifts of the Holy Ghost.\f*
\c 111
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Of the return of Aggeus and Zachary. Blessed is the man that feareth our Lord: he shall have great delight in his commandments. \f + \fr 111:1 \ft The Septuagint Interpreters added this mention of Aggeus and Zacharie, returning from captivity, to signify that this Psalm was very proper, & meet to be commended to the people at that time, whereby they might learn, that their sins were the cause of their captivity, and of all their miseries: and if they desired temporal or spiritual prosperity, they must observe the means here prescribed to obtain the same.\f* \f + \fr 111:1 \ft He that sincerely feareth God, will take great delight in keeping his commandments.\f* \f + \fr 111:1 \ft This Psalm is also composed by the Alphabet, as the next before.\f*
\v 2 His seed shall be mighty in the earth: the generation of the righteous shall be blessed. \f + \fr 111:2 \ft So doing he and his shall prosper.\f*
\v 3 Glory and riches in his house: and his justice abideth for ever and ever. \f + \fr 111:3 \ft The just shall not only prosper in this world but also in the next.\f*
\v 4 Light is risen up in darkness to the righteous: he is merciful, and pitiful, and just. \f + \fr 111:4 \ft God will also comfort the just in tribulations.\f*
\v 5 Acceptable is the man, that is merciful and lendeth, that shall dispose his words in judgment: \f + \fr 111:5 \ft That shall give discreet and wholesome counsel to the afflicted.\f*
\v 6 Because he shall not be moved for ever.
\v 7 The just shall be in eternal memory: he shall not fear at the hearing of evil. His heart is ready to hope in our Lord,
\v 8 his heart is confirmed: he shall not be moved till he look over his enemies.
\v 9 He distributed, he gave to the poor: his justice remaineth for ever and ever, his horn shall be exalted in glory. \f + \fr 111:9 \ft Works of mercy are also called justice, because they concur to man's justification,\f* \f + \fr 111:9 \ft and to his salvation.\f*
\v 10 The sinner shall see, and will be angry, he shall gnash his teeth and pine away: the desire of sinners shall perish.
\c 112
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Praise our Lord ye children: praise ye the name of our Lord. \f + \fr 112:1 \ft All God's servants.\f*
\v 2 Be the name of our Lord blessed, from henceforth now and for ever,
\v 3 From the rising of the sun unto the going down, the name of our Lord is laudable.
\v 4 Our Lord is high above all nations, and his glory above the heavens.
\v 5 Who is as the Lord our God, that dwelleth on high,
\v 6 and beholdeth the low things in heaven and in earth? \f + \fr 112:6 \ft In respect of God all creatures are low, though they be in heaven.\f*
\v 7 Raising up the needy from the earth, and lifting up the poor out of the dung:
\v 8 To place him with Princes, with the Princes of his people. \f + \fr 112:8 \ft See the example of Ioseph so advanced.\f*
\v 9 Who maketh the barren woman to dwell in a house, a joyful mother of children. \f + \fr 112:9 \ft of Sara, Rebecca, Rachæl, and other women made fruitful.\f*
\c 113
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. In the coming forth of Israel out of Ægypt: of the house of Jacob from the barbarous people. \f + \fr 113:1 \ft People of false religion counted barbarous, especially such as also persecute the true Religion; for otherwise the Ægyptians were both civil in manners, and learned in many sciences.\f*
\v 2 Jewry was made his sanctification, Israel his dominion. \f + \fr 113:2 \ft The people of Jews were more notoriously renowned in the world from the time of their delivery out of Ægypt, for the peculiar people, whom God sanctified, & in whom, as in his elected inheritance or dominion, he dwelled and reigned.\f*
\v 3 The sea saw, and fled: Jordan was turned backward. \f + \fr 113:3 \ft The Psalmist writing in verse doth often describe things in poetical manner,\f* \f + \fr 113:3 \ft when the Israelites went forth of Ægypt,\f* \f + \fr 113:3 \ft when they entered into Chanaan, but more truly than profane poets: for that in very deed all creatures, otherwise senseless, as the sea, do in a sort feel the power of their Creator, & obey his will.\f*
\v 4 The mountains leaped as rams: and the little hills as the lambs of sheep. \f + \fr 113:4 \ft Either there was an earthquake, or some other moving of hills, not mentioned by Moyses, or else the Psalmist speaketh of the rocks of the torrents, which bowed, that the Israelites might rest in Ar, and lie in the borders of the Moabites, Num. 21. v. 15.\f*
\v 5 What aileth thee o sea that thou didst fly: and thou o Jordan, that thou was turned backward? \f + \fr 113:5 \ft By the figure Apostrophe he speaketh to the sea, river, and hills: using also Prosopopoeia, as if senseless things understood, and should answer.\f*
\v 6 Ye mountains leaped as rams, and ye little hills as the lambs of sheep.
\v 7 At the face of our Lord was the earth moved, at the face of the God of Jacob.
\v 8 Who turned the rock into pools of waters, and stony hill into fountains of waters. \f + \fr 113:8 \ft Another miraculous benefit, that rock yielded them water in their necessity.\f*
\v 9 \sc Not to us O Lord, Not\sc* TO US: but to thy name give the glory. \f + \fr 113:9 \ft Here some Hebrew Rabbins begin another Psalm, but by the coherence of the matter Saint Augustine proveth that it is but one Psalm, where is shewed that the true invisible God is known by such works as are here recited: and contrarywise, that the gentiles' idols are not Gods, because they are made of silver, gold, or other matter, by men's hands; having resemblance of living things are altogether senseless.\f*
\v 10 For thy mercy, and thy truth: lest at any time the Gentiles say: Where is their God? \f + \fr 113:10 \ft Thou didst all this, o God, of mere mercy towards thy people:\f* \f + \fr 113:10 \ft for thy truth's sake, seeing thou didst promise to protect them:\f* \f + \fr 113:10 \ft that the Gentiles should not take occasion to blaspheme.\f*
\v 11 But our God is in heaven: he hath done all things what soever he would.
\v 12 The idols of the gentiles are silver, and gold, the works of men's hands.
\v 13 They have mouth, and shall not speak: they have eyes, an shall not see.
\v 14 They have ears, and shall not hear: they have nostrils and shall not smell.
\v 15 They have hands, and shall not handle: they have feet, and shall not walk: they shall not cry in their throat.
\v 16 Let them that make them become like to them: and all that have confidence in them. \f + \fr 113:16 \ft This is a just prayer of the zealous, conforming their desires to God's will. But if God give idolaters grace to amend, then all the just will also rejoice in their conversion.\f*
\v 17 The house of Israel hath hoped in our Lord: he is their helper and their protector. \f + \fr 113:17 \ft Though many Jews fell to idolatry, yet there always remained so many in God's true service, that it might still be truly said: The house of Israel hath hoped in our Lord, as is here averred.\f*
\v 18 The house of Aaron hath hoped in our Lord: he is their helper and their protector.
\v 19 They that fear our Lord have hoped in our Lord; he is their helper and their protector.
\v 20 Our Lord hath been mindful of us: and hath blessed us. He hath blessed the house of Israel: he hath blessed the house of Aaron.
\v 21 He hath blessed all that fear our Lord, the little with the great.
\v 22 Our Lord add upon you: upon you, & upon your children.
\v 23 Blessed be you of our Lord, which made heaven and earth.
\v 24 The heaven of heaven is to our Lord: but the earth he hath given to the children of men. \f + \fr 113:24 \ft This in effect all worldly politics say in their hearts: as\f* \f + \fr 113:24 \ft and contenting themselves with earthly possessions.\f*
\v 25 The dead shall not praise thee, o Lord: nor all they that go down into hell: \f + \fr 113:25 \ft But when such profane men are dead, they make no shew at all of praising God:\f* \f + \fr 113:25 \ft for parting from the earth, they descend into hell, and there eternally blaspheme God.\f*
\v 26 but we that live do bless our Lord, from this time, and for ever. \f + \fr 113:26 \ft Contrarywise the just, aspiring to heaven, which is the proper Kingdom of God, & using this world as they ought to do, for a means to ascend into heaven, shall bless and praise God for evermore.\f*
\c 114
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. I have loved, because our Lord will hear the voice of my prayer. \f + \fr 114:1 \ft Iam induced to love God,\f* \f + \fr 114:1 \ft because he always heareth my prayers.\f*
\v 2 Because he hath inclined his ear to me: and in my days I will invocate. \f + \fr 114:2 \ft So long as I shall live.\f*
\v 3 The sorrows of death have compassed me: and the perils of hell have found me. I have found tribulation and sorrow: \f + \fr 114:3 \ft When I erred like a stray sheep from thee, the pains of death,\f* \f + \fr 114:3 \ft and the danger of hell-torments, both due for sin, environed me, and I was not ware thereof.\f* \f + \fr 114:3 \ft But by tribulation falling upon me, I came to know my dangerous estate:\f*
\v 4 and I invocated the name of our Lord. O Lord deliver my soul: \f + \fr 114:4 \ft turned to thee, and prayed as followeth.\f*
\v 5 our Lord is merciful, and just, and our God doth mercy.
\v 6 Our Lord keepeth little ones: I was humbled, and he hath delivered me. \f + \fr 114:6 \ft Afflicted with tribulations.\f*
\v 7 Turn o my soul into thy rest: because our Lord hath done good to thee.
\v 8 Because he hath delivered my soul from death: mine eyes from tears, my feet from sliding.
\v 9 I will please our Lord in the country of the living. \f + \fr 114:9 \ft Iwill endeavour to please God, in the congregation of those that live here in grace, and in heaven in glory.\f*
\c 115
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. I believed, for which cause I spake: but I was humbled exceedingly. \f + \fr 115:1 \ft Ibelieved that God would help me:\f* \f + \fr 115:1 \ft therefore I freely professed that I trusted in him. For then indeed faith is perfect, when we confess with mouth, that which we believe in heart.\f* \f + \fr 115:1 \ft Iwas vehemently afflicted in tribulations.\f* \f + \fr 115:1 \ft This in the Hebrew is joined to the next Psalm before.\f*
\v 2 Isaid in mine excess: Every man is a liar. \f + \fr 115:2 \ft In the midst of my great affliction I professed, that all man's help is vain, false, deceitful, and defective, and therefore our trust must be in God only.\f*
\v 3 What shall I render to our Lord, for all things that he hath rendered to me? \f + \fr 115:3 \ft See previous note\f*
\v 4 I will take the chalice of salvation: and I will invocate the name of our Lord. \f + \fr 115:4 \ft Seeing I am not able to render any thing worthy of God's favour to me, yet I will do that I can: I will gratefully accept his great benefit, the cup of Christ's passion, which\f* \f + \fr 115:4 \ft and will praise, and call upon his name.\f*
\v 5 I will render my vows to our Lord before all his people: \f + \fr 115:5 \ft Iwill pay voluntary vows,\f* \f + \fr 115:5 \ft for God's glory, and edification of others:\f*
\v 6 precious in the sight of our Lord is the death of his Saints. \f + \fr 115:6 \ft yea I will offer my life, and suffer death, when God's glory shall require it, in whose sight the death of Saints is precious, and most highly esteemed.\f*
\v 7 O Lord because I am thy servant: I am thy servant, and the son of thy handmaid. Thou hast broken my bonds: \f + \fr 115:7 \ft Always understood, that such as suffer persecution, be in good state of their souls, the true servants of God,\f* \f + \fr 115:7 \ft the children of the Church his handmaid.\f* \f + \fr 115:7 \ft Delivered me from captivity of sin.\f*
\v 8 I will sacrifice to thee the host of praise, and I will invocate the name of our Lord.
\v 9 I will render my vows to our Lord in the sight of all his people:
\v 10 in the courts of the house of our Lord, in the midst of thee, o Jerusalem. \f + \fr 115:10 \ft In the Church of the faithful.\f*
\c 116
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Praise our Lord all ye Gentiles: praise him all ye peoples. \f + \fr 116:1 \ft Not only some, but all nations of the Gentiles:\f* \f + \fr 116:1 \ft and all Jews (Christ's Redemption being aboundantly sufficient for all) are invited to praise God.\f*
\v 2 Because his mercy is confirmed, upon us: and his truth remaineth for ever. \f + \fr 116:2 \ft Because he hath multiplied his mercy to us Gentiles, to whom he made no promise:\f* \f + \fr 116:2 \ft and most truly performed his promise made to the Jews.\f*
\c 117
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Confess ye to our Lord because he is good: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 117:1 \ft Let us praise God, for his goodness, in making us of nothing, giving us many benefits,\f* \f + \fr 117:1 \ft and remitting our sins.\f*
\v 2 Let Israel now say that he is good: that his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 117:2 \ft Let the Church of the new testament especially confess his goodness, which hath received more mercy and grace.\f*
\v 3 Let the house of Aaron now say: that his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 117:3 \ft Let all the Clergy praise God now in the time of more grace, and of greater spiritual functions.\f*
\v 4 Let them now say which fear our Lord: that his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 117:4 \ft Yea let the whole body of the Church, all that fear and serve God, praise his mercy.\f*
\v 5 From tribulation I invocated our Lord: and our Lord heard me in largeness. \f + \fr 117:5 \ft As well spiritual as temporal.\f*
\v 6 Our Lord is my helper: I will not fear what man can do to me.
\v 7 Our Lord is my helper: and I will look over mine enemies.
\v 8 It is good to hope in our Lord, rather than to hope in man.
\v 9 It is good to hope in our Lord, rather than to hope in Princes.
\v 10 All nations have compassed me: and in the name of our Lord am I revenged on them. \f + \fr 117:10 \ft Though innumerable oppose, and endeavour to hurt me (saith the Church, or any just person)\f* \f + \fr 117:10 \ft yet by God's power, not by mine own, I am defended, and they punished, and so the just hath the victory, and triumpheth.\f*
\v 11 Compassing they have compassed me: and in the name of our Lord I was revenged on them.
\v 12 They compassed me as bees, and were inflamed as fire in thorns: and in the name of our Lord I was revenged on them. \f + \fr 117:12 \ft In great troops, and fury,\f* \f + \fr 117:12 \ft with sharp though short force, and with special noise, to terrify me, but in God I overcame all.\f*
\v 13 Being thrust I was overturned to fall: and our Lord received me. \f + \fr 117:13 \ft Iwas sometimes by vehemency of tentation declining to sin:\f* \f + \fr 117:13 \ft but God's grace assisted and strengthened me.\f*
\v 14 Our Lord is my strength, and my praise: and he is made my salvation.
\v 15 The voice of exultation, and of salvation in the tabernacles of the just.
\v 16 The right hand of our Lord hath wrought strength: the right hand of our Lord hath exalted me, the right hand of our Lord hath wrought strength. \f + \fr 117:16 \ft The same word (right hand) thrice mentioned, signifieth the B. Trinity. Also (Our Lord) signifying Christ in his humanity, the chief instrument of God, is here often repeated, to signify the singular efficacy, thereof.\f*
\v 17 Ishall not die, but shall live: and I will tell the works of our Lord.
\v 18 Our Lord chastising hath chastised me: and to death he hath not delivered me. \f + \fr 117:18 \ft God chastiseth his children,\f* \f + \fr 117:18 \ft because he would not that they should die eternally. So he punisheth as a father, not as an enemy.\f*
\v 19 Open ye the gates of justice to me, being entered into them I will confess to our Lord: \f + \fr 117:19 \ft The Prophet now speaketh in the person of just souls, requiring spiritual doctrine, and food,\f*
\v 20 this is the gate of our Lord, the just shall enter into it. \f + \fr 117:20 \ft and promising to serve God.\f*
\v 21 I will confess to thee because thou hast heard me: and art become my salvation.
\v 22 The stone, which the builders rejected: the same is made into the head of the corner. \f + \fr 117:22 \ft An evident Prophecy of Christ uttered by the Royal Psalmist, and now confessed by every Christian, that our Saviour rejected by the Jews, is nevertheless the builder of his Church, by joining the two peoples of Jews and Gentiles, as two walls into one house.\f*
\v 23 This was done by our Lord: and it is marvelous in our eyes.
\v 24 This is the day, which our Lord made: let us rejoice, and be glad therein. \f + \fr 117:24 \ft God ordained this acceptable time of grace.\f*
\v 25 O Lord save me, o Lord give good success: Blessed be he that cometh in the name of our Lord. \f + \fr 117:25 \ft The song of the Hebrew children, when Christ entered Jerusalem with palms of triumph, and acclamations.\f*
\v 26 We have blessed you of the house of our Lord: \f + \fr 117:26 \ft The voice of Christ, and his Apostles, and other Clergy blessing the people as they desire.\f*
\v 27 our Lord is God, and he hath given light to us. Appoint a solemn day with thick boughs, even to the horn of the altar. \f + \fr 117:27 \ft This was fulfilled when Christ was brought with bows of palm, and other signs of triumph, from Bethania,\f* \f + \fr 117:27 \ft through the whole city, even into the Temple and unto the Altar. Mat. 21.\f*
\v 28 Thou art my God, and I will confess to thee: thou art my God, and I will exalt thee. I will confess to thee because thou hast heard me: and art become my salvation.
\v 29 Confess ye to our Lord because he is good: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 117:29 \ft Our first, chief, and final duty is to praise God. v. 1. & ult.\f*
\c 118
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Aleph. Doctrine. Blessed are the immaculate in the way: which walk in the law of our Lord. \f + \fr 118:1 \ft Whereas all without exception, desire to be happy and blessed:\f* \f + \fr 118:1 \ft they are indeed happy (according to the perfectest happiness of this life) that are immaculate:\f* \f + \fr 118:1 \ft and they are immaculate, that walk in the law of God. Where the holy Psalmist presupposeth, that some can and do keep the law of God, and so are immaculate, and blessed in the way of this life.\f* \f + \fr 118:1 \ft This title was added by the Septuagint, to admonish us that this Psalm containeth that singular manner of praising God, signified by the two Hebrew words Alleluia, as before Psal. 104.\f*
\v 2 Blessed are they that search his testimonies: that seek after him with all their heart. \f + \fr 118:2 \ft Those that are immaculate, are again blessed, by searching God's testimonies, that is, his law, testifying that the good shall be rewarded, and the wicked punished: but searching these testimonies, whilst one is contaminate with sins against God's law, maketh not blessed:\f* \f + \fr 118:2 \ft neither doth every superficial careless search bring this blessing, but searching with true affection of the heart.\f*
\v 3 For they that work iniquity, have not walked in his ways. \f + \fr 118:3 \ft contrarywise they that work iniquity are not blessed;\f* \f + \fr 118:3 \ft because they have not walked in the ways of God, to wit, not kept his commandments and law, which are the way to happiness.\f*
\v 4 Thou hast very much commanded thy commandments to be kept. \f + \fr 118:4 \ft For man's own good, that he may come to true happiness, God hath most seriously commanded us to keep his commandments, that is, to observe his Law commanded by most sovereign divine authority.\f*
\v 5 Would God my ways might be directed, to keep thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:5 \ft Therefore the faithful servant of God, knowing his own insufficiency, desireth that God by his grace will direct and strengthen him,\f* \f + \fr 118:5 \ft to keep his law, called Justifications, because thereby man is made just.\f*
\v 6 Then shall I not be confounded, when I shall look throughly in all thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:6 \ft They shall be safe from eternal confusion, when they shall keep not only part, but all thy commandments: because breach of any bringeth confusion.\f*
\v 7 I will confess to thee in direction of heart: in that I have learned the judgments of thy justice. \f + \fr 118:7 \ft So shall I praise thee, and render thanks,\f* \f + \fr 118:7 \ft with sincere not feigned affection,\f* \f + \fr 118:7 \ft for this great benefit, that I have learned, that thy law is according to most just judgement.\f*
\v 8 I will keep thy justifications: forsake me not wholly. \f + \fr 118:8 \ft Ihave therefore a firm purpose, & do faithfully promise to keep thy law, which maketh the keeper thereof just.\f* \f + \fr 118:8 \ft Albeit thou suffer me sometimes to be in tribulation, or in tentation, yet forsake me not wholly. The Psalmist knew well (saith S. Gregory) that he might be profitably left a while, who prayed, that he should not be wholly forsaken.\f*
\v 9 Beth. House. Wherein doth a young man correct his way? In keeping thy words. \f + \fr 118:9 \ft In this second octonary, as also in all the rest, the Holy Ghost by the Prophet's pen teacheth the means how to come to perfection & happiness. Here by way of interrogation, as it were demanding how a young man, that is every man prone to worldly pleasure, & slow in God's service, shall begin to correct his course?\f* \f + \fr 118:9 \ft Whereto the same Holy Ghost answereth, that he must keep God's law, called here his words. For all the words which God uttereth, are laws to his servants.\f* \f + \fr 118:9 \ft * sermones.\f*
\v 10 With my whole heart I have sought after thee: repel me not from thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:10 \ft The Psalmist now speaketh in the person of perfect just men, or of the whole Church in general. Whose common spirit seeketh God entirely.\f* \f + \fr 118:10 \ft And considering that this perfect good will is the gift of God, prayeth that he will conserve the same, and not suffer it to be altered, or to err from his commandments.\f*
\v 11 In my heart I have hid thy words: that I may not sin to thee. \f + \fr 118:11 \ft Another, sincere profession of a resolute good purpose not to sin.\f* \f + \fr 118:11 \ft * eloquia.\f*
\v 12 Blessed art thou, o Lord: teach me thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:12 \ft Agrateful aspiration praising God.\f* \f + \fr 118:12 \ft Again the just prayeth to be more and more instructed in justifications: that which S. John exhorteth unto: He that is just, let him yet be justified. Apoc. 22.\f*
\v 13 In my lips I have pronounced all the judgments of thy mouth. \f + \fr 118:13 \ft God's law is also called his judgements, because sitting in judgement he giveth sentence according to his Law.\f*
\v 14 I am delighted in the way of thy testimonies, as in all riches. \f + \fr 118:14 \ft As the just professeth by mouth, so he delighteth in heart.\f*
\v 15 I will be exercised in thy commandments: and I will consider thy ways. \f + \fr 118:15 \ft Practiseth in work.\f*
\v 16 I will meditate in thy justifications: I will not forget thy words. \f + \fr 118:16 \ft And diligently meditateth God's law.\f* \f + \fr 118:16 \ft * sermones.\f*
\v 17 Gimel. Fullness. Render to thy servant, quicken me: and I shall keep thy words. \f + \fr 118:17 \ft O Lord liberally give me that which I here crave,\f* \f + \fr 118:17 \ft quicken me with spiritual life, thy grace.\f* \f + \fr 118:17 \ft so I shall keep thy law, which otherwise I cannot.\f* \f + \fr 118:17 \ft * sermones.\f*
\v 18 Reveal mine eyes: and I shall consider the marvelous things of thy law. \f + \fr 118:18 \ft Illuminate mine understanding by thy grace,\f* \f + \fr 118:18 \ft that I may be able to see the marvelous great and just reasons of thy law, instructing all, threatening the perverse, encouraging the well disposed, punishing the wicked, rewarding the good, doing right to all.\f*
\v 19 I am a sojourner in the land, hide not thy commandments from me. \f + \fr 118:19 \ft Ithat have but a small time in this world,\f* \f + \fr 118:19 \ft desire to be instructed in thy law, what is therein commanded.\f*
\v 20 My soul hath coveted to desire thy justifications, at all time.
\v 21 Thou hast rebuked the proud: cursed are they that decline from thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:21 \ft Iconsider that thou, o God, dost sharply reprove the proud contemners of thy commandments:\f* \f + \fr 118:21 \ft laying curses upon them for declining from thine obedience.\f*
\v 22 Take from me reproach, and contempt: because I have sought after thy testimonies.
\v 23 For Princes sat, and they spake against me: but thy servant was exercised in thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:23 \ft Though persecutors were very potent,\f* \f + \fr 118:23 \ft yet the faithful servant of God persevered in his service.\f*
\v 24 For both thy testimonies are my meditation: and thy justifications my counsel. \f + \fr 118:24 \ft In time of persecution and tentation we must think and meditate, that God's law testifieth eternal reward, or punishment,\f* \f + \fr 118:24 \ft and in our deliberation or consultation, we must consider that keeping God's law maketh just: & consequently meriteth reward.\f*
\v 25 Daleth. Of Tables. My soul hath cleaved to the pavement: quicken me according to thy word. \f + \fr 118:25 \ft This also is uttered in the person of the just, who is often brought to great distress: as it were, even near to death,\f* \f + \fr 118:25 \ft in which case he confidently prayeth to be relieved, according to God's word, law, and promise.\f*
\v 26 I have uttered my ways, and thou hast heard me: teach me thy justifications.
\v 27 Instruct me the way of thy justifications: and I shall be exercised in thy marvelous works.
\v 28 My soul hath slumbered for tediousness: confirm me in thy words. \f + \fr 118:28 \ft Being in so great anxiety that my mind is almost distracted or overcome.\f* \f + \fr 118:28 \ft Icall to thee God, that thou wilt conserve me, that I still keep thy law, uttered by thy words.\f*
\v 29 Remove from me the way of iniquity: and according to thy law, have mercy on me. \f + \fr 118:29 \ft Protect me that I fall not to iniquity.\f* \f + \fr 118:29 \ft And of thy mercy conserve me in state of grace.\f*
\v 30 I have chosen the way of truth: I have not forgotten thy judgments.
\v 31 I have cleaved to thy testimonies, o Lord: do not confound me. \f + \fr 118:31 \ft Suffer me not to be confounded.\f*
\v 32 I ran the way of thy commandments: when thou didst dilate my heart. \f + \fr 118:32 \ft Man is able, and doth run in the right way of God's commandments,\f* \f + \fr 118:32 \ft yet not of himself, but when God replenisheth his heart with grace.\f*
\v 33 He. This thing. Set me a law, o Lord, the way of thy justifications: and I will seek after it always. \f + \fr 118:33 \ft Impress, o God, thy law in mine affection, make me to love it, and to desire to be justified,\f* \f + \fr 118:33 \ft so shall I heartily and always seek it.\f*
\v 34 Give me understanding, and I will search thy law: and I will keep it with my whole heart. \f + \fr 118:34 \ft After thou hast given me a desire to keep thy law, give me also understanding,\f* \f + \fr 118:34 \ft then shall I fruitfully search it. For this is the right order (as before in the first, and second verses) first to love God's law, to be justified, and to become immaculate, and then to search to know the law, and so it is more easily learned.\f*
\v 35 Conduct me into the path of thy commandments: because I would it. \f + \fr 118:35 \ft God's grace first draweth and leadeth,\f* \f + \fr 118:35 \ft then freewill inflamed with desire effectually concurreth.\f*
\v 36 Incline my heart into thy testimonies: and not into avarice. \f + \fr 118:36 \ft Still the Prophet inculcateth the necessity of God's grace, as well to make us desire that is good;\f* \f + \fr 118:36 \ft as to fly from evil.\f*
\v 37 Turn away mine eyes that they see not vanity: in thy way quicken me. \f + \fr 118:37 \ft It is necessary also to pray that God will take away occasions, which might move to sin:\f* \f + \fr 118:37 \ft and still to grant his helping grace in progress of virtue.\f*
\v 38 Establish thy word to thy servant, in thy fear. \f + \fr 118:38 \ft Again the just prayeth for confirmation in grace, to be established in the fear of God.\f* \f + \fr 118:38 \ft * eloquium.\f*
\v 39 Take away my reproach, which I have feared: because thy judgments are pleasant. \f + \fr 118:39 \ft To be delivered also from all the effects of former sins,\f* \f + \fr 118:39 \ft for sin is therefore reproachful and odious, because it is contrary to God's law, & true judgements, which are most pleasant.\f*
\v 40 Behold I have coveted thy commandments: in thine equity quicken me. \f + \fr 118:40 \ft Being thus affected with desire to keep the commandments, the soul prayeth to be still quickened, more and more with good spirit, and so to persevere to the end.\f*
\v 41 Vau. And. And let thy mercy come upon me, o Lord: thy salvation according to thy word. \f + \fr 118:41 \ft Again considering that without God's grace preventing, man cannot do any good thing, the Prophet reneweth his prayer, requesting God's mercy,\f* \f + \fr 118:41 \ft and his help freely promised to all that ask it.\f* \f + \fr 118:41 \ft * eloquium.\f*
\v 42 And I shall answer a word to them that upbraid me: because I have hoped in thy words. \f + \fr 118:42 \ft Wherewith being assisted and strengthened, he that before was weak will boldly answer all calumniators, that reproachfully say: God will not help him:\f* \f + \fr 118:42 \ft that indeed he hath not in vain trusted in God's promised help.\f* \f + \fr 118:42 \ft * sermonibus.\f*
\v 43 And take not away out of my mouth the word of truth utterly: because I have much hoped in thy judgments. \f + \fr 118:43 \ft He also prayeth, though he be sometimes fearful, that God will not suffer him wholly to omit manifest profession of faith and true religion,\f* \f + \fr 118:43 \ft seeing by thy former grace I have already reposed my trust in thy promises, made to them that are resolved to keep thy law.\f*
\v 44 And I will keep thy law always: for ever, and for ever and ever. \f + \fr 118:44 \ft For I do firmly purpose ever and always to keep thy law.\f*
\v 45 And I walked in largeness: because I have sought after thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:45 \ft In this I have had great joy and comfort of mind:\f* \f + \fr 118:45 \ft because I did indeed seek after thy commandments, which is specially uttered (as also the three next verses) in the person of those, that are in trial of persecution for their faith:\f*
\v 46 And I spake of thy testimonies in the sight of kings: and was not confounded. \f + \fr 118:46 \ft Who boldly in time of persecution, even before persecuting Kings and Emperors, profess Christ's true Religion. Verified in innumerable glorious Martyrs, yea also of the frail sex, in S. Catharine, S. Cecily, S. Lucy, S. Margaret, S. Wenefride, S. Ursula, and her fellows, and many more, most constantly answering all words of reproach objected, as if it were a base or contemptible thing to be Christians, to be Catholics, to be Papists. No, all these & the like, are honourable & glorious titles; importing the true service of Christ, in unity of the Catholic Church: and spiritual participation with the visible head thereof, Christ's Vicar in earth.\f*
\v 47 And I meditated in thy commandments, which I loved. \f + \fr 118:47 \ft Such confessors as yet mortal, rejoice in that they have meditated in God's commandments, which they have fervently loved.\f*
\v 48 And I have lifted up my hands to thy commandments, which I loved: and I was exercised in thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:48 \ft Also shewed the same in external work, not dissembling by silence, by word, nor fact.\f* \f + \fr 118:48 \ft every way exercising God's law, which maketh the observers just.\f*
\v 49 Zain. This. Be mindful of thy word to thy servant, wherein thou hast given me hope. \f + \fr 118:49 \ft That which God hath decreed and promised, being in it-self most certain and assured, yet includeth the means, whereby it shall be put in execution: and therefore the just, his elect, do pray for the performance of his will.\f*
\v 50 This hath comforted me in my humiliation: because thy word hath quickened me. \f + \fr 118:50 \ft Expectation of thy promise hath given me courage.\f* \f + \fr 118:50 \ft eloquium.\f*
\v 51 The proud did unjustly exceedingly: but I declined not from thy law. \f + \fr 118:51 \ft Proud contemners of God's law, have every way molested me, by detracting, deriding, calumniating, and violently persecuting me.\f* \f + \fr 118:51 \ft All which I have borne patiently, and not declined from thy law.\f*
\v 52 I have been mindful of thy judgments from everlasting, o Lord: and was comforted. \f + \fr 118:52 \ft Iremembered and considered thy just punishments inflicted upon the impious,\f* \f + \fr 118:52 \ft even from the beginning of the world (both upon the devils and wicked men) and that thou wilt exercise the like hereafter,\f* \f + \fr 118:52 \ft which consideration of thy justice comforted me.\f*
\v 53 Fainting possessed me, because of sinners forsaking thy Law. \f + \fr 118:53 \ft Otherwise if I had not seen thy justice, my zeal against contemners of thy law would have killed me.\f*
\v 54 Thy justifications were song by me, in the place of my peregrination. \f + \fr 118:54 \ft In this place of my peregrination from heaven, I am comforted by remembering, celebrating, and singing thy just commandments and laws, which make thy servants just.\f*
\v 55 I have been mindful in the night of thy name, o Lord: and have kept thy law. \f + \fr 118:55 \ft In persecution, and in all tribulation, I kept thy law, because I would not dishonour thy name:\f*
\v 56 This was done to me: because I sought after thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:56 \ft And my tribulation especially fell upon me, because I sought to be justified by keeping thy law.\f*
\v 57 Heth. Life. My portion, o Lord, I said to keep thy law. \f + \fr 118:57 \ft The Prophet proceedeth speaking in the person of the just tending to perfection, and saying: This is my happy choice, that I desire no other inheritance, nor possession, but to keep God's Law.\f*
\v 58 I besought thy face, with all my heart: have mercy on me according to thy word. \f + \fr 118:58 \ft And seeing this exceedeth my proper strength, I prayed God of his mercy to make able to keep it.\f* \f + \fr 118:58 \ft eloquium.\f*
\v 59 I thought upon my ways: and converted my feet unto thy testimonies. \f + \fr 118:59 \ft Pondering my former actions, I turned my paths to observe more perfectly the Law, which God hath testified to be the right way.\f*
\v 60 I am prepared, and am not troubled: to keep thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:60 \ft With promptness of mind, and without hesitation I resolved to keep the commandments.\f*
\v 61 The cords of sinners have wrapped me round about: and I have not forgotten thy law. \f + \fr 118:61 \ft The wicked laid cords, nets, or snares, to entrap and hinder me,\f* \f + \fr 118:61 \ft but I kept thy law fresh in memory.\f*
\v 62 At mid-night I rose to confess to thee, for the judgments of thy justification. \f + \fr 118:62 \ft That this is not understood only mystically in time of affliction, but also literally and prophetically, that some special servants of God should observe a godly profession of praying at mid-night, the word (I rose) maketh it probable. Saint Paul & Silas,\f*
\v 63 I am partaker of all that fear thee: and that keep thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:63 \ft Agreat benefit, and a singular consolation, that all true living members of Christ, are partakers of all the prayers, good works, and merits, of the whole Church militant and triumphant. Which in our Creed is called, The Communion of Saints.\f*
\v 64 The earth, o Lord, is full of thy mercy: teach me thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:64 \ft so great is the mercy of God, extended, communicated, and multiplied in the whole earth.\f* \f + \fr 118:64 \ft Instruct me, and direct me therefore, o God, that I may learn and observe thy law, and so be justified, and made participant of so great mercy.\f*
\v 65 Teth. Good. Thou hast done bounty with thy servant, o Lord: according to thy word. \f + \fr 118:65 \ft Dealt very bountifully\f* \f + \fr 118:65 \ft as thou didst promise.\f*
\v 66 Teach me goodness, and discipline, and knowledge: because I have believed thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:66 \ft He that hath bountifully received grace at God's hand, prayeth for more grace, that he may be beneficial to others in relieving the needy,\f* \f + \fr 118:66 \ft in instructing the ignorant,\f* \f + \fr 118:66 \ft in persuading to keep the law of God:\f* \f + \fr 118:66 \ft because he hath learned and believeth the commandments, by which he is bound to love, and have care of his neighbour.\f*
\v 67 Before I was humbled I offended: therefore have I kept thy word. \f + \fr 118:67 \ft Before I was afflicted, I often fell into sin:\f* \f + \fr 118:67 \ft but vexation gave me understanding, therefore now I keep thy law.\f* \f + \fr 118:67 \ft eloquium.\f*
\v 68 Thou art good: and in thy goodness teach me thy justifications.
\v 69 The iniquity of the proud is multiplied upon me: but I in all my heart will search thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:69 \ft Contemners of thy law have endeavoured to entangle me,\f* \f + \fr 118:69 \ft but I persist in keeping thy commandments. As before v. 51. 61.\f*
\v 70 Their heart is curded together as milk: but I have meditated thy law. \f + \fr 118:70 \ft Though the wicked combine themselves together against me,\f* \f + \fr 118:70 \ft yet I consider, that it is necessary to persevere in thy law.\f*
\v 71 It is good for me that thou hast humbled me: that I may learn thy justifications.
\v 72 The law of thy mouth is good unto me, above thousands of gold and silver. \f + \fr 118:72 \ft Aclear comparison, that it is better to keep God's law, which bringeth life everlasting, than to have all the riches & Kingdoms of this world.\f*
\v 73 Iod. Beginning. Thy hands have made me, and formed me: give me understanding, and I will learn thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:73 \ft God being our Creator, we may with confidence pray him to illuminate our minds, that we may learn what is his pleasure, and so endeavour to fulfill it.\f*
\v 74 They that fear thee shall see me, & shall rejoice: because I have much hoped in thy words. \f + \fr 118:74 \ft Others that love God will be glad to see me also serve him.\f*
\v 75 I know, o Lord, that thy judgments are equity: and in thy truth thou hast humbled me. \f + \fr 118:75 \ft The just being afflicted, and not seeing the particular cause thereof, yet knoweth and confesseth, that God doth it for most just cause.\f* \f + \fr 118:75 \ft And therefore with patience prayeth for comfort, as followeth:\f*
\v 76 Let thy mercy be done to comfort me, according to thy word unto thy servant. \f + \fr 118:76 \ft * eloquium.\f*
\v 77 Let thy commiserations come to me, and I shall live: because thy law is my meditation. \f + \fr 118:77 \ft Who am almost dead in tribulation.\f*
\v 78 Let the proud be confounded, because they have done unjustly toward me: but I will be exercised in thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:78 \ft The just also prayeth that the wicked may be ashamed, and converted, for so the Hebrew word here signifieth, though it is also lawful to desire the just punishment of obstinate sinners.\f*
\v 79 Let them be converted to me that fear thee: and that know thy testimonies. \f + \fr 118:79 \ft He prayeth again for conversion of the wicked, and to have peace with them.\f*
\v 80 Let my heart be made immaculate in thy justifications, that I be not confounded.
\v 81 Caph. Hand, or Palm of the hand. My soul hath fainted for thy salvation: and I have much hoped in thy word. \f + \fr 118:81 \ft Many just of the old testament most fervently desired the coming of Christ our Saviour, as our Lord himself testifieth, Mat. 13. v. 17. And now the just desire his coming in glory. 2. Tim. 4. v. 8.\f*
\v 82 Mine eyes have failed for thy word, saying: When wilt thou comfort me? \f + \fr 118:82 \ft Delayed hope afflicteth.\f* \f + \fr 118:82 \ft * eloquium.\f*
\v 83 Because I am made as a bottle in the hoar frost: I have not forgotten thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:83 \ft As a leather bottle made of a beast's skin, congealed with the frost, and after parched in smoke, so is the body of the just mortified by diverse sorts of afflictions, made a new bottle fit to receive new wine, that is perfect doctrine of Christian life, as of fasting, and other austerity, whereof our Saviour speaketh. Mat. 9. v. 17.\f*
\v 84 How many are the days of thy servant: when wilt thou do judgment on them that persecute me? \f + \fr 118:84 \ft Such is man's infirmity, yea of the just, that he apprehendeth tribulations to be very long, and therefore desireth consummation; and that without sin, so he still submit his will to God's will.\f*
\v 85 The unjust have told me fables: but not as thy law. \f + \fr 118:85 \ft Frivolous idle tails, which are not according to God's law.\f*
\v 86 All thy commandments are truth: they have unjustly persecuted me, help me.
\v 87 They have well near made end of me in the earth: but I have not forsaken thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:87 \ft Iwas in great danger; but am not overthrown.\f*
\v 88 According to thy mercy quicken me: and I shall keep the testimonies of thy mouth. \f + \fr 118:88 \ft And by thy merciful grace shall persist.\f*
\v 89 Lamed. Discipline. For ever Lord thy word is permanent in heaven. \f + \fr 118:89 \ft The praise of God's works, which are firm and permanent in the order, wherein he set them.\f*
\v 90 Thy truth in generation and generation: thou hast founded the earth, and it is permanent.
\v 91 By thy ordinance the day continueth: because all things serve thee. \f + \fr 118:91 \ft All things of this world, man excepted, do God's will.\f*
\v 92 But that thy law is my meditation: I had then perhaps perished in my humiliation. \f + \fr 118:92 \ft Man, except he meditate God's law, and thereby be holden up, is in danger,\f* \f + \fr 118:92 \ft perhaps in every tentation to perish eternally. For he can never rise out of mortal sin, by his own power, and all should perish if God's mercy did not spare some, and give them new effectual grace to repent.\f*
\v 93 I will not forget thy justifications for ever: because in them thou hast quickened me.
\v 94 I am thine, save me: because I have sought out thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:94 \ft Always understood, that God's grace prevented, else no man can seek to observe the commandments.\f*
\v 95 Sinners have expected me to destroy me: I understood thy testimonies.
\v 96 Of all consummation I have seen the end: thy commandment is exceeding large. \f + \fr 118:96 \ft All worldly things have their consummation and end:\f* \f + \fr 118:96 \ft God's commandment continueth ever. For we are perpetually bound to love and serve God: to love our neighbours, yea and enemies. The reward also for keeping God's commandments, & punishment for breaking them, are eternal without end.\f*
\v 97 Mem. Of them. How have I loved thy law, o Lord! All the day it is my meditation. \f + \fr 118:97 \ft It is marvel to a perfect just man, that he hath so much loved and observed God's law. By acknowledging whereof, he yieldeth praise and thanks to God, whose gift it is.\f*
\v 98 Above mine enemies thou hast made me wise by thy commandment: because it is to me for ever. \f + \fr 118:98 \ft The fruits of observing God's law are many and great. Amongst others, it maketh the observer, wiser than his enemies.\f*
\v 99 Above all that taught me have I understood: because thy testimonies are my meditation. \f + \fr 118:99 \ft It maketh the observer wiser than his temporal masters, that taught him, to wit, than those that teach well, and do not perform the same.\f*
\v 100 Above ancients have I understood: because I have sought thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:100 \ft Younger in years that keep God's commandments, are wiser than the more ancient that keep them not.\f*
\v 101 I have stayed my feet from all evil way: that I may keep thy words.
\v 102 I have not declined from thy judgments: because thou hast set me a law.
\v 103 How sweet are thy words to my jaws. More than honey to my mouth! \f + \fr 118:103 \ft Another fruit is the sweetness, which the just feeleth in his own soul.\f* \f + \fr 118:103 \ft eloquia.\f*
\v 104 By thy commandments I have understood: therefore have I hated all the way of iniquity. \f + \fr 118:104 \ft It brideth also just hatred to sin.\f*
\v 105 Nun. Everlasting. Thy word is a lamp to my feet, and a light to my paths. \f + \fr 118:105 \ft The word or law of god declared by Prophets, Pastors, or other Preachers, is the ordinary means for others to learn, how to direct their ways and actions.\f*
\v 106 I sware, and have determined to keep the judgments of thy justice. \f + \fr 118:106 \ft Such profession God's people made in the old law, in\f*
\v 107 I am humbled exceedingly, o Lord: quicken me according to thy word. \f + \fr 118:107 \ft All that will live godly in Christ Jesus, shall suffer persecution. 2. Tim. 3. v. 12.\f*
\v 108 The voluntaries of my mouth make acceptable, o Lord: and teach me thy judgments. \f + \fr 118:108 \ft Besides the commandments, the just also offer voluntary works of supererogation, acceptable to God.\f*
\v 109 My soul is in my hands always: and I have not forgotten thy law. \f + \fr 118:109 \ft By this Hebrew proverb is signified, that a just man's temporal life is in continual danger, as the thing that is in one's hand, is ready to be laid by, put out of his hand, or to be by and by disposed of, or may forthwith fall from his hand.\f*
\v 110 Sinners laid a snare for me: and I have not erred from thy commandments.
\v 111 For inheritance I have purchased thy testimonies for ever: because they are the joy of my heart.
\v 112 I have inclined my heart to do thy justifications for ever, for reward. \f + \fr 118:112 \ft Amost evident place, that the keeping of God's commandments merit reward, and are rightly observed in respect of reward.\f*
\v 113 Samech. Help. I have hated the unjust: and I have loved thy law. \f + \fr 118:113 \ft Not any mortal man is to be hated, in his person, but his iniquity, by which he is an enemy to God's law,\f* \f + \fr 118:113 \ft which every just man loveth.\f*
\v 114 Thou art my helper, and protector: and upon thy word I have much hoped.
\v 115 Depart from me ye malignant: and I will search the commandments of my God. \f + \fr 118:115 \ft Whosoever will seriously and securely search the law of God, must avoid the conversation of evil men.\f*
\v 116 Receive me according to thy word, and I shall live: and confound me not of mine expectation. \f + \fr 118:116 \ft Ageneral and very fit prayer, when we addict ourselves by a firm resolution to serve God, beseeching him to receive us into his protection:\f* \f + \fr 118:116 \ft whereby spiritual life is conserved:\f* \f + \fr 118:116 \ft which we pray with great confidence, because he hath promised to hear those that seek, ask, and knock at the door of his grace.\f* \f + \fr 118:116 \ft eloquium.\f*
\v 117 Help me, and I shall be saved: and I will meditate in thy justifications always. \f + \fr 118:117 \ft We must pray also that he suffer us not to be confounded, or made frustrate of the reward which we expect; for hope confoundeth not, if charity be poured in our hearts, by the Holy Ghost which is given us. Rom. 5. v. 5.\f*
\v 118 Thou hast despised all that revolt from thy judgments: because their cogitation is unjust. \f + \fr 118:118 \ft God rejecteth sinners:\f* \f + \fr 118:118 \ft so long as they think perversely: that is, until by his grace, some return to a better mind, which of themselves they can never do.\f*
\v 119 All the sinners of the earth I have reputed prevaricators: therefore have I loved thy testimonies. \f + \fr 118:119 \ft as God accounteth of sinners, so the just also esteemeth them, conforming his judgement to God's.\f*
\v 120 Pierce my flesh with thy fear: for I am afraid of thy judgments. \f + \fr 118:120 \ft Servile fear is profitable as this place maketh evident: though perfect charity afterwards succeeding, expelleth that fear, and moveth to do well for the love of God, not for fear of punishment. 1. Ioan. 4.\f*
\v 121 Ain. A fountain, or an eye. I have done judgment and justice: deliver me not to them that calumniate me. \f + \fr 118:121 \ft The just again in fervent zeal, not arrogantly, but confidently professing his innocency,\f* \f + \fr 118:121 \ft prayeth to be defended from calumniators.\f*
\v 122 Receive thy servant unto good: let not the proud calumniate me. \f + \fr 118:122 \ft Grant therefore, o God, the good and lawful request which I demand.\f*
\v 123 Mine eyes have failed after thy salvation: and for the word of thy justice. \f + \fr 118:123 \ft By long expecting to be delivered and saved from tribulation.\f* \f + \fr 118:123 \ft eloquium.\f*
\v 124 Do with thy servant according to thy mercy: and teach me thy justifications.
\v 125 I am thy servant: give me understanding, that I may know thy testimonies.
\v 126 It is time to do, o Lord: they have dissipated thy law. \f + \fr 118:126 \ft It is time, and high time, saith fervent zeal of the just man, that God deliver the innocent:\f* \f + \fr 118:126 \ft when the wicked have not only persecuted the good, but have also contemptuously made havoc of God's law and true religion.\f*
\v 127 Therefore have I loved thy commandments, above gold and topazius. \f + \fr 118:127 \ft For this zeal of God's law so despised and dissipated, the just more and more loveth, that which the wicked so deadly hate.\f*
\v 128 Therefore was I directed to all thy commandments: all wicked way I have hated. \f + \fr 118:128 \ft Even by the mortal hate of the wicked I saw that God's law is most excellent, and therefore addicted myself so much the more to love it,\f* \f + \fr 118:128 \ft and to hate all wicked ways.\f*
\v 129 Phe. Mouth. Thy testimonies are marvelous: therefore hath my soul searched them. \f + \fr 118:129 \ft God's marvelous power and wisdom, testified by his works and commandments,\f* \f + \fr 118:129 \ft worthily invite just souls to meditate and contemplate the same.\f*
\v 130 The declaration of thy words doth illuminate: and giveth understanding to little ones. \f + \fr 118:130 \ft First entrance into knowledge of holy Scripture, illuminateth the understanding of the humble, whereby they proceed to know more.\f* \f + \fr 118:130 \ft Sermonum.\f*
\v 131 I opened my mouth, and drew breath: because I desired thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:131 \ft By this Metaphor, of gaping or wide opening the mouth, and drawing breath, the Prophet describeth the great desire of the just, to know and keep God's commandments.\f*
\v 132 Look upon me, and have mercy on me, according to the judgment of them that love thy name. \f + \fr 118:132 \ft According to thy accustomed equity, in shewing mercy to them that love thy name.\f*
\v 133 Direct my steps according to thy word: and let not any injustice have domination over me. \f + \fr 118:133 \ft eloquium.\f*
\v 134 Redeem me from the calumnies of men: that I may keep thy commandments.
\v 135 Illuminate thy face upon thy servant: and teach me thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:135 \ft Let thy divine Majesty look upon me with favourable countenance.\f*
\v 136 Mine eyes have gushed forth issues of waters: because they have not kept thy law. \f + \fr 118:136 \ft True repentance consisteth not only in purpose to avoid sin hereafter, which indeed is first required, but also in sorrow and lamentation for sins past.\f*
\v 137 Sade. Justice. Thou art just, o Lord: and thy judgment is right. \f + \fr 118:137 \ft God being essentially just of himself, maketh men just according to right judgement, by giving them grace of mercy, wherewith they cooperating are just by justice indeed inherent in their souls, not by imputation only: for it were not right judgement to impute, or account man just, who is not so indeed.\f*
\v 138 Thou hast commanded justice thy testimonies: and thy verity exceedingly. \f + \fr 118:138 \ft The same is more confirmed by these three synonyma, Justice, Testimonies, Verity, signifying the law of God, most earnestly commanded.\f*
\v 139 My zeal hath made me to pine away: because mine enemies have forgotten thy words.
\v 140 Thy word is fired exceedingly: and thy servant hath loved it. \f + \fr 118:140 \ft God's law is as pure as any thing purged by fire.\f* \f + \fr 118:140 \ft * eloquia.\f*
\v 141 I am a youngman, and contemned: I have not forgotten thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:141 \ft Ajust man is often judged ignorant, immature, unexperienced, by the worldly wise;\f* \f + \fr 118:141 \ft but indeed is wise, in that he forgetteth not to keep the law, which maketh him just.\f*
\v 142 Thy justice is justice for ever: and thy law is verity.
\v 143 Tribulation and distress have found me: thy commandments are my meditation.
\v 144 Thy testimonies are equity for ever give me understanding, and I shall live. \f + \fr 118:144 \ft Having professed the necessity of perfect justice, he concludeth this Octonary, praying to be illuminated in his understanding, that so he may attain justice and live thereby.\f*
\v 145 Coph. Vocation. I have cried in my whole heart, hear me, o Lord: I will seek after thy justifications. \f + \fr 118:145 \ft Most serious and fervent invocation of God for his grace is necessary to the fulfilling of his law.\f*
\v 146 I have cried to thee, save me: that I may keep thy commandments.
\v 147 I have prevented in maturity, and have cried: because I hoped much in thy words. \f + \fr 118:147 \ft Ihave prevented the nature and ordinary time of the night, and have prayed\f* \f + \fr 118:147 \ft very attentively.\f*
\v 148 Mine eyes have prevented early unto thee: that I might meditate thy words. \f + \fr 118:148 \ft Again in the morning I have prevented the accustomed time of prayer.\f* \f + \fr 118:148 \ft eloquia.\f*
\v 149 Hear my voice according to thy mercy, o Lord: and according to thy judgment quicken me. \f + \fr 118:149 \ft According to thy accustomed manner of shewing mercy, shew it me, that thereby I may live.\f*
\v 150 They that persecute me have approached to iniquity: but from thy law they are made far off.
\v 151 Thou art nigh, o Lord: and all thy ways are truth. \f + \fr 118:151 \ft God is always ready to hear all that sincerely invocate him.\f*
\v 152 From the beginning I knew of thy testimonies: that thou hast founded them for ever. \f + \fr 118:152 \ft God's law is the same in substance from the beginning of the world, and will be for ever.\f*
\v 153 Res. Head. See my humiliation, and deliver me: because I have not forgotten thy law. \f + \fr 118:153 \ft Another prayer of the just in affliction.\f*
\v 154 Judge my judgment, & redeem me: for thy word quicken thou me. \f + \fr 118:154 \ft Conserve me in thy grace.\f* \f + \fr 118:154 \ft eloquium.\f*
\v 155 Salvation is far from sinners: because they have not sought after thy justifications.
\v 156 Thy mercies are many, o Lord: according to thy judgment quicken me. \f + \fr 118:156 \ft As before v. 149.\f*
\v 157 There are many that persecute me, and afflict me: I have not declined from thy testimonies.
\v 158 Isaw the prevaricators, and I pined away: because they kept not thy words. \f + \fr 118:158 \ft eloquia.\f*
\v 159 See that I have loved thy commandments, o Lord: in thy mercy quicken me. \f + \fr 118:159 \ft Sincere profession of innocency is no arrogancy.\f*
\v 160 The beginning of thy words is truth: all the judgments of thy justice are for ever. \f + \fr 118:160 \ft God's essential verity is the beginning from whence, as from the fountain, all other truths are derived:\f* \f + \fr 118:160 \ft And all commandments proceeding from this first truth, are for ever immutable.\f*
\v 161 Sin. Tooth. Princes have persecuted me without cause: and my heart hath been afraid of thy words. \f + \fr 118:161 \ft Potent wicked men persecute the godly without cause, that is, without any just reason moving them; & without the effect intended by them which is to draw God's servants from truth and equity;\f* \f + \fr 118:161 \ft whose heart being possessed with the true fear of God, they persist in keeping God's commandments.\f*
\v 162 I will rejoice at thy words: as he that findeth many spoils. \f + \fr 118:162 \ft Yea they also rejoice in keeping the commandments, with such difficulty, as those do, that gaining the victory over their enemies, carry away great and rich spoils.\f* \f + \fr 118:162 \ft eloquia.\f*
\v 163 I have heard iniquity, and abhorred it: but thy law I have loved.
\v 164 Seven times in the day I have said praise to thee, for the judgments of thy justice. \f + \fr 118:164 \ft Every day the just praise God often, signified by the number of seven. From hence also the Church of Christ took example to institute the seven Canonical Hours,\f*
\v 165 There is much peace to them that love thy law: & there is no scandal to them. \f + \fr 118:165 \ft Amongst other benefits, it is a special commodity, that those which perfectly love God's law have always peace in their own conscience:\f* \f + \fr 118:165 \ft and are never scandalized, that is, do not fall nor commit sin, by any occasion whatsoever given them by others. For it is a general assured doctrine, that the perfect are not scandalized, because they are constant in virtue, and not moved by any example, persuasion, provocation, or other means to offend God: but only the weak and unperfect are moved and drawn to sin by occasions given them, who otherwise would not have sinned. Neither is he excused that falleth by such occasions, because he ought to be constant.\f*
\v 166 I expected thy salvation, o Lord: and have loved thy commandments.
\v 167 My soul hath kept thy testimonies: & hath loved them exceedingly. \f + \fr 118:167 \ft Not of servile fear, but of true charity & filial love.\f*
\v 168 I have kept thy commandments, and thy testimonies: because all my ways are in thy sight. \f + \fr 118:168 \ft Because whatsoever I do is in thy sight, whom I will in no case offend.\f*
\v 169 Tau. Sign. Let my petition approach in thy sight, o Lord: according to thy word give me understanding. \f + \fr 118:169 \ft In this last Octonary, and conclusion of this Psalm, the faithful servant of God prayeth,\f* \f + \fr 118:169 \ft not for human knowledge, or other temporal things, but to understand God's law.\f*
\v 170 Let my request enter in thy sight: according to thy word deliver me. \f + \fr 118:170 \ft Thou that hast promised to hear all that invocate thee,\f* \f + \fr 118:170 \ft vouchsafe to deliver me in time of tribulations and tentations.\f*
\v 171 My lips shall utter an hymn, when thou shalt teach me thy justifications.
\v 172 My tongue shall pronounce thy word: because all thy commandments are equity. \f + \fr 118:172 \ft God giving grace, it behoveth his servants thankfully to serve and praise him.\f* \f + \fr 118:172 \ft Why the 15 Psalms following are called Gradual Canticles. Here follow in order fifteen Psalms entitle Gradual Canticles.\f*
\v 173 Let thy hand be to save me: because I have chosen thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:173 \ft Though man be endued with grace, yet he needeth more grace, that by God's hand and power, not by his own, he may resist tentations.\f*
\v 174 I have coveted thy salvation, o Lord: and thy law is my meditation.
\v 175 My soul shall live, and shall praise thee: and thy judgments shall help me. \f + \fr 118:175 \ft By this assistance of grace, the soul continueth in spiritual life, and praiseth God.\f*
\v 176 I have strayed as a sheep that is lost: seek thy servant, because I have not forgotten thy commandments. \f + \fr 118:176 \ft All mankind, and universally every one, hath been as a lost sheep,\f* \f + \fr 118:176 \ft & Christ came into this world to seek and save all:\f* \f + \fr 118:176 \ft but effectually findeth and saveth those only, that forget not to keep his commandments.\f*
\c 119
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. When I was in tribulation I cried to our Lord: and he heard me. \f + \fr 119:1 \ft Former experience of God's mercy in hearing the prayers of those that invocated him, giveth hope that he will hear in like case.\f*
\v 2 O Lord deliver my soul from unjust lips, and from a deceitful tongue. \f + \fr 119:2 \ft Nothing is more dangerous than untrue and deceitful tongues, nothing more damage than to diminish, and detract from the good fame of the just: and therefore this is a most necessary prayer, that God will deliver us from the wicked tongues of Turks, Heretics, and other wicked men.\f*
\v 3 What may be given thee, or what may be added unto thee to a deceitful tongue? \f + \fr 119:3 \ft What punishment is great enough for wicked tongues?\f*
\v 4 The sharp arrows of the mighty, with coals of desolation. \f + \fr 119:4 \ft Surely the malice of wicked tongues deserveth sharpest punishments to be afflicted by strong hands.\f*
\v 5 Woe is to me, that my sojourning is prolonged: I have dwelt with the inhabitants of Cedar: \f + \fr 119:5 \ft Jews lamented their long absence from the holy land, especially from Jerusalem and the Temple. Christians mourn for their restraint from God's service, and long peregrination from heaven.\f* \f + \fr 119:5 \ft Of Cedar the son of Ismael, came Mahomet, the Turks' false Prophet, whose tyranny is great and long. The name Cedar is interpreted, blackness, and obscurity, which signifieth darkness of error and sin.\f*
\v 6 My soul hath been long a sojourner.
\v 7 With them that hated peace I was peaceable: when I spake to them, they impugned me without cause. \f + \fr 119:7 \ft The wicked afflict those that give no cause of offence.\f*
\c 120
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. I have lifted up mine eyes unto the mountains, from whence help shall come to me. \f + \fr 120:1 \ft Towards Jerusalem, and towards heaven.\f* \f + \fr 120:1 \ft All help cometh from heaven, that is, from God, who of his divine ordinance especially heareth prayers made in holy places. 3. Reg. 7.\f*
\v 2 My help is from our Lord, who made heaven and earth.
\v 3 Give he not thy foot to be moved: neither do he slumber that keepeth thee. \f + \fr 120:3 \ft The just speaketh and wisheth well to his own soul. Especially the whole Church rejoiceth in God's assured protection.\f*
\v 4 Lo he shall not slumber nor sleep, that keepeth Israel. \f + \fr 120:4 \ft The militant Church.\f*
\v 5 Our Lord keepeth thee, our Lord is thy protection, upon thy right hand.
\v 6 By day the sun shall not burn thee: nor the moon by night. \f + \fr 120:6 \ft Prosperity,\f* \f + \fr 120:6 \ft nor adversity can overthrow the Church.\f*
\v 7 Our Lord doth keep thee from all evil: our Lord keep thy soul. \f + \fr 120:7 \ft Spiritual life.\f*
\v 8 Our Lord keep thy coming in, and thy going out: from hence forth now, and for ever.
\c 121
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. I rejoiced in these things, which were said to me: We shall go into the house of our Lord. \f + \fr 121:1 \ft Diverse Prophets told the Jews in captivity, that they should return to Jerusalem. All Prophets, Christ also, and his Apostles, and Priests, preach the entrance, and joys of heaven to the just. All which the Psalmist saw in prophetical spirit, and rejoiced.\f*
\v 2 Our feet were standing, in thy courts, o Jerusalem. \f + \fr 121:2 \ft The Jews consider that sometimes they were joyful in the Temple of Jerusalem: Christians rejoice in the comfort they have in the militant Church.\f*
\v 3 Jerusalem, which is built as a city: whose participation is together in it-self. \f + \fr 121:3 \ft Community and participation of spiritual graces, is a great joy to Catholics, whereof the same Prophet speaketh, Psal. 118. v. 63. and often elsewhere.\f*
\v 4 For thither did the tribes ascend, the tribes of our Lord: the testimony of Israel to confess unto the name of our Lord. \f + \fr 121:4 \ft All the twelve Tribes frequented Jerusalem,\f* \f + \fr 121:4 \ft and all nations of the world do come to the Catholic Church.\f*
\v 5 Because seats sat there in judgment, seats upon the house of David. \f + \fr 121:5 \ft Seats of Judgement were placed in Jerusalem,\f* \f + \fr 121:5 \ft and seats of Judgement in the Catholic Church\f* \f + \fr 121:5 \ft of Christ.\f*
\v 6 Ask ye the things that are for the peace of Jerusalem: and aboundance to them that love thee. \f + \fr 121:6 \ft Christ exhorteth to ask,\f* \f + \fr 121:6 \ft and promiseth to give that is rightly asked, Christians also invite each other to pray for the Church.\f*
\v 7 Peace be made in thy strength: and aboundance in thy towers.
\v 8 For my brethren, and my neighbours' sakes, I spake peace of thee: \f + \fr 121:8 \ft Christ prayeth for his Church,\f* \f + \fr 121:8 \ft and gave his peace to the Apostles, and in them to their successors.\f*
\v 9 For the house of our Lord God, I have sought good things to thee. \f + \fr 121:9 \ft For in heavenly Jerusalem, all good things are prepared, & are given to Saints reigning there for ever.\f*
\c 122
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. To thee have I lifted up mine eyes, which dwellest in the heavens.
\v 2 Behold as the eyes of servants, are on the hands of their masters, As the eyes of the handmaid on the hands of her mistress: so are our eyes to our Lord God until he have mercy on us. \f + \fr 122:2 \ft Servants expecting necessaries at their masters hands are commonly very attentive to receive that which they hope for: so must the faithful praying God, be very attentive, and not distracted in their prayers.\f* \f + \fr 122:2 \ft Another example of handmaids, who generally are more diligent than men.\f*
\v 3 Have mercy on us, o Lord, have mercy on us: because we are much replenished with contempt. \f + \fr 122:3 \ft Though God suffer his servants to sustain some affliction and reproach, yet he heareth and delivereth them before they be oppressed.\f*
\v 4 Because our soul is much replenished: reproach to them that abound, and contempt to the proud. \f + \fr 122:4 \ft Seeing persecution still increase, or continue long, the faithful are then specially to conceive hope of speedy relief.\f*
\c 123
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. But that our Lord was in us, let Israel now say, \f + \fr 123:1 \ft If God had not sent his help and defence to us.\f*
\v 2 but that our Lord was in us. When men rose up against us, \f + \fr 123:2 \ft We could not have escaped the force of our enemies.\f*
\v 3 perhaps they had swallowed us alive: When their fury was angry against us, \f + \fr 123:3 \ft The word (perhaps) doth not here import a doubt, or uncertainty, but in modest manner of asseveration, leaveth he judgement of the event that should happen (if God did not protect his servants) to their own consideration: which is an usual phrase in most languages.\f* \f + \fr 123:3 \ft So suddenly should the weak, without God's protection be destroyed, as men are devoured & swallowed up by ravening wild beasts, even before they be throughly dead. So was Jonas swallowed into the whale's belly.\f*
\v 4 perhaps water had swallowed us. \f + \fr 123:4 \ft Furious persecution.\f*
\v 5 Our soul hath passed through a torrent: perhaps our soul had passed through an intolerable water. \f + \fr 123:5 \ft Sudden great troubles.\f*
\v 6 Blessed be our Lord which hath not given us for a prey to their teeth.
\v 7 Our soul as a sparrow is delivered from the snare of the fowlers: The snare is broken, and we are delivered. \f + \fr 123:7 \ft Man's subtlety often deceiveth another man, but there is no counsel able to circumvent God.\f*
\v 8 Our help is in the name of our Lord, who made heaven and earth.
\c 124
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. They that trust in our Lord, as mount Sion: he shall not be moved for ever that dwelleth \f + \fr 124:1 \ft Those that confidently trust in God, are in such security as is mount Sion, which is a hill, defended also with other hills round about.\f* \f + \fr 124:1 \ft Another thing required to this security, is to dwell within Jerusalem, not the terrestrial city, for (as S. Augustin observeth) the Jews that dwelt therein are destroyed or made captives, and hitherto rejected of God, but in the Catholic Church.\f*
\v 2 in Jerusalem. Mountains round about it: and our Lord round about his people, from hence forth now and for ever.
\v 3 Because our Lord will not leave the rod of sinners upon the lot of the just: that the just reach not their hands to iniquity. \f + \fr 124:3 \ft God will not always, nor finally leave his servants in tribulation, but only a while for their good.\f*
\v 4 Do well, o Lord, to the good, and right of heart. \f + \fr 124:4 \ft This prayer is also an asseveration, for it is certain that God will defend, and reward the good, and right of heart:\f*
\v 5 But those that decline into obligations, our Lord will bring with them that work iniquity: peace upon Israel. \f + \fr 124:5 \ft And no less assuredly God will punish not only the notorious wicked, and principal Authors of wickedness, but\f*
\c 125
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. When our Lord turned the captivity of Sion: we were made as men comforted. \f + \fr 125:1 \ft The Jews released from captivity, were exceedingly, and almost incredibly comforted, as men for great, and unexpected sudden joy, think it rather a dream than a truth that they are delivered from miseries. So S. Peter when he was delivered out of prison by an Angel, thought it rather a vision, than a true delivery.\f*
\v 2 Then was our mouth replenished with joy: and our tongue with exultation. Then shall they say among the Gentiles: Our Lord hath done magnifically with them. \f + \fr 125:2 \ft Whereas in the two former verses (and very commonly) the Prophet speaketh in the pretertense, for the assurance of that he foresheweth, as if it were already done, yet here he uttereth his Prophecy in the future tense, that the Gentiles will confess that God dealeth magnifically with his people.\f*
\v 3 Our Lord hath done magnifically with us: we are made joyful. \f + \fr 125:3 \ft The people also themselves gratefully confess that God dealeth magnifically with them.\f*
\v 4 Turn our captivity, o Lord, as a torrent in the South. \f + \fr 125:4 \ft The Prophet foreseeing all this in spirit, prayeth for the performance hereof.\f* \f + \fr 125:4 \ft And that it may speedily be done, as a torrent that runneth in the south part of the world, is commonly very great, much desired, but scarce expected.\f*
\v 5 They that sow in tears, shall reap in joyfulness. \f + \fr 125:5 \ft This is the ordinary disposition of God, that his servants shall make their seeding, which is, do good works (saith S. Augustin) with tears, in tribulation upon earth:\f* \f + \fr 125:5 \ft and reap a plentiful harvest, the reward of their suffering and well working, in the next life. In assured hope whereof the Psalmist, and the whole Church joyfully conclude this Psalm with the two verses following.\f*
\v 6 Going they went and wept, casting their seeds. But coming they shall come with exultation, carrying their sheaves.
\c 126
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle of Salomon. Unless our Lord build the house, they have laboured in vain that build it. Unless our Lord keep the city, he watcheth in vain that keepeth it. \f + \fr 126:1 \ft God not permitting David to build the Temple, promised that his son should build it, and therefore besides other good admonitions, given to his son Salomon, he\f* \f + \fr 126:1 \ft Unless God be the principal Angel, no work can prosper.\f*
\v 2 It is vain for you to rise before light: rise ye after ye have sitten, which eat the bread of sorrow. \f + \fr 126:2 \ft It is vain to attempt any thing without God's grace assisting:\f* \f + \fr 126:2 \ft they that so doing, & thinking they have done something, rest\f* \f + \fr 126:2 \ft after their painful travail, must rise again & begin anew, because that which they seem to have done well, is nothing worth, nor shall have reward.\f*
\v 3 When he shall give sleep to his beloved: behold the inheritance of our Lord are children: the reward, the fruit of the womb. \f + \fr 126:3 \ft Contrarywise where God giving grace, those that truly love him, do good works,\f* \f + \fr 126:3 \ft with great ease, and delight, as they take their sleep,\f* \f + \fr 126:3 \ft they merit inheritance in heaven,\f* \f + \fr 126:3 \ft for their good works.\f* \f + \fr 126:3 \ft The reward is promised to the true children of God, born to him in the womb of the Catholic Church.\f*
\v 4 As arrows in the hand of the mighty: so are the children of them that are shaken. \f + \fr 126:4 \ft Moreover as a strong archer striketh deep with his arrows; so they that patiently suffer much in this world,\f* \f + \fr 126:4 \ft do multiply good works.\f*
\v 5 Blessed is the man that hath filled his desire of them: he shall not be confounded when he shall speak to his enemies in the gate. \f + \fr 126:5 \ft Such shall be very happy,\f* \f + \fr 126:5 \ft & very easily answer all that can be objected against them\f* \f + \fr 126:5 \ft in the day of Judgement.\f*
\c 127
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. Blessed are all that fear our Lord, that walk in his ways.
\v 2 Because thou shalt eat the labours of thy hands: blessed art thou, and it shall be well with thee.
\v 3 Thy wife as a fruitful vine, in the sides of thy house. Thy children as young plants of olive-trees, round about thy table. \f + \fr 127:3 \ft If such servants of God be married, they shall ordinarily have issue, & succession in their family, but especially the souls of such shall bring forth many meritorious works,\f* \f + \fr 127:3 \ft in the bosom of the Catholic Church, which was founded in Christ's side.\f* \f + \fr 127:3 \ft Children also signify good works.\f*
\v 4 Behold so shall the man be blessed, that feareth our Lord.
\v 5 Our Lord out of Sion bless thee: and that thou mayst see the good things of Jerusalem all the days of thy life.
\v 6 And that thou mayst see thy children's children, peace upon Israel. \f + \fr 127:6 \ft Reward in heaven for good works in earth.\f*
\c 128
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. Often have they impugned me from my youth, let Israel now say: \f + \fr 128:1 \ft Israel which is the Church of God, rejoicing saith: that enemies have often,\f* \f + \fr 128:1 \ft even from the beginning of the world, persecuted me, as when Cain persecuted Abel, other wicked persecuted Seth, Enoch, Noe: the Chaldeas persecuted Abraham: the Ægyptians persecuted the Israelites: and so in other generations.\f*
\v 2 Often have they impugned me from my youth: but they have not prevailed against me. \f + \fr 128:2 \ft But they have never overcome me. So the Psalmist testifieth for all times past, & prophesieth the same for times to come.\f*
\v 3 Sinners have builded upon my back: they have prolonged their iniquity. \f + \fr 128:3 \ft Persecuters not being able to overthrow or suppress the Church, have laid great weighty burdens of tribulations upon her back, which she hath patiently and strongly borne,\f* \f + \fr 128:3 \ft they have still persisted, one sort after another, but with longanimity the Church hath stood fast, and constantly passed through all distresses. In moral sense sinners build iniquity upon the back of the Church, yea and upon God's back, when they presume to sin, trusting in the end to be absolved by virtue of holy Sacraments left in the Church. Likewise when they excuse their sins, imputing the cause to other creatures of God, whereby they are allured. Which is in effect (saith S. Augustin) to accuse God, and to build iniquities on God's back, who made those creatures.\f*
\v 4 Our just Lord will cut the necks of sinners: \f + \fr 128:4 \ft God therefore who is just, will at last cast such presumptuous sinners from his back, and break their stiff necks:\f*
\v 5 let them all be confounded and turned backward, that hate Sion. \f + \fr 128:5 \ft then shall they be confounded,\f* \f + \fr 128:5 \ft separated, eternally from God, become like fruitless and withered grass, cast away, despised, yea cursed of all, and blessed by none, as the Prophet denounceth in the next verses.\f*
\v 6 Let them be made as grass in the tops of houses: which is withered before it be plucked up.
\v 7 Whereof the reaper hath not filled his hand, and he that gathereth the sheaves his bosom.
\v 8 And they said not that passed by: The blessing of our Lord be upon you: we have blessed you in the name of our Lord.
\c 129
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. From the depths I have cried to thee, o Lord: \f + \fr 129:1 \ft This prayer agreeth to all true penitents, crying to God for help, being either in depth of sorrow for sin, and so it is one of the Penitential Psalms; or the depth of fervent desire to ascend towards perfection in virtue, and from this vale of misery into heaven, and so it is a Gradual Psalm; or in the depth of temporal pains, and so it is a special prayer for souls in Purgatory, offered by the Church in their behalf.\f*
\v 2 Lord hear my voice: Let thine ears be intent to the voice of my petition.
\v 3 If thou shalt observe iniquities, o Lord: Lord who shall sustain it? \f + \fr 129:3 \ft None is able to abide the rigour of God's justice.\f*
\v 4 Because with thee there is propitiation: and for thy law I have expected thee, o Lord. My soul hath expected in his word: \f + \fr 129:4 \ft But all must rely upon his mercy.\f* \f + \fr 129:4 \ft For thy promises made in the law, that thou wilt remit sins to the penitent, give more grace to them that seek it, and mitigate also the pains due for sins.\f*
\v 5 my soul hath hoped in our Lord.
\v 6 From the morning watch even until night: let Israel hope in our Lord. \f + \fr 129:6 \ft The hope of penitents is like to the watches of the day time, from morning until night, which are more comfortable than watches of the night:\f*
\v 7 Because with our Lord there is mercy: and with him plenteous redemption. \f + \fr 129:7 \ft The greatest comfort is in Christ our Redeemer, whose plentiful Redemption bringeth more aboundance of grace.\f*
\v 8 And he shall redeem Israel, from all his iniquities. \f + \fr 129:8 \ft Christ's Redemption being sufficient for all the world, is effectual only to true living members of the Catholic Church.\f*
\c 130
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle of David. Lord my heart is not exalted: neither are mine eyes lofty. Neither have I walked in great matters: nor in marvelous things above me. \f + \fr 130:1 \ft David by God's special grace having a sincere mind towards all men, even towards his enemies, and an humble heart, not desiring any thing ambitiously, but all to the honour of God, proposeth his own example, for others to imitate: that they may with him offer the sacrifice of humility and innocency unto God, from whom all good things proceed.\f* \f + \fr 130:1 \ft All this with a thankful mind to God who gave this grace.\f*
\v 2 If I was not humbly minded: but exalted my soul: As the weaned child is toward his mother, so retribution in my soul. \f + \fr 130:2 \ft As children after they are weaned come still willingly to their mother, so doth the child of God rely upon God's help, though he always feel not the same sweetness:\f* \f + \fr 130:2 \ft & according to his demeanor herein, he expecteth reward.\f*
\v 3 Let Israel hope in our Lord, from henceforth now and for ever. \f + \fr 130:3 \ft King David, or any other, being for his virtue advanced, & rewarded by God, is a good example to move others to do the like, so shall they receive like reward.\f*
\c 131
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. Remember David, o Lord, and all his meekness: \f + \fr 131:1 \ft It is an usual thing that David, Moyses, & other Prophets speak of themselves in the third person.\f*
\v 2 As he sware to our Lord, vowed a vow to the God of Jacob. \f + \fr 131:2 \ft King David desiring, and so far as lay in him, promising to build a Temple to God, with great instance prayeth that he might perform the same. But God disposing otherwise, that not he, but his son should build it, he nevertheless prepared the matter, workmen, and money, shewed the form, and disposed the Levites how to serve therein.\f*
\v 3 If I shall enter into the tabernacle of my house, if I shall ascend into the bed of my couch. \f + \fr 131:3 \ft Moreover by vow deprived himself of entering into his own house, or taking his ordinary rest, till he might (if it so pleased God) know the place where it should be built.\f*
\v 4 If I shall give sleep to mine eyes, and slumbering to mine eye lids:
\v 5 And rest to my temples: until I find a place for our Lord, a tabernacle for the God of Jacob.
\v 6 Behold we have heard of it in Ephrata: we have found it in the fields of the wood. \f + \fr 131:6 \ft It was revealed to David, that the Temple should be built in that part of Jerusalem, which looketh towards Bethleem (otherwise called Ephrata) where our Saviour was born.\f* \f + \fr 131:6 \ft Within Jerusalem, which is compassed with woods. In this vision also the whole form of the Temple was revealed unto him, as he testifieth. 1. Par. 28. v. 19. All things, quoth he, came written with the hand of our Lord unto me: that I might understand all the works of the pattern.\f*
\v 7 We will enter into his tabernacle: we will adore in the place where his feet stood. \f + \fr 131:7 \ft Holy David moved with exceeding devotion, repaired to the place, where God's Temple should be built,\f* \f + \fr 131:7 \ft & adored God, where the Propitiatory, as a footstool representing God's presence, should stand. What marvel then if devotion move Christians to visit the holy places, where our Saviour, God and Man was Incarnate, was born, suffered death, was buried, ascended into heaven, or any\f*
\v 8 Arise Lord into thy rest, thou, and the ark of thy sanctification. \f + \fr 131:8 \ft O God, leaving Silo, Gabaon, and the like places, come into thy holy Temple,\f* \f + \fr 131:8 \ft with the ark of covenant, where thou sanctifiest thy people. And here again the Prophet illuminated with a higher Mystery, and inflamed with more devotion, prayeth for Christ's coming into the world, and prophesieth that after his Passion he will rise, not only in glory of soul, but also of body, prefigured by the Ark of testimony, which was in the tabernacle, and after in the Temple.\f*
\v 9 Let thy Priests be clothed with justice: & let thy saints rejoice. \f + \fr 131:9 \ft Grant therefore that thy Priests, which must offer sacrifice in this sacred place, be endued with virtues, and good life worthy of their degree:\f* \f + \fr 131:9 \ft and the Levites who are ordained to serve there, be likewise made fit for their diverse functions, both in the old and new Testament.\f*
\v 10 For David thy servant's sake, turn not away the face of thy Christ. \f + \fr 131:10 \ft And seeing thou hast given such meekness, devotion, zeal, sincerity, and other virtues, making him a man according to thine own heart, and thereupon promised to establish his see,\f* \f + \fr 131:10 \ft defer not to send thy promised Messias, Christ our Redeemer.\f*
\v 11 Our Lord hath sworn truth to David, and he will not disappoint it: Of the fruit of thy womb I will set upon thy seat. \f + \fr 131:11 \ft Hence forth to the end of this Psalm the Prophet relateth God's revelation to him: That he hath truly promised with an oath,\f* \f + \fr 131:11 \ft and will perform,\f* \f + \fr 131:11 \ft to set one of David's sons upon his Throne: which was not only fulfilled in Salomon, who reigned in great peace, and builded the Temple, but especially in Christ the Son of David, to whom our Lord God gave the seat of David his father, & he shall reign in the house of Jacob for ever, and of his Kingdom there shall be no end. Luc. 1. v. 32. 33. By this promise Saint Peter also proveth Christ's Resurrection. Act. 2. v. 30.\f*
\v 12 If thy children shall keep my testament, and these my testimonies which I will teach them: Their children also even for ever, shall sit upon thy seat. \f + \fr 131:12 \ft Concerning the children of Christ, members of his Kingdom the Church, the promise is conditional, if they observe God's commandments, they shall sit upon his seat: be coheirs of his Kingdom. Rom. 8. v. 17.\f*
\v 13 Because our Lord hath chosen Sion: he hath chosen it for an habitation to himself.
\v 14 This is my rest for ever and ever: here will I dwell because I have chosen it. \f + \fr 131:14 \ft Sion, the Catholic Church, is a perpetual place where God dwelleth.\f*
\v 15 Blessing I will bless her widow: her poor I will fill with breads. \f + \fr 131:15 \ft The Church wanting Christ's visible presence, is replenished with many blessings,\f* \f + \fr 131:15 \ft and all her humble children are relieved with holy Sacraments.\f*
\v 16 Her Priests I will clothe with salvation: and her saints shall rejoice with joyfulness. \f + \fr 131:16 \ft The Church hath always some holy Priests\f* \f + \fr 131:16 \ft and some holy people.\f*
\v 17 Thither will I bring forth a horn to David, I have prepared a lamp to my Christ. \f + \fr 131:17 \ft Of this Church, elected by God, Christ is the Protector, and strong defence.\f* \f + \fr 131:17 \ft And the same Church shall be a perpetual lamp, whereby others may come to him.\f*
\v 18 His enemies I will clothe with confusion: but upon him shall my sanctification flourish.
\c 132
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle of David. Behold how good and how pleasant a thing it is, for brethren to dwell in one. \f + \fr 132:1 \ft David being a most peaceable man, even toward his enemies, is added by Esdras in this title, as an example for others to imitate.\f* \f + \fr 132:1 \ft That concord is both good and pleasant, needeth no other proof, but only to consider & to behold the fruit thereof in every community, and especially\f*
\v 2 As ointment on the head, which ran down upon the beard, the beard of Aaron, which ran down unto the hem of his garment. \f + \fr 132:2 \ft The ointment, wherewith Aaron and other High Priests were consecrated, was precious, and most odoriferous, signifying grace bought by Christ's blood, and producing virtues, which make sweet savour:\f* \f + \fr 132:2 \ft was poured upon the High Priest's head, who being head of the Church,\f* \f + \fr 132:2 \ft unity and concord descended from him to other Priests,\f* \f + \fr 132:2 \ft and so to the people, even to the lowest and meanest in God's Church.\f*
\v 3 As the dew of Hermon, which runneth down upon mount Sion. Because there hath our Lord commanded blessing, and life even for ever. \f + \fr 132:3 \ft Another similitude to declare the excellency of concord: As the dew of mount Hermon, which is perpetually covered with snow, that falleth from the heaven, thence descending refresheth & fructifieth the hill of Sion: so mutual concord, and fraternal charity amongst the faithful, nourisheth each other, making them fruitful in all good works.\f* \f + \fr 132:3 \ft Where there is unity God giveth aboundance of grace, as where the Apostles with other faithful were gathered, and continued in prayer, the Holy Ghost came upon them all. And the multitude of believers (then increasing) had one heart and one soul. Act. 2. & 4. v. 32.\f*
\c 133
\p
\v 1 Agradual Canticle. Lo now bless our Lord, all ye the servants of our Lord: Which stand in the house of our Lord, in the courts of the house of our God. \f + \fr 133:1 \ft This last Gradual Psalm, as a conclusion exhorteth all to praise God.\f*
\v 2 In the nights lift up your hands unto the holy places, and bless ye our Lord.
\v 3 Our Lord out of Sion bless thee, who made heaven and earth. \f + \fr 133:3 \ft For to this end he made all creatures in heaven & in earth.\f*
\c 134
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Praise ye the name of our Lord, ye servants praise our Lord. \f + \fr 134:1 \ft God's servants.\f*
\v 2 Ye that stand in the house of our Lord, in the courts of the house of our God. \f + \fr 134:2 \ft Clergy that serve in the Temple,\f* \f + \fr 134:2 \ft and ye Laity that attend to his service, must praise him for these causes.\f*
\v 3 Praise ye our Lord, because our Lord is good: sing ye to his name, because it is sweet. \f + \fr 134:3 \ft his goodness.\f* \f + \fr 134:3 \ft his benignity.\f*
\v 4 Because our Lord hath chosen Jacob to himself, Israel for his own possession. \f + \fr 134:4 \ft He hath adopted us his children.\f*
\v 5 Because I have known that our Lord is great, and our God above all gods. \f + \fr 134:5 \ft He is omnipotent, as appeareth by his works, here and elsewhere recited: and many ways known to the world.\f*
\v 6 All things whatsoever our Lord would he hath done, in heaven, in earth, in the sea, and in all the depths.
\v 7 Bring forth clouds from the uttermost of the earth: lightnings he hath turned into rain. Who bringeth forth the winds out of his treasures:
\v 8 who struck the first begotten of Ægypt from man even to beast.
\v 9 He sent forth signs and wonders in the midst of thee, o Ægypt: upon Pharao, and upon all his servants.
\v 10 Who struck many nations: and slew strong kings:
\v 11 Sehon the king of the Amorrheites, & Og the king of Basan, and all the Kingdoms of Chanaan.
\v 12 And he gave their land for inheritance, for an inheritance to Israel his people.
\v 13 Lord thy name is for ever: Lord thy memorial is unto generation and generation.
\v 14 Because our Lord shall judge his people: and will be entreated toward his servants.
\v 15 The idols of the Gentiles are silver, and gold, the works of men's hands.
\v 16 They have mouth, & shall not speak: they have eyes, and shall not see.
\v 17 They have ears, and shall not hear: for neither is there breath in their mouth.
\v 18 Let them that make them become like to them: and all that have confidence in them.
\v 19 Ye house of Israel bless our Lord: ye house of Aaron bless our Lord.
\v 20 Ye house of Levi bless our Lord: you that fear our Lord, bless ye our Lord.
\v 21 Blessed be our Lord out of Sion, who dwelleth in Jerusalem.
\c 135
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Confess ye to our Lord because he is good: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 135:1 \ft Whose goodness is incomparable.\f* \f + \fr 135:1 \ft This second part of every verse, first pronounced by the Priests, confessing & praising God's mercy above all his works, was still repeated by musicians, or other assistants, in manner as now in Litanies (o Lord deliver us) and (We beseech thee to hear us.) And as Gloria Patri, &c. is added in the end of Psalms, and our Lord's prayer, and the Angelical salutation are often repeated in diverse Offices, and in the Rosary.\f*
\v 2 Confess ye to the God of gods: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 135:2 \ft Whose divine power created all other things.\f*
\v 3 Confess ye to the Lord of lords: because his mercy is for ever \f + \fr 135:3 \ft By this invitation to praise our Lord God, thrice repeated, we profess the Blessed Trinity, who is one God in substance, and three Divine Persons.\f* \f + \fr 135:3 \ft Whose dominion is over all the world.\f*
\v 4 Who only doth great marvels: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 135:4 \ft Only God can do true miracles; to wit, works above the course of all nature.\f*
\v 5 Who made the heaven in understanding: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 135:5 \ft In admirable wisdom.\f*
\v 6 Who established the earth over the waters: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 135:6 \ft Made the waters above nature to remain within their bonds, & not to cover the earth.\f*
\v 7 Who made the great lights: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 8 The sun to rule the day: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 9 The moon and stars to rule the night: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 10 Who struck Ægypt with their first-begotten: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 11 Who brought forth Israel out of the midst of them: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 12 In a mighty hand, and lofty arm: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 13 Who divided the Red sea into divisions: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 14 And brought forth Israel through the midst thereof: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 15 And he overthrew Pharao, and his host in the Red sea: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 16 Who led his people through the desert: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 17 Who struck great kings: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 18 And slew strong kings: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 19 Sehon the king of the Amorrheites: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 20 And Og the king of Basan: because his mercy is for ever:
\v 21 And he gave their land for an inheritance: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 22 For an inheritance to Israel his servant: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 23 For in our humiliation he was mindful of us: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 24 And he redeemed us from our enemies: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 25 Who giveth food to all flesh: because his mercy is for ever. \f + \fr 135:25 \ft All God's benignity, as well of particular benefits towards his people, as general to them and all others, proceedeth from his mercy.\f*
\v 26 Confess ye to the God of heaven: because his mercy is for ever. Confess ye to the Lord of lords: because his mercy is for ever.
\c 136
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of David for Jeremy. Upon the rivers of Babylon, there we sat and wept: whilst we remembered Sion. \f + \fr 136:1 \ft By adding to this title (for Jeremy) the Septuagint Interpreters signify that this Psalm treateth of the same captivity, in which Jeremias writ his Lamentations.\f* \f + \fr 136:1 \ft Near the rivers in Chaldea, whereof Babylon was the head city,\f* \f + \fr 136:1 \ft the Jews remained mourning,\f* \f + \fr 136:1 \ft remembering the holy rites and service of God, which had been in Sion, whereof they were deprived in the captivity.\f*
\v 2 On the willows in the midst thereof, we hanged up our instruments. \f + \fr 136:2 \ft All their musical instruments, as having no use of them.\f*
\v 3 Because there they that led us captive, demanded of us words of songs. And they that led us away: Sing ye an hymn to us of the songs of Sion. \f + \fr 136:3 \ft Either in earnest or in scorn the Chaldees willed them to sing, as they were accustomed in their country.\f*
\v 4 How shall we sing the song of our Lord in a strange land? \f + \fr 136:4 \ft They excused themselves, and refused to sing sacred Psalms before profane people, neither had they mind to sing in that mourning state of captivity.\f*
\v 5 If I shall forget thee, o Jerusalem, let my right hand be forgotten. \f + \fr 136:5 \ft The people shew not only their fervent present desire to serve God in Jerusalem, but also their firm purpose still to desire the same, wishing that if they forget it, or lose this affection, their right hands, or what soever is most dear, or necessary for them, may be forgotten, not conserved, but suffered to perish.\f*
\v 6 Let my tongue cleave to my jaws, if I do not remember thee: If I shall not set Jerusalem in the beginning of my joy. \f + \fr 136:6 \ft If I lose this affection, let me also lose the use of my tongue.\f*
\v 7 Be mindful, o Lord, of the children of Edom, in the day of Jerusalem: That say: Rase it, rase it, even unto the foundation thereof. \f + \fr 136:7 \ft The Idumeans incensed the Chaldees to be cruel against the Jews, whereof they pray for just revenge, and withal the Psalmist prophesieth that it will be revenged, which Isaias also prophesieth, c. 21. v. 11.\f* \f + \fr 136:7 \ft for their rejoicing in Jerusalem's misery.\f* \f + \fr 136:7 \ft The voice of the Idumeans, inciting the Babylonians utterly to destroy Jerusalem.\f*
\v 8 Daughter of Babylon miserable: blessed is he, that shall repay thee thy payment, which thou hast payed us. \f + \fr 136:8 \ft A Prophecy that the people of Babylon should also be punished, for their cruelty against the Jews, whereof Isaias\f*
\v 9 Blessed is he that shall hold, and shall dash thy little ones against the rock. \f + \fr 136:9 \ft God will bless, or reward them that shall severely afflict the Babylonians,\f* \f + \fr 136:9 \ft not sparing their children. Morally he is blessed, that mortifieth his own passions, cutteth off first ill motions, or punisheth venial sins, that they grow not strong within his soul, and so draw it to commit mortal sin. S. Aug. hic, & S. Greg. in fine expos. Psal. 4. pænit.\f*
\c 137
\p
\v 1 To David himself. I will confess to thee, o Lord, in my whole heart: because thou hast heard the words of my mouth. In the sight of Angels I will sing to thee: \f + \fr 137:1 \ft This Psalm is a fit form of thanks for David, or any other servant of God.\f* \f + \fr 137:1 \ft Iwill render thanks and praise.\f* \f + \fr 137:1 \ft God ever heareth the prayer that is rightly made, for which the suppliant is therefore to give thanks.\f* \f + \fr 137:1 \ft Angels are present where the faithful pray, observe our prayers, and offer them to God, if they be sincere, as the prayers of Tobias, and Cornelius.\f*
\v 2 I will adore toward thy holy temple, and will confess to thy name: For thy mercy, and thy truth: because thou hast magnified above every thing thy holy name. \f + \fr 137:2 \ft When there was not access to the Temple, yet the Jews praying in captivity, turned themselves towards the Temple.\f* \f + \fr 137:2 \ft The Name and Majesty of GOD, the WORD (which is the Son of God) also the name of JESUS, is magnified above all names, or temporal things.\f* \f + \fr 137:2 \ft 1. Cor. v. 10. Tob. 12. Act. 10. Psal. 24. v. 10.\f*
\v 3 In what day soever I shall invocate thee, hear me: thou wilt multiply strength in my soul.
\v 4 Let all the kings of the earth, o Lord, confess to thee: because they have heard all the words of thy mouth: \f + \fr 137:4 \ft Sooner or later Kings and Princes of all Kingdoms and nations, have been or shall be connected to Christ.\f*
\v 5 And let them sing in the ways of our Lord: because great is the glory of our Lord.
\v 6 Because our Lord is high, and he beholdeth low things: and high things he knoweth far off. \f + \fr 137:6 \ft God knoweth proud men, not as his friends or servants, but far off, as strangers and enemies.\f*
\v 7 If I shall walk in the midst of tribulation, thou wilt quicken me: and upon the wrath of mine enemies thou hast extended thy hand, and thy right hand hath saved me.
\v 8 Our Lord will repay for me: o Lord thy mercy is for ever: despise not the works of thy hands.
\c 138
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm of David. Lord thou hast proved me, and hast known me: \f + \fr 138:1 \ft By this part of the title (to the end) is signified (as is noted Psal. 4.) that the matter contained in the Psalm, pertaineth to the new Testament.\f* \f + \fr 138:1 \ft God who knoweth all things most absolutely and perfectly, without discourse or searching, yet as it were, maketh experimental trial of his servants, to make them in some sort to know him, and to know themselves. And so here holy David or other faithful man, acknowledgeth God's Omniscience, that is, perfect knowledge of all things, without exception, past,\f*
\v 2 thou hast known my sitting down, and my rising up.
\v 3 Thou hast understood my cogitations far off: my path, and my cord thou hast searched out. \f + \fr 138:3 \ft The uttermost measure and reach of mine intention.\f*
\v 4 And thou hast foreseen all my ways: because there is not a word in my tongue. \f + \fr 138:4 \ft The word holden in by the tongue, and not uttered by mouth, is not hidden from God.\f*
\v 5 Behold, o Lord, thou hast known all the last things, & them of old: thou hast formed me, and hast put thy hand upon me.
\v 6 Thy knowledge is become marvelous of me: it is made great, and I cannot reach to it. \f + \fr 138:6 \ft By experience we see that God's knowledge exceedeth our reach.\f*
\v 7 Whither shall I go from thy spirit? And whither shall I fly from thy face? \f + \fr 138:7 \ft As God's knowledge comprehendeth all things, so his presence extendeth itself to all places, neither is contained in place, but exceedeth all place, in his divine immensity.\f*
\v 8 If I shall ascend into heaven, thou art there: if I descend into hell, thou art present.
\v 9 If I shall take my wings early, and dwell in the extreme parts of the sea.
\v 10 Certes thither also shall thy hand conduct me: and thy right hand shall hold me.
\v 11 And I said: Perhaps darkness shall tread over me: and the night is mine illumination in my delights. \f + \fr 138:11 \ft The Prophet also in the person of any curious imaginative man, examineth and findeth that no darkness nor cover can hide any thing from God.\f*
\v 12 For darkness shall not be darkened from thee, and the night shall be lightened as the day: as the darkness thereof, so also the light thereof.
\v 13 Because thou hast possessed my reins: thou hast received me from my mother's womb. \f + \fr 138:13 \ft Nothing seemeth more hidden, than a man's entrails,\f* \f + \fr 138:13 \ft or a child in the mother's womb.\f*
\v 14 I will confess to thee, because thou art terribly magnified: thy works are marvelous, & my soul knoweth exceedingly.
\v 15 My bone is not hid from thee, which thou madest in secret: and my substance in the lower parts of the earth. \f + \fr 138:15 \ft Or bones in the flesh.\f*
\v 16 Mine imperfection thine eyes have seen, & in thy book all shall be written: days shall be formed, & no man in them. \f + \fr 138:16 \ft Or man's bodily imperfection before his birth,\f* \f + \fr 138:16 \ft daily formed by God, not by man. Job. 10. v. 8. 2. Mac. 7. v. 22. 23.\f* \f + \fr 138:16 \ft Colem, Embryonem.\f* \f + \fr 138:16 \ft Of knowledge.\f*
\v 17 But to me thy friends, o God, are become honourable exceedingly: their principality is exceedingly strengthened. \f + \fr 138:17 \ft Above all considerations it most exceedeth, that God so high and infinite, honoureth his humble poor servants so exceedingly, that it seemeth to themselves far more than can be due. For he rewardeth even over & above merits; which merits also are founded in God's mercy given without merit.\f* \f + \fr 138:17 \ft New translaters pervert this place, translating (thoughts) for (friends) contrary to the Hebrew, Greek, and Latin, and all ancient Fathers, only pretending that the same word in the Chaldee tongue also signifieth thoughts.\f*
\v 18 I will number them, and they shall be multiplied above the sand: I rose up and I am yet with thee. \f + \fr 138:18 \ft The number also of Saints whom God hath chosen, called, justified and will glorify, exceed man's conceit. Apoc. 7.\f* \f + \fr 138:18 \ft Incensed with this excellent glory, and desiring to be of this innumerable multitude, by thy grace I have risen from sin, and in confidence of thy perpetual help, I stand and hope to persevere in thy service.\f*
\v 19 If thou shalt kill sinners, o God: ye men of blood depart from me. \f + \fr 138:19 \ft And if it be so, yea seeing it is so, that as thou, o God, doest exalt thy Saints to exceeding and unspeakable honour: so thou hast also decreed to punish obstinate sinners with eternal death and damnation:\f* \f + \fr 138:19 \ft Irenounce all wicked association, get ye away from me all cruel bloody men, that would draw me into everlasting torments.\f*
\v 20 Because you say in thought: they shall receive thy cities in vain. \f + \fr 138:20 \ft Away from me, you that think,\f* \f + \fr 138:20 \ft the glorious mansions in heaven, prepared and promised to the just, are vain hopes, and in vain expected.\f*
\v 21 Did not I hate them that hate thee, o Lord: and pined away because of thine enemies? \f + \fr 138:21 \ft This hate of such sinners the just shall confidently plead, and happy are they that shall be able truly to allege for themselves in the day of judgement, that they hated all, whom God hateth,\f* \f + \fr 138:21 \ft yea hated them with fervent zeal, that are God's enemies.\f*
\v 22 with perfect hatred did I hate them: they are become enemies to me. \f + \fr 138:22 \ft Still the Prophet inculcateth this necessary perfect hatred\f* \f + \fr 138:22 \ft and enmity towards God's enemies.\f*
\v 23 Prove me, o God, and know my heart: examine me, and know my paths. \f + \fr 138:23 \ft For that none in this life (without special and extraordinary revelation) knoweth certainly their own state, whether they be worthy of God's love or hatred (Eccle. 9.) the just submit themselves to God's examination of their heart and actions:\f*
\v 24 And see, if the way of iniquity be in me: and conduct me in the everlasting way. \f + \fr 138:24 \ft Humbly praying God, that if they be in the way of iniquity,\f* \f + \fr 138:24 \ft he will vouchsafe to reduce and guide them into the right way of everlasting life.\f*
\c 139
\p
\v 1 Unto the end, a Psalm of David.
\v 2 Deliver me, o Lord, from the evil man: from the unjust man rescue me.
\v 3 Which have devised iniquity in their heart: all the day they did appoint battles. They have whet their tongues as that of a serpent: \f + \fr 139:3 \ft Unquiet evil disposed, men still devise wicked plots\f* \f + \fr 139:3 \ft and never cease to make discord and debates.\f*
\v 4 the venom of asps is under their lips.
\v 5 Keep me, o Lord, from the hand of the sinner: and from unjust men deliver me.
\v 6 Who have devised to supplant my steps: the proud have hid a snare for me: And they have stretched out ropes for a snare: they have laid a stumbling block for me near the way. \f + \fr 139:6 \ft Scandalum.\f*
\v 7 I said to our Lord: Thou art my God: hear, o Lord, the voice of my petition. \f + \fr 139:7 \ft In time of tentation prayer is most necessary.\f*
\v 8 O Lord, Lord the strength of my salvation: thou hast overshadowed my head in the day of battle. \f + \fr 139:8 \ft Man is not able to resist tentations,\f* \f + \fr 139:8 \ft unless God by his grace, as by a helmet, defend him from yielding consent.\f*
\v 9 Yield me not, o Lord, from my desire to the sinner: they have devised against me, forsake me not, lest they perhaps be proud. \f + \fr 139:9 \ft Suffer me not to fall from that which I now desire (which is to be constant in virtue) not to consent to sinners' persuasions.\f* \f + \fr 139:9 \ft Who then would triumph over me.\f*
\v 10 The head of their compass: the labour of their lips shall cover them. \f + \fr 139:10 \ft The sum of their mischievous devices,\f* \f + \fr 139:10 \ft consisting in their subtle persuasions with sweet words,\f* \f + \fr 139:10 \ft shall overwhelm, and bring themselves to perdition.\f*
\v 11 Coals shall fall upon them, thou shalt cast them down into fire: in miseries they shall not stand up. \f + \fr 139:11 \ft Hell fire shall be their lot,\f* \f + \fr 139:11 \ft into which they shall fall,\f* \f + \fr 139:11 \ft & ever be in intolerable torments.\f*
\v 12 Aman full of tongue shall not be directed in the earth: evils shall take the unjust man into destruction.
\v 13 I have known that our Lord will do the judgment of the needy: and the revenge of the poor. \f + \fr 139:13 \ft Ihave learned by good instructions, and by experience, that in the end thou, o God, wilt comfort the just, who are now afflicted, and punish the unjust, that live in temporal delights, as it happened to Lazarus and the glutton.\f*
\v 14 But as for the just, they shall confess to thy name: and the righteous shall dwell with thy countenance. \f + \fr 139:14 \ft Eternal glory consisteth in seeing God.\f*
\c 140
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of David. Lord I have cried to thee, hear me: attend to my voice when I shall cry to thee.
\v 2 Let my prayer be directed as incense in thy sight: the elevation of my hands as evening sacrifice. \f + \fr 140:2 \ft As the fume of incense is sweet and ascendeth upwards: so the Church prayeth that her petitions may be grateful, and ascend to God.\f* \f + \fr 140:2 \ft In the old testament morning sacrifice was rather more solemn, and more frequent, but the Prophet seemeth to allude unto Christ's Sacrifice, which he was to offer towards evening on the Cross; and the same also in unbloody manner, the evening before his Passion, in the Eucharist.\f* \f + \fr 140:2 \ft In these words the Church prayeth, offering incense in her solemn Offices.\f*
\v 3 Set o Lord a watch to my mouth: and a door round about to my lips. \f + \fr 140:3 \ft Ajust care and consideration what to speak, before the mouth be opened.\f* \f + \fr 140:3 \ft Lips must not be always stopt, for it is a sin sometimes not to speak, but as a door that is to be opened and shut at due seasons, for example, opened to confess our sins, and God's truth.\f*
\v 4 Decline not my heart into words of malice, to make excuses in sins. With men that work iniquity: and I will not communicate with the chief of them. \f + \fr 140:4 \ft Shut from words of malice, and from excusing sins committed.\f*
\v 5 The just shall rebuke me in mercy, and shall reprehend me: but let not the oil of a sinner fat my head. Because yet also my prayer is in their good pleasures: \f + \fr 140:5 \ft Admonition of the just is a profitable reprehension,\f* \f + \fr 140:5 \ft but the fawning of flatterers is pernicious.\f* \f + \fr 140:5 \ft The Church ceaseth not to pray for sinners,\f* \f + \fr 140:5 \ft though as yet they take pleasure in their sins,\f*
\v 6 their judges are swallowed up joined to the rock. They shall hear my words because they have prevailed: \f + \fr 140:6 \ft but the very chiefest of them, which seem most potent, if they remain obstinate to their death, shall then perish, as men thrown against rocks.\f* \f + \fr 140:6 \ft They shall then hear and understand, that the prayers of the Church\f* \f + \fr 140:6 \ft are effectual, obtaining grace of constancy to her children, not to fear any persecution, nor any kind of death; obtaining also justification of their cause, when the persecuters shall see that the words and doctrine of the Church are true, and prevail in true judgement, as true, modest, peaceable, not seditious, turbulent, nor against the commonwealth.\f*
\v 7 as the grossness of the earth is broken out upon the earth. Our bones are dissipated near to hell: \f + \fr 140:7 \ft As much earth sticking together is made fruitful by breaking it into small mould, so the children of the Church by persecution bring forth more fruit than before, S. Aug.\f* \f + \fr 140:7 \ft Some persecuters are so cruel as to rage against the bones, and other relics of Martyrs,\f* \f + \fr 140:7 \ft casting them into the vilest places they can, willing if they could to throw them into hell,\f*
\v 8 for to thee, o Lord, Lord are mine eyes; in thee have I hoped, take not away my soul. \f + \fr 140:8 \ft but the Church and all her members repose confidence in God.\f* \f + \fr 140:8 \ft * life.\f*
\v 9 Keep me from the snare, which they have set for me: and from the scandals of them that work iniquity. \f + \fr 140:9 \ft Therefore she prayeth that her children be not entrapped by guileful deceits,\f* \f + \fr 140:9 \ft nor overthrown by any stumbling block cast in their way.\f*
\v 10 Sinners shall fall in his net: I am alone until I pass. \f + \fr 140:10 \ft In the end all persecuters and other wicked shall be caught in their own net of perdition,\f* \f + \fr 140:10 \ft the Church is\f*
\c 141
\p
\v 1 Of understanding to David, when he was in the cave, a prayer. \f + \fr 141:1 \ft This Psalm in form of a prayer, sheweth what cogitations David had in extreme danger.\f*
\v 2 With my voice I have cried to our Lord: with my voice I have prayed to our Lord: \f + \fr 141:2 \ft Not with exterior voice, for so he should have detected himself, but with fervour of spirit.\f*
\v 3 I pour out my prayer in his sight, and I pronounce my tribulation before him.
\v 4 When my spirit faileth of myself, and thou hast known my paths. In this way, which I walked, they hid a snare for me. \f + \fr 141:4 \ft When by reason of extremity I was not able to think how to help myself,\f* \f + \fr 141:4 \ft thou o God knowing my actions and demeanor, didst deliver me.\f*
\v 5 I looked toward the right hand, and saw: and there was none that would know me. Flight hath failed me: and there is none to require my soul. \f + \fr 141:5 \ft Ilooked for help,\f* \f + \fr 141:5 \ft and diligently looked about me,\f* \f + \fr 141:5 \ft but none would seem to know me, when I required their help.\f* \f + \fr 141:5 \ft Endeavouring to save myself by flight, I found no secure place, for being in a cave or hole of a mountain, the whole army besieged me; all seek to take away my life, none to save it.\f*
\v 6 I have cried to thee, o Lord, I have said: Thou art my hope, my portion in the land of the living. \f + \fr 141:6 \ft Thus left desolate of all man's help, and destitute of all worldly shift, I cried to thee, o Lord,\f* \f + \fr 141:6 \ft my only hopeful refuge,\f* \f + \fr 141:6 \ft neither do I desire to live for any worldly respect, but having chosen thee, o God, for my portion, and inheritance,\f* \f + \fr 141:6 \ft Idesire to be out of this desert place, and to be in the land, where is right use of religious divine service.\f*
\v 7 Attend to my petition: because I am humbled exceedingly. Deliver me from them that persecute me: because they are made strong over me. \f + \fr 141:7 \ft Afflicted.\f*
\v 8 Bring forth my soul out of prison, to confess unto thy name: the just expect me, till thou reward me. \f + \fr 141:8 \ft David's desire of liberty, was especially to this end; that he might have convenient place, and other means to serve and praise God:\f* \f + \fr 141:8 \ft the good, and well disposed people of Israel, cannot now serve thee as they desire, but expect me,\f* \f + \fr 141:8 \ft whom thou, o Lord, wilt advance to the Kingdom, that then we may serve thee more freely and more commodiously. All this happened in figure of Christ, of whom prophetically S. Augustin, S. Hilary, Cassianus, Cassiodorus, and others expound the whole Psalm.\f*
\c 142
\p
\v 0 to be speedily delivered; 11. and confidently assureth \add himself thereof.\add* \f + \fr 142:0 \ft The seventh penitential Psalm. The 7. key.\f*
\v 1 A Psalm of David, when Absalom his son persecuted him. Lord hear my prayer: with thine ears receive my petition in thy truth: hear me in thy justice. \f + \fr 142:1 \ft God having so promised is bound by his truth\f* \f + \fr 142:1 \ft and his justice, to hear penitents praying for remission of sins.\f*
\v 2 And enter not into judgment with thy servant: because no man living shall be justified in thy sight. \f + \fr 142:2 \ft Deal not with me in rigor of justice,\f* \f + \fr 142:2 \ft for no mortal man is able of himself to be justified, abstracting from God's mercy.\f*
\v 3 Because the enemy hath persecuted my soul: he hath humbled my life in the earth. He hath set me in obscure places as the dead of the world: \f + \fr 142:3 \ft Sought my life,\f* \f + \fr 142:3 \ft and brought it into great danger. Spiritually, the devil as a roaring lion still seeking whom he may devour, hath tempted me vehemently.\f* \f + \fr 142:3 \ft Iam pressed with great calamities, temporal or spiritual.\f*
\v 4 and my spirit is in anguish upon me, within me my heart is troubled.
\v 5 I was mindful of old days, I have meditated in all thy works: in the facts of thy hands did I meditate. \f + \fr 142:5 \ft In this case I consider, how God hath heretofore shewed his goodness towards me and others.\f*
\v 6 I have stretched forth my hands to thee: my soul is as earth without water unto thee. \f + \fr 142:6 \ft Stretching forth hands a ceremony in prayer, whereby the suppliant is made more attentive, and also endureth some pain for part of satisfaction.\f* \f + \fr 142:6 \ft Man's mind without God's illumination is dry and barren.\f*
\v 7 Hear me quickly, o Lord: my spirit hath fainted. Turn not away thy face from me: and I shall be like to them that descend into the lake. \f + \fr 142:7 \ft In great tentations God's grace and help is more presently needful to prevent our weakness, lest we yield consent.\f* \f + \fr 142:7 \ft If God leave man without special and continual grace, he will fall\f* \f + \fr 142:7 \ft into sin, as into a deep lake from whence without help he cannot rise up again.\f*
\v 8 Make me hear thy mercy in the morning: because I have hoped in thee. Make the way known to me, wherein I may walk: because I have lifted up my soul to thee. \f + \fr 142:8 \ft In the first assault of tentation.\f* \f + \fr 142:8 \ft Seeing by thy grace I have begun to pray unto thee.\f*
\v 9 Deliver me from mine enemies, o Lord, to thee I have fled:
\v 10 teach me to do thy will, because thou art my God. Thy good spirit will conduct me into the right way: \f + \fr 142:10 \ft The penitent thus humbling himself and praying may assuredly trust that God doth remit his sins by the holy Sacraments, and justifieth him, protecteth him, and will bring him out of all dangers of spiritual or temporal enemies.\f*
\v 11 for thy name sake, o Lord, thou wilt quicken me in thine equity. Thou wilt bring forth my soul out of tribulation:
\v 12 and in thy mercy thou wilt destroy mine enemies. And thou wilt destroy all that afflict my soul: because I am thy servant.
\c 143
\p
\v 1 A Psalm of David, against Goliath. Blessed be our Lord my God, who teacheth my hands to battle, and my fingers to war. \f + \fr 143:1 \ft Because this was David's first, and a very notable victory, the Septuagint Interpreters make mention of Goliath in this title.\f* \f + \fr 143:1 \ft God made David a warrior, and victorer against Goliath, without any former training in arms.\f*
\v 2 My mercy, and my refuge: my defender, and my deliverer. My protector; and I have hoped in him, who subdueth my people under me. \f + \fr 143:2 \ft Made him afterwards King of a great people.\f*
\v 3 Lord what is man, that thou art made known to him? Or the son of man, that thou esteemest him? \f + \fr 143:3 \ft All mankind was unworthy before Christ,\f* \f + \fr 143:3 \ft That God should be revealed unto them,\f* \f + \fr 143:3 \ft especially that he should have care of the progeny of men, after their sin.\f*
\v 4 Man is made like to vanity: his days pass as a shadow. \f + \fr 143:4 \ft Indeed man in himself, in his own nature and frailty, is but a vain and transitory creature, passing from life to death, as a shadow that cannot consist of itself, neither can man without God.\f*
\v 5 Lord incline thy heavens, and descend: touch the mountains, and they will smoke. \f + \fr 143:5 \ft By a poetical description he prayeth for God's help, as if God should make the heavens to bow, and so descend; or make the mountains smoke, as when Moyses received the law; or declare himself by Meteors, as followeth:\f*
\v 6 Lighten lightning, and thou shalt disperse them: shoot out thine arrows, and thou shalt destroy them.
\v 7 Send forth thy hand from on high, take me out, and deliver me from many waters: from the hand of children strangers. \f + \fr 143:7 \ft Tribulations or tentations.\f* \f + \fr 143:7 \ft Children of the Church,\f* \f + \fr 143:7 \ft but of evil life.\f*
\v 8 Whose mouth hath spoken vanity: and their right hand is the right hand of iniquity. \f + \fr 143:8 \ft They speak in vanity that promise to keep God's law, and perform it not.\f*
\v 9 O God I will sing to thee a new song: in the psalter of ten strings, I will sing to thee. \f + \fr 143:9 \ft In that principal instrument, apt for a new song, and for extraordinary benefits.\f*
\v 10 Who givest salvation to kings: who hast redeemed David thy servant from the malignant sword:
\v 11 deliver me. And rescue me out of the hand of children strangers, whose mouth hath spoken vanity: and their right hand, is the right hand of iniquity. \f + \fr 143:11 \ft Both Jews & Christians that live not well, are as strangers that frame to themselves such as false felicity, as is here described: making riches or worldly pleasures their God.\f*
\v 12 Whose sons, are as new plants in their youth. Their daughters comely trimmed: decked about after the similitude of a temple.
\v 13 Their store-houses full, flowing out of this into that. Their ewes full of young, abounding in their going forth:
\v 14 their oxen are fat. There is no ruin of wall, nor passage, nor cry in their streets. \f + \fr 143:14 \ft * transmigration.\f*
\v 15 They have said, that it is a happy people, which hath these things: blessed is the people, whose God is our Lord. \f + \fr 143:15 \ft True happiness consisteth not in worldly things.\f* \f + \fr 143:15 \ft But in preferring God before all.\f*
\c 144
\p
\v 1 Praising, to David himself. I will exalt thee my God the King: and I will bless thy name for ever and for ever. \f + \fr 144:1 \ft By this title Esdras signifieth that the Holy Ghost, who indited all the Psalms to God's praise, more specially in these seven last suggested to David, & by him to all God's servants, that all their other service must ten and be directed to the praise of God: and that therein we must continue, and finally rest, as in the sabbath of the seventh day, signified (as S. Beda supposeth) by these seven last Psalms of praise, eternally praising our Lord God. For\f* \f + \fr 144:1 \ft King is the proper epitheton of Christ, the Son of God, to whom, in his humanity, God the Father promised the Church of all nations for his kingdom. Psal. 2. in whom also the whole Blessed Trinity is praised.\f* \f + \fr 144:1 \ft All the time of this world they praise God,\f* \f + \fr 144:1 \ft & after in eternity.\f*
\v 2 Every day will I bless thee: and will praise thy name for ever, and for ever and ever.
\v 3 Great is our Lord and exceeding laudable, and of his greatness there is no end.
\v 4 Generation and generation shall praise thy works: and they shall pronounce thy power.
\v 5 They shall speak the magnificence of the glory of thy holiness: and shall tell thy marvelous works.
\v 6 And they shall tell the force of thy terrible things: and shall declare thy greatness: \f + \fr 144:6 \ft Of wonderful and miraculous things, which strike terror into men's minds.\f*
\v 7 They shall utter the memory of the aboundance of thy sweetness: and in thy justice they shall rejoice.
\v 8 Our Lord is pitiful and merciful: patient and very merciful.
\v 9 Our Lord is sweet to all: and his commiserations are over all his works. \f + \fr 144:9 \ft The effects of God's mercy in redeeming, and recalling sinners, are eminent above all other works.\f*
\v 10 Let all thy works, o Lord, confess to thee: and let thy Saints bless thee. \f + \fr 144:10 \ft Therefore the sanctified have special cause to praise\f*
\v 11 They shall tell the glory of thy kingdom: and shall speak thy might.
\v 12 That they may make thy might known to the children of men: and the glory of the magnificence of thy kingdom.
\v 13 Thy kingdom is a kingdom of all worlds: and thy dominion in all generation and generation. Our Lord is faithful in all his words, and holy in all his works. \f + \fr 144:13 \ft Christ's kingdom the militant Church is magnified, but much more the triumphant which is eternal.\f*
\v 14 Our Lord lifteth up all that fall: and setteth up all that are bruised. \f + \fr 144:14 \ft God is ready of his part to lift up all.\f*
\v 15 The eyes of all hope in thee, o Lord: and thou givest their meat in time convenient.
\v 16 Thou openest thy hand: and fillest every living creature with blessing. \f + \fr 144:16 \ft He giveth necessary things to all living creatures, even to brute beasts.\f*
\v 17 Our Lord is just in all his ways: and holy in all his works.
\v 18 Our Lord is near to all that invocate him: to all that invocate him in truth.
\v 19 He will do the will of them that fear him, and will hear their prayer, and save them.
\v 20 Our Lord keepeth all that love him: and he will destroy all sinners.
\v 21 My mouth shall speak the praise of our Lord: and let all flesh bless his holy name for ever, and for ever and ever.
\c 145
\p
\v 1 Alleluia, of Aggæus and Zacharie. \f + \fr 145:1 \ft The Septuagint added the names of these two Prophets, for the like reason as they added Jeremy, Psal. 136. because Aggæus and Zacharias prophesying in the reduction of the people from captivity, exhorted them, as here the Psalmist doth, to trust in God's providence, and prefer his service before worldly cares.\f*
\v 2 My soul praise thou our Lord, I will praise our Lord in my life: I will sing to my God as long as I shall be. Put not confidence in Princes:
\v 3 in the sons of men: in whom there is no salvation. \f + \fr 145:3 \ft In one Son of Man (Christ) is salvation (saith S. Augustin) and in him, not because he is the son of man, but because he is the Son of God.\f*
\v 4 His spirit shall go forth, and he shall return into his earth: in that day all their cogitations shall perish. \f + \fr 145:4 \ft He saith not that the spirit or soul shall turn into the earth, but the soul shall depart from the body, and so every one (in whom worldly men put their trust) shall according to the body, return into his earth.\f*
\v 5 Blessed is he, whose helper is the God of Jacob, his hope in our Lord his God:
\v 6 who made heaven and earth, the sea, and all things that are in them.
\v 7 Which keepeth truth for ever, doth judgment for them that suffer wrong: giveth food to the hungry. Our Lord looseth the fettered:
\v 8 our Lord illuminateth the blind. Our Lord lifteth up the bruised, our Lord loveth the just.
\v 9 Our Lord keepeth strangers, the pupil and widow he will receive: and the ways of sinners he will destroy.
\v 10 Our Lord will reign for ever thy God, o Sion in generation & generation.
\c 146
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Praise ye our Lord because Psalm is good: to our God let there be pleasant and comely praise. \f + \fr 146:1 \ft It is good to sing Psalms of praise to God.\f*
\v 2 Our Lord building up Jerusalem: will gather together the dispersions of Israel. \f + \fr 146:2 \ft Aprophecy of the restoration of Jerusalem after the captivity.\f*
\v 3 Who healeth the contrite of heart: and bindeth up their sores. \f + \fr 146:3 \ft Remitteth sins to the penitent.\f*
\v 4 Who numbereth the multitude of stars: & giveth names to them all. \f + \fr 146:4 \ft Besides experience of every one that shall behold the firmament in a clear night, the holy Scripture (Gen. 15. v. 5.) sheweth, that the stars are innumerable to man. For albeit Ptolomey and other Astronomers numbereth certain more notorious stars, which serve especially for some knowledge in the science of Astronomy, numbering 349. such in the Zodiach; 316. in the South part thereof; and 360. on the North part, which are in all 1025. Yet all acknowledge that no man can come near to any probable conjecture of the whole number, nor is able to attain any perfect knowledge of their natural influences, and special proprieties. And therefore the Psalmist proposeth here the admirable and unsearchable knowledge of God: who both most exactly knoweth the number,\f* \f + \fr 146:4 \ft and so perfectly their nature, that his divine Omniscience giveth to every star a proper name, according to their singular differences and proprieties.\f*
\v 5 Great is our Lord, and great is his strength: and of his wisdom there is no number. \f + \fr 146:5 \ft Things subject to God's knowledge and wisdom are innumerable.\f*
\v 6 Our Lord receiving the meek: & humbling sinners even to the ground.
\v 7 Sing ye to our Lord in confession: sing ye to our God on harp.
\v 8 Who covereth the heaven with clouds: and prepareth rain for the earth. Who bringeth forth grass in the mountains: and herb for the service of men. \f + \fr 146:8 \ft All these and the like benefits do shew God's incomparable greatness, wisdom, and goodness.\f*
\v 9 Who giveth to beasts their food: and to the young ravens that call upon him. \f + \fr 146:9 \ft Both sacred and profane authors testify, that ravens seeing their young ones, either without feathers, or to have whitish unlike to theirs, as suspecting that they are not their own birds, but of some other kind, leave them destitute of meat; therefore God the author of nature, and conserver of all kinds of creatures, by his special providence, feedeth them: either by a certain dew hanging near them in the air, as Isidorus supposeth; or by little beasts, or flies, sent by God's providence, which they catching into their mouths, are nourished and brought up as S. Chrysostom teacheth, ser. in Heliam; or by what other means soever, all agree that young ravens are neglected by their parents, and are fed marvelously by God's ordinance; by which example the Psalmist sheweth, that much more God hath care of men: especially of such men (saith S. Chrysostom.) as honour him with hymns and praises,\f*
\v 10 He shall not have pleasure in the strength of an horse: nor in the legs of a man shall he be well pleased.
\v 11 Our Lord is well pleased toward them that fear him: and in them that hope upon his mercy.
\c 147
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. O Jerusalem praise our Lord: praise thy God, o Sion. \f + \fr 147:1 \ft Jerusalem in the latter part of David's time, all the time of Salomon, and part of other Kings' reigns till the captivity, had peace & prospered. Again after the captivity, the City was repaired, the Temple re-edified, and the whole land received and enjoyed many blessings. But all this was no more than a figure of the excellent benefits here prophesied, and more evidently verified in Christ's Catholic Church: partly here militant in the whole world, & especially in the glorious Jerusalem, and Sion, the perfect vision of peace, and contemplation of God in eternal life.\f* \f + \fr 147:1 \ft The Hebrews join this Psalm with the precedent.\f*
\v 2 Because he hath strengthened the locks of thy gates: he hath blessed thy children in thee. \f + \fr 147:2 \ft In comparison of other cities and peoples of the world, the gates of Jerusalem were strongly fenced,\f* \f + \fr 147:2 \ft and the citizens blessed: much more the Church of Christ is built upon a sure rock, her faithful children endued with all spiritual graces; and most of all, heaven it-self is free from all danger of calamity, and the Saints are most secure & most happy, enjoying eternal fruition of God.\f*
\v 3 Who hath set thy borders peace: and filleth thee with the fat of corn. \f + \fr 147:3 \ft Hath given peace in thy borders,\f* \f + \fr 147:3 \ft and the very best corn, and all other fruits: wine, oil, milk, honey, and the rest. Allegorically in the Church, reconciliation with God, by remission of sins, & peace of conscience, in the Sacraments of Baptism & Penance; with the most spiritual food of Christ's Body & Blood in the Eucharist, and graces of other Sacraments. In heaven most assured peace and joy without end.\f*
\v 4 Who sendeth forth his speech to the earth: his word runneth swiftly. \f + \fr 147:4 \ft This pertaineth most specially to Evangelical doctrine, preached\f* \f + \fr 147:4 \ft and quickly received in all the world. Rom. 10. v. 18.\f*
\v 5 Who giveth snow as wool: scattereth mist as ashes. \f + \fr 147:5 \ft Snow nourisheth the earth, making it warm by Antiperistasis, as is evident in natural Philosophy,\f* \f + \fr 147:5 \ft and noisome air is changed into clear weather. In the Church by penance & austere life men are purged from sins and vices, evil spirits are also driven away. If your sins shall be as scarlet, they shall be made white as snow, and if they be red as vermilion, they shall be white as wool. Isaie 1. v. 18.\f*
\v 6 He casteth his crystal as morsels: before the face of his cold who shall endure? \f + \fr 147:6 \ft Yea some that are hardened in sins, as ice or crystal, shall be melted, broken, or made fit to be engrafted in God's Church. So S. Peter was admonished by a vision (Act. 10. v. 13.) to kill and eat.\f* \f + \fr 147:6 \ft Otherwise without God's grace giving remorse and sorrow, no man can overcome his own vices.\f*
\v 7 He shall send forth his word, and shall melt them: his spirit shall blow, and waters shall flow. \f + \fr 147:7 \ft But God's word preached,\f* \f + \fr 147:7 \ft and his grace touching men's hearts,\f* \f + \fr 147:7 \ft innumerable are converted.\f*
\v 8 Who declareth his word to Jacob: his justices and judgments to Israel. \f + \fr 147:8 \ft The Church only enjoyeth these spiritual benefits.\f*
\v 9 He hath not done in like manner to any nation: and his judgements he hath not made manifest to them. Alleluia. \f + \fr 147:9 \ft Considering that all mankind was in the mass of sin, and that God letteth many justly perish, those to whom he giveth his grace to justification, are specially bound to praise him.\f* \f + \fr 147:9 \ft And therefore the Prophet concludeth this Psalm, and the rest following, with Alleluia.\f*
\c 148
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Praise ye our Lord from the heavens: praise ye him in the high places. \f + \fr 148:1 \ft All ye heavenly spirits praise God for the excellency of your nature.\f*
\v 2 Praise ye him all his Angels: praise ye him all his hosts: \f + \fr 148:2 \ft And for your innumerable multitude.\f*
\v 3 Praise ye him sun and moon: praise him all ye stars, and light. \f + \fr 148:3 \ft All creatures, wanting sense or reason, shew forth the Majesty and excellency of their Creator.\f*
\v 4 Praise him ye heavens of heavens: and the waters that are above the heavens,
\v 5 let them praise the name of our Lord. Because he said, and they were made: he commanded, and they were created.
\v 6 He established them for ever, and for ever and ever: he put a precept, and it shall not pass.
\v 7 Praise our Lord from the earth: ye dragons, and all depths.
\v 8 Fire, hail, snow, ice, spirit of storms: which do his word:
\v 9 Mountains, and all little hills: trees that bear fruit, and all cedars.
\v 10 Beasts, and all cattle: serpents, and feathered fowls:
\v 11 Kings of the earth, & all peoples: Princes, and all judges of the earth. \f + \fr 148:11 \ft Again God is to be praised for the diversity of states in men, whereby the whole community is conserved & governed.\f*
\v 12 Young men and virgins: old with young let them praise the name of our Lord:
\v 13 because the name of him alone is exalted. \f + \fr 148:13 \ft God only, & no false imagined god made & disposed all things in order.\f*
\v 14 The confession of him above heaven and earth: and he hath exalted the horn of his people. An hymn to all his saints: to the children of Israel a people approaching unto him. Alleluia. \f + \fr 148:14 \ft More especially for that God hath so fortified his Church.\f* \f + \fr 148:14 \ft Sanctified children,\f* \f + \fr 148:14 \ft that by grace and free will, which he giveth them, approach unto him.\f* \f + \fr 148:14 \ft All this considered the Psalmist concluding with Alleluia, inviteth all to praise Our Lord.\f*
\c 149
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Sing ye to our Lord a new song: let his praise be in the Church of saints. \f + \fr 149:1 \ft God our Lord whom all creatures are bound to praise, only accepteth those men's praises, that live in his holy Church.\f*
\v 2 Let Israel be joyful in him, that made him: and let the children of Sion rejoice in their King.
\v 3 Let them praise his name in choir: on timbrel and psalter let them sing to him.
\v 4 Because our Lord is well pleased in his people: and he will exalt the meek unto salvation.
\v 5 The saints shall rejoice in glory: they shall be joyful in their beds. \f + \fr 149:5 \ft Eternal rest.\f*
\v 6 The exaltations of God in their throat: and two edged swords in their hands. \f + \fr 149:6 \ft Highest praises of God shall be continually uttered by Saints in glory: for still as praises pass by their tongues and mouths, more like praises shall succeed from their throat, and heart affection, so out of the aboundance of the heart their mouth shall still speak God's praise.\f* \f + \fr 149:6 \ft Glorified Saints shall also have judiciary power. First, all in general shall like and approve God's justice in punishing the wicked. Secondly, the wicked shall be justly condemned in comparison of the blessed, who passed through and overcame the like, yea and greater tribulations and tentations than those by which the damned were overcome. Thirdly, certain more excellent Saints, namely the Apostles and all those that forsaking propriety of temporal goods, give that they have to the poor, as some religious Orders do; or into a Community as the Apostles, and many primitive Christians did (Mat. 4. v. 20. cap. 19. v. 27. Act. 4. v. 34. 1. Cor. 6. v. 3.) shall sit in judgement seats, assessory judges with Christ,\f*
\v 7 To do revenge in the nations: chastisements among the peoples.
\v 8 To bind their kings in fetters: and their nobles in iron manacles.
\v 9 That they may do in them the judgement that is written: this glory is to all his saints. Alleluia. \f + \fr 149:9 \ft Decreed by God.\f* \f + \fr 149:9 \ft This judicial power is part of Saint's glory.\f*
\c 150
\p
\v 1 Alleluia. Praise ye our Lord in his holies: praise ye him in the firmament of his strength. \f + \fr 150:1 \ft All ye Angels and men that are in the holy and highest\f* \f + \fr 150:1 \ft All ye creatures that are in and under the first moveable firmament, praise our Lord.\f*
\v 2 Praise ye him in his powers: praise ye him according to the multitude of his greatness. \f + \fr 150:2 \ft And you especially (God's peculiar people) amongst whom and for whom divine miracles have been wrought, praise our Lord,\f* \f + \fr 150:2 \ft with all your possible endeavour, for though his infinite Excellency exceedeth the power of all creatures to praise him sufficiently, yet it resteth that you may infinitely extend your will and desire to praise our Lord, according to the multitude of his greatness.\f*
\v 3 Praise ye him in the sound of trumpet: praise ye him on psalter and harp. \f + \fr 150:3 \ft Out of this your great and infinite desire, let your tongues sound and sing divine praises, as well with voice, as musical instruments.\f* \f + \fr 150:3 \ft Whereof six most usual in the Tabernacle and Temple were these: Trumpet, Psalter, Harp, Timbrel, Organ, and Cymbal.\f*
\v 4 Praise ye him on timbrel and choir: praise ye him on strings and organ. \f + \fr 150:4 \ft By the way the Psalmist interposeth again two especial things, which make perfect harmony, without which no instrument is grateful to God: Unity amongst his servants, signified by the Quire of consonant voices:\f* \f + \fr 150:4 \ft and mortification of passions, signified by Strings, which are made of dead beast's bowels.\f*
\v 5 Praise ye him on well sounding cymbals: praise ye him on cymbals of jubilation:
\v 6 let every spirit praise our Lord. Alleluia. \f + \fr 150:6 \ft Man created of corruptible body and immortal soul, is finally admonished to praise our Lord, over and above the praises of all other corporal creatures; who also is more especially bound thereto than Angels, because God hath vouchsafed to make himself man, to redeem man that was lost by sin, and to endow him with new grace, and so bring him to everlasting glory, where with holy Angels men also for ever & ever shall praise our Lord, with heart, voice, and jubilation of spirit, singing as the Psalmist concludeth, Alleluia.\f*
